    head_unit_id = "1.3";
    head_unit_title = "Water-Repellency";
    content = "Water-repellency in textiles relates to the surface tension of fibers, fabric structures and their relationship with that of contacting water molecules. This phenomenon can be easily observed in various objects such as water beading on lotus leaves or certain fabrics. The surface structure of, for example, lotus leaves creates a level of surface tension insufficiently strong to break the internal tension of water molecules, causing water droplets to maintain their shapes. \nCotton and Wool: Cotton fibers and fabrics have a high affinity for water due to the presence of the hydroxyl groups in cellulose. This causes water to penetrate and spread quickly through the materials. Wool, on the other hand, behaves differently because of its unique surface structure. While the protein in the wool also has a strong affinity for water, it is protected by the scales, as shown in Fig.3, on the fiber surface that provide a certain level of water repellency and resistance. However, once water penetrates through the gaps of the scales and wets the protein, it quickly spreads.\nWith their inherent affinity for water, fabrics made with cotton and wool may require chemical treatments to provide a desired level of water repellency, if used in textiles designed for direct contact with rain or snow. \nSynthetic Materials: In contrast, tightly woven synthetic fabrics, even without chemical water-repellent treatments, can behave like lotus leaves to a certain degree, causing water droplets to bead up on the surface. This natural water repellency is closely related to the hydrophobic nature and smooth surface structure of most synthetic fibers. \nChemical Treatment: Per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS) are applied to the weather-facing side of fabrics to create a high(er) degree of water repellency, preventing rain from wetting the surface. This treatment is commonly used on textiles made with natural fibers such as a woolen (brushed) winter coat, cotton jackets, etc. Another example is various outdoor jackets made with synthetic fibers. Although synthetic fibers naturally repel water as mentioned earlier, the chemical treatment boosts their performance to a level more suitable for avid outdoor activities.\nThe PFAS are organic compounds that come in different variations, such as C8, C6, and C4, with the numbers referring to the number of carbon atoms. Traditionally, the industry used the compounds with higher carbon numbers, like C8, also known as perfluorooctanoic acid (PFOA), because they offer superior water repellency and durability on textile materials compared to the compounds with fewer carbons.\nToxicity Recognition and Regulatory Works: In the late 1990s, several lawsuits were filed against DuPont by residents living near its Washington Works plant in Parkersburg, West Virginia, due to a PFOA contamination originated from the plant in the local drinking water. Subsequent research identified the PFOA as carcinogen, with a particular link to kidney and testicular cancers.\nIn 2006, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and eight major companies that used these chemicals in various industrial applications agreed to the 2010/2015 PFOA Stewardship Program. The program'\''s goal was to reduce PFOA emissions by 95% by 2010 and to work toward eliminating them by 2015. This initiative was successfully implemented, and by the mid-2010s, these companies had phased out the use of the PFOA in manufacturing consumer products and other intermediary materials such as fibers, yarns and fabrics.\nIn June 2020, the EPA issued the Significant New Use Rule (SNUR), requiring US manufacturers and importers to notify the agency before beginning or resuming the use of these chemicals for any significant new purposes. Following the EPA'\''s actions, the European Union also took major steps to regulate these chemicals. In 2019, many countries participating in the Stockholm Convention agreed to add the PFOA to the list of the Persistent Organic Pollutants (POPs).\nContinued Use and Environmental Impacts: Despite these regulations, various PFAS chemicals are still used in many countries where environmental regulations are less strict. Additionally, significant loopholes exist in the regulatory actions of many countries. For instance, the EPA'\''s action against the PFOA (C8) led to the use of other PFAS with shorter carbon chains, such as C6 (perfluorohexanoic acid, PFHxA) and C4 (perfluorobutane sulfonate, PFBS). However, concerns on the health impacts and the persistence of these chemicals in nature remain, as they belong to the same family of chemical groups. \nSeveral studies have revealed the potential health impacts of the chemicals with fewer carbon atoms, such as thyroid hormone disruption, developmental toxicity, liver toxicity, and effects on the immune system at high doses. Even without these studies, scientific reasoning suggests that, while the impacts of C6 and C4 may be less severe than those of C8, they still exist and create proportionally harmful impacts.\nThese chemicals contaminate water either from manufacturing processes or laundering the textiles containing the chemicals, then spread globally through water streams. Moreover, the PFOAs applied to a large number of consumer and industrial products before the implementation of the environmental regulations still persist in the environment due to their extreme durability. Combined with the ongoing use of these chemicals in many regions of the world, they will continue to impact the environment and human health for generations.  \nConsumer Awareness: As mentioned earlier regarding my approach to purchasing textile goods, the same principles apply when it comes to the water repellency feature. \nI have often been caught in the rain before finding a shelter in my everyday clothing, and the feature could have provided some relief by keeping my body dry in such situations. With this, I recognize that the water repellency might be more useful for people like me in their city life than the water resistant and breathable technology. However, I still weigh my decisions carefully: These chemicals gradually wash out with each laundry cycle, eventually losing their effectiveness. The preference for C8 compounds over C6 and C4 largely stems from their superior durability on fibers and fabrics. Nevertheless, no matter how durable, this performance feature usually has a shorter lifespan than the textile item itself. In some cases, the repellency lasts only few washes, depending on wash conditions.\nJustification: Given the limited duration of its effectiveness, as well as the associated costs and environmental impacts, it is hard for me to justify purchasing items employing this chemically treated feature. For these reasons, I actively seek out the products without any water-repellent treatment. \n***\nAs the section title suggests, consumers are often \"unfortunate\" because they are frequently targeted by various stakeholders who promote a range of technical claims, making certain features seem relevant when, in reality, they may not be as beneficial as advertised. Additionally, consumers'\'' choices are often limited by the decisions made by these stakeholders. For example, when shopping for a jacket, it can be difficult to find options that don'\''t include unnecessary chemical treatments. Even if a shopper prefers to avoid these features, they may still end up purchasing a jacket with extensive chemical treatments, as these features are routinely applied to many textile products. \nUnfortunately, consumers’ limited understanding, coupled with a lack of interest in learning about the science behind these technologies, enables many organizations to prioritize performance claims over health and environmental concerns. This highlights the importance of consumer education. It is crucial for consumers to be informed about the practicality of certain performance features and to ask relevant questions about their environmental impacts. Given the importance of this issue, I explore it further in Chapter V: Solutions, particularly in the section titled Education, Education, and Education.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Water-Repellency in Textiles\n\nWater-repellency in textiles involves how fibers and fabric structures interact with water molecules, primarily through surface tension. This can be easily seen in nature, like the way water droplets bead up on lotus leaves. The unique surface of lotus leaves creates surface tension strong enough to make the water droplets hold their shape without spreading.\n\n## Cotton and Wool\n\n- **Cotton**: Cotton fibers absorb water quickly due to the hydroxyl groups in cellulose, which allows water to penetrate and spread rapidly.\n  \n- **Wool**: While wool fibers also attract water, their surface is covered in scales (as seen in Fig. 3) that provide some water resistance. However, when water gets through these scales and touches the protein in wool, it spreads quickly across the fabric.\n\nBoth cotton and wool fabrics may need chemical treatments to enhance their water repellency, especially for clothing exposed to rain or snow.\n\n## Synthetic Materials\n\nTightly woven synthetic fabrics can mimic the water-repelling effect of lotus leaves. Even without chemical treatments, they can cause water to bead on their surfaces due to their smooth texture and hydrophobic properties.\n\n## Chemical Treatment\n\nTo improve water repellency, fabrics are often treated with per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS). These treatments are applied to the outside of fabrics to keep rain from soaking through. They are commonly used on natural fiber textiles, like wool coats and cotton jackets, as well as synthetic outdoor gear. \n\nPFAS come in different types, such as C8, C6, and C4, with the number indicating the carbon atom count. C8, known as perfluorooctanoic acid (PFOA), was historically favored for its strong water repellency and durability.\n\n## Toxicity Recognition and Regulation\n\nIn the late 1990s, residents near DuPont'\''s Washington Works plant in West Virginia filed lawsuits due to PFOA contamination in drinking water. Research later linked PFOA to serious health issues, such as certain cancers.\n\nIn 2006, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) and major companies agreed to the PFOA Stewardship Program, aiming to cut PFOA emissions by 95% by 2010 and eliminate them by 2015. This effort significantly reduced PFOA use in consumer products by the mid-2010s.\n\nIn June 2020, the EPA implemented the Significant New Use Rule (SNUR), requiring manufacturers to inform the agency before using PFAS for new purposes. The European Union has also taken steps to regulate these chemicals, adding PFOA to a list of harmful persistent organic pollutants (POPs) in 2019.\n\n## Continued Use and Environmental Impacts\n\nDespite regulations, PFAS are still used in many countries with less strict environmental laws. This includes using shorter carbon-chain PFAS, such as C6 and C4, which also raise health concerns similar to those of C8. Studies indicate these chemicals can disrupt hormones, cause developmental issues, and affect the liver and immune system at high doses. \n\nPFAS can enter water systems during production and laundering of treated textiles, leading to widespread environmental contamination. The durability of PFOA means it remains in the environment long after its use has ceased, affecting health and ecosystems for years.\n\n## Consumer Awareness\n\nWhen purchasing textile products, it’s important to consider the water-repellency feature. For individuals who get caught in the rain often, this trait can be beneficial. However, these chemical treatments can lose effectiveness after several washes, and many consumers might unknowingly buy items treated with these chemicals due to a lack of options.\n\nConsumers tend to be \"unfortunate\" as they'\''re often targeted by companies promoting various technical claims that may not be as advantageous as they seem. As a result, it'\''s crucial to educate oneself about the effectiveness and potential environmental impacts of these features. \n\nIn light of these considerations, I regularly choose products without chemical treatments, recognizing that the costs and environmental consequences don'\''t justify purchasing treated items.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nConsumer education is essential in navigating the available options for textiles and understanding their implications for health and the environment. Raising awareness about the real effects of water-repellency treatments can empower consumers to make more informed decisions. This topic will be explored further in Chapter V: Solutions, specifically in the section on Education.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the primary reason cotton fabrics have high water affinity?"; options = vec { "A. Presence of fatty acids"; "B. Presence of hydroxyl groups in cellulose"; "C. Tightly woven structure"; "D. Synthetic additives" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What chemical treatment is commonly used to enhance water repellency in textiles?"; options = vec { "A. Polyethylene glycol"; "B. Per- and polyfluoroalkyl substances (PFAS)"; "C. Sodium chloride"; "D. Silicones" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which group of PFAS was traditionally used due to superior water repellency?"; options = vec { "A. C2"; "B. C4"; "C. C6"; "D. C8" }; answer = 3; }; record { question = "What is a significant environmental concern related to PFAS?"; options = vec { "A. They are biodegradable"; "B. They can contaminate water sources"; "C. They enhance fabric durability"; "D. They are completely harmless" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Why do consumers find it challenging to avoid textiles with chemical treatments?"; options = vec { "A. All products are sold without labels"; "B. Limited awareness and interest in textile science"; "C. High cost of untreated fabrics"; "D. Lack of availability of untreated products" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "1.4.0";
    unit_title = "Artificially Conceptual Value (ACV) (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "1.4";
    head_unit_title = "Artificially Conceptual Value (ACV)";
    content = "An Artificially Conceptual Value (ACV) is a performance feature, that operates similarly to a placebo effect in medicine, but it can lead to unfavorable outcomes for the environmental sustainability. \nDefinition and Corporate Behaviors: To further define Artificially Conceptual Value (ACV), it refers to a technical feature that lacks scientific evidence to prove its effectiveness in real-life situations but makes people believe it works. Companies engaged in ACVs often introduce related scientific concepts to explain how their technologies theoretically function. Unfortunately, these explanations are frequently designed to quickly convince consumers who lack in-depth knowledge about the related science. This approach is highly effective because it seems logical and plausible on the surface.\nConsequences: In the medical world, relying solely on placebo effect can worsen an illness over time, leading to serious consequences. For example, it is well known that Steve Jobs could have potentially saved his life by turning to modern medical treatments rather than relying on naturopathy for too long. The same logic applies to the environmental impacts of various ACVs. A scientifically accurate evaluation can help remove potentially harmful and unnecessary chemical treatments in the textile goods we consume for the good of environment.\n***\nUnfortunately, ACVs are widespread in the textile industry. I'\''m often astonished to see large, reputable, and respected companies engaging in such practices. In this subsection, we will review several examples of ACVs in textiles to help readers better understand this concept.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Artificially Conceptual Value (ACV)\n\n## What is ACV?\nAn **Artificially Conceptual Value (ACV)** is a feature that affects performance, similar to how a placebo works in medicine. However, it can negatively impact environmental sustainability.\n\n## Definition and Corporate Behavior\nACV refers to a technical attribute that lacks solid scientific evidence supporting its effectiveness in real-world applications yet creates the illusion that it is beneficial. Companies that utilize ACVs often provide explanations involving scientific concepts to describe how their products supposedly work. Unfortunately, these explanations are often tailored to quickly persuade consumers who might not have a deep understanding of the science involved. This tactic is effective because it appears logical and believable at first glance.\n\n## Consequences\nIn the medical field, depending solely on a placebo can lead to worsening health issues over time. A notable example is Steve Jobs, who might have survived longer if he had opted for conventional medical treatments instead of relying on alternative therapies. The same reasoning applies to the environmental effects of various ACVs. A scientifically sound assessment can help eliminate harmful and unnecessary chemicals found in textile products, benefiting the environment.\n\n## ACVs in the Textile Industry\nRegrettably, ACVs are common in the textile sector. It can be surprising to discover that even large, reputable companies engage in these practices. In the following sections, we will explore several examples of ACVs in textiles to clarify this concept for readers.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What does ACV stand for?"; options = vec { "Artificially Creative Value"; "Artificially Conceptual Value"; "Actual Concept Value"; "Authentic Creative Value" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How do companies typically support their ACVs?"; options = vec { "By providing extensive scientific data"; "By relying on customer testimonials"; "By introducing related scientific concepts"; "By promoting environmental sustainability" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is one example given for the negative consequences of relying on placebo effects?"; options = vec { "Increased product sales"; "Potential worsening of illness"; "Improved consumer trust"; "Greater innovation in medicine" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "In which industry are ACVs particularly prevalent according to the content?"; options = vec { "Pharmaceuticals"; "Textiles"; "Technology"; "Automotive" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What can a scientifically accurate evaluation help with regarding ACVs?"; options = vec { "Improving company profits"; "Removing harmful chemical treatments"; "Enhancing marketing strategies"; "Increasing consumer engagement" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "1.4.1";
    unit_title = "Heat Reflective Technology";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "1.4";
    head_unit_title = "Artificially Conceptual Value (ACV)";
    content = "A thin layer of a metallic silver pattern is applied to the inner lining fabric of winter jackets with the claim that it reflects the body heat back toward the wearer, conserving the heat and keeping him/her warmer than the person would be without this technology. This concept sounds logical and plausible to many, and as a result, the technology has become commercially successful in cold-climate regions where effective thermal technologies are essential for winter garments. \nHeat Exchange: To understand the scientific foundation of this technology, it is essential to understand how the heat exchanges occur in the human body through five different mechanisms: conduction, convection, radiation, respiration, and evaporation, as illustrated in Fig. 8. These processes help prevent overheating by dissipating the heat generated from the food we consume, which raises body temperature, and helps maintain a constant temperature of approximately 36.5°C (97.7°F).\nFig.8   Heat Exchanges of Body\nThe degree of the heat exchanges depends on several factors, including weather and individual body conditions, where some of these factors can be controlled, while others cannot. Without delving too deeply into the science of thermodynamics, simplified concepts are as follows:\nRespiration, Convection, Conduction and Evaporation: Given a specific set of weather conditions and personal variables, our body heat escapes through respiration as we breathe. Wind removes the heat through convection, as though standing in front of a fan. A conductive heat loss happens when cold air molecules come into contact with the molecules warmed by our body heat, transferring the heat from the higher energy level of being warm to the lower energy level of the cold surroundings. An evaporative heat loss occurs through the sweat glands on the skin to release the heat through moisture, which evaporates and cools the body. Increased physical activity, such as running, generates more heat and moisture, leading to visible sweat and greater heat loss through this mechanism of evaporation. \nRadiation: A radiative heat exchange, the focus of this heat-reflective technology, involves the transfer of the body heat through radiation. This type of heat exchange can be easily experienced by standing near a radiator in a room during winter; you can feel the warmth radiating upwards when the radiator is on. Similarly, someone engaged in intense physical activity, like vigorous running, can feel this radiative effect by placing her/his hand near the forehead. When the body needs to dissipate excess heat quickly, it radiates the heat through the skin, working in tandem with other mechanisms like heavy breathing and perspiration.\nMechanisms of Controllable Heat Exchanges: Of the five heat exchange mechanisms, three - radiation, respiration and evaporation - are mostly under the control of our body, while conduction and convection depend more heavily on weather conditions. These three “controllable” mechanisms are most active during a high physical activity in warm and humid conditions as the body needs to remove the heat more efficiently in those conditions.\nConversely, in a cold weather with a low activity level, the body attempts to conserve the heat by minimizing these three exchanges. In such cases, the respiration slows, the body’s sweat pores shrink and close, and the skin works to prevent the heat from escaping, reducing the radiative heat loss to nearly negligible levels.\nHypothesis and Scientific Analysis: If the heat reflective technology were truly effective in real-life situations, one could wear nothing but a sheet of aluminum foil, seal it tightly to minimize convective heat loss from cold air and feel warmer than if they were nude. However, this setup would actually make the person feel colder due to another scientific principle: the aluminum has a much higher thermal conductivity than air, meaning it would transfer the cold energy more quickly. Fig. 9 illustrates the thermal conductivity map of different materials. \nFig.9   Thermal Conductivity Chart\nDry air is among the least conductive, while metals are among the most conductive.\nBasics of Thermal Science: In the thermal science relating to textiles, a critical area of focus is the microclimate, the region between the body and the garment system, as shown in Fig.10. This microclimate traps warmer air generated by the body heat. The benefits of placing an aluminum sheet in the microclimate to prevent the radiative heat loss can be easily overshadowed by the rapid conductive heat loss caused by the metal'\''s (or any other solid materials’) high thermal conductivity.\nFig.10   Microclimate and Condensation\nTest: A study was conducted to measure the effect of the heat reflective technology on the thermal efficiency of a textile structure typically used for winter garments. The study compared the CLO values of a conventional non-woven thermal insulation material with and without a lining fabric printed with the silver reflective dots, obtained from a specific brand’s garments promoting this technology. \nAbout CLO: The CLO is a metric used to measure the thermal efficiency of a material in the apparel industry, similar to the R-value used in the construction industry. A lower R-value indicates a less efficient thermal protection, leading to higher energy costs for heating and cooling of a house or building. Likewise, a higher CLO value in a textile material indicates a better thermal efficiency in conserving the body heat.  \nTest Environment: CLO tests are typically conducted in a controlled laboratory environment with a testing device, which includes a heat plate covered by the tested material, typically in a sheet form factor. The plate is heated to a certain temperature, for example, the body temperature of 36.5°C (97.7°F), and once the temperatures of the plate and the air above the material stabilize, the sensors located in the air above the material measure the heat energy trapped in the material by subtracting the temperature difference of the plate and the air, which is then expressed as a CLO value. \nResults: The difference in the CLO values between the samples with and without the heat reflective liner fabric was less than 0.2 CLO, a range too small to be considered detectable by the general population. Given that the liner fabric hosting the reflective dots already has its own intrinsic CLO value, the impact of the reflective dots was negligible. \nReal-World Scenarios: Under the premise of the heat-reflective technology, it might be more effective in cold weather when a person is engaged in high-intensity activities, causing the body to emit more radiative heat. However, in such scenarios, the body is already warm and doesn’t need additional heat from the reflected energy. In fact, reflecting the heat back in these situations could do more harm than good by further raising the body temperature, increasing sweat levels in the microclimate, and potentially leading to hyperthermia, as heat exchanges occur more rapidly in moist air.\nImportance of Thermal Technologies: Unlike highly specialized garments such as flame-resistant suits for firefighters or bulletproof vests for police officers, most everyday clothing is chosen for more mundane factors like appearance, materials, comfort, and price, rather than for its protective features. However, winter clothing is an exception, as it is essential for the health and safety of consumers in cold climates. While some may argue that a placebo effect in winter apparel is harmless if it provides a sense of warmth, in reality, relying on inadequate protection in cold weather can be dangerous and the potential harm should not be taken lightly. \nEnvironmental Impacts: From an environmental and sustainability perspective, the printed patterns with different materials on the fabric surfaces introduce unnecessary impurities. While more details will be provided in Chapter V: Solutions, specifically in Clean Recycling Initiative™ section, the success of recycling efforts, particularly with synthetics, relies heavily on the material purity and the foreign materials used in the heat reflective technology can hinder the efforts. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Heat-Reflective Technology in Winter Jackets\n\nA thin layer of metallic silver is added to the inner lining of winter jackets, claiming to reflect body heat back to the wearer. This technology is thought to conserve heat, making the person feel warmer than they would without it. Many find this idea sensible, leading to its popularity in cold regions where effective insulation is crucial for winter wear.\n\n## Heat Exchange Mechanisms\n\nTo grasp the scientific basis behind this technology, it'\''s important to know how heat is exchanged in the human body through five methods:\n\n1. **Conduction**\n2. **Convection**\n3. **Radiation**\n4. **Respiration**\n5. **Evaporation**\n\nThese processes help prevent overheating by releasing the heat from the food we eat, keeping our body temperature stable at around 36.5°C (97.7°F). \n![Heat Exchanges of Body](link_to_fig8)\n\n### The Heat Exchange Processes\n\nThe effectiveness of these heat exchanges is influenced by various factors, including weather and individual characteristics. Here'\''s a simplified explanation of how these mechanisms operate:\n\n- **Respiration**: As we breathe, our body heat escapes.\n- **Convection**: Wind moves the heat away from our bodies, similar to a fan blowing on us.\n- **Conduction**: When warm air from our bodies touches the cold air, heat transfers from warm to cold.\n- **Evaporation**: Sweat on our skin evaporates and cools the body, especially during physical activity.\n\n### Focus on Radiation\n\nThe heat-reflective technology specifically highlights **radiation**, which is the transfer of body heat through radiation. You can feel this effect when near a heated radiator. For instance, when exercising intensely, you can feel heat radiating from your body, particularly from areas like your forehead. When the body needs to lose excess heat fast, it radiates this heat through the skin, working in combination with breathing and sweating.\n\n### Controllable Heat Exchange Mechanisms\n\nThree heat exchange mechanisms—radiation, respiration, and evaporation—are largely within our body'\''s control, while conduction and convection are more affected by external weather conditions. During intense physical activity in warm, humid weather, our bodies effectively remove excess heat. In contrast, during cold weather and low activity, our body tries to conserve heat by slowing down respiration, closing sweat pores, and minimizing heat loss from radiation.\n\n## Hypothesis and Scientific Analysis\n\nIf the heat-reflective technology worked as claimed, one might suggest that wearing a tightly sealed sheet of aluminum foil could keep a person warmer than being nude. However, this would actually result in feeling colder because aluminum conducts cold much more effectively than air.  \n![Thermal Conductivity Chart](link_to_fig9)\n\n## Basics of Thermal Science\n\nIn textile thermal science, a key focus is the **microclimate**—the area between the body and the fabric. \n![Microclimate and Condensation](link_to_fig10) \n\nThis microclimate traps warm air generated by our body. The benefits of using aluminum to prevent heat loss can be overshadowed by its high thermal conductivity, leading to faster heat loss.\n\n## Testing Heat Reflective Technology\n\nA study was conducted to examine how effective the heat-reflective technology is in winter garments. Researchers compared the thermal efficiency (measured in CLO values) of traditional insulation materials with and without silver reflective lining.\n\n### Understanding CLO\n\n**CLO** measures a material'\''s thermal efficiency in clothing, similar to how **R-value** works in construction. Lower CLO values indicate less thermal protection, leading to higher energy costs for heating and cooling. Conversely, a higher CLO value signifies better heat conservation.\n\n### Test Conditions\n\nCLO tests take place in a lab setting using a heated plate that mimics body temperature (36.5°C or 97.7°F). Sensors measure the heat energy retained by the material above the heat plate and provide a CLO value based on the temperature difference.\n\n### Results\n\nThe CLO values showed a difference of less than 0.2 between samples with and without the heat-reflective lining, a difference too small for the average person to notice. This indicated that the effect of the reflective dots was minimal since the lining fabric itself contributed to heat retention.\n\n## Real-World Applications\n\nIn cold weather with vigorous activity, the heat-reflective technology might provide some benefit, as the body emits extra radiant heat. However, when the body is already warm, additional heat retention may hinder performance and increase the risk of **hyperthermia** due to excess moisture.\n\n## Importance of Effective Thermal Technologies\n\nWhile most everyday clothes focus on appearance and cost, winter clothing plays a critical role in protecting health in cold climates. Relying on ineffective clothing can pose safety risks, especially in harsh weather conditions.\n\n## Environmental Considerations\n\nThe use of various materials in heat-reflective patterns may introduce unnecessary impurities, complicating recycling efforts, particularly with synthetic fabrics. Future discussions in Chapter V: Solutions will address the Clean Recycling Initiative™ and its dependence on material purity for effective recycling.\n\nBy understanding these concepts, we can appreciate the science behind winter clothing technology and its importance for health and safety, while also considering environmental impacts.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the primary claim of the heat reflective technology used in winter jackets?"; options = vec { "It makes the jacket waterproof."; "It reflects body heat back to the wearer."; "It provides additional insulation."; "It increases breathability." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which of the following mechanisms is responsible for conductive heat loss?"; options = vec { "Evaporation"; "Respiration"; "Standing near a fan"; "Contact with cold air" }; answer = 3; }; record { question = "What metric is used to measure the thermal efficiency of apparel materials?"; options = vec { "CLO"; "R-value"; "Thermal conductivity"; "Insulation factor" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What was the difference in CLO values between the samples with and without the heat reflective liner?"; options = vec { "0.5 CLO"; "2.0 CLO"; "Less than 0.2 CLO"; "1.0 CLO" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is a potential downside of using heat reflective technology during high-intensity activities in cold weather?"; options = vec { "It can lead to inefficient insulation."; "It may raise body temperature too much."; "It has no impact on comfort."; "It prevents sweat evaporation." }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "1.4.2";
    unit_title = "Phase-Change-Material (PCM) technology";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "1.4";
    head_unit_title = "Artificially Conceptual Value (ACV)";
    content = "Another performance feature whose value I find difficult to comprehend is the Phase Change Material (PCM) technology, commonly applied also in winter textiles. The PCM technology involves certain materials that change their phases from, for example, liquid to solid, and maintain a constant temperature during the phase change. For instance, when ice melts, it transitions from solid to liquid state, maintaining the constant temperature of 0°C (32°F) during the process. Similarly, water maintains the temperature of 100°C (212°F) during its phase change from liquid to vapor when boiling. A cooling gel used for stressed muscles maintains a consistent temperature while transitioning from semi-solid to liquid state on the skin.\nImportant Factors: The effectiveness of this PCM principle depends on several factors: the activation temperature, and the duration for which the material maintains a certain temperature. For example, to provide adequate protection in cold climates, the material must activate at a desired temperature and sustain it for a reasonable period. Therefore, evaluating the effectiveness of PCM in textiles requires an understanding of these factors. Unfortunately, many companies promoting PCM technologies often focus on marketing slogans like \"NASA used it for astronauts'\'' suits on the moon\" rather than providing this crucial information.\nScientific Analysis: This misleads many people, who assume that, because the moon is extremely cold, this must be an effective technology. This is a typical example of how Artificially Conceptual Values (ACVs) can create misguided assumptions. However, for those with an analytical mindset, the issue is clear: the environmental conditions on the moon are vastly different from those on Earth, and the amount of PCM used in astronauts’ suits is unknown. Our experience with ice gel packs for cooling sprained muscles provides insight into the importance of quantity. A gel pack of sufficient size and weight offers lasting relief, a concept which an astronaut’s suit can easily accommodate in the effective use of PCM. However, if only a small amount were applied to a winter jacket as we cannot wear an attire as bulky and heavy as astronauts’ suits, it would change its phase so quickly that the chemical application would offer virtually no benefit. Therefore, just because a technology works on the moon does not guarantee its effectiveness on Earth in real-life. \nEnvironmental Impacts: Typically, a PCM applied on textiles is a chemical material derived from petroleum sources, with the paraffin wax being the most common type. The material consists of long-chain hydrocarbons with 20 to 40 carbon atoms. As discussed earlier, long-chain hydrocarbons are used in water repellent treatments for garments. Certain water repellent chemicals such as C8 are banned in many countries due to their carcinogenic properties and long persistence in nature. Although these PCMs are designed to adhere to textile materials for extended periods, they gradually wash off during laundering and regular wear, contaminating the environment. \nWhen purchasing textile goods containing PCMs, it is essential to understand the specific technical details mentioned above. From a performance perspective, a purchase should only be justified if the performance metrics align with shopper’s intended needs. In practical textile applications, I have yet to observe any benefit from PCM materials in real-world situations. In most cases, PCMs are combined with conventional thermal insulation materials because they are either insufficient on their own or not effective at all, which poses a question for its usefulness despite of the associated environmental harm.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Phase Change Material (PCM) Technology in Textiles\n\n## What is PCM Technology?\n\nPhase Change Material (PCM) technology is used in various textiles, including those designed for winter wear. PCMs are special materials that can change their physical state, such as from liquid to solid, while maintaining a stable temperature during this transition. \n\nFor example:\n- When ice melts, it changes from solid to liquid and stays at a temperature of 0°C (32°F) until it has completely turned to water.\n- Similarly, water keeps a temperature of 100°C (212°F) during its phase change from liquid to steam when it boils.\n\nA cooling gel used on sore muscles also reflects this principle, maintaining a steady temperature as it transforms from a semi-solid to a liquid on the skin.\n\n## Key Factors Influencing PCM Effectiveness\n\nThe efficiency of PCM technology depends on important factors:\n\n1. **Activation Temperature**: This is the temperature at which the PCM starts to change its phase.\n2. **Duration of Temperature Maintenance**: How long the PCM can sustain a specific temperature during the phase change.\n\nFor instance, to function well in cold conditions, the material must activate at the right temperature and keep that temperature stable for a sufficient amount of time. Evaluating PCM'\''s effectiveness in textiles requires understanding these factors. \n\nUnfortunately, many companies mislead customers with catchy phrases like \"NASA used it for astronauts'\'' suits on the moon,\" instead of sharing this vital information.\n\n## Misunderstandings Around PCM Technology\n\nSuch marketing can mislead people into thinking that because the moon is very cold, PCM technology must also be effective on Earth. However, this is a classic example of the confusion caused by **Artificially Conceptual Values (ACVs)**. The truth is that the lunar environment is vastly different from that on Earth, and we do not know how much PCM is used in astronaut suits.\n\nUsing ice gel packs as an example, we can see how quantity matters. A large gel pack can provide long-lasting relief because it'\''s designed to be effective. In contrast, if a small amount of PCM were applied to a winter jacket, it would change phases too quickly, making it ineffective. Thus, just because a technology works in space does not mean it will work well on Earth.\n\n## Environmental Considerations\n\nTypically, PCMs in textiles are made from chemical materials sourced from petroleum, with paraffin wax being the most common type. These materials consist of long-chain hydrocarbons made up of 20 to 40 carbon atoms. Although these hydrocarbons have uses in water-resistant treatments, some, like C8, are banned in many areas due to health risks and their long-lasting presence in the environment.\n\nWhile PCMs are designed to stick to fabrics for a long time, they gradually wash off during cleaning and everyday use, which leads to environmental contamination.\n\n## Making Informed Textile Purchases\n\nWhen buying textiles containing PCMs, it’s crucial to understand the technical details mentioned above. A purchase should be justified only if the performance of the product meets your specific needs. \n\nIn practical applications, I'\''ve observed minimal benefits from PCM materials. Usually, PCMs are combined with traditional insulation due to their limited effectiveness on their own, raising questions about their value when considering their potential environmental impact.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What does PCM stand for in the context of textile technology?"; options = vec { "Performance Control Material"; "Phase Change Material"; "Pressure Change Mechanism"; "Phase Consistency Material" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is a critical factor that affects the effectiveness of PCM?"; options = vec { "The color of the textile"; "The activation temperature"; "The brand of the textile"; "The size of the garment" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which property does PCM maintain during its phase change?"; options = vec { "Variable temperature"; "Constant temperature"; "High viscosity"; "Low density" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What common chemical is primarily derived from petroleum used in PCM applications?"; options = vec { "Polyester"; "Paraffin wax"; "Cotton"; "Nylon" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Why might PCM technology not work effectively in real-world situations?"; options = vec { "It is too old-fashioned."; "It is often insufficient on its own."; "It is too expensive to produce."; "It is banned in many countries." }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "1.4.3";
    unit_title = "Heat-Generating Technology";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "1.4";
    head_unit_title = "Artificially Conceptual Value (ACV)";
    content = "One prominent example of ACVs involves a heat generating technology, often marketed with various other performance benefits, including several health benefits such as blood circulation enhancement, negative ion emission for improved mood, etc.  \nNature of ACVs and Analytical Skills of Consumers: After considering the earlier examples, readers might wonder why these apparent ACVs exist. In fact, there are many others that if I were to list and explain them all, this book would extend to additional hundreds of pages. Moreover, new ACVs will inevitably emerge as various organizations continue to find easy ways to appeal to consumers without making necessary efforts in truly effective technological advancements. I believe that the individuals and organizations making such claims often lack the depth of knowledge needed to fully understand the implications of their assertions. Unfortunately, this is a significant part of the dynamics of the consumer market today, once again highlighting the “unfortunate” nature of being a consumer.\nSince it is impractical to cover all existing and potential future ACVs, the primary goal of this book is to help readers develop their analytical skills to better identify and recognize these misleading claims, an extendable skill for evaluating various environmental claims too. \nMagical Technology?: Returning to the subject of the heat-generating technology, it can seem incredibly appealing, even almost magical, to believe that a piece of garment with the technology can offer such significant benefits, not only providing warmth but also improving blood circulation, mood enhancement, etc. Let us delve into the foundations of this technology.\nManufacturing Principles: Extremely small particles of various materials including ceramic, clay, carbon nanotube, etc., are added to and evenly distributed in a polymer tank where the polymer is in a molten state. Fibers are then extruded with these particles embedded in them. According to the companies which promote this technology, these particles alter the properties of the fibers with the proposed characteristics, creating the purported benefits. To substantiate these claims, they frequently use seemingly scientific data obtained from specifically designed tests such as the one explained below.\nTest Methods and Results: A common testing method involves comparing two fabric samples: one containing the purportedly beneficial particles and another without. These fabrics are placed at the bottom of a test chamber with a high-wattage light source positioned directly above them. The specific test I observed utilized a 500-watt Kawasaki lamp placed approximately 20 ~ 30 centimeters above the fabric samples. Temperature probes are inserted beneath the tested fabrics to monitor the temperature changes.\nWith the test setup complete, the light source is activated, and the fabrics absorb the heat energy from the bulb. The fabric containing the particles is claimed to exhibit a faster rate of temperature increase compared to the control fabric without the particles. In the observed test, a temperature difference of 10°C (18°F) was achieved within 30 ~ 40 minutes after the initiation.\nBases of Claims: The observed temperature rise in the fabric containing the particles is interpreted as evidence of the increased energy absorption from the light source. The more energy the material absorbs, the more it emits in the desired forms of energy such as infrared-, negative ion, etc. \nThis premise suggests that the garments incorporating this technology would function similarly during real-life use, absorbing energy from sunlight or body heat and subsequently releasing it to generate the advertised benefits. Companies making such claims may present additional supporting information, drawing analogies to related natural phenomena that supposedly produce similar effects. Examples might include experiencing health benefits while sunbathing or walking in a forest, etc. However, the validity of these analogies and the scientific basis for the claimed functionalities require critical evaluation.\nInterpretations and Truth\nSeveral key issues undermine the credibility of such claims regarding the enhanced heat generation and other associated functionalities.\nEnergy Level: A high-wattage light bulb generates an extremely high surface temperature and emits a level of energy far exceeding what humans can tolerate. For example, a 500-watt Kawasaki lamp becomes extremely hot, with a surface temperature easily reaching 400 ~ 500°C (752 ~ 932°F). At this temperature, it is impossible to put skin within 20 ~ 30 cm (8 ~ 12 in) distance of the bulb without immediate burns. This illustrates that the test conditions used to support these claims are not realistic. Companies may argue that such tests are stress tests, intended to demonstrate the effect under extreme conditions and that the results are proportionally applicable to lower temperatures, such as those from the sun or human body heat. To test this hypothesis, I conducted an experiment.\nExperiment: I took two pieces of fabric samples, one containing the particles and the other without, to the rooftop of a 10-story building on a hot sunny day, setting them up on the floor. The only principal difference from the laboratory test method was that the heat source was the sun instead of the 500-watt Kawasaki bulb. Although the conditions were not exactly same, my test was much closer to real-life scenarios. The rooftop was extremely hot due to the scorching sun, with an ambient temperature of 30°C (86°F) with no wind. After the setup, I monitored the temperature change on the two fabrics every 10 minutes. No difference was found between them for the duration of two hours, then I decided to stop.\nRelated Science: It is important to recognize that stress tests are typically performed to study a material'\''s behavior under accelerated and extreme conditions. These tests are inherently limited when it comes to directly applying the results to real-world scenarios under normal conditions. Assuming that the outcomes observed under a 500-watt Kawasaki lamp will occur in real-life situations is overly simplistic and scientifically inaccurate. It is clear that even the test conditions I used are extreme for most people, such as being exposed for two hours under the scorching sun at an ambient temperature of 30°C (86°F). Moreover, the energy level from the sun in my test is unlikely to be encountered during winter, when this technology is more relevant, while the energy level our body generates is nowhere near that of the sunlight, let alone a 500-watt Kawasaki lamp.\nHealth Benefits?: Another perspective on this claim involves its purported health benefits. In some forms of oriental medicine, infrared lamps are used alongside acupuncture to enhance the blood circulation of a patient and promote healing; An infrared emitting lamp with a typical temperature range between 200 ~ 300°C (392 ~ 572°F) is directed at the treated area with a certain distance and limited duration of exposure, where needles are typically inserted into the skin, supposedly amplifying the therapeutic effects. However, this situation is analogous to the earlier example, where the heat energy from the infrared lamp significantly exceeds what people typically experience with sunlight and body heat. \nMechanics and Improbability: Examining the mechanics of this technology reveals further issues. The quantity of the particles used to create these fibers is limited because the molten polymer must be extruded through extremely small holes – more information on this extrusion process presented in Chapter II: Synthesizing - Polymerization of Synthetic Fibers section. \nAdding the particles into a polymer melting tank is tricky because the small holes can be easily clogged up. Furthermore, the particles can settle to the bottom of the tank, which can create significant issues for continuous operations, such as fiber breakage and process failures. Typically, the particles do not exceed 10 ~ 15% of the weight of the molten polymer due to the concerns and process challenges. \nHaving had plenty of experiences in polymerization and extrusion processes in my career as textile engineer, I can attest that 10 ~ 15% is an extremely small quantity to create such magical benefits. Moreover, a large portion of the particles are encased within the fibers, surrounded by numerous polymer chains. For this technology to work, the sun’s rays or the body’s heat energy must penetrate the polymer structure, reach the particles, reflect enough energy, and then travel back through the structure to reach the skin. This scenario is, in my view, implausible even in science fiction.\n***\nIf this technology truly had such remarkable benefits, one could simply bring a piece of rock into their living room and sit on it to gain the same effects, as the rocks naturally contain a much higher concentration of the substances claimed to provide these benefits. If it were that simple, this practice would already be widespread across the world.\nCautions and Environmental Impacts: Not to be persuaded by these types of ACVs, cautionary approaches are necessary. If a company presents test reports indicating medical effects, such as negative ion emission or far-infrared emission similar to the heat generation test results reviewed earlier, it is important to verify whether these tests were conducted under real-life conditions and whether the effects are proven to be truly beneficial for human health.\nFrom an environmental perspective, the particles compromise the purity of the fibers and impede effective recycling, while the particles shed and contaminate, thereby negatively impacting the environment during manufacturing and consumption. \n***\nI’ve highlighted several examples of ACVs and performance features that, when fully considered, offer little or no practical benefit while potentially harming the environment. In fact, I regard some of these technologies and practices widely practiced in the industry as truly absurd.\nHistorically, profit-driven organizations have often prioritized profits over social responsibility and due diligence. Even in my own professional experiences, I have witnessed many instances of similarly natured corporate misconducts. \nConsumers often place too much trust in organizations around us, assuming they have thoroughly done their homework and offer products grounded with valid sciences. Unfortunately, time and time again, it has been proven that this trust may be misplaced and exploited. This underscores the vital importance of consumer education, a topic I will explore further in Chapter V: Solutions, in the Education, Education, and Education section.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Misleading Claims in Heat-Generating Technologies\n\n## Example of Apparent Consumer Value (ACVs)\n\nAn example of an apparent consumer value (ACV) is a heat-generating technology often advertised alongside various benefits, including improved blood circulation and mood enhancement through negative ion emission. \n\n## The Nature of ACVs and Consumer Analysis\n\nThese ACVs raise questions about their existence. Numerous ACVs exist, and more will continue to emerge as companies look for ways to attract consumers without genuine technological improvements. Many organizations making these claims may not fully grasp the implications of what they assert. This situation reflects a common challenge for today’s consumers.\n\nInstead of listing every ACV, this book aims to enhance readers'\'' analytical skills to identify and assess misleading claims, which will also apply to environmental claims.\n\n## The Appeal of Technology\n\nThe heat-generating technology may seem almost magical. It suggests that a garment could provide warmth and additional health benefits, such as better blood circulation. To understand this technology, let’s explore how it works.\n\n## Manufacturing Principles\n\nThis technology incorporates tiny particles, like ceramic, clay, or carbon nanotubes, into molten polymer. These particles are evenly mixed and embedded into the fibers during the manufacturing process. Companies claim these particles modify the fibers'\'' properties, leading to the advertised benefits. They often use scientific tests to support these assertions.\n\n## Testing Methods and Findings\n\nOne common testing method compares two fabric samples: one with the supposed beneficial particles and one without. The fabrics are placed in a test chamber under a high-wattage light source, such as a 500-watt lamp positioned above them. Temperature sensors are placed beneath the samples to monitor changes. \n\nWhen the lamp is turned on, the fabrics absorb heat. The fabric with the particles reportedly heats up faster than the control fabric. For instance, in one test, a temperature difference of 10°C (18°F) was noted within 30 to 40 minutes.\n\n## Basis of Claims\n\nThe increased temperature in the fabric with particles is claimed as evidence that it absorbs more energy, which could then be emitted as infrared rays or negative ions. The idea is that these garments would similarly absorb energy from sunlight or body heat to produce the claimed benefits. However, the validity of such claims requires careful scrutiny.\n\n## Critical Evaluation of Claims\n\nSeveral issues cast doubt on the credibility of these claims:\n- **Energy Levels:** A 500-watt bulb generates much higher temperatures than humans can tolerate, making the test conditions unrealistic. Companies may argue these are stress tests meant to reflect real-life scenarios, but this assumption is flawed.\n  \n### Experimental Investigation\n\nTo test this theory, I compared two fabric samples on a rooftop on a hot, sunny day, allowing them to absorb sunlight. Over two hours, no temperature difference was observed between the two fabrics, suggesting that real-life conditions differ significantly from those in laboratory tests.\n\n### Technical Realities\n\nStress tests are designed to assess materials under extreme conditions. It’s overly simplistic to assume that results from such tests will apply under normal conditions. My test conditions were extreme by everyday standards, and results would likely vary significantly in typical environments.\n\n## Health Claims Examination\n\nThe claims of health benefits from such technology bear scrutiny. In traditional medicine, infrared lamps are used under specific conditions to improve blood circulation. However, these lamps operate at temperatures much higher than what humans typically experience from sunlight or body heat.\n\n### Technical Challenges and Limitations\n\nThe quantity of particles in the fibers is limited due to manufacturing challenges. The polymer must be extruded through very small holes, which can clog easily. Usually, only a small percentage of particles (10-15%) can be incorporated. This limited amount raises questions about the feasibility of the claimed benefits. \n\nFor the technology to work as advertised, energy from the sun or body heat must penetrate the polymer, reach the particles, and then be emitted back to the skin. This scenario seems improbable.\n\n## Consumer Awareness and Environmental Impact\n\nConsumers should approach such claims with caution. If companies provide test results indicating health benefits, it’s essential to verify that these tests were conducted under realistic conditions and that the benefits are genuinely helpful.\n\nFrom an environmental perspective, added particles can reduce the recyclability of the fibers and create contamination during production and use.\n\n### Conclusion\n\nMany ACVs, when examined closely, reveal minimal real benefits and may harm the environment. Profit-driven motives often outweigh social responsibility in business practices, leading consumers to place unwarranted trust in these claims. To navigate this landscape, consumer education is crucial, a topic I will discuss in Chapter V: Solutions. ";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is one of the claimed benefits of the heat-generating technology mentioned in the content?"; options = vec { "Improved mood"; "Increased physical strength"; "Enhanced color vision"; "Rejuvenation of cells" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What is a common testing method for the fabric samples mentioned in the text?"; options = vec { "Microscopic analysis"; "Comparing temperature changes under a light source"; "Chemical composition testing"; "Durability testing under water" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "According to the text, what is a significant limitation of the testing methods used to validate claims?"; options = vec { "They are conducted in extreme conditions that are unrealistic"; "They require an excessive amount of fabric samples"; "They are too simple to produce accurate results"; "They often overlook environmental impacts" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "How much of the weight of the molten polymer do the particles typically account for, according to the author?"; options = vec { "5% - 10%"; "10% - 15%"; "20% - 25%"; "30% - 35%" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What caution does the author suggest regarding claims made by companies about their products?"; options = vec { "Believing all claims is essential for consumer trust"; "Verifying if tests are conducted under realistic conditions"; "Taking all test results at face value"; "Assuming that innovative companies always provide beneficial products" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "1.5.0";
    unit_title = "Other Important Textiles and Environmental Impacts (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "1.5";
    head_unit_title = "Other Important Textiles and Environmental Impacts";
    content = "In this subsection, I will explore a couple of textile technologies that can either greatly benefit or harm consumers while also having significant environmental impacts. \n";
    paraphrase = "## Exploring Textile Technologies: Benefits and Risks\n\nIn this section, I'\''ll look at two types of textile technologies that can either offer major advantages or pose risks to consumers. These technologies also have important effects on the environment.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the focus of the subsection?"; options = vec { "Exploring cooking technologies"; "Examining textile technologies"; "Analyzing electronic technologies"; "Investigating agricultural technologies" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How can textile technologies affect consumers?"; options = vec { "They can only benefit consumers."; "They can only harm consumers."; "They can either greatly benefit or harm consumers."; "They have no impact on consumers." }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What environmental aspect is mentioned in relation to textile technologies?"; options = vec { "Significant impact"; "Negligible impact"; "Positive impact"; "No impact at all" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "Textile technologies can lead to what type of consumer outcomes?"; options = vec { "Only financial outcomes"; "Social outcomes"; "Health outcomes"; "Both benefits and harms" }; answer = 3; }; record { question = "What type of consumers'\'' interests may be affected by textile technologies?"; options = vec { "Only wealthy consumers"; "Only environmentalists"; "All consumers"; "Only manufacturers" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "1.5.1";
    unit_title = "Home Textile & Energy Savings";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "1.5";
    head_unit_title = "Other Important Textiles and Environmental Impacts";
    content = "The modern world demands unprecedented amounts of energy, with technology advances such as artificial intelligence and electric vehicles further driving up the energy needs. Consequently, the importance of conserving energy has never been greater. With this pressing issue in mind, I introduce a simple, low-cost solution involving a textile application that can significantly reduce the worldwide energy consumption. \nConstruction and Energy Efficiency: Considerable efforts have been made to enhance the energy efficiency of our living environments, including homes, appliances, commercial buildings and maintenance practices, etc. Many governments offer incentive programs to encourage their citizens to adopt the materials and technologies that improve the energy efficiency of their living.  \nOne such example is the effort to reduce the rate of heat exchange between the interior and exterior of establishments. As briefly mentioned along with the CLO, the thermal efficiency, expressed as R-value, is measured and optimized on construction materials. Furthermore, thermal imaging techniques are used to identify the areas of high heat exchange for necessary improvements. \nWindows and Energy Loss: A defining trend in modern homes and buildings is the increased use of large windows for an aesthetic appeal and better views. Unfortunately, windows are inherently less efficient at preserving energy compared to walls, which are typically insulated with specialized materials. Fig.11 shows an example of excessive heat loss through window areas.\nFig.11 Heat Loss through Windows\nhttps://loe.org/shows/segmentprint.html?programID=12-P13-00046&segmentID=5   \nWhile many factors influence a building'\''s energy efficiency, such as total window areas, efficiencies of air conditioning or heating systems, orientation of building and windows relative to the sun, integrity of window frames and seals, etc., some studies have shown that a significant portion of energy, up to 70 ~ 90%, can be lost through the windows in thermally inefficient buildings.\nWindow Tint: Tinted glass windows can reduce heat gain during summer by blocking parts of sunlight, leading to lower cooling costs. However, this approach has its limitations. Many people value window transparency and are hesitant to darken their windows too much, which reduces potential energy savings. Additionally, tinted windows can block beneficial heat gain in winter, increasing heating demand.\nThermal Break: Some newer window frames are designed with two or more layers of glass, separated by gaps that act as a thermal break, helping reduce energy loss in winter and heat gain in summer. While this solution can improve energy efficiency, it is often costly, potentially requiring thousands of dollars to replace existing window frames, even for small homes. For large commercial buildings with older window frames, retrofitting can be nearly impossible. Although this technology can reduce energy bills in both summer and winter, its effectiveness is somewhat limited by the laws of thermodynamics: larger air pockets between the glass panes transfer energy more efficiently than smaller, compartmentalized pockets, making it less thermally efficient overall despite the high costs.\nOther Means: Some people turn to solutions like window films or bubble wrap to save energy, particularly during winter in colder climates. However, these options require considerable effort for seasonal installation and removal with annually recurring costs while incurring environmental burden from the used and disposed materials.\n***\nAlthough the measures above can help conserve energy, combining them with, or even relying solely on, “thermally insulated curtains” can greatly enhance the thermal efficiency of homes and commercial buildings. \nThermally Insulated Curtains \nThe thermally insulated curtains are a cost-effective and simple solution suitable for any homes or commercial buildings, regardless of the age of construction or window size and location. These curtains are made with specifically designed synthetic non-woven fabrics, which are engineered to provide optimal thermal efficiencies while using a minimal quantity of textile materials.\nDuring the manufacturing process of such non-woven fabrics, numerous tiny air pockets are created, forming an effective thermal barrier year-round. In summer, these curtains minimize heat gain from sunlight, creating a cooling effect, while in winter, they minimize heat loss from heating systems. Although heavy blackout curtains can provide similar benefits, optimally engineered thermally insulated curtains offer superior thermal efficiency, leading to a better energy conservation while using less textile materials.\nThese thermally efficient curtains can effectively address all forms of the heat exchanges in a building, namely conduction, convection and radiation. In general, the effects they create are far superior to any other methods mentioned earlier. \nCommercial Availability: Despite their significant benefits, affordability, and flexibility, these thermally insulated curtains are difficult to find in the market. A USA retailer briefly offered them many years ago, but the product line was discontinued due to a low popularity and several logistical challenges associated with the product for the retailer. For example, these curtains took up considerably more spaces in their retail stores and warehouses compared to their non-insulated counterparts. Although this difference is negligible once installed in homes and buildings, the increased retail space requirement and associated challenges combined with a low popularity among consumers likely influenced the retailer’s decision to discontinue the product.\nConsumer Awareness: In my view, two main issues contributed to the unsuccessful market deployment of these curtains at the time.\nFirstly, had the consumers been made aware of the potential savings with hundreds or even thousands of dollars in electricity bills and significant environmental benefits, many more would have purchased the product. A comparable example is the widespread adoption of solar panels on homes and buildings, where homeowners are willing to invest thousands or tens of thousands of dollars while enduring significant renovation work during the construction of their living quarters. \nSecondly, the increased storage spaces and handling costs for the retailer could have been easily offset by higher price tags. If consumers had understood the clear benefits, many would have been willing to pay a premium; Based on my industry experience and knowledge of textile goods'\'' cost structures, the additional cost to consumers for these products would likely be only a few dollars. Furthermore, the logistical challenges could have been addressed with a vacuum packaging, reducing the product'\''s volume and making it comparable to, or even smaller than, other heavy blackout curtains. While vacuum packaging might slightly reduce the thermal efficiency of the product, a careful engineering can minimize this impact.\nBased on this analysis, I believe the failure of the retailer’s thermally insulated curtain program was a result of poor execution in promoting the clear benefits both economically and environmentally. If any retailers, curtain brands, or related businesses are reading this and interested in exploring this concept, I would be more than happy to assist with product engineering, logistics, and even some marketing ideas.  \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Energy Conservation and Thermally Insulated Curtains\n\nThe modern world has a huge demand for energy, mainly due to advancements in technology like artificial intelligence and electric vehicles. As a result, saving energy has become more important than ever. This document discusses a simple and affordable solution involving a textile application that can help reduce energy use globally.\n\n## Construction and Energy Efficiency\nSignificant efforts are being made to improve energy efficiency in our living spaces. This includes homes, appliances, commercial buildings, and maintenance practices. Many governments provide incentives to encourage their citizens to use materials and technologies that enhance energy efficiency in their lives.\n\nOne effective approach focuses on reducing heat exchange between the inside and outside of buildings. The effectiveness of construction materials is measured using an R-value, which indicates thermal efficiency. Thermal imaging can also identify areas with high heat loss, highlighting where improvements are needed.\n\n## Windows and Energy Loss\nModern architecture often features large windows for visual appeal and natural light. However, windows are generally less energy-efficient compared to insulated walls. Research suggests that in poorly insulated buildings, around 70% to 90% of energy can be lost through windows.\n\n### Window Tint\nTinted windows help to block sunlight, reducing heat during summer and thus lowering cooling costs. However, many people prefer transparent windows, which limits the potential energy savings. Tinted windows can also prevent beneficial heat gain during winter, leading to higher heating needs.\n\n### Thermal Break\nNewer window designs use multiple layers of glass separated by spaces, known as thermal breaks, to reduce winter heat loss and summer heat gain. While these improvements can enhance energy efficiency, they can be expensive to implement, often costing thousands of dollars, especially in older commercial buildings.\n\n### Other Means\nSome individuals use DIY solutions like window films or bubble wrap to save energy during winter, but these methods can be labor-intensive and create waste.\n\n## Thermally Insulated Curtains\nWhile the solutions mentioned above can assist in energy conservation, using \"thermally insulated curtains\" is a highly effective method for enhancing energy efficiency in homes and commercial spaces.\n\n### What Are Thermally Insulated Curtains?\nThese curtains are a cost-effective solution suitable for any building, regardless of its age or window specifications. Made from specifically engineered synthetic non-woven fabrics, they provide excellent thermal efficiency using minimal material. During manufacturing, tiny air pockets are created, forming an effective thermal barrier throughout the year. \n\n- **In Summer:** They reduce heat gain from sunlight, providing a cooling effect.\n- **In Winter:** They minimize heat loss from heating systems.\n\nWhile heavy blackout curtains can offer some advantages, thermally insulated curtains are superior in energy conservation while requiring less material.\n\n### Effectiveness\nThese curtains address heat exchange through conduction, convection, and radiation more effectively than other methods previously discussed.\n\n### Commercial Availability\nDespite their numerous benefits, thermally insulated curtains are not widely available in the market. A retailer in the USA previously offered them, but sales were low due to logistical challenges and storage space requirements. This led to the discontinuation of the product line.\n\n### Consumer Awareness\nThe lack of success in the market can be attributed to two main factors:\n\n1. **Lack of Awareness:** If consumers had known about the potential savings in energy bills amounting to hundreds or thousands of dollars and the associated environmental benefits, more people would have purchased these curtains.\n   \n2. **Cost and Storage Issues:** Although these curtains are bulkier, retailers could have adjusted prices to accommodate higher storage costs. If consumers had been made aware of their advantages, many would have been willing to pay a bit more for the product. \n\n## Conclusion\nThe failure of thermally insulated curtains to gain market traction stemmed from inadequate promotion of their economic and environmental benefits. If any retailers or manufacturers are interested in exploring this product further, I would gladly offer assistance in product design, logistics, and marketing strategies. \n\nBy focusing on these curtains, we can make strides toward better energy conservation and a more sustainable future.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the main focus of the text?"; options = vec { "The importance of aesthetics in home design"; "The need for energy conservation solutions"; "The rise of artificial intelligence technologies"; "The efficiency of different window types" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What energy-saving feature do thermally insulated curtains offer?"; options = vec { "They enhance air conditioning efficiency"; "They reduce heat gain in summer and heat loss in winter"; "They provide better window views"; "They are more aesthetically pleasing than regular curtains" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Why did the retailer discontinue thermally insulated curtains?"; options = vec { "They were too expensive to manufacture"; "They took up too much space and were not popular"; "There was a lack of consumer interest in energy conservation"; "The competition from blackout curtains was too strong" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How do tinted windows contribute to energy savings?"; options = vec { "By improving window transparency"; "By blocking parts of sunlight to reduce heat gain"; "By preventing all heat loss"; "By increasing window aesthetic appeal" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What was one suggested way to improve the marketability of thermally insulated curtains?"; options = vec { "Lower the price significantly"; "Increase the size for better visibility"; "Vacuum packaging to reduce storage space"; "Focus on marketing for aesthetic appeal" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "1.5.2";
    unit_title = "Harmful Face Masks for Health and Environment";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "1.5";
    head_unit_title = "Other Important Textiles and Environmental Impacts";
    content = "Even well before the COVID-19 pandemic, many people in Asia had recognized the importance of wearing face masks when facing respiratory viral infections due to several previous health crises like the avian flu, the H1N1 influenza, the MERS, etc. Additionally, masks were commonly worn as a protection against severe air pollutions in heavily industrialized regions. So, when the COVID-19 emerged, people instinctively reached for masks in their closets or from local stores.\nFor many, it was surprising when Dr. Anthony Fauci, the head of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID) in US, initially stated that masks were unnecessary for the general public. He emphasized the importance of reserving masks for healthcare workers and suggested that while masks might offer some protection, they were not essential for those who were not infected or caring for the infected.\nThen, several weeks later, the guidance was reversed, and the public was urged to wear masks during all social interactions. While there is an ongoing debate, albeit by some minority opinions, about the effectiveness of face masks in preventing the spread of respiratory viral infections and, also acknowledging my lack of expertise in the medical science, I refrain from drawing any conclusions about whether wearing face masks is right or wrong in this discussion. However, based on the conventional understanding promoted by the authorities around the world after a short period following the breakout and other similar viral outbreaks of the past, the initial response from Dr. Fauci appears to have been mistaken.\nImportance of Developing Analytical Skills: In my view, prioritizing healthcare workers'\'' protection was something most of our society would have readily supported. However, providing accurate information to the public is equally critical in the efforts to mitigate the crises of this nature. The initial lack of understanding in some countries about the asymptomatic transmission of the COVID-19 stood in a stark contrast to the immediate mask-wearing response in many Asian countries.\nThis incident highlights that even top authorities can make mistakes. In fact, there have been many other examples of such occurrences, some of which will be discussed later in this chapter and in Chapter V: Solutions, specifically in the United Efforts section. These examples remind us that blindly following authorities may not always lead to the best outcomes, especially when it comes to matters as crucial as our health and safety.\nWhile I do not aim to promote conspiracy theories or encourage those who spread misinformation and provoke unwarranted fear, we must develop analytical skills needed to recognize flawed guidance. In such situations, it is crucial to approach the issues with a scientific and analytical mindset and, at times, rely on common sense. While expert advice is invaluable, applying critical thinking and questioning authority on questionable guidance is key to managing our lives more effectively.\nCopper Particle Masks\nThe lengthy prelude to this subsection serves to alert people about a health product that poses significant risks. \nIntroduction of Dangerous Mask: Recently, I was in an online meeting with an Asian manufacturer regarding a specific technology I was seeking. During the call, I learned that the company was involved in various other businesses, including face masks. After completing the discussions on the planed subject, the manufacturer began promoting a specific mask product, which featured copper nanoparticles. As they showcased a sample on the camera, I noticed a diluted yellowish tint evenly distributed across the mask, indicating the presence of copper in small particle forms.\nFrom a particular research project during my tenure as research and development engineer in South Korea, I gained considerable insights about the concept behind this product: the copper particles are intended to kill microorganisms by releasing electrically charged ions that destroy viruses and bacterial cells in contact. Silver has similar properties, but it is much more expensive. The manufacturer claimed that these masks were quite popular with customers in many countries including USA, Japan and many countries in Europe.  \nSignificant Concerns and Flag: However, my experience in the project in South Korea immediately raised serious concerns on this mask product. Metal particles, such as copper and silver, cannot be permanently fixed to fibers and fabric structures. In fact, a significant quantity of these particles is released into the air during use, and the release quantity depends on how they were impregnated into the material structures during manufacturing.  \nResearch Project: In the research project, I was tasked with developing acrylic fibers impregnated with copper particles to reduce static electricity that people experience when putting on or removing acrylic sweaters. The idea was that the metallic ions in copper would help dissipate the stagnant electricity. From that experience, I learned that, despite my best efforts to keep the process clean, copper particles contaminated the entire laboratory surfaces. When I swiped my fingers across any surface, I observed a greenish-yellowish tint, typical of the copper particles in high concentration, on my skin.    \nDanger and Potential Health Impacts: Placing such particles in the path of our breath is dangerous. It is not difficult to imagine that these particles can be easily inhaled through the mouth and nose while breathing. Once inhaled, they can reach organs and bloodstreams in the body. For instance, asbestos, now banned in many countries after extensive research, causes lung cancer because its fibrous particles scratch and damage lung tissues. Metals like copper, being potentially harder than the asbestos, could inflict even more damage inside the body. Additionally, metals can trigger other unknown reactions due to their heightened chemical reactivities.\nAfter my meeting with the manufacturer, I searched the ChatGPT, which resulted in the following description: “During the COVID-19 pandemic, the FDA issued Emergency Use Authorizations (EUAs) to facilitate the availability of various types of face masks, including those with antimicrobial materials like copper and silver, to help prevent the spread of the virus.” \nAlthough I immediately advised the manufacturer against selling the mask product during the meeting, they likely believed that the FDA’s approval carried higher authority and validity than my anecdote and assessment for the health risks.  \nVariables and Environmental Impacts: If a mask is made with copper or silver in a strong filament yarn form factor, it could serve its intended purpose as antimicrobial with a lower health risk, as the continuous filaments are much less likely to shed particles during use. However, the masks made with copper or silver in such form factors as particles or fibers significantly increase the risk of the particle inhalation. In my research project, I embedded fine copper particles into molten acrylic polymer in polymerization process and then extruded it into fibers. This process is one of the most secure methods of embedding fine particles into various forms of polymer structures. However, even with this secure method, the resulting fibers still contained considerable quantities of copper particles on their surfaces, which easily transferred onto my skin when touched.\nReaders, please do not wear the face masks made with any particles regardless of its kind. Inhaling the particles can pose more harm than any potential benefit. \nEnvironmentally, small particles of metals with their inherently heightened chemical reactivity will persist in the environment and create significantly harmful effects on all living organisms. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Face Masks and Their Risks\n\n## Importance of Masks in Asia Before COVID-19\n\nEven before the COVID-19 pandemic, many people in Asia understood the importance of wearing face masks to protect themselves from respiratory viral infections. This awareness came from experiencing previous health crises, such as avian flu, H1N1 influenza, and MERS. Additionally, masks were commonly worn in heavily industrialized areas to guard against severe air pollution. Thus, when COVID-19 emerged, people quickly turned to their stored masks or purchased new ones.\n\n## Changing Guidance on Mask Use\n\nInitially, Dr. Anthony Fauci, the head of the National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (NIAID) in the United States, stated that masks were not necessary for the general public. He believed it was more important to reserve masks for healthcare workers and suggested that while masks might offer some protection, they were not crucial for individuals not infected or not caring for infected patients.\n\nHowever, weeks later, this guidance changed, and the public was advised to wear masks in all social situations. There continues to be debate about the effectiveness of face masks in preventing the spread of respiratory viruses. While I do not have medical expertise, the reversal of Dr. Fauci'\''s initial advice seems to indicate an error in understanding the situation. \n\n## The Need for Analytical Skills\n\nI believe it is important to prioritize the protection of healthcare workers, which is something most people would agree on. However, providing accurate information to the public is equally vital in managing health crises. The initial lack of understanding in some countries about asymptomatic transmission of COVID-19 contrasted sharply with the immediate adoption of mask-wearing in many Asian nations.\n\nThis situation highlights that even reputable authorities can make mistakes. There are many instances of this that will be discussed later in this chapter and in Chapter V: Solutions. These examples remind us that following authorities without question may not always yield the best outcomes, especially regarding health and safety.\n\nWhile I do not want to promote conspiracy theories or misinformation, it is essential to develop the analytical skills necessary to identify flawed guidance. This means approaching public health issues with a scientific mindset and applying critical thinking when evaluating expert advice. Questioning questionable guidance is crucial for managing our health effectively.\n\n## Risks of Certain Mask Types\n\n### Introduction to Dangerous Masks\n\nRecently, during an online meeting with an Asian manufacturer, I learned about a specific mask containing copper nanoparticles. The mask had a noticeable yellowish tint due to the copper particles. The idea behind using copper is that it can kill microorganisms by releasing charged ions that destroy viruses and bacteria. While silver has similar properties and is more expensive, copper masks became popular in various countries.\n\n### Serious Concerns About Copper Masks\n\nHowever, my background as a research and development engineer in South Korea raised significant worries about this type of mask. Metal particles like copper cannot be permanently fixed to the mask material, meaning many particles can be released into the air during use. \n\nIn a prior research project, I attempted to create acrylic fibers embedded with copper particles to reduce static electricity. I found that despite efforts to maintain cleanliness, copper particles contaminated surfaces throughout the lab. When I touched surfaces, I noticed a greenish-yellow tint on my skin, signalling a high concentration of copper particles.\n\n### Health Risks of Inhaling Copper Particles\n\nInhaling particles from these masks poses serious health risks. Just like asbestos, which is now banned in many places due to its link to lung cancer, inhaled copper particles can damage lung tissue and other organs. Metals can also provoke unknown reactions due to their high chemical reactivity.\n\nAfter my discussion with the manufacturer, I learned that the FDA had authorized masks with antimicrobial materials like copper during the pandemic, which might have influenced their confidence in the product. \n\n### Environmental Impact\n\nIf a mask is made with copper or silver as strong filament yarns, the health risks decrease, as these materials are less likely to shed particles. However, if they are made with copper or silver in smaller particles or fibers, the inhalation risk significantly increases. In my research, even the best methods for embedding copper particles still resulted in some particles remaining on the fiber surfaces.\n\n**Final Recommendation:** \n\nI strongly advise against wearing face masks made with any kind of particles, including metallic particles. The risk of inhaling these particles outweighs any potential benefits. Furthermore, small metal particles can persist in the environment and may harm living organisms.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What prompted many people in Asia to wear face masks even before the COVID-19 pandemic?"; options = vec { "Severe air pollution"; "The emergence of COVID-19"; "Fashion trends"; "Government regulations" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "According to Dr. Anthony Fauci, what was the initial stance on mask-wearing for the general public?"; options = vec { "Masks were essential for everyone"; "Masks were only needed for healthcare workers"; "Masks were unnecessary for the general public"; "Masks should be worn at all times" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What was a major concern regarding masks with copper nanoparticles?"; options = vec { "They are stylish but ineffective"; "They release metal particles into the air"; "They are too expensive for consumers"; "They have no antimicrobial properties" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which of the following materials was mentioned as having similar properties to copper but more expensive?"; options = vec { "Gold"; "Cotton"; "Silver"; "Plastic" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What potential risk does inhaling copper particles pose according to the text?"; options = vec { "No risk at all"; "Skin irritation"; "Lung damage and unknown chemical reactions"; "Allergic reactions" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "2.0";
    unit_title = "“Fast Fashion” (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I: Consumers, Be Aware and Beware!";
    head_unit_id = "2";
    head_unit_title = ". “Fast fashion”";
    content = "Although this topic aligns with the theme of the previous section, Unfortunate Consumers, I felt it necessary to create a dedicated section due to the widespread misconceptions surrounding it and its importance in key environmental initiatives. \n“The term, “fast fashion” was first popularized in a New York Times article in 1989 to describe retail store Zara’s first opening in the United States” – CNN \nhttps://www.cnn.com/style/what-is-fast fashion-sustainable-fashion/index.html   \nSince then, the concept has rapidly gained global attention and is now frequently used as a symbol of various environmental issues associated with textile goods and organizations, often based on unscientific and vague notions. \nDisagreement: The term \"fast fashion\" is encapsulated in the quotation marks throughout this book, reflecting my disagreement regarding its conventional usage and definition. This reservation is rooted in my background in textile engineering and decades of industry experience, which provide me with a deeper understanding of the complexities of textile production, quality, and market dynamics than most in the public, media, environmental advocacy groups and activists, including the New York Times reporter who created it. \nVarying Perceptions: The ambiguity surrounding the concept of \"fast fashion\" is evident in the varied public perceptions of different apparel brands in the market. Some consumers may categorize a particular brand as \"fast fashion,\" while others may not, highlighting the subjective nature of this classification. These divergent opinions often arise from the differing interpretations of various aspects of business operations, which may not necessarily relate to the quality or durability of the goods categorized as “fast fashion”.\nAs a habit of a person, deeply involved in the textile industry, I often conduct informal surveys, asking people around me on various subjects related to textiles. One such example is to ask them to classify well-known brands such as Lululemon, Adidas, Nike, etc., as either \"fast fashion\" or not. The responses I receive are notably diverse, with no clear consensus emerging for any particular brand. This variability in people’s perception extends even to some brands, which are considered as “luxury” brands by a large portion of the public, primarily due to the high retail values of their merchandises, surprisingly classified by some as \"fast fashion\". \nUneducated Notions: Given the vagueness, the public might recognize that the original coining of the term \"fast fashion\" in the 1989 New York Times article may have been based on uninformed notions by the author, rather than a clear and scientific understanding of the complexities of textile quality. \nIn light of this, I present several points for consideration concerning this situation in the following discussions. These deeper examinations will reflect my view of the term as more of a social phenomenon than the accurate measure of textile quality and durability, underscoring the importance of a more nuanced understanding of textile materials and their environmental impacts.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Fast Fashion: A Refined Perspective\n\nThis topic builds on the previous section, \"Unfortunate Consumers,\" but I believe it’s important to dedicate space to address common misconceptions and the significance of fast fashion in environmental conversations.\n\n## What is Fast Fashion?\n\nThe phrase “fast fashion” was first introduced in a **New York Times** article in 1989 to describe the launch of Zara’s first store in the United States. Since then, it has gained worldwide attention, often representing various environmental concerns related to clothing and the fashion industry. However, this concept is often based on vague and unscientific ideas.\n\n## My Stance on Fast Fashion\n\nI use quotation marks around \"fast fashion\" throughout this discussion because I disagree with how it is commonly defined. My perspective is shaped by my background in textile engineering and many years of industry experience. This background gives me a more comprehensive understanding of textile production, quality, and market dynamics than what is typically presented by the media and environmental advocates, including the reporter from the **New York Times** who coined the term.\n\n## Different Views on Fashion Brands\n\nThe idea of fast fashion is confusing because people see different clothing brands in varying ways. For example, some might label a brand like Lululemon or Adidas as \"fast fashion,\" while others might disagree. This inconsistency shows how subjective this classification can be and reflects differing interpretations of business practices, which may not directly relate to the quality or durability of the products labeled as \"fast fashion.\"\n\nAs someone who works in textiles, I often informally survey people about how they categorize well-known brands. When I ask if brands like Lululemon, Adidas, or Nike fall into the \"fast fashion\" category, I receive a wide range of opinions, with no clear agreement on any brand. Interestingly, some brands viewed as \"luxury\" by many due to their high prices are sometimes classified as \"fast fashion\" by others.\n\n## Misunderstanding in the Public Perception\n\nDue to the confusion surrounding the term, it seems that the original use of \"fast fashion\" in the 1989 **New York Times** article may have stemmed from uninformed ideas rather than a solid scientific understanding of textile quality. \n\nWith this context in mind, I will present several points to consider in the following discussions. I believe that the term \"fast fashion\" should be seen more as a social phenomenon rather than a precise measure of textile quality and durability. This highlights the need for a more nuanced understanding of textile materials and their environmental effects.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What year was the term '\''fast fashion'\'' first popularized?"; options = vec { "1985"; "1989"; "1995"; "2000" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is the author'\''s profession that informs their perspective on '\''fast fashion'\''?"; options = vec { "Environmental activist"; "Fashion designer"; "Textile engineer"; "Consumer advocate" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "How does the author perceive the classification of brands as '\''fast fashion'\''?"; options = vec { "It is universally agreed upon"; "It is based on objective criteria"; "It is subjective and varies among consumers"; "It is based solely on brand value" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What does the author suggest about the original definition of '\''fast fashion'\''?"; options = vec { "It is scientifically accurate"; "It was well-informed"; "It is rooted in uninformed notions"; "It reflects a deep understanding of textile quality" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What does the author intend to provide in the following discussions about '\''fast fashion'\''?"; options = vec { "A list of fast fashion brands"; "A comparison of prices"; "A deeper examination of textile quality and environmental impact"; "A history of fashion trends" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "2.1.0";
    unit_title = "Ambiguity in Definition";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "2.1";
    head_unit_title = "Ambiguity in Definition";
    content = "From the perspective of the New York Times reporter, all garments in Zara’s stores would be categorized as \"fast fashion,\" regardless of material choices, durability, or other factors related to the quality. This label comes with several associated perceptions and environmental concerns including:   \nPerceptions\n\"Fast fashion\" goods are produced quickly and have shorter lifecycles due to poor quality.  \n“Fast fashion” goods are made with cheap materials, a notion frequently associated with synthetic fibers\n“Fast fashion” goods persist in nature for too long, a notion once again associated with synthetic fibers\n“Fast fashion” goods do not last long in consumption\n“Fast fashion” goods create microplastic pollution from synthetic fibres\n“Fast fashion” goods lead to overconsumption \n“Fast fashion” increases carbon footprint due to reliance on air shipments rather than ocean transport \nFurthermore, the opposite concept is often described as “slow fashion” and represent more favourable images consumers form towards certain materials, merchandises, brands, forms of operations, etc. \nExpanded Interpretations: In addition, the term \"fast fashion\" has acquired connotations beyond its original meaning, often encompassing broader social aspects of a company'\''s operations. For instance, some individuals automatically associate overseas production utilizing lower labor costs with \"fast fashion\", regardless of the actual quality of the goods produced.\nConversely, the varying interpretation of \"fast fashion\" appears to blur the boundaries between the product-specific characteristics in quality measurements and the broader concept of ESG (Environmental, Social, and Governance) practices within a company'\''s overall operations. While some may argue that this broader definition provides a more comprehensive representation of a company or brand, there are drawbacks to such an expansive interpretation, particularly, in the perspectives of making more effective environmental efforts.\nMixed Values and Discrepancies: For instance, the quality, durability, and speed of factory-to-market for a particular product can be managed through specific operational strategies, which may be distinct from an organization'\''s commitment to social and environmental responsibilities. If a company aims to align with consumers’ notion that synthetic fiber products are inferior in quality and longevity, they might simply substitute natural fibers for synthetic ones. The perceived improvement in the longevity from the switch would lead equally to the perceived improvement in sustainability and this action can be executed independently of the company'\''s efforts to fulfill its other responsibilities.\nCombining these diverse concepts under a single term, therefore, may impede the public'\''s ability to accurately evaluate matters related to the \"fast fashion\" and its overall environmental impacts. The following subsections will explore how ambiguous notions of the \"fast fashion\" can potentially lead to unintended consequences for environmental and sustainability efforts.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Fast Fashion\n\n## Overview\nAccording to a New York Times reporter, all clothes sold at Zara are considered \"fast fashion,\" regardless of how they are made or how long they last. This term comes with certain ideas and worries about the environment, including:\n\n### Key Concerns About Fast Fashion\n- **Quick Production & Short Lifespan:** Fast fashion items are made quickly and tend to fall apart sooner due to lower quality.\n- **Cheap Materials:** These goods often use inexpensive materials, which are commonly synthetic fibers.\n- **Environmental Persistence:** Many fast fashion items do not break down easily in nature, which is again linked to synthetic fibers.\n- **Short Use Span:** Fast fashion garments wear out quickly when used by consumers.\n- **Microplastic Pollution:** The synthetic materials can contribute to microplastic pollution.\n- **Overconsumption:** Fast fashion encourages people to buy more than they need.\n- **Increased Carbon Footprint:** Fast fashion often relies on air transport, which emits more carbon dioxide compared to ocean shipping.\n\n### Slow Fashion\nIn contrast, \"slow fashion\" refers to a more positive view of certain materials, products, brands, and business practices. \n\n## Broader Interpretations\nThe term \"fast fashion\" now carries meanings that extend beyond just the quality of the items. For example, people often link it with overseas manufacturing and lower labor costs, regardless of how well the products are made.\n\nOn another note, the different ways people interpret \"fast fashion\" can confuse the distinction between the specific quality of products and broader Environmental, Social, and Governance (ESG) practices within a company. While a broader view might paint a fuller picture of a company, it can also complicate efforts to improve environmental practices.\n\n## Mixed Values and Potential Issues\nThe qualities of a product—like its quality, durability, and speed from production to store—can often be influenced by specific strategies that don’t necessarily relate to a company’s environmental or social responsibilities. For instance, a brand that recognizes that synthetic fibers are seen as lower quality might switch to natural fibers. While this change may enhance the fabric'\''s durability and improve perceived sustainability, it does not automatically mean the company is committed to broader social or environmental goals.\n\nBy merging diverse ideas under one label, it can make it harder for people to understand \"fast fashion\" and its effects on the environment. The following sections will delve deeper into how the vague definitions of \"fast fashion\" may unintentionally affect sustainability efforts.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What primary label does the New York Times reporter use to categorize garments in Zara'\''s stores?"; options = vec { "Eco-friendly fashion"; "Slow fashion"; "Fast fashion"; "Luxury fashion" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which of the following is NOT associated with '\''fast fashion'\'' according to the content?"; options = vec { "Microplastic pollution"; "Overconsumption"; "Higher quality materials"; "Increased carbon footprint" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What term is often used to describe the opposite of '\''fast fashion'\''?"; options = vec { "Ethical fashion"; "Slow fashion"; "Sustainable fashion"; "Traditional fashion" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How does the concept of '\''fast fashion'\'' expand beyond product quality?"; options = vec { "Through higher retail prices"; "By focusing on sustainability only"; "By encompassing broader social aspects and labor practices"; "By promoting local production" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What risk is associated with combining various concepts under the term '\''fast fashion'\''?"; options = vec { "Improving customer satisfaction"; "Misleading public evaluation of sustainability efforts"; "Encouraging more natural fiber use"; "Increasing production speed" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "2.2.0";
    unit_title = "Manufacturing Factors – Material, Quality and Cost";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "2.2";
    head_unit_title = "Manufacturing Factors – Material, Quality and Cost";
    content = "This subsection begins by exploring the concept of \"Quality\", a term often misunderstood in the context of \"fast fashion.\"\nDefinition of Quality – Oxford Languages\nthe standard of something as measured against other things of a similar kind; the degree of excellence of something.\na distinctive attribute or characteristic possessed by someone or something.\nThe definition emphasizes the \"measurable\" attributes or characteristics, which contrasts with ambiguity often associated with the products or brands labeled as \"fast fashion\". Therefore, using specific metrics commonly applied in evaluating textile quality provides a more scientific basis for assessing the true quality of the materials and goods associated with “fast fashion” and “slow fashion”.\nWhile \"quality\" can refer to many different factors, the following analyses focus on the material aspects of natural and synthetic fibers, as well as their derivatives like yarns, fabrics, and finished products. For instance, if a seamline breaks, it is more likely due to poor workmanship or the weakness of the sewing thread, rather than the fabric'\''s strength. Although a consumer may interpret this as a sign of “poor” quality, this discussion distinguishes the scientifically measurable durability of the fabric from other potential causes of failure. Here, I present these quality factors with a focus on the material considerations.\nStrength: Synthetic fibers are generally five to ten times stronger than natural fibers - A detailed analysis of this topic will be presented in the section, 3.2.1 Strength Factor and Dust Quantity, with supporting scientific data. This strength advantage means that products made from synthetic fibers are better able to withstand forces such as abrasion, tensile stress, tear strength, stretching, etc., key factors that contribute to the failure of textile goods. The higher strength of synthetic fibers directly enhances the durability of the resulting materials, including yarns, fabrics, and finished products, compared to those made from natural fibers.\nDurability Factors: While this is a straightforward scientific fact, it can become more complex when different care methods are applied to different items, as previously reviewed in this chapter. In a brief recap, home laundry involves water usage and significant physical forces from the washing mechanisms, leading to accelerated material fatigue and degrade whereas drycleaning does not involve such forces. Additionally, interactions between the chemicals contained in textiles, water and detergents can increase the risk of color fading. Although synthetic materials generally withstand these physical and chemical forces exceptionally well, comparing home-washed items with dry-cleaned ones is not an accurate measure of their overall quality and durability. \nContradictory Perceptions: Furthermore, contradictory perceptions exist regarding \"fast fashion\" goods: “They do not last long in consumption, but last too long in nature.” \nScientifically, if a material lasts long in nature, it typically reflects a quality that also offers longevity in consumption. Therefore, an analytical mind can draw a conclusion that the perception, contradictory to the underlying science, may be created by different metrics such as varying measuring sticks with subjective quality references. Conversely, there is a significant gap in the public perception of quality and designations of certain brands as \"fast fashion\" or \"slow fashion.\"\n***\nI recognize that many readers may not yet grasp the full extent of the scope presented so far in this discussion. It is natural as textile quality and manufacturing are more complex than most people think. With the tangible examples in the following discussions, the scope will become clearer.  \nComplex Manufacturing and Market Structures\nThroughout my career as textile engineer, I have visited countless factories involved in every stage of textile manufacturing, from raw materials to finished goods. These experiences have shown me that it is not uncommon to find a single factory producing goods for both \"slow fashion\" and \"fast fashion\" brands simultaneously, using identical raw materials, craftsmanship, and processes.\nSimilar Qualities with Different Prices: These goods are essentially of similar quality, if not identical, but their price tags can differ considerably based on the brands in question and their retail strategies. For instance, one brand may sell its products in an upscale storefront, while another sells online with large differences in the prices between the two. Without knowing the origins of these goods, many consumers may distinguish them as either “fast fashion” or “slow fashion”, “good quality” or “poor quality”.  This example illustrates the complexities of manufacturing and market structures which most consumers do not fully understand, yet it can lead to improper judgements on the quality of goods, leading to actions which impact environmental sustainability.  \nDifferent Qualities with Different Prices: Different scenarios do exist, which correspond more to consumers’ general expectations for a higher quality in relation with a higher price in retail. For instance, a brand implements rigorous quality control programs to ensure that their products respect safety and quality standards for its workers and consumers. This may include avoiding harmful chemicals, which can be otherwise used to enhance visual appeal or reduce production costs, among many other operational measures taken by brands and manufacturers. Such approach requires a system with necessary resources, such as experienced personnel and effective operational structures. This responsible approach adds to the cost structure of the organization, which is naturally reflected in the pricing of their products.\nHowever, it is essential to recognize that certain operational systems and cost structures, while critical, should not be confused with the material quality of the products themselves in the context of “fast fashion” vs. “slow fashion” and its associated misperceptions described earlier. This distinction leads to a broader discussion on the nature of material quality and cost as follow.\nMaterials Matter: To illustrate the perspective of material choices, associated with their impacts on quality and costs, I use a scenario involving a brand using silk material for producing a dress instead of polyester, leading to a significant cost increase. Many consumers would prefer an expensive silk dress if they could afford it, not considering it as a \"fast fashion\" item. However, in terms of the “measurable” strength and durability, an equivalent dress made with polyester offers much higher strength, thus would last longer under identical care conditions. The silk dress could be ruined in a single heavy home laundry cycle, whereas the polyester dress would endure repeated washes. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Quality in Fashion: A Simplified Exploration\n\nIn this section, we take a closer look at what \"Quality\" really means, particularly in the world of \"fast fashion,\" which can often be misinterpreted.\n\n## What is Quality?\n\n### Definition from Oxford Languages\n\n- **Quality** is defined as:\n  - The standard of something compared to similar items, reflecting its level of excellence.\n  - A unique characteristic that someone or something possesses.\n\nThis definition highlights that quality is measurable, which contrasts with the confusion often associated with products that fall under the \"fast fashion\" label. To effectively assess the true quality of materials in both \"fast fashion\" and \"slow fashion,\" we can refer to specific measurements used in textile evaluation. \n\nWhile quality can vary in many aspects, this discussion will zero in on the physical properties of natural and synthetic fibers, along with their derivatives like yarns, fabrics, and finished goods. For example, if a seam breaks, it may be due to inferior sewing or weak thread rather than the fabric itself being of low quality. Here, we will break down the quality factors with a focus on the materials involved.\n\n### Key Quality Factors\n\n- **Strength**: \n  - Synthetic fibers are usually five to ten times stronger than natural fibers. This key point will be elaborated in a later section (3.2.1 Strength Factor and Dust Quantity), supported by scientific data. The greater strength of synthetic fibers means products made from them are better equipped to endure stress from abrasion, pulling, tearing, and stretching—critical factors that could cause textile failure. As a result, synthetic materials tend to last longer than those made from natural fibers.\n\n- **Durability**: \n  - While it'\''s straightforward to say synthetic fibers are more durable, this can become complicated based on how the items are cared for. For instance, washing at home subjects fabrics to significant water usage and mechanical action, which can lead to faster wear and tear, unlike dry cleaning, which is gentler. Additionally, chemicals in water and detergents can cause colors to fade. Thus, comparing durability between home-washed and dry-cleaned items can be misleading, especially since synthetic materials generally resist these physical and chemical stresses better. \n\n### Conflicting Views\n\nThere'\''s also a misconception about the longevity of \"fast fashion.\" People often believe that these items don’t last long for consumers, yet they persist in the environment longer than expected. Scientifically, if a material is durable in nature, it usually reflects a quality that suggests it should last longer for consumers too. This discrepancy may arise from differing perspectives and standards of measurement used to evaluate quality, highlighting a gap in public perception of what qualifies as \"fast\" or \"slow\" fashion.\n\n---\n\n## Clarifying Complexities in Manufacturing\n\nRecognizing that understanding textile quality and production can be intricate is essential. As an experienced textile engineer, I’ve visited numerous factories where textiles are made, and I’ve observed that often, a single factory supplies both \"slow\" and \"fast fashion\" brands, using similar raw materials and processes.\n\n### Similar Qualities with Different Prices\n\nWhile the quality of goods may be very similar, their prices can vary greatly depending on the brand and retail approach. For example, one brand may sell items in an upscale store, while another offers the same products online at a lower price. Uninformed consumers may mistakenly categorize these as \"fast fashion\" or \"slow fashion\" based solely on the brand, not realizing they are assessing quality without understanding the manufacturing complexities.\n\n### Different Qualities with Different Prices\n\nHowever, there are cases where higher-priced items may genuinely reflect higher quality. For instance, some brands employ strict quality control standards to ensure their products meet safety and performance criteria. This may include minimizing harmful chemicals, which can enhance appearance but increase production costs. This responsible approach increases the costs for the brand, which is then passed on to consumers.\n\nImportantly, the operational framework of a brand, while vital for quality assurance, should not be confused with the actual material qualities of the products when distinguishing between “fast fashion” and “slow fashion.”\n\n### Materials Make a Difference\n\nTo highlight how material choices influence quality and cost, consider a brand that produces a dress using silk versus polyester. Many consumers prefer silk if they can afford it, not viewing it as \"fast fashion.\" However, in terms of measurable strength and durability, the polyester dress would likely last longer under similar care. A silk dress might be ruined after a single wash, while a polyester one could withstand numerous washes. \n\nBy understanding these factors, consumers can make more informed decisions regarding fabric quality and its impact on clothing longevity.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the definition of '\''Quality'\'' according to Oxford Languages?"; options = vec { "A term used only in fashion."; "The state of being superior to others."; "The standard of something as measured against others."; "An attribute that cannot be measured." }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which type of fibers are generally considered stronger?"; options = vec { "Natural fibers"; "Synthetic fibers"; "Both are equally strong"; "Wool fibers" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is a key factor that leads to the perceived quality differences in fast fashion versus slow fashion?"; options = vec { "Different colors of the fabrics used."; "Different retail prices based on brand strategies."; "The presence of logos on the clothing."; "The speed of fashion production." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What does the text suggest about the durability of synthetic materials compared to natural materials?"; options = vec { "They are less durable."; "They are equally durable."; "They withstand physical and chemical forces better."; "They degrade faster." }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "How do materials like silk and polyester compare in terms of strength and durability?"; options = vec { "Silk is stronger and lasts longer."; "Polyester is stronger and lasts longer."; "Both are equally strong."; "Silk and polyester have the same durability." }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "2.3.0";
    unit_title = "Retail Price Factors";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "2.3";
    head_unit_title = "Retail Price Factors";
    content = "Among consumers, there is a common belief expressed by phrases like \"you get what you pay for\", suggesting that higher prices equate better quality. This subsection explores the disconnect between this perception and the actual impact of material costs on the retail prices of various textile goods.\nCost Bases: Revisiting the example of silk and polyester dresses, it is evident that a portion of the cost is tied to materials, such as the silk yarn for the silk dress and the polyester yarn for the polyester counterpart. However, numerous other factors contribute also to the final retail price. In fact, several other key factors exert a stronger influence on the cost structures, which in turn affect retail prices. As mentioned earlier in the discussion on Different Qualities with Different Prices, some costs are related to quality assurance. Of all associated factors in manufacturing, however, labor costs typically represent the largest expense, often far exceeding the cost of materials. \nOther significant factors are non-manufacturing related, such as the point of sale (POS) structures and administrative functions. It is widely understood within the industry that a substantial portion of the costs associated with retail products comes from administrative operations, often far exceeding manufacturing costs, including materials. These administrative costs include employee and executive salaries, benefits, office space, storefronts, inventory storage in major cities, and marketing expenses for advertising campaigns. \nWhile retail prices are shaped by complex operational structures that cannot be fully understood without examining a company’s cost base, certain patterns are well known in the industry. For instance, special sales events like Boxing Day and Black Friday, offering, for example, 50% discounts, often still yield profits for the sellers. End-of-season sales with discounts like 70% may bring companies to a break-even point or close to it, covering both manufacturing and administrative costs.  \nBy applying this logic (material cost < labor cost < administrative cost + 50% profit, for example), it becomes clear that material costs represent only a small fraction of the retail prices of the most textile goods we purchase.\nPricing Strategies: Additionally, pricing strategies vary across companies. Some brands may opt for lower sales volume with higher price points to maintain a desired brand value.  Conversely, other companies may prioritize maximizing profits by selling larger quantities at lower margins. These strategies are often influenced by factors such as existing brand values, target markets, demographics, among many others.\nDisparities – Quality and Price: Regardless of the rationale behind such price variations, a significant gap between raw material costs and retail prices often exists across both expensive and affordable textile goods. This disparity can result in consumers paying a premium for perceived brand value or administrative overhead rather than the inherent quality of the products.\nPersonally, I prioritize the value proposition of the goods I purchase rather than assuming a direct correlation between brand recognition and product quality. This approach involves a comprehensive evaluation that considers price, quality, durability, maintenance costs, and overall performance.\nFor instance, a suit I purchased from Zara, the brand initially labeled as \"fast fashion\" in the New York Times article, has remained in excellent condition for over 15 years. Contrary to the reporter'\''s perception, I see no reason to associate it with the negative connotations of \"fast fashion\" in terms of its quality. Despite avoiding highly recognized brands and expensive prices, I rarely fail in my purchasing decisions, even considering the environmental sustainability aspects of the items I buy.\nThis book aims to provide readers with the knowledge they need to make informed decisions in their textile purchases, including understanding how their choices impact the environment.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Retail Prices and Quality in Textiles\n\nMany consumers often believe that \"you get what you pay for,\" meaning that higher prices usually mean better quality. However, this section will discuss the gap between this belief and how material costs actually affect the retail prices of different textile products.\n\n## Cost Factors\n\nTaking silk and polyester dresses as an example, part of the price comes from the materials used, like silk yarn for silk dresses and polyester yarn for polyester dresses. But, many other factors also play a significant role in determining the final retail price. In fact, some of these factors have a much greater effect on costs than materials do. \n\nAs previously mentioned in the section about different qualities and prices, some costs are linked to quality assurance. However, labor costs are usually the biggest expense in manufacturing, often exceeding material costs by a large margin.\n\nThere are also important costs that are not related to manufacturing, like the structure of the point of sale (POS) and various administrative functions. The textile industry widely acknowledges that a large portion of costs comes from administrative tasks, which often surpass the costs of manufacturing, including materials. These administrative costs encompass wages and benefits for employees and executives, office space, storefronts, and storage for inventory in major cities, as well as advertising expenses for promotional campaigns.\n\nAlthough retail prices are shaped by complex operational structures that require a detailed look at a company'\''s cost base to fully understand, certain patterns are recognized in the industry. For example, during sales events such as Boxing Day and Black Friday, which might offer discounts of 50%, retailers often still make a profit. Even end-of-season sales with discounts of 70% may allow companies to break even, covering both manufacturing and administrative costs.\n\nWhen we apply the logic that material costs are less than labor costs, which are less than administrative costs plus profit, it becomes clear that material costs are only a small part of what we pay for most textile products.\n\n## Pricing Strategies\n\nPricing strategies can vary significantly among companies. Some brands may choose to sell fewer items at higher prices to maintain a certain brand image. On the other hand, some businesses may focus on maximizing profits by selling more products at lower profit margins. These strategies are influenced by various factors, including brand image, target demographics, and market conditions.\n\n## Quality Versus Price Disparities\n\nDespite the reasons behind different pricing strategies, a noticeable gap often exists between the actual material costs and the retail prices of both high-end and budget textile products. This gap means that consumers may be paying more for the perceived value of a brand or the administrative overhead rather than the actual quality of the items.\n\nPersonally, I focus on the value of the products I buy rather than assuming that a well-known brand guarantees good quality. This means I assess several factors, including price, quality, durability, maintenance costs, and overall performance.\n\nFor example, I have a suit I bought from Zara, a brand known for \"fast fashion\" according to a New York Times article. This suit has lasted over 15 years in great condition. Contrary to the negative views often associated with \"fast fashion,\" I do not see any reason to link it to inferior quality. By avoiding overly recognized brands and high prices, I often make satisfactory purchasing choices, even while considering the sustainability of the products I choose.\n\nThis book aims to equip readers with the knowledge to make informed choices when buying textiles, especially regarding how their decisions can impact the environment.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What common belief is discussed regarding price and quality among consumers?"; options = vec { "Lower prices mean better quality"; "You get what you pay for"; "All expensive items are of high quality"; "Quality is not related to price" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which of the following typically represents the largest expense in manufacturing?"; options = vec { "Material costs"; "Marketing expenses"; "Labor costs"; "Administrative costs" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What can influence a company'\''s pricing strategy?"; options = vec { "Employee salaries only"; "Existing brand values and target markets"; "Manufacturer location"; "Raw material costs only" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "According to the content, what often causes a disparity between raw material costs and retail prices?"; options = vec { "Higher quality of materials"; "Consumer perception of brand value"; "Government regulations"; "Market demand for textiles" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is the main focus of the book mentioned in the content?"; options = vec { "To promote luxury brands"; "To explain corporate marketing strategies"; "To help readers make informed textile purchases"; "To analyze the fashion industry" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "2.4.0";
    unit_title = "Misperceptions and Overconsumptions";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "2.4";
    head_unit_title = "Misperceptions and Overconsumptions";
    content = "Apart from the quality and longevity perspectives presented earlier, labeling certain brands as \"fast fashion\" can inadvertently create misperceptions, leading to undesired environmental consequences by influencing consumers'\'' overall consumption habits of textile goods.\nEmotional Values: Most people, including myself, have certain belongings that they feel more attached to than others. They can be expensive items like houses and vehicles, or special gifts attached with precious memories. Conversely, special attractions and perceptual values can certainly exist in textile goods. Personally, I value clothing that is comfortable to wear and easy to maintain, which stems from my background as textile engineer. This perspective may differ from that of the general public, who might not assess textile goods through the same level of technical lens as me. However, like others, I also attach emotional value to certain items, especially those associated with meaningful moments or gifted by special people. These items are often more cherished and cared for due to the emotional connections they hold.\nLower Values: On the other hand, some items may be regarded as having lower value by many. For example, an inexpensive synthetic shirt displayed in a store associated with \"fast fashion\" may lead a shopper to make an impulsive purchase. In this situation, the shopper may develop preconceived notions about the item'\''s quality and durability, often aligning with the common perception that “\"fast fashion\" products have shorter lifespan”.\nConsumption Behaviors: Relating to emotional values and purchasing decisions, it is natural for most consumers to think more carefully when buying higher-priced items. The more expensive the product, the more planning and consideration go into the decision, which in turn creates an emotional value in itself. For this reason, people often vividly remember where and when they bought an expensive silk dress, while they may not have such clear memories of purchasing an inexpensive shirt on impulse.\nDifferences of Fates: Perceptions also influence how people treat items that show signs of wear. If someone believes an item isn'\''t meant to last, even a minor flaw, like a loose button or a broken seam, can prompt them to dispose of or donate the item rather than repair it. In times when materials were scarce, such issues would have been resolved with simple repairs, no question asked. Today’s picture in wealthy countries, however, presents a stark contrast. Large quantities of textile items placed in community recycling bins or donated to charity groups often require only minor repairs. It is evident that the individuals who disposed of these items had little or no emotional attachment and valued them too little to retain them with small fixes. \n***\nIn summary, labeling textiles as \"fast fashion\" can create a perception of lower value in consumers'\'' minds, which may not accurately reflect the real quality or the longevity of the goods in question. This perception shapes the fate of these items, often leading to premature disposal in landfills or incinerators and subsequently driving the consumption of other textile goods as replacements.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Fast Fashion and Its Impact on Consumer Behavior\n\n## Misconceptions About Fast Fashion\nWhen we label certain clothing brands as \"fast fashion,\" it can create misunderstandings. These misperceptions may lead to harmful environmental effects by affecting how much people buy and use textile products.\n\n## Emotional Connection to Items\nMost individuals, including myself, tend to feel a stronger attachment to specific belongings over others. These can be high-value items like homes or cars, or emotional gifts tied to cherished memories. \n\nTextiles can also hold special attraction and emotional significance. Personally, I value clothing that is comfortable and easy to care for, influenced by my background as a textile engineer. This perspective might differ from the general public, who may not analyze textile products as deeply. However, like many others, I also have emotional attachments to certain items, especially those that are linked to significant moments or are gifts from important people. These pieces are often more valued and taken care of due to the feelings associated with them.\n\n## Perceived Value of Items\nConversely, some items might be viewed as having less value. For example, a low-cost synthetic shirt from a \"fast fashion\" brand may prompt shoppers to make impulse purchases. In such cases, customers may have preconceived ideas about the quality and lifespan of the item, usually thinking that “fast fashion” goods don’t last long.\n\n## Impact on Purchasing Behavior\nWhen it comes to purchasing decisions, emotional values play a significant role. Many consumers tend to think more carefully when buying high-priced items. The more expensive something is, the more thought goes into the decision, which creates a higher emotional value. For instance, people often remember the details of when and where they bought a silk dress but may forget the impulse buy of a cheap shirt.\n\n## Treatment of Items and Their Fate\nPerceptions also affect how individuals care for items that show wear. If someone believes an item isn’t meant to last, even a minor flaw, like a loose button, might lead them to throw it away or donate it instead of repairing it. In the past, when materials were limited, people would simply fix minor issues without hesitation. Today, however, in affluent countries, many textile items placed in recycling bins or donated often only need small repairs. This reflects a lack of emotional attachment and a perception of low value, leading people to discard items they could easily fix.\n\n## Conclusion\nIn summary, labeling textiles as \"fast fashion\" can lead consumers to perceive them as lower quality than they might be. This perception influences the longevity of these items, often resulting in premature disposal and increased consumption of replacement textiles.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is one consequence of labeling brands as '\''fast fashion'\''?"; options = vec { "It improves the quality of textiles"; "It can create misperceptions about value"; "It reduces the lifespan of clothing"; "It increases the price of textile goods" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What do emotional values in textile goods often include?"; options = vec { "The technical quality of materials"; "Price comparison between items"; "Attachment to items with memories"; "Brand names associated with high fashion" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "How do consumers typically behave when purchasing higher-priced items?"; options = vec { "They make quick decisions without consideration"; "They often forget about the purchase"; "They think carefully and plan before buying"; "They tend to purchase more lower-value items" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What impact does perceived lower value have on the treatment of clothing items?"; options = vec { "Items are often repaired rather than discarded"; "Items are cherished and maintained"; "Minor flaws lead to quicker disposal of items"; "Items are purchased for their sentimental value" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is the primary concern regarding disposal of textile items linked to '\''fast fashion'\''?"; options = vec { "They have higher quality than perceived"; "They are often kept for many years"; "They may end up in landfills or incinerators prematurely"; "They are donated with significant emotional attachment" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "3.0";
    unit_title = "Microplastic vs. Natural Fiber Dust (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I: Consumers, Be Aware and Beware!";
    head_unit_id = "3";
    head_unit_title = ". Microplastics vs. Natural Fiber Dust";
    content = "Dust, by definition, consists of small particles detached from their original body mass, either from natural or synthetic materials, due to various physical or chemical impacts, then spread primarily through air. Many individuals suffer from allergies caused by pollens during flowering seasons. Pollens are an example of dust originating from nature, illustrating that not all natural sources are harmless. The impacts of dust particles on health and environment can vary widely depending on two main factors: chemical compositions and quantity.\nSince the invention of the plastics over a century ago, these materials have become deeply embedded in our daily lives. Due to their thin and long form factors, synthetic fibers have been a major source of microplastics for more than 100 years, shedding dust particles during manufacturing, normal wear and washing.\nThis contamination has led to growing concerns about microplastics in virtually all our food sources, and rightfully so. It is well known that microplastics are present in almost everything we eat and drink, even in unexpected places like inside meat, fish, and vegetables. These tiny particles are so small that they even float in the air we breathe.\nIn this discussion, I delve into the nature of the dust particles from textiles and their environmental and health impacts. \nNatural Fibre Dust and…: We would be living in a rather strange, and almost magical, world if only synthetic fibers shed dust (microplastics), especially considering that natural fibers are generally much weaker than synthetic ones - a point that will be explored in more depth in subsequent discussions later in this section. Yet, the dust from the natural fibers is largely overlooked. As a result, many readers may be unaware of its nature and impacts. \n***\nTo address this topic on a scientifically fair basis, I will examine the sources and impacts of the dust from both synthetic and natural fibers, beginning with the scientific understanding on the microplastic. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Dust and Its Impact\n\n## What is Dust?\nDust is made up of tiny particles that have broken away from their original material. These particles can come from both natural sources (like pollen) and synthetic materials (like plastics). They spread mainly through the air. For example, during flowering seasons, many people experience allergies from pollen, showing that not all natural particles are safe. The health and environmental effects of dust can differ significantly based on two main factors: the chemical makeup of the particles and their quantity.\n\n## The Role of Plastics\nSince plastic was invented over a century ago, it has become a significant part of our lives. A major contributor to dust pollution is synthetic fibers, which produce microplastics. These microplastics can get released into the air during their production, regular use, and washing.\n\nThis widespread contamination has raised alarms about microplastics being found in many of our food sources. Studies show that microplastics are present in nearly all the food we consume and can even be discovered in surprising places like meats, fish, and vegetables. The particles are so small that they can also be found floating in the air we breathe.\n\n## The Impact of Textile Dust\nIn this section, I will explore the dust created by textiles and its effects on the environment and our health. \n\n### Natural Fiber Dust\nIt would be unusual to think that only synthetic fibers produce dust, especially since natural fibers are typically weaker than synthetic ones. However, the dust from natural fibers is often overlooked. Many readers may not recognize its nature and the potential impacts it can have.\n\n## A Balanced Examination\nTo provide a fair scientific perspective, I will investigate the sources and effects of dust from both synthetic and natural fibers, starting with an understanding of microplastics.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What are dust particles primarily spread through?"; options = vec { "Water"; "Soil"; "Air"; "Light" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is a significant source of microplastics mentioned in the text?"; options = vec { "Natural fibers"; "Heavy metals"; "Synthetic fibers"; "Pollen" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Microplastics have been found in which of the following food sources?"; options = vec { "Only vegetables"; "Only fish"; "Only meat"; "All of the above" }; answer = 3; }; record { question = "Which factor does NOT influence the impact of dust particles on health and environment?"; options = vec { "Chemical composition"; "Quantity"; "Size"; "None of the above" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What aspect of dust from natural fibers is largely overlooked?"; options = vec { "Health impacts"; "Sources of dust"; "Chemical composition"; "Presence in air" }; answer = 0; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "3.1.0";
    unit_title = "Microplastics and Synthetic Fibers";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "3.1";
    head_unit_title = "Microplastics and Synthetic Fibers";
    content = "Microplastics are generated from plastic sources through physical impacts during manufacturing and consumption. A common misconception is that microplastics mainly originate from the obvious plastic materials we encounter routinely in our daily lives like bottles and bags. While these sources do contribute, one of the most significant sources of the microplastics is the synthetic fibers in textile goods. This is due to their extreme length directionality and inherent weakness along the length side.  \nForces for Microplastic Creations against Polymer Formation Structures: Scientifically, there are 13 different physical forces that can cause materials to break, and in the case of plastics, this breakage often results in the creation of what is commonly referred to as \"microplastic\". These forces include tensile, compressive, shear, bending, abrasive, and frictional forces, among others.\nWhen it comes to the structural integrity, which plays a crucial role in determining the amount of dust produced, plastic bottles and bags offer much greater resistance to physical impacts compared to synthetic fibers. This is due to their more favorable formation structures and form factors, which become apparent when examining their surface structures. Under extreme magnification, modern microscopes reveal that the polymer chains in plastic bottles or bags are tightly intertwined, providing strong structural integrity, as shown in Fig.12. \nFig.12   Plastic Formation in Surace Structure\nhttps://www.nature.com/articles/pj201567   \nIn this robust structure, the polymer chains are arranged in random directions, making the material inherently resistant from all directions of the physical forces mentioned earlier. Weaknesses arises, however, when plastics are formed into thin sheets, like grocery bags, which are more susceptible to stretching, tearing and puncturing compared to thicker plastics, such as food containers. \nDespite this, thin plastic bags still demonstrate an impressive strength-to-weight ratio, often capable of holding thousands of times their own weight (typically a 1:1,000 to 1:2,000 weight ratio). This combination of strength and lightness has contributed to the widespread popularity of plastic bags and bottles, while significant environmental concerns surrounding them have grown. \nMicroplastics from Synthetic Fibers: In contrast, synthetic fibers are far more susceptible to breakage due to the extreme directionality created by the long and thin form factors. The difference in strength becomes evident when comparing the two: while a thin plastic bag weighing 5 grams can hold 5 ~ 10 kg (11 ~ 22 lbs) of groceries, synthetic fibers can break under just a few grams of weight, which explains why a large number of them are bundled together and twisted into a yarn in part to enhance the strength – more on this in Chapter II: Yarn-Making discussion. \nWhile the resulting yarn becomes considerably stronger, the comprising fibers remain weak. As a result, mundane everyday activities such as putting on or taking off garments, friction with other objects, or laundering can easily generate enough force to produce microplastics.\nA study by a team at Plymouth University highlights the significant amount of microplastics released during laundering. They reported that an average washing load of 6 kg of laundry could release an estimated 137,951 fibers from polyester-cotton blend fabric, 496,030 fibers from 100% polyester, and 728,789 fibers from 100% acrylic.\nCautionary Analysis: While the data clearly indicates the generation of a large quantity of microplastics from a single laundry load, I approach these findings with caution. Three key considerations warrant this careful analysis: 1) the methods used to capture microplastics, as even the most advanced filtering systems cannot capture all microplastics due to their extremely small and lightweight nature, 2) the difficulty in distinguishing between the dust from natural and synthetic materials, especially in the blended fabric of the polyester-cotton mixes; and 3) the lack of information on the quantity of the dust from the cotton in the blended fabric.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Microplastics\n\nMicroplastics are tiny plastic particles that come from larger plastic materials being broken down during manufacturing and use. Many people mistakenly think that microplastics mainly come from the plastic items we see every day, such as bottles and bags. While these items do contribute to the problem, a major source of microplastics is actually the synthetic fibers used in textiles. This is largely because these fibers are long and thin, making them weaker and more easily breakable.\n\n## How Microplastics are Formed\n\nThere are various physical forces that can break down materials, and for plastics, these forces often lead to the formation of microplastics. In total, there are 13 different types of physical forces that can cause this breakdown, including:\n\n- **Tensile** (pulling)\n- **Compressive** (pushing)\n- **Shear** (sliding)\n- **Bending**\n- **Abrasive** (scraping)\n- **Frictional** (rubbing)\n\nWhen we look at the strength of materials, plastic bottles and bags are much more resistant to physical impacts compared to synthetic fibers. This is because the structure of plastic allows for strong connections between the polymer chains, as illustrated in Figure 12. \n\n### Figure 12: Structure of Plastic at the Surface Level  \n![Plastic Formation in Surface Structure](https://www.nature.com/articles/pj201567)\n\nIn sturdy plastics, the polymer chains are arranged in a random way, which helps the material resist damage from various forces. Problems arise when plastics are made into thin sheets like grocery bags. These are more likely to stretch, tear, or puncture than thicker plastics, such as those used for food containers.\n\nDespite being thin, plastic bags can hold a remarkable amount of weight—up to 1,000 to 2,000 times their own weight. This strength combined with lightness has made plastic bags and bottles very popular, though they pose serious environmental challenges.\n\n## Microplastics from Synthetic Fibers\n\nOn the other hand, synthetic fibers are more prone to breaking because of their long and thin design. For example, a lightweight plastic bag can support 5 to 10 kg (11 to 22 lbs) of groceries, while synthetic fibers can snap under only a few grams of weight. To improve their strength, many of these fibers are bundled together and twisted into yarn, which is discussed further in Chapter II: Yarn-Making.\n\nHowever, even when these fibers are combined into yarn, the individual fibers remain relatively weak. Everyday activities such as putting on or taking off clothes, rubbing against other items, or washing clothes can easily create enough force to produce microplastics.\n\nA study by researchers at Plymouth University found that washing a typical load of 6 kg of laundry can release nearly 138,000 fibers from polyester-cotton blends, over 496,000 fibers from pure polyester, and about 729,000 fibers from 100% acrylic fabrics.\n\n## Important Considerations\n\nWhile these findings show a large amount of microplastics generated from a single laundry load, it'\''s essential to analyze them carefully. Here are three critical points to consider:\n\n1. **Microplastic Capture Methods:** Even the best filtering systems cannot catch all microplastics because they are extremely small and light.\n2. **Material Distinction:** It'\''s challenging to tell the difference between dust from natural and synthetic materials, particularly in blended fabrics like polyester-cotton.\n3. **Cotton Dust Information:** There isn'\''t enough data about the amount of dust from the cotton content in these blended fabrics.\n\nThis careful analysis emphasizes the complexity of the microplastic issue, reminding us that understanding how they are created and measured is vital for addressing their environmental impact.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is one of the significant sources of microplastics mentioned in the text?"; options = vec { "Plastic bottles"; "Synthetic fibers in textile goods"; "Plastic bags"; "Food containers" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is the estimated number of fibers released from 6 kg of 100% polyester laundry, according to the study by Plymouth University?"; options = vec { "137,951"; "496,030"; "728,789"; "5,000" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Why are synthetic fibers more susceptible to breakage compared to plastics?"; options = vec { "They are heavier"; "They have extreme directionality and long, thin form factors"; "They are made from natural materials"; "They are harder to clean" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What affects the structural integrity of plastic bags and bottles?"; options = vec { "Their color"; "Their thickness and formation structures"; "Their manufacturing process"; "Their use in grocery stores" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which of the following is a cautionary consideration regarding microplastics?"; options = vec { "They are easy to filter out"; "Natural fibers contribute significantly to microplastics"; "The methods used to capture microplastics can be flawed"; "All microplastics come from synthetic materials" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "3.2.0";
    unit_title = "Dust of Natural Fibers (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "3.2";
    head_unit_title = "Dust of Natural Fibers";
    content = "Similar to synthetic fibers, natural fibers exhibit extreme directionality with the thin and long form factors. The same physical forces that generate microplastics from the synthetic fibers, such as tensile, shear, and frictional forces, also apply to the natural fibers. In fact, these forces can have much greater impacts on the natural fibers, leading to the production of significantly larger quantities of dust compared to their synthetic equivalents under the same amount of physical force. \nContrary to the popular belief, the dust from the natural fibers can have more harmful environmental impacts due to the larger amounts of residual chemicals and their higher toxicity levels. Toxicity aspect related to different textile materials, a central theme of this book, requires detailed analysis and a comprehensive understanding, as it plays a crucial role in our environmental management. As such, this topic will remain a focal point and will be discussed in depth throughout the relevant sections of the book.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Natural vs. Synthetic Fibers\n\nNatural fibers, like synthetic fibers, have a unique property known as directionality, which means they are very thin and long. When these fibers are subjected to physical forces like tension, shear, and friction—forces that can also break down synthetic fibers into microplastics—natural fibers can be affected even more intensely. This results in the generation of larger amounts of dust from natural fibers when compared to synthetic fibers that experience the same physical forces.\n\nIt'\''s important to note that the dust created by natural fibers may actually be more harmful to the environment. This is because it often contains higher levels of leftover chemicals and is generally more toxic. Understanding the toxicity of different textile materials is a key focus of this book, and it'\''s essential for effective environmental management. We will explore this topic in depth in the relevant sections to provide a comprehensive overview.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is a significant similarity between natural and synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "Both are completely biodegradable"; "Both exhibit extreme directionality with thin and long form factors"; "Both require the same amount of energy to produce"; "Both have no impact on the environment" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What physical forces affect both synthetic and natural fibers?"; options = vec { "Chemical reactions"; "Thermal expansion"; "Tensile, shear, and frictional forces"; "Electrical charges" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Why might dust from natural fibers be more harmful than that from synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "It is more abundant"; "It contains larger particles"; "It has higher toxicity levels and residual chemicals"; "It is less regulated" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is the central theme of the book mentioned in the content?"; options = vec { "The production process of fibers"; "The aesthetic qualities of textiles"; "The toxicity of different textile materials"; "The ecological benefits of synthetic fibers" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "How is the environmental management topic treated in the book?"; options = vec { "As an optional chapter"; "As a focal point discussed in depth"; "As a brief mention"; "As unrelated to textiles" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "3.2.1";
    unit_title = "Strength Factor and Dust Quantity";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "3.2";
    head_unit_title = "Dust of Natural Fibers";
    content = "To comprehend the quantity of dust generated from textile materials in both natural and synthetic compositions, it is essential to understand the strength of each type of fiber and how it is measured. In this discussion, we employ the breaking energy analysis method.\n***Industry Specifics (1) – Start***\nTest Method: Each fiber strand is affixed to two gripping mechanisms, one at the top and one at the bottom, within the test equipment, illustrated in Fig.13. The top gripping head then pulls the fiber strand in the length direction until it breaks. During this process, the sensor attached to the moving head measures the breaking force and the distance the fiber travels until breakage. This method, commonly referred to as “tensile test”, is also applicable to various other intermediary textile materials such as yarns and fabrics. Beyond the textile applications, it is often used in such materials as films, steel, etc., where tensile strength is a critical quality indicator. \nFig.13   Tensile \nStrength Tester\nIn standard laboratory practices, a selected number of fibers are tested based on a statistical method for determining the sampling size, and the average values of related properties are reported.\nStress-Strain Curve: Fig.14 provides an example set of data obtained from a tensile test. The value on the Y-axis represents the stress, and the value on the X-axis represents the strain, hence the name \"Stress-Strain (SS) curve.\"\nFig.14   Breaking Energy Measurements \nThe SS curve is highly useful for a wide range of analyses on fiber characteristics as it offers comprehensive insights into the physical behaviors and internal structures of the tested materials. Given the scope of this book, I will not delve deeply into the technical analysis on this particular set of data. Instead, I will focus on analyzing the properties related to the dust creation between polyester and cotton. \nAnalysis: The SS curves for the cotton and the polyester reveal distinctly different patterns. The cotton curves typically form triangles, while the polyester exhibits curved shapes with multiple inclinations before breaking. The shape of the polyester on Fig.14 reflects its internal polymer structure characteristics, particularly its degree of crystallinity, a trait shared with other synthetic fibers: the initial steep slope of the polyester indicates the strength required until the tensile force reaches a yield point, the point at which the crystallinity no longer provides the dimensional strength to maintain the original fiber structure. Beyond this point, the curve'\''s slope decreases, showing that the fiber stretches more easily with the applied unit force. The degree of the stretchiness is the function of the non-crystalline parts of the polymer structure. Together, these characteristics contribute to the total energy required to break the fiber. \nIn contrast, the cotton exhibits a straight line until it breaks, a typical behavior for most plant-based fibers. This can be largely attributed to the cellulosic structure of cotton, which has a more uniformly distributed structure throughout and lacks the combination of the distinct crystalline and non-crystalline regions found in synthetic fibers. \n***Industry Specifics (1) – End***\nThe critical point for the readers to understand in this analysis is that the area under each graph represents the breaking energy of the tested fiber. Higher breaking energy indicates greater resistance to physical forces, making the fiber less prone to breaking (or creating dust) during manufacturing and consumption.  \nVariability: Prior to delving further into the analysis, it is imperative to acknowledge an inherent variability in this type of data. The characteristics of natural fibers such as cotton can exhibit significant fluctuations contingent upon various factors, including geographical origins and climatic conditions during cultivation, specific genetic variants of cotton plants, farming methods, etc. Similarly, synthetic fibers like polyester demonstrate considerable variability in their properties, largely influenced by diverse manufacturing parameters. \nConsequently, various scientific literatures and other sources of information present a wide spectrum of data pertaining to the physical characteristics of these fibers. This variability underscores the importance of cautious interpretation and contextualization of the data of this nature. \nNotwithstanding these variations, the dataset selected and used in Fig.14 represents the values typically accepted within the industry.\nStrength Comparison: Notably, the polyester maintains consistent stress and strain characteristics whether dry or wet, as illustrated in the table of Fig.14. This is due to the hydrophobic nature of polyester and its strength is unaffected by moisture as a result. In contrast, the cotton exhibits significant differences between wet and dry because of its strong affinity for water, attributed to the presence of the hydroxyl groups in cellulose and the absorption of water significantly increases the cotton'\''s strength.\nThe breaking energy of the polyester, represented by the red area on Fig.14, is significantly higher by a factor of 5 to 10 times than that of the cotton when wet, represented by the area under the graph in black, and when dry, by the graph in blue respectively.  \nIn most situations other than during laundry, cotton remains relatively dry in consumption, therefore, the strength difference between the two fibers in real-world usage, which relates more closely to the creation of the dust in the air, would be closer to 10 times than 5. \nThis significant strength disparity can be understood with a simple analogy: if a polyester shirt produces 1 gram of microplastics, an equivalent cotton shirt could generate nearly 10 grams of dust.\nAs mentioned earlier, variations in these test results can arise from numerous factors. However, most factors favor polyester in the aspect of the dust creation because its manufacturing variables can be easily controlled and adjusted to create more favourable outcomes, whereas cotton is subject to many uncontrollable factors like weather conditions, specific species, etc. This naturally leads to the discussion of the next subject, where much of the variables are accounted for and result in stark differences of the dust quantities in real-world circumstances between natural and synthetic fibers.\n***Industry Specifics (2) – Start***\nProfessional Experiences on Dust\nDuring my tenure as R&D engineer in South Korea, I had an optimal opportunity to gain a profound understanding of the dust creation from different fiber types.  \nQuality Issues related to Dust: As a yarn manufacturer, the company I worked for occasionally received quality complaints from its customers of the weaving and knitting factories. One of the most significant and costly issues of all complaints was an excessive dust creation by some of the company’s yarn products during the manufacturing processes of its customers.\nUnder normal circumstances, it is natural to observe some dust as yarns pass through the hard surfaces of machinery parts, often made with metals, ceramics, plastics, etc. However, if the fibers comprising the yarns are weaker than others, they produce more dust. Excessive dust becomes particularly problematic for weavers and knitters, as it accumulates and obstructs the intended passages of the yarns during their manufacturing processes. This obstruction can lead to the breakage of both yarns and small machinery parts such as needles, causing manufacturing stoppages and resulting in a material loss and waste of labor hours.\nWeavers and knitters may tolerate a certain level of operational inefficiency, but they will complain when it exceeds an acceptable level. The financial and reputational damages from such complaints prompted the company to mandate me with comprehensive studies to understand the causes of wide variations in the dust quantities in some manufacturing batches of yarns, which subsequently led to customer complaints.\nYarn Blends and Dust Quantity Analysis: The company produced yarns with a wide range of fiber compositions, including 100% Cotton, 100% Wool, 100% Polyester, 100% Acrylic, as well as various blended fibers. The blend compositions varied significantly depending on the desired properties of finished textiles, ranging from blends like 95% Wool and 5% Polyester to the reverse, and everything in between as well as widely different other fiber types mixed together. As a result, the company offered hundreds of yarn assortments to its customers.\nTo better understand the variability in the dust generation across this wide spectrum of products, I developed a strategy to measure the nominal dust quantity for the yarns made from homogeneous materials (such as 100% Cotton, 100% Wool, 100% Polyester, etc.) and used the results as the baselines of the dust creation characteristic of each fiber type in normal quality. Then, I tried to correlate the baselines to the variation when it was blended with other fibers in varying proportions. This approach allowed me to understand how each fiber type contributed to the dust creation, regardless of specific blend ratios.\nInvention of Dust Measurement Test Device: One of the challenges I had to overcome on tackling this task was accurately measuring the quantity of the dust in a controlled environment. In the open air of a typical manufacturing facility, it was impossible to obtain precise measurements. For example, enclosing a large weaving machine in an airtight bag to collect the dust over a certain period while the machine was running would have been both impractical and extremely costly. Additionally, this method would have resulted in significant dust loss when opening and closing the bag.\nTo address this, I developed a compact test device that fits comfortably within the company’s laboratory, as illustrated in Fig.15. This device featured a series of needles arranged to simulate the tensile and frictional forces subject to the yarns in conventional knitting machines. When a yarn specimen entered the chamber, it was subjected to a preset degree of physical forces before being wound on the other side. The adjustments for creating different levels of physical forces were made through the speed adjustment of the winding spool and different passage arrangements within the chamber.\nFig.15   Test Equipment for Yarn Dust Collection\nIn 1993, I was granted my first patent in South Korea for the device. With it, I established a nominal range of the dust quantity for varying yarn types based on different manufacturing parameters such as fiber types and blend compositions, yarn thicknesses and twist variables, among others. If a batch of yarn produced by the company exhibited a dust generation characteristic considerably exceeding the nominal range, the batch was segregated and destroyed. This approach improved the company’s operations by minimizing the customer complaints of the nature.  \n***Industry Specifics (2) – End***\nGeneralization of Dust Quantity: Through this experience, I established a strong correlation between the breaking energies of fibers and the amount of dust generated during subsequent manufacturing processes. For example, under identical yarn-making conditions and produced in the same pilot spinning machines, a cotton yarn created multiple times higher quantities of dust than a polyester yarn, assimilating the data presented in Fig.14. This observation was applicable for other fiber types, and it was clear that the weaker strength of natural fibers was translated directly to the higher quantity of dust created. My earlier assertion, “if a polyester shirt produces 1 gram of microplastics, an equivalent cotton shirt could generate nearly 10 grams of dust”, was in part based on the conclusion obtained from this study, exemplifying the nature of scientific studies proportionally reflected in real-life situations. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Dust Generation from Textile Fibers\n\nTo grasp how much dust is created from both natural (like cotton) and synthetic (like polyester) textile fibers, we need to evaluate the strength of these fibers and how we measure that strength. For this, we use a method called breaking energy analysis.\n\n## Test Method\nEach fiber strand is attached to two grips, one at the top and another at the bottom, within specialized equipment (see Fig. 13). The top grip pulls the fiber until it breaks. During this test, a sensor measures the force needed to break the fiber and how far it stretches before breaking. This test is known as a \"tensile test,\" which can also be used for other textiles like yarns and fabrics, as well as materials such as films and steel, where strength is a crucial factor.\n\nIn standard lab practices, a certain number of fibers are chosen using statistical sampling. The average properties of these fibers are then recorded.\n\n## Stress-Strain Curve\nFigure 14 shows sample data from a tensile test. The Y-axis indicates stress, while the X-axis indicates strain, forming what we call a \"Stress-Strain (SS) curve.\" \n\nThe SS curve is important because it provides valuable insights into the characteristics and behaviors of the tested fibers. While this book won'\''t go into detailed technical analysis of this data, we'\''ll focus on how polyester and cotton differ in terms of dust generation.\n\n### Analysis of Cotton and Polyester\nThe SS curves for cotton and polyester show clear differences. Cotton curves resemble triangles, while polyester curves are more rounded with various slopes before breaking. The shape of the polyester curve (as seen in Fig. 14) reveals details about its internal structure, particularly its crystallinity. Initially, polyester shows a steep slope, indicating strong resistance to breaking until reaching a point where its structure can no longer maintain its strength. After this yield point, the slope decreases, meaning the fiber stretches more easily, which is influenced by the non-crystalline parts of the polymer.\n\nIn contrast, cotton'\''s curve is linear until it breaks, typical for many plant-based fibers. This behavior is due to cotton'\''s uniform cellulosic structure, which lacks the complex crystalline and non-crystalline regions found in synthetic fibers.\n\n### Key Takeaway\nThe area beneath each curve indicates the breaking energy of the fiber. A larger area means the fiber can withstand more stress, making it less likely to break (or create dust) during use.\n\n## Variability\nIt'\''s essential to recognize that natural fibers, like cotton, can vary significantly due to factors like their growing conditions, plant genetics, and farming methods. Synthetic fibers, such as polyester, also show variability depending on the manufacturing process. Because of this variability, scientific studies often report a wide range of data about fiber characteristics, highlighting the need for careful interpretation.\n\nDespite these differences, the data in Fig. 14 represents commonly accepted values in the industry.\n\n### Strength Comparison\nInterestingly, polyester'\''s stress and strain characteristics remain relatively consistent whether wet or dry, as shown in the table in Fig. 14. This stability is due to polyester'\''s hydrophobic properties, which means moisture doesn'\''t affect its strength. Conversely, cotton'\''s strength varies significantly when wet, because it absorbs water due to its hydroxyl groups, increasing its strength.\n\nThe breaking energy of wet polyester (indicated by the red area in Fig. 14) is about 5 to 10 times higher than that of wet cotton (the black area) and even more significant when both fibers are dry (the blue area). \n\nIn practical situations, cotton usually remains dry, so the strength difference in real-world use (and its relation to dust generation) is likely closer to 10 times. For example, if a polyester shirt sheds 1 gram of microplastics, a cotton shirt might create nearly 10 grams of dust.\n\n**Note:** Although variations exist, many factors favor polyester in terms of dust generation because its production conditions can be controlled better than cotton, which is affected by uncontrollable factors like weather or plant species.\n\n## Professional Insights on Dust\nAs an R&D engineer in South Korea, I gained significant insights into dust production from different fiber types.\n\n### Quality Issues Related to Dust\nWhile working at a yarn manufacturing company, I often received complaints from clients regarding excessive dust from our yarn products during the manufacturing processes. Typically, some dust is expected when yarns pass through machinery, but weaker fibers produce more dust. \n\nExcessive dust can obstruct machinery, leading to yarn and needle breakage, which results in production delays and loss of materials and labor.\n\n### Dust Quantity Analysis\nOur company produced a variety of yarns made from different fiber compositions (e.g., 100% cotton, 100% polyester, etc.). I devised a strategy to measure dust quantities for these homogenous yarn types to establish baseline dust generation characteristics, which I then correlated with the variations found in blended yarns.\n\n### Creation of a Dust Measurement Device\nA key challenge was measuring dust in a controlled environment. Traditional methods were impractical and would result in significant losses. So, I designed a compact dust measurement device located in our lab (see Fig. 15). This device simulates the conditions yarns face in conventional machines and accurately measures dust production based on different variables.\n\nIn 1993, I secured my first patent in South Korea for this invention. By establishing nominal dust quantity ranges for various yarn types, we could identify batches with excessive dust production, minimizing customer complaints.\n\n## General Observations\nThrough my professional experiences, I found a strong correlation between a fiber'\''s breaking energy and the dust produced in manufacturing. For instance, under the same conditions, cotton yarn generates significantly more dust than polyester yarn (as shown in Fig. 14). This relationship reinforces the earlier point I made: \"if a polyester shirt produces 1 gram of microplastics, an equivalent cotton shirt could generate nearly 10 grams of dust,\" which exemplifies the connection between scientific data and real-life scenarios.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What method is employed to analyze the breaking energy of fibers?"; options = vec { "Microscopic Analysis"; "Breaking Energy Analysis"; "Chemical Composition Test"; "Moisture Content Analysis" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What type of curve is used to represent the relationship between stress and strain in fibers?"; options = vec { "Viscosity Curve"; "Stress-Strain Curve"; "Elasticity Curve"; "Ductility Curve" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is a key characteristic of polyester compared to cotton in terms of moisture?"; options = vec { "Polyester absorbs more water"; "Cotton is hydrophobic"; "Polyester'\''s strength is unaffected by moisture"; "Cotton maintains constant strength regardless of moisture" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What did the author develop to measure dust quantity in yarns?"; options = vec { "Dust Collection Bag"; "Dust Measurement Test Device"; "Fiber Strength Analyzer"; "Moisture Control Device" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How much more dust does a cotton shirt generate compared to a polyester shirt, according to the text?"; options = vec { "1 gram"; "5 grams"; "10 grams"; "100 grams" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "4.0";
    unit_title = "Unfortunate Disposal (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I: Consumers, Be Aware and Beware!";
    head_unit_id = "4";
    head_unit_title = ". Unfortunate Disposal";
    content = "While many people may not give much thought to the environmental impacts of disposing of textile goods, there are numerous critical factors to consider. These range from the implications of the residual chemicals contained in the waste affecting our environment to humanitarian crises caused by the export of textile waste from affluent countries to underdeveloped and developing countries. Some of these disposal practices may be shocking to those who are unaware. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding the Environmental Impact of Textile Waste Disposal\n\nMany individuals might not realize the significant environmental issues associated with throwing away textile products. It'\''s important to consider several key factors:\n\n1. **Residual Chemicals**: The leftover chemicals in discarded textiles can harm our environment. These substances may leach into soil and waterways, affecting ecosystems and health.\n\n2. **Humanitarian Crises**: The export of textile waste from wealthier countries to less developed nations creates serious humanitarian challenges. These countries often struggle to manage the influx of waste, leading to social and economic problems.\n\n3. **Shocking Disposal Practices**: Some of the methods used for disposing of textiles may be surprising to those who are not aware of the current practices in waste management.\n\nUnderstanding these issues helps highlight the importance of responsible textile disposal and promotes discussions about sustainable solutions.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is a major environmental concern associated with disposing of textile goods?"; options = vec { "Positive economic impacts"; "Increase in wildlife population"; "Residual chemicals affecting the environment"; "Improvement in soil quality" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What humanitarian crisis is associated with textile waste disposal?"; options = vec { "Exporting waste to affluent countries"; "Lack of job opportunities in affluent countries"; "Export of textile waste to underdeveloped countries"; "Importing textile goods from underdeveloped countries" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which group of countries is notably affected by the export of textile waste?"; options = vec { "Developed countries"; "Underdeveloped and developing countries"; "Emerging economies"; "Countries with high textile production" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What might surprise some people about textile waste disposal practices?"; options = vec { "They are all environmentally friendly."; "They often have high economic benefits."; "They can be shocking and harmful."; "They are well-regulated worldwide." }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Why might people overlook the impacts of textile waste disposal?"; options = vec { "They are unaware of the consequences."; "They believe it'\''s a minor issue."; "They have other priorities."; "They don'\''t use textiles." }; answer = 0; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "4.1.0";
    unit_title = "Donation Myth";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "4.1";
    head_unit_title = "Donation Myth";
    content = "Many people assume that the textile goods they drop off in community recycling boxes or donate to charity groups are reused by those in need. However, the reality is starkly different from this common perception. In a 2018 episode of “Marketplace”, aired by the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC), it revealed that only 1% of the textile waste is reclaimed and recycled in a “real sense” of recycling. The fate of a large portion of it is mind-boggling and even exposes a troubling side of humanity.\nUnintended Destinations: Strict environmental regulations in affluent countries make it difficult and expensive to locally incinerate or bury large quantities of textile waste. Consequently, these textiles are shipped to underdeveloped and developing countries far away from the origins of the waste. While a small fraction of them may be reused by the locals in the destinations, the majority are burned or buried without necessary environmental safeguards, such as monitoring for volatile organic compounds (VOCs) or proper analysis and control on soil and water contamination. \nIt is a troubling irony that thick sweaters and winter coats from wealthy northern countries end up in nations near the equator with hot weather, reflecting a typical \"Not In My Back Yard\" (NIMBY) attitude of the citizens of wealthy countries.\nMisperceptions and Environmental Impacts: As the environmental awareness grows across the globe, people are becoming more mindful of their ecological footprints. For example, many would consider it unsustainable to toss a plastic bottle into regular garbage. Yet, these same individuals may dispose of their unwanted clothing in recycling bins or donate them to charity without the same level of concern as they are unaware of the resulting reality.\nThis misperception carries significant environmental consequences. Beyond the carbon footprint from transporting the waste across oceans, the textiles contain residual chemicals that persist in nature, causing long-term harm, a topic explored in detail in Chapter III: Lifecycle Assessment - Disposal section.\nHumanitarian Crisis: Perhaps the most distressing aspect of this issue is the social injustice it perpetuates. People in affluent countries often ignore the harsh living conditions of those in the nations that receive their waste. In these regions, mountains of textile waste pile up along riverbanks or are burned in areas like school playgrounds.\nI am convinced that if people in the origin countries of the waste were fully aware of the impacts from these practices, they would not accept such senseless act of the environmental and social harm.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Textile Waste and Its Impact\n\nMany individuals believe that the clothes they donate to charity or drop off at community recycling bins are given a second life and used by those in need. Unfortunately, this isn'\''t the whole truth. A 2018 report from the Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC) on the show \"Marketplace\" uncovered that only 1% of textile waste is actually recycled in a meaningful way. The rest of this waste follows a troubling path that reveals darker aspects of our global practices.\n\n## Unintended Consequences\n\nDue to strict environmental laws in wealthy nations, it'\''s both challenging and costly to incinerate or dispose of large amounts of textile waste locally. As a result, a significant portion of this waste is sent to developing countries far from where it was generated. While a small amount may be repurposed locally, the majority ends up being burned or buried without appropriate environmental protections, such as monitoring for harmful chemicals or strategies to prevent soil and water contamination.\n\nIt'\''s ironic that bulky sweaters and winter coats from colder regions often find their way to tropical countries, reflecting a prevalent \"Not In My Back Yard\" (NIMBY) mindset among residents of wealthy countries.\n\n## Misunderstandings and Environmental Effects\n\nAs global awareness of environmental issues increases, more people are thinking about their ecological impact. For instance, many would hesitate to throw a plastic bottle in the regular trash. Yet, they might still dump unwanted clothing in recycling bins or donate it to charity without realizing the negative repercussions. \n\nThis lack of understanding has important environmental implications. Not only does transporting this waste across oceans create a carbon footprint, but the textiles also contain harmful chemicals that can linger in the environment and cause long-term damage. This topic is further detailed in Chapter III: Lifecycle Assessment - Disposal.\n\n## A Humanitarian Crisis\n\nOne of the more alarming aspects of this situation is the social injustice it highlights. Residents in affluent countries frequently overlook the poor conditions faced by those in the nations receiving their unwanted textiles. In these areas, massive piles of textile waste can be found near rivers, and materials are often burned in places like school playgrounds.\n\nI believe that if people in the countries generating this waste were fully aware of the consequences of these actions, they would likely oppose such irresponsible practices that harm both the environment and vulnerable communities.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What percentage of textile waste is reclaimed and recycled in a true sense, according to the 2018 episode of '\''Marketplace'\''?"; options = vec { "10%"; "50%"; "1%"; "25%" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is a primary reason affluent countries send their textile waste to developing countries?"; options = vec { "They want to help those in need."; "It is more cost-effective than local disposal."; "They don'\''t have a use for the textiles."; "There are no regulations against it." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What environmental issue is associated with the disposal of textile waste in developing countries?"; options = vec { "Depletion of natural resources"; "Burning and burial without environmental safeguards"; "Increased biodiversity"; "Reduction of soil erosion" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How do affluent individuals often perceive their disposal of unwanted clothing?"; options = vec { "As harmful to the environment"; "As a moral obligation"; "With indifference to its environmental impact"; "As beneficial for those in need" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What do piles of textile waste in developing countries signify?"; options = vec { "Economic growth"; "Efficient recycling processes"; "Social injustice and environmental harm"; "Improved living conditions" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "4.2.0";
    unit_title = "Decomposition Myth (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "4.2";
    head_unit_title = "Decomposition Myth";
    content = "Many environmental interest groups often target synthetic fibers, due to their prolonged persistence in nature. It is commonly understood that natural fibers decompose and return to the environment much faster than synthetic fibers. However, while this basic scientific fact is true, there are many other critical factors that must be considered to fully understand the global environmental impacts of natural versus synthetic fibers.\nResidual Chemicals: Although natural fibers like cotton (cellulose-based) and wool (protein-based) degrade more quickly in nature, the chemicals used during their manufacturing and those left in the textile waste present a significant challenge in the environmental management. For instance, various colors in the textile products indicate the presence of the dye pigments and numerous other processing chemicals. These substances can leach into soil, contaminating runoff and groundwater in landfills, thereby entering the ecosystem. When incinerated, they pollute air and can spread globally through the atmospheric circulation.\nWhile more detailed information will be provided in Chapter II: Basics and Chapter III: Lifecycle Assessment, it is important to recognize that natural fibers often require significantly larger amounts of harmful chemicals during production compared to synthetic fibers, primarily due to their heightened chemical reactivity. Furthermore, the chemicals used for natural fibers are typically more reactive, as they are formulated to interact with the chemically active functional groups in these fibers, whereas the chemicals used for synthetic fibers generally do not depend on chemical reactions in the same manner. \nThus, understanding the quantity and toxicity of the chemicals involved in both natural and synthetic fibers is crucial for accurately assessing their true environmental impacts.\nEnvironmental Impacts \nToxicity of Pesticides for Farming Natural Fibers: Natural fibers, particularly the plant-based ones like cotton, are exposed to toxic chemicals from the very beginning of their lifecycles. Pesticides and fertilizers used in farming are designed to eliminate living organisms like insects and bugs and are therefore highly toxic. In high concentrations, they can even significantly harm humans and large animals. In fact, the toxicity of these chemicals far exceeds than that used in most other textile manufacturing processes such as dyeing. Much of this toxicity remains in the environment or in the textile materials themselves for periods that can far exceed multiples of human lifetime. \nDye Types Overview: Among all the stages of textile production outside the cultivation of natural fibers, the dyeing is typically most chemically intensive and creates the highest environmental impacts. Different types of fibers require different dyes and associated chemicals based on their chemical compositions. For example, cotton and wool require highly reactive dyes, known as \"Reactive Dyes”, while polyester uses a different type, known as \"Disperse Dyes\". As the name indicates, the reactive dyes contain chemical elements and substances which promote reactions with the chemical groups of the targeted fibers whereas the disperse dyes are designed to physically impregnate into the polymer structures of synthetic fibers.\nReaders familiar with hair dyeing and washing plastic food containers can easily draw parallels to textile dyeing. Like wool dyes, which are reactive and designed to chemically bond with the protein in wool, the hair dyes also involve a chemical reaction with the protein contained in the human hair. The dyed hair color fades over time relatively quickly, and proportionally with the frequency of washing. This can be compared with the colors on plastics, often found in food container lids, etc. These colors never fade regardless of how many times they are washed because they do not interact with water and does not shed color pigments. More detailed information on the dyeing related aspects will be provided in the following discussions including the dedicated Chapter II: 10.4.2 Dye Types and Toxicities.    \nChemical Reactivity and Environmental Impacts: In general, the environmental impacts of the reactive chemicals used in textile production relate to both their chemical reactivity and their persistence in the environment, either in their original forms or as the byproducts of associated chemical reactions. These impacts are particularly significant when more reactive substances, such as salts, heavy metals, etc., are involved in the process. On the other hand, less- or non-reactive chemicals, like the disperse dyes, tend to have environmental impacts more due to their persistence on their own rather than chemically reacting with their surroundings or creating byproducts. \nNatural Existence and Densification: Although many of the chemical elements and compounds used in the textile manufacturing exist naturally in the environment, their concentrations are typically low and do not pose health risks to humans and animals under usual circumstances. However, when these are artificially concentrated to achieve specific characteristics, their toxicity increases, posing significant threats to the living organisms and environmental sustainability. Pesticides, fertilizers, dyes, and various other chemicals used in the textiles are examples of these concentrated substances. Some of these compounds are known to cause severe health effects, including cancer, coma, and seizures. \n***\nDifferent chemical treatments required for natural versus synthetic fibers, while both are harmful, can lead to significantly different environmental outcomes. This topic is explored in detail throughout Chapter II and Chapter III. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Simplified Overview of Environmental Impacts of Natural and Synthetic Fibers\n\nMany environmental groups focus on synthetic fibers because they take a long time to break down in nature. It'\''s well-known that natural fibers decompose faster than synthetic ones. However, to really understand the environmental effects of natural versus synthetic fibers, we need to consider several important factors.\n\n## Chemicals Left Behind\nNatural fibers, like cotton (made from cellulose) and wool (made from protein), do break down more quickly. But, the chemicals used in their production and those that end up in waste pose serious environmental problems. For example, dyes and other processing chemicals are often present in textile products. These chemicals can seep into the soil, affecting groundwater and ecosystems when materials are disposed of in landfills. Additionally, incinerating textiles can release harmful substances into the air, which can spread globally.\n\nWhile we'\''ll delve into this further in Chapter II and Chapter III, it'\''s essential to note that natural fibers usually require more harmful chemicals during production than synthetic fibers. This is mainly because natural fibers are more chemically reactive. The chemicals used for natural fibers are designed to interact with their functional groups, while chemicals for synthetic fibers generally have a different interaction mechanism. Therefore, assessing the amount and toxicity of the chemicals involved in both types of fibers is critical for understanding their environmental impact.\n\n## Environmental Effects\n\n### Pesticides in Natural Fiber Farming\nNatural fibers, particularly plant-based ones like cotton, are exposed to harmful chemicals right from the farming stage. The pesticides and fertilizers used in agriculture are toxic, and at high levels, they can be dangerous to humans and large animals. The toxicity of these pesticides is much higher than that found in most textile manufacturing processes, such as dyeing. These harmful chemicals can remain in the environment and in textile products for much longer than a human lifespan.\n\n### Types of Dyes\nDyeing, which occurs after harvesting natural fibers, is one of the most chemical-intensive stages of textile production and has significant environmental impacts. Different fibers require different dyes based on their chemical makeup. For example, cotton and wool use \"Reactive Dyes,\" which are designed to chemically bond with the fibers, while polyester uses \"Disperse Dyes,\" which physically embed themselves in the synthetic fibers.\n\nTo understand this better, think about hair dyeing and washing plastic containers. Wool dyes work like hair dyes, forming a chemical bond with the protein in wool — the color fades quickly when washed frequently. In contrast, colors on plastics don'\''t fade because they don'\''t chemically interact with water.\n\nMore details about dyeing will be discussed in Chapter II, specifically in section 10.4.2 on Dye Types and Toxicities.\n\n### Chemical Reactivity and Environmental Impact\nThe environmental issues related to the reactive chemicals in textile production stem from their reactivity and how long they persist in the environment. More reactive substances, like salts and heavy metals, can have significant impacts. On the other hand, less reactive substances like disperse dyes mainly affect the environment due to their long-lasting presence rather than their reactivity.\n\n### Natural vs. Concentrated Chemicals\nWhile many chemicals used in textile production exist naturally, they are usually in low concentrations and don’t pose health risks. However, when these natural elements are concentrated for specific properties, their toxicity increases, becoming a major threat to living organisms and the environment. Chemicals used in textiles, such as pesticides and dyes, can lead to severe health issues, including cancer and severe neurological effects.\n\n---\n\nIn summary, both natural and synthetic fibers require different chemical treatments that, while harmful, can lead to different environmental outcomes. This topic will be explored further in Chapters II and III.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is a primary concern of environmental interest groups regarding synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "They are more expensive to produce."; "They decompose faster than natural fibers."; "They have a prolonged persistence in nature."; "They require less chemical processing." }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is one major issue with natural fibers like cotton regarding their environmental impact?"; options = vec { "They do not require any chemicals during production."; "They degrade quickly without any pollution."; "They are exposed to toxic pesticides during farming."; "They are made entirely from renewable resources." }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which type of dye is typically used for cotton and wool?"; options = vec { "Disperse Dyes"; "Reactive Dyes"; "Natural Dyes"; "Synthetic Dyes" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How do reactive chemicals in textile production primarily impact the environment?"; options = vec { "They evaporate completely."; "They are non-toxic."; "They can persist in the environment and create harmful byproducts."; "They degrade instantly without contaminating the soil." }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What happens when chemical substances used in textiles are artificially concentrated?"; options = vec { "Their health risks decrease."; "They become less reactive."; "Their toxicity increases and can harm living organisms."; "They blend into the environment without issues." }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "4.2.1";
    unit_title = "Duration of Decomposition";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "4.2";
    head_unit_title = "Decomposition Myth";
    content = "There is a myriad of information online regarding the decomposition durations of synthetic materials, but much of it lacks scientific validity, leading to widespread public misconceptions and associated environmental harm. An example is illustrated in Fig.16, where it is claimed that plastic bottles and diapers last for 450 years in nature. Other sources suggest even longer durations, some stating that plastic bottles may persist for 650 years or even indefinitely. These claims, often ranking high in various search engines like Google, contribute to the misinformation crisis we face today – more discussions to be presented in Chapter IV: Misinformation Crisis.\nFig.16   Example of Plastic Duration in Nature on Internet\nValidity of Information\nPlastic was invented in 1907 and has been around for just over a century. Naturally, scientific and analytical minds might question the claims about plastic persisting in nature for hundreds of years. Some might argue, \"If the modern science can calculate the Earth'\''s age at 4.55 billion years*, estimating plastic'\''s longevity in the range of hundreds of years shouldn’t be difficult.\" However, this line of thinking overlooks the fundamental principles behind the underlaying science.\n* The figure established by Dr. Clair Patterson and widely accepted in the scientific community\nRadioactive vs. Chemically Inert Materials: The methods used to determine the age of Earth and also ancient artifacts rely on the radioactive decay of certain elements. For example, Dr. Patterson used the half-life of a lead isotope to calculate the Earth'\''s age where the half-life refers to the time it takes for half of the atoms in a radioactive substance to decay.\nHowever, for these calculations to work, the material in question must contain a “radioactive” element. Plastics, by contrast, are chemically inert and do not undergo radioactive decay. In fact, if plastics were radioactive, it would be too dangerous for us to use them so close in our daily lives due to high health risks. This means that the science behind calculating the Earth'\''s age is fundamentally different from estimating the duration of the plastic decomposition. While there are scientific methods for studying the plastic degradation under specific conditions, these methods are based on vastly different scientific principles and cannot be used to accurately predict plastic'\''s decomposition timeline in the context of several hundreds of years. While related scientific details will be discussed in subsequent discussions, it is clear that widely circulated information on plastic decomposition such as the earlier “450 years” example lacks a solid scientific basis. \nPlastic Decomposition and Evidence \nAs such, one common misunderstanding in the textile sustainability is the perceived longevity of synthetic fibers (or plastics in general) in nature. To better understand this, let'\''s travel back in time to Seoul, South Korea, between 1978 and 1993. During this period, Nanji-do served as a massive landfill for the greater Seoul area, receiving an average of 3,000 truckloads of household waste daily. By the time it closed, it was the tallest landfill in the world, containing the total of 93 million tons of waste. \nPersonal Experience: I have a personal anecdote which relates to this site of Nanji-do. In 1995, as a young professional freshly landed in Seoul, I decided to save money on driving lessons by practicing at Nanji-do. Unlicensed driving instructors used the landfill site to draw parking and practice routes on flattened areas on top of the waste and offered lessons at much cheaper rates than licensed ones in the city. I commuted there for the lessons, enduring severe odor coming from the decaying waste and observed firsthand the compositions of the waste, including large amounts of plastics (see Fig.17 for the examples of colorful plastic waste).\nFig.17 Nanji-do in the 90’s\nAfter I immigrated to Canada in the late 1990s, Nanji-do faded from my memory. Then, years later, I came across a news article reporting that the landfill had been transformed into a part of the Seoul Sangam World Cup Stadium Park. Interestingly, a portion of Nanji-do was designated for a power plant that generates electricity using the gas from the decomposition of the household waste, including plastics. From the landfill'\''s closure to the extraction of this gas, it took about 30 years.\nFig.18   Nanji-do NOW\nOur Own Observations: Now, let’s fly out of Seoul and return to our own backyards and surroundings. Many of us have encountered plastic pieces left in the environment, perhaps picked up while walking or gardening. If you have purchased plants from a local store, you may have noticed that they often come wrapped in black plastic bags around the soil.\nSignificant Strength Degradation: Our experiences with unused or freshly used plastic bags give us a baseline for the typical strength of plastics in daily use. Compare this to the plastics used to wrap the soil, which often show significant strength degradation after being in contact with the soil for a relatively short time. In the perspective of the plastic manufacturing, it is implausible to intentionally make the initial quality of the plastics so fragile due to their inherent characteristics related to the polymerization principles. Although not a perfect \"apples-to-apples\" comparison, we can easily estimate that these plastics weakened over time as they tear or puncture far more easily than the baseline reference based on our experiences, suggesting that the decrease in the strength was associated with the soil contact. \nScience of Degradation: In scientific terms, the degradation of the plastic strength indicates that the polymer chains inside the plastics broke down. To illustrate this concept, imagine a fishnet: if a few of its connecting parts are broken, the net'\''s overall structure becomes compromised and the strength decreases. Similarly, when the bonds within the plastic'\''s polymer chains break, the material loses its strength. \nPractical Experiment: A curious mind can easily verify this phenomenon at home: Bury a piece of plastic bag under wet soil in a shaded area and leave it for a month or two while keeping another identical piece in a kitchen cabinet. After a certain duration, the buried plastic will have significantly lost its strength, while the stored plastic will remain intact. This experiment is a practical way to observe the plastic degradation without having to wait \"hundreds of years\", the durations often cited on the internet - I recommended using plastic bags used in grocery shopping for this experiment because the effects will be more readily noticeable in a relatively short time frame and can be verified without the need of laboratory equipment. \n***\nAs mentioned earlier, plastics are not radioactive and chemically inert. Thus, the plastic degradation is based on a different scientific principle than the radioactive decay method of accurately calculating the ages of ancient artifacts. It is in fact due to the existence of the plastic-eating bacteria in nature. In certain conditions, such as chemically active landfills, these bacteria thrive in higher densities and exhibit increased level of activities. Certain chemical compositions, temperatures, and pressures present in such landfills significantly aid these bacteria in degrading plastics at a much faster rate than what many sources suggest on the internet. The Nanji-do landfill is a prime example of this accelerated degradation process. Furthermore, the subsequent discussion of creating the artificial conditions of plastic decomposition is another example.  \nArtificial Conditions of Decomposition: Another piece of evidence comes from various “biodegradability” claims made by many companies today on certain plastics. In some laboratory or manufacturing environments, specific conditions such as particular bacterial compositions, temperature, pressure, etc., can be created for plastic degradation, the conditions reflective of actual landfills (anaerobic degradation), or left in the open air (aerobic degradation). \nWhile humans can create and adjust these conditions for accelerating or decelerating the degradation rates, they do not create the bacteria themselves. These organisms naturally exist in the environment and constantly at work to break down the materials left in nature. By definition, therefore, all plastics are biodegradable and many biodegradability claims, unfortunately, are simply the exploitation of the public interests on the environmental sustainability with the misrepresentation of the underlying science for their benefits.  \nVariabilities of Plastic Decomposition: Different pieces of plastics degrade at varying speeds. The form factor of plastics whether they are thin and light like plastic bags and bottles or thicker and heavier like food containers affects how easily the bacteria can access and break down the polymer chains. Additionally, the density of plastics plays a crucial role: the higher the density, the more challenging it is for the bacteria to penetrate the polymer structures and break the links.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Plastic Decomposition\n\nThere is a lot of information available online about how long synthetic materials take to decompose, but much of this information is not scientifically accurate. This can lead to public misunderstandings and environmental damage. For instance, some sources claim that plastic bottles and diapers take 450 years to decompose in nature, with others suggesting even longer durations, like 650 years or more. These popular claims often appear at the top of search results, contributing to the ongoing misinformation issues we face today, which will be further discussed in Chapter IV: Misinformation Crisis.\n\n## Validity of Information\n\nPlastic has been around since 1907, and scientific experts may wonder about the accuracy of claims regarding its long-lasting presence in nature. Some might think, \"If scientists can determine the Earth'\''s age as 4.55 billion years*, deciding how long plastic lasts should be simpler.\" However, this reasoning misunderstands the principles behind the science involved.\n\n*This figure was established by Dr. Clair Patterson and is widely accepted in the scientific community.\n\n### Radioactive vs. Chemically Inert Materials\n\nThe methods used to determine the Earth'\''s age and the age of ancient items depend on the radioactive decay of certain elements. Dr. Patterson, for example, calculated the Earth'\''s age by using the half-life of a lead isotope, which indicates the time needed for half of the atoms in a radioactive substance to decay.\n\nFor these methods to work, the materials being studied must contain radioactive elements. Plastics, on the other hand, are chemically inert and do not decay radioactively. If plastics were radioactive, they would pose significant health dangers if used in everyday products. This highlights that the science of determining the Earth'\''s age is fundamentally different from predicting how long plastics take to decompose. While there are scientific methods to study plastic degradation under specific conditions, these methods cannot accurately determine how long it takes plastic to break down over hundreds of years. The widely shared claims about plastic decomposition, such as the \"450 years\" example, lack a strong scientific basis.\n\n## Plastic Decomposition and Evidence\n\nA common misconception in textile sustainability is the belief that synthetic fibers (or plastics in general) last a long time in nature. To illustrate this idea, let’s look back at Seoul, South Korea, from 1978 to 1993. During this time, Nanji-do was a massive landfill for the greater Seoul area, receiving about 3,000 truckloads of household waste daily. By the time it closed, it had become the tallest landfill in the world, containing a staggering 93 million tons of waste.\n\n### Personal Experience\n\nI have a personal story related to Nanji-do. In 1995, as a new professional in Seoul, I chose to save money on driving lessons by practicing at the landfill. Unlicensed instructors offered lessons in the area, which was significantly cheaper than licensed ones in the city. Traveling there, I endured strong odors from the decaying waste and saw firsthand the types of refuse, including large amounts of plastics (see Fig. 17 for examples of colorful plastic waste).\n\nAfter moving to Canada in the late 1990s, I forgot about Nanji-do. Years later, I read that the landfill had been converted into part of the Seoul Sangam World Cup Stadium Park. Interestingly, a section of Nanji-do was turned into a power plant using gas from the breakdown of household waste, including plastics. This transformation took about 30 years after the landfill closed.\n\n### Observing Our Environment\n\nLet'\''s take a moment to consider our own surroundings. Many of us have seen plastic pieces left behind in nature, perhaps while walking or gardening. If you'\''ve bought plants from a local store, you'\''ve likely noticed them wrapped in black plastic bags around the soil.\n\n### Comparing Plastics\n\nOur experiences with new plastic bags set a baseline for understanding their typical strength. In contrast, the plastic wrapping soil often shows noticeable degradation in strength after only a short time. From a manufacturing perspective, it'\''s unlikely that plastics are intentionally made weak, as this does not align with the principles of polymer chemistry. While it isn’t a perfect comparison, we can conclude that these plastics weaken over time, tearing and puncturing more easily after being in soil, suggesting that their strength reduction is related to this contact.\n\n## The Science of Degradation\n\nScientifically speaking, the weakening of plastic indicates that its polymer chains are breaking down. To visualize this, consider a fishnet: if some connections break, the net loses its overall strength. Similarly, when bonds within a plastic'\''s polymer chains fail, the material'\''s strength diminishes.\n\n### Practical Experiment\n\nAnyone curious can easily test this concept at home: bury a piece of a plastic bag in moist soil in a shaded area and leave it there for a month or two, while keeping another identical piece in a kitchen cabinet. After a while, the buried plastic will show significant strength loss, while the stored plastic will remain undamaged. This simple experiment can demonstrate plastic degradation without waiting \"hundreds of years,\" as commonly claimed online. I recommend using grocery store plastic bags for this experiment because the changes will be visible in a shorter period and require no laboratory tools.\n\n## Key Points on Plastic Decomposition\n\nAs previously mentioned, plastics are chemically inert and not radioactive. This means that the degradation of plastics is governed by different scientific principles than those used in determining the ages of ancient artifacts. The breakdown of plastics is influenced by naturally occurring plastic-eating bacteria. In environments like active landfills, these bacteria can thrive and break down plastics much more quickly than many sources online suggest. Nanji-do serves as a prime example of accelerated degradation.\n\n### Artificial Decomposition Conditions\n\nAnother aspect to consider is the claims of \"biodegradability\" advertised by many companies for specific plastics. In controlled lab or manufacturing environments, certain conditions—such as bacterial types, temperature, and pressure—can be created that mimic real landfill conditions (anaerobic degradation) or open-air environments (aerobic degradation).\n\nWhile it’s possible for us to set conditions that speed up or slow down degradation, we do not create the bacteria themselves; these organisms exist in nature and work continuously to break down materials left in the environment. Therefore, all plastics are technically biodegradable. Unfortunately, many claims about biodegradability exploit public interest in environmental sustainability by misrepresenting the science for profit.\n\n### Factors Affecting Plastic Decomposition\n\nNot all plastics decompose at the same rate. The shape and thickness of plastic—whether thin like bags or thick like food containers—affect how easily bacteria can access and break down their polymer chains. Furthermore, the density of plastics is crucial: the denser the plastic, the harder it is for bacteria to penetrate and degrade the structure.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is a common misconception about the decomposition of plastic materials?"; options = vec { "Plastic decomposes in a few years."; "Plastic is radioactive and decays like certain elements."; "Plastic bottles last for hundreds of years in nature."; "Plastic is entirely non-biodegradable." }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What factor does NOT impact the degradation rate of plastics in landfills?"; options = vec { "Chemical compositions present"; "Temperature and pressure conditions"; "The history of the plastic material"; "Presence of plastic-eating bacteria" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What experiment can one perform to observe plastic degradation?"; options = vec { "Bury a piece of metal in the soil."; "Leave a plastic bag outside for years."; "Bury a piece of plastic bag under wet soil and compare it with one kept indoors."; "Soak a plastic bag in water for a week." }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Why are plastics not subjected to radioactive decay?"; options = vec { "Plastics are made from metals."; "Plastics are chemically inert and do not contain radioactive elements."; "Plastics decompose quickly compared to other materials."; "Plastics are biodegradable in all conditions." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What environmental condition accelerates plastic degradation?"; options = vec { "High temperatures and dry conditions."; "Low density of plastics."; "Presence of specific bacteria in chemically active landfills."; "Exposure to sunlight." }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "4.3.0";
    unit_title = "Biodegradability";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I";
    head_unit_id = "4.3";
    head_unit_title = "Biodegradability";
    content = "The term \"biodegradability\" has recently become a major source of misinformation and greenwashing by many organizations, exploiting the public’s keen interest and pursuit of the environmental sustainability. In this subsection, I will debunk some myths surrounding \"biodegradable\" plastics.\nBefore diving in, it is important for the public to understand that the term \"biodegradable\" by itself does not necessarily indicate an environmental benefit. There are many factors involved in this simple term, and without understanding these nuances, the public can be misled as the term is often used out of context.\nDefinitions\nThe first step is to clearly define the “biodegradability”. A plastic is considered biodegradable if it breaks down under natural conditions. As discussed earlier, however, all plastics are technically biodegradable due to the activities of the plastic-eating bacteria in nature. Given enough time, all plastics will eventually degrade. Therefore, this discussion begins with highlighting the inherent flaw in “biodegradable” claims. \nContext: In the context of labeling a plastic as “biodegradable”, specific conditions, typically in laboratory settings, are used to assess its degradation characteristics in a certain form factor under controlled environment. These conditions involve carefully regulated factors such as bacterial activity, temperature, pressure, and chemical composition in relation with a time factor. \nHowever, this approach has limitations. For example, a thin plastic might be classified as \"biodegradable\" based on the test results obtained under certain conditions, while a thicker piece of the same polymer may not be, due to the differences in how easily bacteria can access the polymer chains and the rate of degradation. Additionally, real-world conditions in landfills vary significantly across the globe, making it unrealistic to expect that a plastic labeled \"biodegradable\" will degrade the same way in diverse environmental conditions as it did in the controlled test environment.\nThus, it is important to approach the term \"biodegradable\" with caution, as it can be easily misunderstood or misused by profit-driven organizations. The public should also be aware that they should not mistakenly assume plastics without a \"biodegradable\" label do not naturally degrade.\nIn this discussion, I use the term \"biodegradable\" reluctantly and only within the context of common understanding in the industry, while acknowledging the limitations of its definition. \nBioplastic: The term \"bioplastic\" refers to the plastics that are produced from natural biomass sources of either plants or animals such as corn starch, woodchips, proteins, etc., or the presence of bacteria in their synthesis. However, not all bioplastics can be identified as “biodegradable” according to the definition mentioned earlier. For example, bio-based PET (polyethylene terephthalate) is a non-“biodegradable” bioplastic. Even though it is synthesized with the presence of bacteria, the chemical structure of the bio-based PET remains identical to its fossil fuel-derived counterparts, including its decomposition properties. Some studies show that certain bioplastics can be manufactured with a lower carbon footprint than their fossil counterparts while other bioplastics'\'' processes are less efficient and result in a higher carbon footprint than fossil plastics. \nAlthough more comprehensive understanding is required rather than simply accepting the results of these studies, it can be easily concluded that we cannot automatically assume an environmental benefit from the term of “bioplastic”, the theme which applies for the remainder of the discussions of this subject. \nOxo-Degradable Plastics: Another example is “oxo-degradable” plastics. Despite their seemingly eco-friendly name, they are essentially conventional plastics with additives known as pro-degradants that accelerate oxidation process under specific conditions involving oxygen. While oxo-degradable plastics break down more quickly when exposed to sunlight and oxygen, conditions typically found in open air rather than in landfills or water, this process merely fragments the plastic into microplastics. As a result, the perceived benefit can lead to other environmental and health risks as microplastics contaminate air and water, ultimately entering the food chain and posing threats to both human and animal health.\nCompostable Plastics: In some cases, compostable plastics are labeled as “biodegradable”. Compostable plastics decompose within a specified timeframe under controlled conditions typically found in industrial composting facilities. These facilities create optimal environments for decomposition, including high temperatures, controlled pressure, and specific chemical conditions. Accelerating the decomposition rate of otherwise-naturally-degrading plastics renders this factory-based decomposition process economically inviable. Thus, there are very few such facilities, and they are generally used for specialized purposes.\nDegradability of Plastics: An important aspect of these discussions is the natural degradability of all plastics, as repeatedly emphasized throughout this section. To substantiate claims of more favorable environmental impacts, a “biodegradable” plastic must be proven to degrade in natural conditions, such as in landfills, air, or water, considerably faster than other plastics, and without creating harmful side effects.\nWith this premise in mind, it is beneficial to review the scopes of a typical test method used to label plastics as “biodegradable” and other related claims.\n***Industry Specifics (3) – Start***\nASTM D5511 – 18\nExcerpts of the test method includes the following statements: \nThis test method is designed to yield a percentage of conversion of carbon in the sample to carbon in the gaseous form under conditions found in high-solids anaerobic digesters, treating municipal solid waste.  This test method may also resemble some conditions in biologically active landfills where the gas generated is recovered and biogas production is actively promoted by inoculation (for example, code position of anaerobic sewage sludge, anaerobic leachate recirculation), moisture control (for example, leachate recirculation), and temperature control (for example, short-term injection of oxygen, heating of recirculated leachate).\nClaims of performance shall be limited to the numerical result obtained in the test and not be used for unqualified “biodegradable” claims. Reports shall clearly state the percentage of net gaseous carbon generation for both the test and reference samples at the completion of the test. Furthermore, results shall not be extrapolated past the actual duration of the test. \n***Industry Specifics (3) – End***\nAs a result, the outcomes of this test method can only be presented as numeric data and cannot be used to justify \"biodegradable\" claims. Several other test methods under similar scope exist globally.\nCorporate Misconduct: Unfortunately, many companies exploit the fact that consumers are unlikely to fully understand the implications of such claims, taking advantage of this loophole. While this approach is clearly unethical, such corporate misconduct is not uncommon. Companies often present limited information without proper context, leading consumers to instant misperceptions. This behavior is typical of the organizations that prioritize short-term gains over transparency, due diligence and honest effort to truly benefit the environment.\nEven if we extend the benefit of doubt and assume that these companies lacked the necessary knowledge and acted unknowingly, this does not absolve them of their social and environmental responsibilities. A couple of hours of thorough reading would be enough to grasp the basics of the subject matters and guide them to avoid being engaged in such acts. Failing to put in even this minimal effort and commitment can only be described as misconduct and greenwashing. Having spent decades in the global textile industry, I find it deplorable to witness this level of dishonesty even from some of the most reputable brands which undeservedly enjoy a high level of consumer trust.\nPoor Business Practices and Greenwashing\nCompanies making “biodegradable” claims must present all relevant information clearly and transparently, ensuring consumers can easily understand the scope and limitations of the tests utilised, rather than simply labeling products as \"biodegradable\". Several countries, including the USA, European Union, Australia, and Japan, have regulations to prevent companies from using \"biodegradability\" claims as a form of greenwashing. However, many claims are still made without proper substantiation or adequate context, leaving consumers misinformed. \n“Biodegradable” Thermal Insulation?: Some companies exploit other loopholes in “biodegradability”. For example, a company in the thermal insulation industry claims that one of its products is “biodegradable”. \nIn manufacturing, thermal insulation materials are sandwiched between lining fabrics and enclosed within the structure of finished goods. This means that these materials are not typically exposed to the external environment in nature. The lining fabrics themselves can vary widely in characteristics - some are thin and lightweight, while others are thick and heavy, often coated with polymeric membranes, all acting as barriers against bacterial access.\nWhen testing “biodegradable” materials, they are evaluated in isolation, without considering other components of finished products. Therefore, this approach of using the “biodegradable” conclusion obtained from such method works for single-layer items, such as shirts or pants, where the fabrics in question can be directly exposed to similar decomposition conditions in nature. However, for multi-layered structures like winter jackets or heavy blankets that contain thermal insulation materials inside, any “biodegradability” claim about the insulation material must also account for various lining fabrics used. \nGiven the wide variability in these fabrics and structures of finished products, I can confidently assert that verifying the “biodegradability” of thermal insulation materials in nature is virtually impossible.\nJust Another Exploitation Example: Yet, the thermal insulation company continues to make their unsubstantiated “biodegradability” claims without addressing these concerns. As previously discussed, the public'\''s lack of knowledge enables the prevalence of numerous cases of exploitation by these greenwashing organizations.\n***\nAs a consumer, I do not consider accelerated biodegradability of plastics to be beneficial to my lifestyle. If a plastic'\''s biodegradability is significantly enhanced compared to regular plastics, I would be concerned about its degradation during use. I keep most of my textile goods for decades, such as the very first suit I wore for my university graduations, still hanging in my closet and occasionally worn. I would not want them to degrade in my closet and continuous use.  \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Biodegradability and Its Implications\n\nThe concept of \"biodegradability\" has become a common topic of confusion and may even be used misleadingly by various organizations. They often take advantage of people'\''s interest in environmental sustainability. In this section, we will clarify some common misconceptions about \"biodegradable\" plastics.\n\n## What Does \"Biodegradable\" Mean?\n\nFirst, let'\''s define what \"biodegradable\" means. A plastic is labeled biodegradable if it can break down naturally over time. However, technically speaking, all plastics can eventually biodegrade because of bacteria that consume plastic in the environment. This brings us to the main issue: the term \"biodegradable\" can be misleading.\n\n### The Context of Biodegradability\n\nWhen a plastic is described as \"biodegradable,\" it often refers to specific laboratory conditions designed to test how quickly it breaks down. These controlled tests consider various factors, such as:\n\n- Bacterial presence\n- Temperature\n- Pressure\n- Chemical composition\n- Time\n\nHowever, this testing method has drawbacks. For instance, a thin plastic might be labeled \"biodegradable\" because it degrades faster in a controlled environment, while a thicker piece made of the same material may not degrade as quickly. Furthermore, real-world conditions in landfills and natural settings differ from laboratory conditions, making it unrealistic to assume \"biodegradable\" plastics will break down similarly in everyday environments.\n\nThus, we should be cautious about the term \"biodegradable,\" as it can be misused by companies looking to profit. It’s also important to note that just because a plastic does not carry a \"biodegradable\" label, it doesn’t mean it won’t eventually break down.\n\n### Awareness of Bioplastics\n\nMoving on, the term \"bioplastic\" refers to plastics made from natural materials like plants or animals (for example, corn starch or woodchips). However, not all bioplastics are biodegradable. A case in point is bio-based PET (polyethylene terephthalate), which is made with bacteria but does not biodegrade any faster than its fossil-fuel-derived counterpart.\n\nSome studies suggest that certain bioplastics can have a lower carbon footprint than traditional plastics, while others may actually result in a higher carbon footprint. It is crucial not to automatically assume that \"bioplastics\" are better for the environment without carefully examining the details.\n\n### Understanding Oxo-Degradable Plastics\n\nNext, let’s discuss \"oxo-degradable\" plastics. These are regular plastics enhanced with additives (called pro-degradants) that speed up oxidation under certain conditions, like exposure to sunlight and oxygen. While they break down faster in the open air, they only fragment into microplastics rather than fully degrading. This creates new environmental concerns, as these microplastics can pollute air and water and enter the food chain, posing risks to both humans and wildlife.\n\n### The Role of Compostable Plastics\n\nSome plastics are also labeled as \"compostable,\" which leads to confusion with \"biodegradable.\" Compostable plastics can break down within a specific timeframe under controlled conditions found in industrial compost facilities. However, these facilities are uncommon, so it’s not a widely applicable solution for all biodegradable claims.\n\n### Key Points About Plastic Degradability\n\nIt’s important to remember that all plastics will degrade naturally over time. Claims about a \"biodegradable\" plastic must demonstrate that it breaks down significantly faster than other plastics in natural settings (like landfills, soil, or water) and does not produce harmful substances in the process.\n\n### Industry Testing Standards\n\nTo ensure clarity, let’s review a typical test method used for assessing biodegradability, such as **ASTM D5511 – 18**. This method measures how much carbon from a plastic sample converts to gaseous carbon under the anaerobic conditions found in high-solid digesters. The results of such tests should only be presented as numerical data and cannot be used to make broad claims about biodegradability.\n\n### Corporate Responsibility and Transparency\n\nUnfortunately, many companies take advantage of the confusion surrounding biodegradability. They often provide incomplete information or misrepresent their products for profit. This practice is unethical and can mislead consumers. Companies have a responsibility to be transparent and clarify the specifics of their products instead of relying on vague terms.\n\n### The Case of Thermal Insulation Products\n\nSome companies even exploit the term \"biodegradable\" in niche markets, such as thermal insulation. For instance, these materials are usually enclosed within other layers, making it difficult for them to decompose naturally. Thus, claims about biodegradability must consider the entire structure of the product, not just isolated materials.\n\n### Personal Consumer Perspective\n\nAs a consumer, I do not find enhanced biodegradability appealing. For example, if a plastic is designed to degrade much faster than usual, I would worry about its durability during use. I want my textile items, like my graduation suit, to last for years rather than degrade when I store or wear them.\n\n---\n\nBy taking a closer look at these concepts, we can make more informed choices about plastics and their environmental impact, while also holding companies accountable for their claims.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What does the term '\''biodegradable'\'' imply about plastics?"; options = vec { "They are guaranteed to decompose quickly in all environments"; "They can break down under natural conditions"; "They are always eco-friendly"; "They cannot be made from fossil fuels" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which type of plastic is specifically identified as non-biodegradable despite being produced from natural sources?"; options = vec { "Oxo-degradable plastics"; "Compostable plastics"; "Bioplastics"; "Bio-based PET" }; answer = 3; }; record { question = "What is a major concern regarding oxo-degradable plastics?"; options = vec { "They completely disappear without a trace"; "They can take longer to degrade than regular plastics"; "They break down into microplastics, which are harmful"; "They are easier to recycle than regular plastics" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "How are compostable plastics defined differently from other biodegradable plastics?"; options = vec { "They decompose in any environment"; "They require specific conditions in industrial composting facilities"; "They are synthetically produced"; "They do not produce any gases during decomposition" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is a criticism of companies making '\''biodegradable'\'' claims?"; options = vec { "They always provide complete and transparent information"; "They may exploit consumer misconceptions and greenwash"; "They use biodegradable materials exclusively"; "They prioritize long-term sustainability practices" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "5.0";
    unit_title = "Unfortunate Recycling";
    chapter_id = "I";
    chapter_title = "Chapter I: Consumers, Be Aware and Beware!";
    head_unit_id = "5";
    head_unit_title = ". Unfortunate Recycling";
    content = "Many people form opinions and perspectives on various aspects of life based on single-word descriptions or short phrases. \"Recycling\" is one such example. Given the global importance of the environmental sustainability, one might expect questions like, \"Is recycling done without creating negative environmental impacts?\" to be common. However, this is often not the case.\nFace value: Even among the most educated members of our society, there is a tendency to accept convenient notions and purchase textiles with such brief sustainability claims. Labels such as \"Recycled\" or \"Made from x number of plastic bottles\" are often taken at face value.\nSerious Gap: There are several key reasons for this phenomenon. One is that consumers often place too much trust in the companies making various sustainability claims. Furthermore, consumers may not be trained to ask critical questions and often lack diligence to seek truth on more complex issues which do not create more immediate and observable impacts in their lives. Unfortunately, environmental matters are of such characteristics. Together, these factors create a significant gap that allows for numerous corporate misconducts, where untrained consumers are exploited. \nGiven the prevalence of greenwashing, even by some of the most trusted organizations globally, the public'\''s overly simplistic approach to various sustainability claims does little to benefit the environment. It is crucial for consumers to take a more critical stance and demand transparent, comprehensive information in order to make informed decisions that truly benefit the environment.\nRecycling Myth\nPlastic recycling can be conducted in various ways, but the most conventional methods unfortunately result in critically negative environmental impacts. In fact, we do not even know if there is a clear net benefit from the current global recycling efforts. For many readers, this statement may be surprising, as most consumers believe that purchasing goods made from recycled contents is beneficial for the environment. Here, I present the information that may challenge this common understanding.\nImportation Ban on Plastic Waste: Many people may recall the garbage crisis that most Western countries experienced in the late 2010s, which was precipitated by China’s total ban on the importation of plastic waste, the primary source for plastic recycling - For years, advanced economies had been exporting large quantities of their plastic waste to China and other countries, and this sudden ban led to local waste crises.\nChina’s Gradual Actions and Similar Actions by Other Countries: Although the ban seemed abrupt to the Western world, the Chinese government had initiated related measures as early as 2013 with the CHINA GREEN FENCE policy. This was followed by the CHINA NATIONAL SWORD policy in 2017, culminating in the total ban in 2018. Subsequently, many other countries, such as Vietnam, Malaysia, Thailand, etc., implemented similar measures, focusing on processing only their own domestic plastic waste. The actions taken by these governments stem from a clear understanding of the negative environmental impacts associated with the conventional recycling processes and are now spread to a large number of other underdeveloped and developing countries around the world.\nIn this discussion, I will elucidate four main areas of negative impacts caused by the conventional methods, accompanied by the flow map depicted in Fig.19.\nFig.19   Overview of Conventional Plastic Recycling\nInefficient Carbon Footprint: The processes result in a significantly inefficient carbon footprint due to the transportation of plastic waste across international oceans, as most recycling facilities are located in countries far from the consumption centers where the waste is generated. Given that a substantial portion of the plastics used in the products and packaging originates from these distant countries to begin with, shipping the waste back to the regions of origin exacerbates the inefficiency in the carbon footprint management\nMicroplastics in Manufacturing: Most conventional recycling is carried out through a process known as “crushing” and “grinding”, shown by “2” in Fig.19. This method involves applying substantial physical force to break the waste into small pieces, which are then submerged in a large pool of water.\nThe purpose of this process is to remove dirt and foreign materials contained in the waste. Observations at the storage yards of recycling facilities readily reveal such heavy contamination present in the plastic waste, waiting to be processed.\nFig.20   Contaminated Plastic Bottles\nGiven the diverse shapes, sizes, and types of contamination present, the only commercially viable way is to crush the plastics and break them into small pieces, then use water to wash away the contaminants. Fig.21 illustrates the stage of the process where the crushed plastics are deposited into a large quantity of water. \nFig.21   Crushed Plastics \nAdditional details of such process can be found in the YouTube video link below.\nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=URfgzIa1UfY&t=35s  \nThe application of heavy physical forces to break down the plastics inevitably generates a significant amount of debris, including microplastics. \nStrength Factor and Environmental Harm: Despite the extensive cleaning efforts, which involve heavy water and electricity usage, microplastic generation, and potential chemical use to dissolve certain types of contaminants, it is virtually impossible to remove all foreign materials. As a result, significant quantities of these contaminants persist throughout the subsequent recycling processes and become integrated into the recycled fibers. \nThese contaminated recycled plastics exhibit distinctive colors. Higher proportions of contaminants result in a more greyish tone in the polymer pellets, as shown in Fig.22, which are then converted into fibers, carrying the grey tone over. This color difference cannot be detected by consumers, as various efforts are made during subsequent dyeing processes to conceal such imperfections.\nFig.22   Recycled Pellets (left) vs. Virgin Pellets (right)\nThe presence of contaminants in the recycled fibers adversely affects their strength as it hinders the formation of polymer structures during the subsequent melting process. As a result, most recycled fibers are invariably much weaker than their virgin counterparts. In some cases, the tensile stress and strain, and consequently the total breaking energy, of recycled fibers are less than 50% of those of virgin fibers.\nThe reduced strength of recycled fibers contributes to shedding more microplastics and chemicals during manufacturing and consumption as textile materials encounter various physical forces during their lifecycles. \nHarmful Chemicals: Recycled fibers undergo identical manufacturing and consumption processes as virgin fibers, including chemically intensive dyeing process. It is well-known within the industry that different dyeing formulations must be used for recycled fibers to compensate the varying degrees of contamination to achieve desired color tones and hues whereas pure virgin fibers do not present such issue. This necessity may lead to increased usage of color pigments and other chemicals to counteract their inherent greyish tones.\nMoreover, recycled fibers may lose color pigments and other chemicals more readily during use as the contaminants can impede the fixation of these chemicals within their polymer structures, resulting in a higher quantity of chemical release into the environment.\n***\nIn conclusion, there is no clear evidence to suggest that the conventional recycling efforts yield a net benefit in the overall environmental management. In my view, the disadvantages can easily outweigh the benefits. Increased quantities of microplastics alone could justify ceasing these activities altogether. \nI have long argued that, given today’s inefficiencies in plastic recycling, resulting in considerable harm, the best option is to place plastics in landfills. Unlike textile waste, plastics generally do not contain harmful dyes or chemicals. Even colorized plastics likely contain non-reactive dyes that do not interact with the environment. While plastics may remain in landfills for extended periods, they are less likely to contribute to other significant environmental harms.\nThe good news is that we do have a viable solution based on the principles of successful plastic recycling. This topic will be further explored in Chapter V: Solutions, specifically in the Clean Recycling Initiative™ section. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Recycling and Its Challenges\n\nMany people form opinions about different aspects of life based on single words or short phrases. One example is \"recycling.\" Given how important environmental sustainability is globally, you might expect questions like, \"Does recycling have negative environmental effects?\" to be common. Unfortunately, that’s not often the case.\n\n## Face Value of Sustainability Claims\nEven among well-educated individuals, there'\''s a tendency to accept simple claims and buy textiles with brief sustainability labels. Terms like \"Recycled\" or \"Made from X number of plastic bottles\" are frequently taken at face value without further investigation.\n\n## The Serious Gap\nSeveral reasons explain this trend. First, consumers often overly trust companies that make sustainability claims. Additionally, many people are not trained to ask critical questions or may not feel compelled to find out more about complex environmental issues, especially when these issues don’t have immediate impacts on their daily lives. This lack of scrutiny can lead to significant gaps, allowing corporate misconduct where uninformed consumers may be exploited.\n\nWith the prevalence of \"greenwashing,\" even by trusted organizations, the public’s simplistic approach to sustainability claims doesn’t benefit the environment. It’s crucial for consumers to adopt a more critical attitude and demand clear, comprehensive information to make informed choices that genuinely help the planet.\n\n## The Recycling Myth\nRecycling plastic can be done in various ways, but the standard methods often have serious negative environmental effects. Surprisingly, we still lack clear evidence that global recycling efforts have a net positive effect. Many consumers believe buying products made from recycled materials is eco-friendly, but this assumption needs reevaluation.\n\n### Importation Ban on Plastic Waste\nYou may remember the trash crisis in Western countries during the late 2010s, which stemmed from China’s ban on importing plastic waste—the main source for plastic recycling. For years, developed nations had been sending large amounts of plastic waste to China, and this sudden ban caused local waste management issues.\n\n### China and Other Countries'\'' Actions\nWhile the ban appeared sudden, the Chinese government had introduced related policies starting in 2013 with the CHINA GREEN FENCE and followed by the CHINA NATIONAL SWORD policy in 2017, culminating in the total ban in 2018. Other countries, like Vietnam and Thailand, soon implemented similar measures, focusing on processing only their own domestic plastic waste. These decisions were driven by an understanding of the negative environmental impacts tied to traditional recycling methods.\n\n### Key Negative Impacts of Conventional Recycling\nI will outline four main areas of concern regarding traditional recycling methods.\n\n1. **Inefficient Carbon Footprint**: Recycling often involves shipping plastic waste over long distances, especially since most recycling facilities are far from where the waste is generated. This transportation adds significantly to the carbon footprint, worsening rather than improving sustainability.\n\n2. **Microplastics in Manufacturing**: Conventional recycling typically uses a crushing and grinding method to break down plastics, which generates a lot of debris, including microplastics. Contaminated plastic needs heavy cleaning, which also adds to environmental degradation.\n\n3. **Strength Factor and Environmental Harm**: Despite extensive cleaning efforts, it’s almost impossible to eliminate all contaminants, which remain in the recycling process. These impurities weaken the recycled fibers, leading to the production of weaker textiles that shed more microplastics and chemicals into the environment.\n\n4. **Harmful Chemicals**: Recycled fibers go through the same manufacturing processes as virgin fibers, including chemical dyeing. However, recycled fibers require different formulations due to their contamination levels, which can increase the amount of harmful chemicals used. Contaminants can also prevent dyes from binding properly, leading to greater chemical release during use.\n\n## Conclusion\nThere is no strong evidence that traditional recycling provides a net benefit for environmental management. The disadvantages, especially the increase in microplastics, may outweigh the benefits. Given the current inefficiencies in plastic recycling, which lead to significant harm, it may be better to place plastics in landfills. Unlike textile waste, plastics generally do not contain harmful dyes or chemicals. Even colored plastics tend to have non-reactive dyes that are less likely to harm the environment.\n\nHowever, there is a viable solution based on successful recycling principles, which will be discussed further in Chapter V: Solutions, specifically in the Clean Recycling Initiative™ section.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is a common misconception consumers have about recycling?"; options = vec { "Recycling is always beneficial for the environment."; "Recycling reduces the need for landfills."; "All recycling processes are effective."; "Recycling requires no energy." }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "Which country implemented a total ban on the importation of plastic waste in 2018?"; options = vec { "Vietnam"; "Malaysia"; "China"; "Thailand" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What major impact does the international transport of plastic waste have?"; options = vec { "It improves recycling efficiency."; "It results in a significantly inefficient carbon footprint."; "It decreases ocean pollution."; "It promotes sustainable practices." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What happens during the recycling process that generates microplastics?"; options = vec { "Plastics are melted down."; "Plastics are crushed and ground."; "Plastics are chemically dissolved."; "Plastics are reassembled into new products." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "According to the text, what is considered a better option than conventional recycling?"; options = vec { "Incinerating plastic waste."; "Landfilling plastics."; "Composting organic materials."; "Increasing plastic production." }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "6.0";
    unit_title = "Overview - Fibers";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II: Basics";
    head_unit_id = "6";
    head_unit_title = ". Overview - Fibers";
    content = "In this section, we will explore the fundamental concepts of fibers, grouped into three broad categories: natural, synthetic, and semi-natural. This overview will cover the origins of these fibers, how they are produced, and their relevance to environmental sustainability. While some readers may already be familiar with certain aspects discussed here, this section aims to build on foundational knowledge rooted in relevant scientific principles, laying the groundwork for more science-based discussions in the subsequent sections and chapters of the book.\nBasic Scope\nFibers constitute the fundamental unit and primary component of the majority of textile goods. Typically, fibers are transformed into yarns, then to various forms of fabrics such as woven, knitted, and non-woven materials before becoming the finished goods we consume. \nFig.23   Textile Manufacturing Flow Chart from Fibers to Apparel* \n* Typical process and may vary depending on the needs of finished goods\nThere are notable exceptions to this generalization, including materials like leather, fur (a subset of leather), mycotextiles derived from fungi (also known as plant-based leather), which naturally form sheet structures from the growth of animals or fungi. Another exception is down-feathers (also known simply as “down”), sourced from different bird species and commonly used as filling material in winter garments, home textiles, sleeping bags, etc. These materials are utilized in their harvested form without having to go through a conversion into other intermediary materials such as yarns or processed forms of fabrics. \nTransformation: The thin and elongated structure of fibers allows for their alignment and multiplication in the desired length directions. When a large number of fibers are aligned and twisted together, they form a strong, flexible, and pliable yarn. These versatile properties of yarns are transferred to subsequent intermediary materials such as woven and knitted fabrics and finished goods, enabling them to withstand physical and chemical forces throughout their lifecycles.\nFiber Types: As mentioned earlier, there are three primary fiber types: natural, synthetic, and semi-synthetic (also known as semi-natural) fibers. Natural fibers are derived from the growth of living organisms, while synthetic fibers are produced through the synthesis of petroleum-based raw materials. Semi-synthetic fibers, as the name suggests, occupy a middle ground between these two categories.\nBasics Overview of Natural Fibers: The characteristics of natural fibers, such as thickness, length, strength, chemical resistance, etc., are determined by the species of specific sources, such as plants or animals. Typically, the properties of fibers within a particular species are influenced by various farming factors, including weather conditions, rainfall quantities, food sources, farming techniques, etc., prior to harvesting. Human-mediated genetic modifications may be utilized for altering these characteristics beyond their natural ranges or for benefiting farming outcomes. Such examples include genetically modified cotton, known as Bt cotton, or bioengineered silk, etc. \nBasics Overview of Synthetic Fibers: In contrast, the characteristics of synthetic fibers are determined by specific polymer types and can be adjusted to reflect the desired properties of finished goods. For instance, the length of synthetic fibers can be easily adjusted with simple adjustments made during manufacturing processes; continuous fibers are known as “filaments”, while those cut into shorter lengths to mimic natural fibers are called “staple” fibers. The thickness can also be as easily adjusted ranging from extremely thin strands, measured in micrometers or even nanometers, to much thicker strands such as the filaments of fishing rods and ropes for industrial use. The cross-sectional shapes of synthetic fibers can be modified from the conventional round to hexagonal, oval, hollow, or peanut shapes, among others, with equally simple manufacturing adjustments.\nVersatility and Flexibility: The versatility and flexibility of creating widely different properties of synthetic fibers largely explain why they account for nearly 65% of the worldwide fiber consumption reviewed in Chapter I. While there are too many to mention, one relatable example for everyone is the use of synthetic fibers in vehicle safety components such as seat belts and airbags. Although these safety parts could theoretically be made from natural fibers, doing so would be both impractical and dangerous. To achieve the same strength as synthetic fibers, seat belts and airbags made from natural fibers would need to be five to ten times heavier, which would pose significant safety risks from their own weights up on collision. Additionally, natural fibers degrade more rapidly under extreme conditions inside vehicles in hot and cold climates. This would necessitate frequent replacements to maintain their strength and functionality. Clearly, relying on natural fibers for such application does not make sense. There are numerous other examples where natural fibers are neither practical nor beneficial in performance metrics. This consideration naturally leads to the next discussion on the chemical reactivity and toxicity. \nChemical Reactivity and Toxicity\nOne critical aspect of the environmental impacts associated with different fiber materials is their chemical reactivity and its associated environmental impacts. Although this factor is arguably the most important to consider, it is often overlooked by many environmental interest groups and activists who assert that natural fibers are more sustainable. A common assertion among them is that synthetic fibers are \"toxic.\" However, this characterization does not align with the traditional definition of the term \"toxic\" or “toxicity”. \nDefinitions of Cambridge Dictionary - \nToxicity:  the quality of being poisonous, or the degree to which something is poisonous\nPoison:  a substance that can make people or animals ill or kill them if they eat or drink it\nOverview of Toxicity: In a conventional viewpoint and a layman’s term, toxicity can be defined as the property of a chemical to create immediately harmful effects on the health of living organisms. For example, a poison can kill humans instantly at a certain concentration. Common examples of toxic chemicals include heavy metals such as lead, mercury, cadmium, etc., pesticides and herbicides, as well as a wide range of other chemicals found in various industrial and farming applications such as benzene, formaldehyde, etc.\nThese toxic substances possess chemically active functional groups that readily react with their surroundings. These reactions occur instantly and violently. Although lower densities of some of these chemicals may not pose immediate health impacts, they can accumulate in living organisms over time and result in serious mid- to long-term health effects.\nChemical Reactivity of Natural and Synthetic Fibers: While further details will be explored in the subsections of this chapter, it is important to understand that natural fibers contain numerous functional groups in their chemical compositions that readily react with other elements and substances they come into contact with. In contrast, synthetic fibers either lack chemically active functional groups altogether or have them in much lower densities, resulting in significantly reduced reactivity compared to natural fibers. In fact, this chemical stability of synthetic fibers is a key factor in their lower consumption of chemicals and water throughout their entire lifecycles, from manufacturing to consumption, significantly benefiting the environment.\n“Toxicity” vs. (Longer-term) “Damage”: Labeling synthetic fibers as “toxic” by some environmental interest groups and activists may stem from studies that show microplastics can accumulate in the body and potentially lead to health issues. However, this is not due to the chemical reactivity, or lack thereof, of the microplastics themselves. Instead, it is the result of other forces that cause certain substances to adhere to or detach from one another. This phenomenon typically involves weaker forces such as surface tension, adsorption and Van der Waals force, which apply to anything entering the bodies of living organisms, even in the absence of chemically active functional groups. Moreover, these forces are much weaker than stronger bonds formed by chemically reactive substances. As a result, they can easily break apart.\nDespite the chemical inertness and weak forces involved in the microplastics, potential risks arise when other chemicals adhere to them, eventually forming harmful compounds. In the meantime, the cumulative effects of microplastics and their interactions with other chemicals to create such compounds tend to occur over longer periods, which distinguishes its nature from the traditional concept of \"toxicity\".\nGiven these factors, it is more accurate to describe the health impacts of microplastics as (longer-term) \"damage\" rather than \"toxicity\". Furthermore, the resulting compounds would not pose significant risks if the adhering chemicals were not toxic. In this context, we understand that the harmful chemicals are the primary sources of \"toxicity\" concerns, not the microplastics. \nEasy Understanding of Chemical Reactivity: The chemical reactivity of a fiber type can be easily grasped without an in-depth knowledge of chemistry. The absorption of water is the result of a chemical reaction between the fiber'\''s chemically functional groups and water. Therefore, one easy way to estimate the chemical reactivity of a material is by observing how much water it absorbs. For example, one can easily test the following at home: submerge two towels, one made of polyester and the other of cotton, in water, then squeeze them to remove excess water. You will notice that the cotton towel retains much more water than the polyester one, which can be further verified by comparing the drying speed of the two in hang dry - I conducted a similar test using my home laundry setup and a weighing scale. The results, which highlight a large difference between cotton and polyester, are detailed in Chapter III: Section 13. Lifecycle Assessment (LCA) - Consumption. \nIn scientific terms, standardized measurements such as \"Moisture Content (MC)\" are used to show how readily a material interacts with water molecules.\nDifferences in Moisture Content: The MC is typically measured under controlled conditions, with relative humidity ranging from 35% to 60%, temperatures between 20°C and 25°C (68°F to 77°F), and a stabilization period (e.g., 24 hours) in laboratory settings. The results of such measurements serve as a reference in the trading of fibers and yarns, ensuring that buyers pay for the fiber'\''s weight rather than the water absorbed.\nArrived from these standardized methods, polyester has the moisture content of around 1%, and polypropylene is a mere 0.1%. Although both polymers lack chemically reactive groups in their compositions, they still absorb small amounts of water due to the previously mentioned weak forces such as surface tension, adsorption, Van der Waals, etc., present in nature. In comparison, cotton has the moisture content of 6% ~ 8%, and wool ranges from 16% to 18%.\nThese differences in the MC reflect significant variations in the chemical reactivity, with natural fibers being tens or even hundreds of times more chemically reactive than synthetic fibers.\nDifferences in Chemical Absorption: Fibers that absorb more water also tend to absorb higher quantities of process chemicals, leading to increased toxicity throughout their lifecycle. This toxicity is a critical environmental and health concern, which we cannot disregard when we discuss the environmental impacts from different fiber types. In the subsequent sections, I will explore the chemical compositions of different fibers and how they contribute to varying levels of toxicity and overall environmental impacts.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Fibers: Natural, Synthetic, and Semi-Natural\n\nIn this section, we'\''ll look at the basic concepts of fibers, which can be divided into three main categories: natural, synthetic, and semi-natural fibers. We'\''ll discuss where these fibers come from, how they are made, and their importance for environmental sustainability. Even if you already know some of this information, our aim is to expand your foundational knowledge and prepare you for the more in-depth scientific discussions that will follow in later chapters.\n\n## Basic Overview of Fibers\n\nFibers are the basic building blocks and main elements of most textile products. They are usually turned into yarns, which can then be made into different types of fabric, like woven, knitted, or non-woven materials, before being turned into the products we use every day.\n\n![Textile Manufacturing Flow Chart from Fibers to Apparel](#)  \n*Note: This flow chart represents a typical process, though it may differ based on the final product needs.*\n\nHowever, there are exceptions to this process. Materials like leather and fur don’t go through the above fiber-to-fabric transformation, and neither do mycotextiles derived from fungi, which are sometimes called plant-based leather. Down feathers, collected from various bird species, are another exception; they’re used as insulation in winter clothing and other textiles without needing to be converted into yarn or fabric.\n\n## Fiber Formation\n\nThe long and thin structure of fibers allows them to be aligned and combined to create yarns. When many fibers come together and twist, they form a strong, flexible yarn. These properties of yarn are carried over to fabrics and finished products, enabling them to resist physical and chemical forces throughout their life cycle.\n\n### Types of Fibers\n\nAs mentioned, fibers fall into three main categories: \n\n1. **Natural Fibers**: Sourced from living organisms, such as plants and animals.\n2. **Synthetic Fibers**: Created from petroleum-based materials through chemical processes.\n3. **Semi-Synthetic Fibers**: Have characteristics of both natural and synthetic fibers.\n\n#### Natural Fibers\n\nThe traits of natural fibers—like their thickness, length, and strength—depend on their biological sources, such as specific plants or animals. These properties can be influenced by farming conditions, such as weather, rainfall, and farming techniques before harvesting. Sometimes, genetic modifications are used to enhance these traits. For example, Bt cotton is a genetically modified type of cotton.\n\n#### Synthetic Fibers\n\nThe properties of synthetic fibers stem from their polymer types and can be tailored to meet desired specifications. For example:\n- Length can be modified; long fibers are called \"filaments,” while shorter ones are \"staple\" fibers.\n- Thickness can range from very fine strands to thicker materials like those found in industrial ropes.\n- The shapes of synthetic fibers can also be varied, changing from rounds to hexagonal or other shapes.\n\n### Versatility of Synthetic Fibers\n\nSynthetic fibers are versatile and capable of being engineered for numerous applications, making up nearly 65% of worldwide fiber use. For example, they are essential for safety features in vehicles, such as seat belts and airbags. Making these components with natural fibers would not only be impractical but also dangerous, as they would need to be much heavier to achieve similar strength, posing safety risks during accidents.\n\n## Chemical Reactivity and Toxicity\n\nA key factor in assessing the environmental impact of different fiber materials is their chemical reactivity. Despite some claims that synthetic fibers are \"toxic,” this view does not fully align with the traditional definition of toxicity.\n\n### Defining Toxicity\n\n- **Toxicity**: The quality of being poisonous. \n- **Poison**: A substance that can cause harm or death if ingested.\n\nIn everyday terms, toxicity refers to a chemical'\''s ability to produce harmful effects. Common toxic substances include heavy metals like lead and mercury, along with various chemicals used in agriculture and industry.\n\n### Chemical Reactivity of Fibers\n\nNatural fibers contain many functional groups that easily react with other chemicals. On the other hand, synthetic fibers typically have fewer or no reactive groups, resulting in lower reactivity. This chemical stability is beneficial as it leads to less chemical and water use throughout their life cycle, positively influencing the environment.\n\n### Understanding \"Toxicity\" vs. \"Damage\"\n\nSome activists describe synthetic fibers as \"toxic\" based on studies showing that microplastics can accumulate in the body. However, this is not due to their reactivity but rather the way certain substances stick to or separate from microplastics. This process usually involves weaker forces, which allows these substances to break apart more easily. \n\nWhile microplastics can have associated risks due to other chemicals attaching to them, it is more accurate to talk about the potential for \"damage\" over a longer period rather than \"toxicity\" in the traditional sense. The actual toxic risks stem primarily from the harmful chemicals, not from the microplastics themselves.\n\n## Easy Way to Understand Chemical Reactivity\n\nAn easy way to grasp the chemical reactivity of a fiber is by looking at how much water it absorbs. For example, if you take a polyester towel and a cotton towel, you'\''ll find that the cotton absorbs much more water. This difference highlights how chemically reactive the fibers are; cotton (natural fiber) is significantly more reactive than polyester (synthetic fiber).\n\n### Measuring Moisture Content (MC)\n\nMoisture content is generally measured under controlled conditions. For example, cotton might have a moisture content of 6-8%, whereas synthetic fibers like polyester have only about 1%. Such differences indicate that natural fibers are far more chemically reactive than synthetic fibers.\n\n### Chemical Absorption\n\nFibers that absorb more water also tend to take in more processing chemicals. This factor is crucial when discussing health and environmental impacts from various fiber types. In upcoming sections, we will further dive into the chemical makeup of different fibers and how their properties relate to toxicity and overall environmental effects.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What are the three broad categories of fibers discussed?"; options = vec { "Natural, synthetic, semi-synthetic"; "Organic, inorganic, synthetic"; "Cotton, polyester, wool"; "Animal, vegetable, mineral" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What is the primary component of most textile goods?"; options = vec { "Yarns"; "Fabrics"; "Fibers"; "Threads" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which type of fiber is derived from the growth of living organisms?"; options = vec { "Synthetic fibers"; "Semi-synthetic fibers"; "Natural fibers"; "Composite fibers" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What characteristic of synthetic fibers allows for their properties to be adjusted during manufacturing?"; options = vec { "Organic composition"; "Chemical stability"; "Polymer types"; "Natural origin" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "According to the text, what term is more accurate when describing the health impacts of microplastics?"; options = vec { "Toxicity"; "Harm"; "Damage"; "Chemical reactivity" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "7.0";
    unit_title = "Natural Fibers (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II: Basics";
    head_unit_id = "7";
    head_unit_title = ". Natural Fibers";
    content = "Natural fibers are derived from two primary sources: plant-based and animal-based. Plant-based fibers include cotton, linen, hemp, jute, etc., while animal-based fibers include wool, silk, angora, alpaca, mohair, etc. Each individual fiber must be long, flexible, and strong enough to withstand manufacturing processes to be suitable for use as textile material.\nDifferent species of plants and animals produce fibers of varying characteristics. For example, garments made from merino wool are known for their smooth texture and natural drape, owing to the fine and soft hair produced by the Merino breed of sheep. Similarly, mohair, which comes from the Angora goat, is renowned for its silky sheen and even softer texture than the merino wool. These differences, though subtle in terms of their chemical composition, are often significant enough for consumers to distinguish between them based on their physical properties.\nThe characteristics of the fibers are measured using various metrics, including appearance, diameter, length, surface structure, smoothness, strength, moisture content, etc.\nConsumption Breakdown: Among natural fibers, cotton has the highest consumption, accounting for approximately 23 ~ 25% of the global fiber use. In contrast, wool, the next most commonly used natural fiber, constitutes only about 1% of the worldwide fiber consumption. Other natural fibers such as silk, hemp, linen, etc., represent negligible proportions of total fiber consumption due to significantly limiting factors such as physical and chemical properties, availability, processing costs, price-quality ratios, etc.\nConsumer Preferences: Many consumers would prefer products made from natural fibers over those made from synthetic fibers. This preference can be attributed to various reasons based on some perceived values such as comfort and skin-friendliness of natural fibers, aesthetic appeals and their belief that natural materials are more sustainable. High fashion industry often reflects these consumer preferences, as luxury products are typically expected to be made from natural fibers rather than synthetic ones. Although there are exceptions where synthetic materials are justified, this general preference applies to a significant portion of the textiles people consume, especially everyday items such as shirts, pants, suits, etc.\nOf the considerations, the perceived environmental benefits of natural fibers have become a focal point by many environmental advocacy groups, activists and consumers alike.  \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Natural Fibers\n\nNatural fibers come from two main sources: **plants** and **animals**. \n\n### Types of Natural Fibers\n- **Plant-based fibers** include:\n  - Cotton\n  - Linen\n  - Hemp\n  - Jute\n\n- **Animal-based fibers** include:\n  - Wool\n  - Silk\n  - Angora\n  - Alpaca\n  - Mohair\n\nFor a fiber to be useful in textiles, it needs to be long, flexible, and strong enough to survive the manufacturing processes.\n\n### Characteristics of Fibers\nDifferent plants and animals produce fibers with unique qualities. For instance:\n- **Merino wool**, from the Merino sheep, is popular for its smooth texture and elegant drape, thanks to its fine and soft hair.\n- **Mohair**, sourced from the Angora goat, is celebrated for its shiny appearance and even softer feel than merino wool.\n\nThough the chemical makeup of these fibers may be similar, consumers can often recognize the differences based on physical properties.\n\nTo understand a fiber'\''s characteristics, several factors are evaluated, such as:\n- Appearance\n- Diameter\n- Length\n- Surface texture\n- Smoothness\n- Strength\n- Moisture content\n\n### Fiber Consumption Statistics\nCotton is the most widely consumed natural fiber, making up about **23% to 25%** of global fiber usage. On the other hand, wool is less common, accounting for only about **1%** of world fiber consumption. Other natural fibers, like silk, hemp, and linen, have a very small share in total fiber use due to limitations like their physical and chemical properties, availability, processing costs, and value-for-money aspects.\n\n### Consumer Preferences\nMany people choose products made from natural fibers instead of synthetic ones. This preference stems from several perceived benefits, including:\n- Comfort and skin-friendliness of natural fibers\n- Aesthetic appeal\n- Belief that natural materials are more sustainable\n\nThe high-fashion industry reflects these preferences, often favoring luxury items made from natural fibers over synthetics. While there are situations where synthetic materials are acceptable, this preference holds true for much of the textiles used daily, such as shirts, pants, and suits.\n\nThe environmental advantages of natural fibers have gained significant attention from advocacy groups and consumers who prioritize sustainability in their choices.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What are the two primary sources of natural fibers?"; options = vec { "Mineral-based and synthetic"; "Plant-based and animal-based"; "Chemical and synthetic"; "Plant-based and artificial" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which natural fiber has the highest global consumption?"; options = vec { "Silk"; "Hemp"; "Cotton"; "Wool" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What characteristic is commonly associated with merino wool?"; options = vec { "High moisture content"; "Silky sheen"; "Smooth texture and natural drape"; "Strong and rigid fibers" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is a reason many consumers prefer natural fibers over synthetic ones?"; options = vec { "Lower cost"; "Higher durability"; "Comfort and skin-friendliness"; "Easier to manufacture" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What percentage of the global fiber use does wool account for?"; options = vec { "Approximately 1%"; "About 10%"; "Around 15%"; "About 5%" }; answer = 0; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "7.1.0";
    unit_title = "Cotton - King of All Natural Fibers";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "7.1";
    head_unit_title = "Cotton - King of All Natural Fibers";
    content = "The basic chemical composition of cotton is cellulose, which contains numerous hydroxyl groups (-OH) as shown in Fig.24. \n***Industry Specifics (4) – Start***\nFig.24   Chemical Structure of Cellulose* \n* Hydroxyl groups are highlighted in the red boxes\nAlthough various terms and descriptions exist to express the chemical behaviors and physical properties of the cellulose, the vast majority of them stem from or are governed by the chemical reactivity of the hydroxyl groups. Examples are below: \nHydrogen Bonding: The hydroxyl groups in the cellulose can form hydrogen bonds with other neighboring hydroxyl groups. These bonds impart strength to cellulose, essential for the subsequent manufacturing processes and consumption. Under the same principle, hydrogen bonding also occurs with neighboring water molecules, and it is referred to as hydrophilicity, explained next. \nHydrophilicity: The strong affinity of the cellulose for water is termed “hydrophilicity” (noun) or “hydrophilic” (adjective). This property impacts the entire lifecycle of the cellulosic fibers. For instance, cotton fibers exhibit higher strength when wet compared to when dry. If cotton becomes too dry, it is more prone to breaking and shedding dust. Therefore, this hydrophilicity plays a critical role in cotton (and other plant-based fibers), maintaining its strength during manufacturing and consumption thereafter. \nThe hydrophilicity of the cellulose also creates other implications. Because the cellulosic fibers readily absorb and retain water, they take longer to dry, leading to increased energy use for manufacturing and laundry during consumption. Additionally, these fibers have a higher probability of shrinking, color-fading and -contamination if not properly handled, especially during laundering. For example, washing a cotton shirt in hot water and using high-temperature dryer settings can result in noticeable color issues and shrinkage. This phenomenon is attributed to the hydrophilicity of cellulose.  \n***Industry Specifics (4) – End***\nChemical Reactivity: The hydroxyl groups in the cellulose contribute also significantly to their elevated level of chemical reactivity. As a result, the cellulosic fibers like cotton, linen, hemp, etc., exhibit a strong tendency to interact with other chemicals, including pesticides, fertilizers, dyes, detergents, bleach, etc., during cultivation, manufacturing and consumption. Conversely, a higher tendency of color migration and fading mentioned earlier is attributed also to the heightened chemical reactivity of both the cellulose and the color pigments, readily interacting with water molecules. \nBiological Degradation – Critically Erroneous Perception: The hydroxyl groups in the cellulose molecules render cotton susceptible to enzymatic degradation by microorganisms such as bacteria and fungi. While rapid biological degradation is a key argument used by environmental interest groups and activists in favor of natural fibers, it is critical to recognize that, while the cellulose degrades, large quantities of chemical elements and compounds present in textile goods do not. These chemicals, used extensively in farming and manufacturing processes, remain either in the fibers themselves or in nature as they are released into the environment during their entire lifecycles. \nFor example, the colors in textile goods, regardless of whether natural or synthetic materials, are a sign for the presence of the coloring pigments, along with many other chemicals employed to fixate the pigments within the fiber structures. These chemicals can include strong and highly toxic chemicals such as heavy metals like lead, arsenic, mercury, cadmium, etc., as well as various types of aromatic compounds and other harmful chemicals that are persistent in the environment for extended periods. \nVarious studies have shown how harmful and long-lasting these substances can be, with some known to persist in nature almost indefinitely, contaminating soil, water, and air, and leading to bioaccumulation in living organisms, including humans even in remote locations from their sources.\n***\nTherefore, it is a significant and detrimental misconception to assume that natural fibers degrade and return to nature quickly without leaving any environmental footprint. Especially in consideration of how much more chemicals are used for natural fibers and their heightened chemical reactivities, compared with those used in synthetic ones, this oversight critically misleads our society regarding the true environmental impacts between them.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Cotton'\''s Chemical Composition and Environmental Impact\n\nCotton'\''s primary chemical component is **cellulose**, which contains many **hydroxyl groups (-OH)**. These groups are crucial for understanding cellulose'\''s behavior in both chemical and physical contexts.\n\n## Chemical Structure of Cellulose\n\nIn the illustration of cellulose (Fig. 24), **hydroxyl groups** are highlighted in red boxes. They significantly influence the properties of cellulose, leading to several key concepts outlined below.\n\n### 1. Hydrogen Bonding\n\nThe **hydroxyl groups** in cellulose are capable of forming **hydrogen bonds** with other hydroxyls nearby. This bonding adds strength to cellulose, which is vital for processes during manufacture and use. Additionally, these groups can form bonds with water molecules, leading to a property known as **hydrophilicity**.\n\n### 2. Hydrophilicity\n\nThe term **hydrophilicity** (which means having an affinity for water) describes how cellulose, such as in cotton fibers, interacts with water. When cotton is wet, it is often stronger than when it is dry. Conversely, if it dries out too much, it is prone to breaking and generating dust. Thus, hydrophilicity is essential for preserving cotton'\''s strength during manufacturing and its use afterward.\n\nHowever, this water-loving nature brings some challenges. Cotton fibers absorb water easily, making them slow to dry and resulting in higher energy use during processing and laundry. If cotton isn’t handled carefully – for example, by washing in hot water or using high-heat drying – it can shrink and lose color. This tendency is largely due to the **hydrophilicity** of cellulose.\n\n### 3. Chemical Reactivity\n\nThe **hydroxyl groups** also lead to greater **chemical reactivity** in cotton and other cellulosic fibers, like linen and hemp. This makes them more likely to interact with various chemicals, such as pesticides, dyes, and detergents, during their production and use. This reactivity can also cause colors to fade or migrate due to their interaction with water.\n\n### 4. Biological Degradation – A Misunderstanding\n\nThe hydroxyl groups in cellulose make cotton vulnerable to breakdown by microorganisms, like bacteria and fungi. While this quick biological degradation is often highlighted as a benefit of natural fibers, it'\''s important to recognize that while cellulose itself might break down, many **chemicals** used in farming and production do not. These chemicals can linger in the environment and can include harmful elements, such as heavy metals (e.g., lead, mercury) or toxic compounds that persist over time.\n\nResearch shows that these substances can contaminate soil, air, and water, affecting wildlife and humans far from their source. \n\n### Conclusion\n\nIt is a significant mistake to believe that natural fibers break down easily and leave no environmental impact. In fact, because natural fibers like cotton often involve greater chemical usage and higher reactivity compared to synthetic ones, it misrepresents their true environmental cost. Understanding these factors is crucial for making informed choices about textiles.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the basic chemical composition of cotton?"; options = vec { "Protein"; "Cellulose"; "Starch"; "Lignin" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What property of cellulose is primarily due to the presence of hydroxyl groups?"; options = vec { "Hydrophobicity"; "Flexibility"; "Hydrophilicity"; "Incombustibility" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What happens to cotton fibers when they become too dry?"; options = vec { "They become stronger"; "They can break and shed dust"; "They expand"; "They color faster" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What misconception is addressed regarding the biological degradation of natural fibers?"; options = vec { "Natural fibers decompose quickly without chemicals"; "All natural fibers are biodegradable"; "Natural fibers always leave an environmental footprint"; "Synthetic fibers degrade faster than natural ones" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "Which of the following can interact strongly with cellulose due to its chemical reactivity?"; options = vec { "Dyes"; "Oils"; "Gases"; "Sugars" }; answer = 0; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "7.2.0";
    unit_title = "Wool - King of Animal-based Natural Fibers";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "7.2";
    head_unit_title = "Wool - King of Animal-based Natural Fibers";
    content = "As many people know, wool refers to the fibers obtained from various animals, most typically sheep, but also from others like angora from rabbits and cashmere from cashmere goats. There is a wide range of sheep, goats, etc., which produce different qualities of wool, varying in appearance, texture, length, and thickness. Some types of wool are more expensive than others due to their more favorable characteristics for consumers. For example, cashmere is renowned for its extremely soft and smooth touch and is much more expensive than the regular wool from sheep.\n***Industry Specifics (5) – Start***\nWool is composed of a particular protein, known as “keratin”, as well as some other chemical compounds such as fat, mineral matters, etc. The keratin plays a critical role in the chemical reactivity of wool fibers, consisting of long polypeptide chains with many different amino acids as shown in Fig.25. \nFig.25   Chemical Composition of Wool Fiber*\n* R side chains of varying characteristics\nSome common chemically reactive groups in the proteins include amino group (-NH2), carboxyl group (-COOH), hydroxyl group (-OH), sulfhydryl group (-SH), imidazole group (-C3H4N2), phenol group (-C6H5OH), etc. \n***Industry Specifics (5) – End***\nChemical Reactivity of Wool: As in the hydroxyl group of cotton, the chemically reactive groups of wool, the keratin, make it highly susceptible for chemical reactions with water, harmful chemicals, and other substances. In fact, the proportion of the chemically reactive groups in the molecular compositions of wool is much higher than that of cellulose and it makes wool’s chemical reactivity even more elevated.  \nAs outlined in the Introduction of this book, I had extensive hands-on experiences in various textile manufacturing processes including dyeing where I dyed a diverse array of fibers and yarns with varying compositions with my own hands. When attempting to achieve similar tone and hue between wool and polyester, it was necessary to use significantly larger quantities of chemicals. My observations in dyeing simply aligned with the scientific understanding of the chemical compositions of different fiber types and their impacts on chemical usage, thus leading to substantial differences in the overall environmental impacts. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Wool and Its Composition\n\nWool comes from the fibers of various animals, mostly sheep, but also from rabbits (like angora) and cashmere goats. Different breeds of these animals produce wool that varies in quality, appearance, texture, length, and thickness. Some types of wool are pricier than others because they have desirable qualities for consumers. For instance, cashmere is well-known for being incredibly soft and smooth, making it much more expensive compared to regular sheep wool.\n\n## The Composition of Wool\n\nWool fibers are made up of a specific protein called **keratin**, along with other compounds like fats and minerals. Keratin is important because it determines how wool fibers react chemically. The structure of keratin includes long chains of amino acids, as illustrated in Fig. 25.\n\n### Key Components of Wool:\n\n- **Amino Group (-NH2)**\n- **Carboxyl Group (-COOH)**\n- **Hydroxyl Group (-OH)**\n- **Sulfhydryl Group (-SH)**\n- **Imidazole Group (-C3H4N2)**\n- **Phenol Group (-C6H5OH)**\n\nThese groups are reactive, meaning they can easily interact with water and other substances, including harmful chemicals. The level of reactivity in wool is higher than in cellulose, which enhances its ability to undergo chemical reactions.\n\n## My Experience with Dyeing Wool\n\nIn my journey through various textile manufacturing processes, including dyeing, I'\''ve had the chance to work with different fibers and yarns. I noticed that when trying to match the color tones and hues between wool and polyester, I needed to use much more dye for the wool. This experience confirmed the scientific understanding of how different fiber compositions affect dye absorption and overall chemical usage, which in turn impacts the environment. \n\nBy recognizing these differences, we can better appreciate the unique qualities of wool and the implications for environmentally friendly practices in textile production.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is wool primarily obtained from?"; options = vec { "Silk worms"; "Sheep"; "Cotton plants"; "Synthetic fibers" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which animal produces cashmere wool?"; options = vec { "Rabbits"; "Cashmere goats"; "Sheep"; "Alpacas" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is the main protein component of wool?"; options = vec { "Collagen"; "Keratin"; "Elastin"; "Casein" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which group in wool'\''s chemical composition makes it highly reactive?"; options = vec { "Amino group"; "Alkyl group"; "Phenol group"; "Carboxyl group" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What characteristic of cashmere makes it more expensive than regular wool?"; options = vec { "Its thickness"; "Its color variety"; "Its softness and smoothness"; "Its length" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "7.3.0";
    unit_title = "Other Natural Fibers and Materials";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "7.3";
    head_unit_title = "Other Natural Fibers and Materials";
    content = "Many other types of natural fibers are utilized in a wide range of textile applications. When combined, the consumption of all natural fibers, excluding cotton and wool, accounts for approximately 5 ~ 5.5% of global fiber consumption. The variations include:\nPlant-based fibers:  Hemp, Jute, Linen, Milkweed, Flax, etc. \nAnimal-based fibers: Silk, Alpaca, Camel hair, Cashmere, Mohair, Yak, Chiengora, Qiviut, etc.  \n* Special Mention: Additional plant-based fibers, such as bamboo, banana, pineapple, soy, seaweed, etc., also exist. However, these fibers require chemical processing to transform them into certain form factors suitable for textile processing and, therefore, are not classified as natural fibers. This topic will be discussed further in the context of semi-natural, also known as semi-synthetic, fibers later in this chapter.\nLeather: Another important form of natural textile materials, albeit not in fiber form, includes leather and fur (subset of leather). Leather, in particular, is widely used in apparel, furniture, automotive parts, etc., and is one of the most commonly used natural materials. Leather is derived from the skin of animals such as cows, horses, goats, sheep, deer, pigs, kangaroos, ostriches, snakes, crocodiles, stingrays, and more. In some cases, leather is used with the hair it comes with, such as in mink, beaver, etc., generally known as fur. \nThe vast majority of leather, including fur, undergoes extensive processing to enhance its visual appeal, similar to how fibers, yarns, and fabrics are dyed to obtain desirable colors for consumers. This leather treatment, commonly referred to as \"tanning,\" is particularly harmful to the environment due to the use of highly toxic chemicals such as chromium, sulfides, formaldehyde, and reactive dyes. These chemicals are essential for stabilizing the leather and achieving the desired aesthetic and physical qualities, but they come with significant environmental and health risks. Workers in tanneries, as well as nearby residents, may face increased risks of serious health issues, including skin conditions, respiratory problems, and long-term illnesses like cancer, due to prolonged exposure to these toxic substances.\nMycotextile: As briefly mentioned in Chapter I, the fungi-based material, known as mycotextile or mycelium, is considered as vegetative leather. There has been a growing popularity on this mycotextile with consumers’ general misperception on natural materials as being more sustainable. However, all the previous discussions in the context of the chemical reactivity of natural materials are also applicable for this vegetative leather. \nWhile this material constitutes a minute portion for the overall textile material consumption, it is important to note that farming mycotextile involves the use of sterilization chemicals such as fungicide and carbon footprint from energy use for temperature-, humidity- and light-control, in cultivation as well as methane (CH4) creation from substrate waste, etc. \nDown-Feather\nAnother important natural material, not in fiber or sheet form, is down and feather material from birds. Certain bird species migrate seasonally, some for breeding and others to escape cold weather. During the migration, these birds require protection against cold air, especially in the chest area because important organs such as hearts, muscles, fat to store energy, etc., are located and must be protected. With this necessity, they developed specialized hair structures in the chest area, known as “down”. The down material consists of much finer strains of hair than those of the feathers covering the rest of their bodies. Together, these materials are referred to as “down feather” or simply “down”.\nFig.26 Locations of Down and Feather\nhttps://www.sciencelearn.org.nz/resources/2372-whio-feathers-what-are-they-for \nThe delicate structure of the down creates numerous tiny air pockets to capture and conserve the body heat, a key element for effective insulation. Fig.27 shows a high quality down material under microscope. \nFig.27   Down under \nMicroscope\nWhen many pieces of this down material are placed in an enclosed bag system for winter jackets, sleeping bags, etc., they form an optimal structure to create a large quantity of extremely small air pockets. The finer the hairs are the smaller and higher quantities of air pockets they can create. Certain species such as the geese from Canada and Hungary are known for producing higher quality down with finer hair structures than others as these birds face colder environment in their migration seasons. Eiderdown is another notable type, recognized for its exceptionally fine hairs, offering superior insulation value.\nValue of Down vs. Feather: When the material is used in textiles, it typically consists of a blend of both down and feather. The higher the proportion of the down in the mix, the greater the value of the material. Given the higher importance in its insulative value of the down, it is often referred to as just “down” by many, while “down-feather” would be more descriptively accurate. Although rare, some high-end products contain 100% down, in which case, calling it as “down” would not be erroneous. The quality of a down feather material is often indicated by the ratio of the down to the feather, such as 90/10, meaning 90% down and 10% feather in the blend. Common ratios for apparel, home textiles, sleeping bags, etc., include 90/10, 80/20, and 70/30, where 90/10 material comprising of a high quality down can be multiple times more expensive than 70/30 in a regular quality. In some countries, a material cannot be labeled as down unless the down blend meets a certain threshold, for example, 60%, meaning that the down/feather mix must be minimally 60/40 ratio.\nFill Power: The quality grading of down also involves measuring its Fill Power, which is the volume a specific weight of down occupies. The higher the Fill Power, the more quantity of air it contains, thus the better the quality and the more expensive the material. For example, a Fill Power of 900 indicates a high-quality down for most consumer products, while a Fill Power of 600 is considered lower end. \nFrom my perspective, the Fill Power provides a more objective quality reference than the blend indication between the down and feather materials. For instance, a 90/10 down from a Hungarian goose, typically a strong indication of high quality, yielding a low Fill Power of 600, could suggest potential issues such as wrong material source, improper storage, high moisture content, inaccurate down-feather blend ratios, etc.\n***\nThe down feather material has been widely used for winter goods, with its first recorded use dating back nearly 5,000 years ago. Unfortunately, it is also one of the most misunderstood textile materials. Given its importance on how it impacts our lives from the protective nature of winter goods, it merits a deeper exploration. However, the discussions extend beyond the main themes of this book, thus I reserve this discussion on another book, focusing on the thermal technologies for textiles, expected to be published in the early part of 2025. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Natural Fibers and Materials in Textiles\n\nNatural fibers play a crucial role in the textile industry. Together, all natural fibers (except cotton and wool) represent about 5% to 5.5% of the total global fiber use. Here are the different categories:\n\n## Types of Natural Fibers\n\n### Plant-Based Fibers\n- **Examples:** Hemp, Jute, Linen, Milkweed, Flax, and more.\n\n### Animal-Based Fibers\n- **Examples:** Silk, Alpaca, Camel hair, Cashmere, Mohair, Yak, Chiengora, Qiviut, and others.\n\n### Special Note on Other Plant-Based Fibers\n- There are additional plant fibers like bamboo, banana, pineapple, soy, and seaweed. However, these often require chemical treatment to be processed into forms suitable for textiles, so they’re not always categorized as natural fibers. Later in this chapter, we will explore this further in relation to semi-natural or semi-synthetic fibers.\n\n## Leather as a Natural Material\nLeather and fur are also significant natural materials used in textiles, especially for clothing, furniture, and car interiors. \n- **Source:** Leather is made from the skins of various animals, including cows, goats, sheep, pigs, and more.\n- **Fur:** Sometimes, leather is used with the animal'\''s hair, known as fur, which includes materials like mink or beaver.\n\nMost leather and fur undergo a process called **tanning** to improve appearance. Unfortunately, this process often involves toxic chemicals, such as chromium, which can pose risks to the environment and health. Exposure to these chemicals can lead to harmful health issues for workers in tanneries and nearby communities.\n\n## Mycotextile\nMycotextile, made from fungi or mycelium, is a type of vegetative leather that is gaining popularity due to a common belief that natural materials are more sustainable. However, similar environmental concerns related to chemical use also apply to this material. Mycotextile farming can involve chemicals and energy usage, contributing to pollution and carbon emissions.\n\n## Down and Feathers\nAnother essential natural material is down and feathers from birds. Migrating birds develop a special down in their chest for insulation against cold weather. This down is finer than the regular feathers on their bodies.\n\n### Properties of Down\n- The down'\''s structure creates tiny air pockets that trap heat, making it effective for insulation.\n- When used in jackets and sleeping bags, down forms an optimal structure to retain warmth. \n\nCertain birds, like Canadian and Hungarian geese, produce superior quality down due to their adapted hair structures for colder climates. Eiderdown is another high-quality type known for its excellent insulation.\n\n### Value of Down vs. Feather\nWhen down is used in textiles, it'\''s often mixed with feathers. The more down in the mixture, the more valuable the material. While both terms \"down\" and \"down-feather\" are used, products with up to 100% down exist, but high-end down products often have ratios like 90% down and 10% feather.\n\n### Fill Power\nDown quality is also measured by **Fill Power**, which indicates how much space a certain weight of down occupies. Higher Fill Power means better insulation and quality:\n- A Fill Power of 900 is considered high-quality, whereas 600 is lower quality.\n\nIt'\''s essential to recognize that a high ratio of down doesn'\''t guarantee quality without adequate Fill Power. \n\n## Conclusion\nDown feather material has a long history in winter goods, dating back around 5,000 years. However, it is often misunderstood. Due to its significance in providing warmth and protection, it deserves further investigation. This topic will be explored in more detail in an upcoming book dedicated to thermal technologies in textiles, expected to be published in early 2025.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What percentage of global fiber consumption do all natural fibers, excluding cotton and wool, account for?"; options = vec { "2 - 2.5%"; "5 - 5.5%"; "10 - 10.5%"; "15 - 15.5%" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which of the following is NOT classified as a natural fiber?"; options = vec { "Hemp"; "Silk"; "Bamboo"; "Wool" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is the term for the processing method used to enhance the visual appeal of leather?"; options = vec { "Dyeing"; "Tanning"; "Weaving"; "Finishing" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which of the following bird species is known for producing high-quality down?"; options = vec { "Pigeons"; "Chickens"; "Geese"; "Robins" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What does a Fill Power of 900 indicate about down material?"; options = vec { "It is low quality."; "It contains less air."; "It is high quality."; "It has a low down percentage." }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "8.0";
    unit_title = "Synthetic Fibers (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II: Basics";
    head_unit_id = "8";
    head_unit_title = ". Synthetic fibers";
    content = "Chemical compositions of synthetic fibers vary widely from one type to another. Most commonly used synthetic fibres include Polyester, Polyamide (with commercially known name as Nylon), Polypropylene (also known as Olefin), Acrylic, etc.  \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Synthetic Fibers\n\nThe chemical makeup of synthetic fibers can differ significantly between various types. Some of the most commonly used synthetic fibers are:\n\n- **Polyester**\n- **Polyamide** (often referred to as Nylon)\n- **Polypropylene** (sometimes called Olefin)\n- **Acrylic**\n\nEach of these fibers has unique properties and uses, making them important in a variety of applications.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is a commonly known name for Polyamide?"; options = vec { "Acrylic"; "Nylon"; "Polypropylene"; "Polyester" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which synthetic fiber is also known as Olefin?"; options = vec { "Polyester"; "Acrylic"; "Polyamide"; "Polypropylene" }; answer = 3; }; record { question = "Which of the following synthetic fibers is the most commonly used?"; options = vec { "Polyester"; "Cotton"; "Wool"; "Silk" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What type of fibers does the term '\''synthetic fibers'\'' refer to?"; options = vec { "Natural fibers"; "Artificial fibers"; "Cotton and silk"; "Wool and linen" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which of the following is NOT mentioned as a synthetic fiber in the content?"; options = vec { "Acrylic"; "Nylon"; "Rayon"; "Polypropylene" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "8.1.0";
    unit_title = "Definition of Plastics";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "8.1";
    head_unit_title = "Definition of Plastics";
    content = "Synthetic fibers are categorized under the family of plastics, specifically thermoplastics. Plastics, in a broad sense, refer to any polymer-based material that can be shaped or molded when heated. According to this definition, natural rubber could be considered a plastic. However, in common usage, the term, plastic, is used for materials synthesized from petroleum sources, thus excludes natural materials like rubber.  \nThere are two primary categories of plastics: thermoplastics and thermoset plastics. Although both types are synthetically produced polymers derived from naphtha, a byproduct of oil refining, they exhibit critical differences in terms of the environmental sustainability.\nThe thermoplastics can be reheated above a specific temperature known as “Melting Point”, unique to each material type. Upon reheating, they revert to a viscous liquid form suitable for reprocessing. In contrast, the thermoset plastics, or thermosets, undergo irreversible chemical changes when exposed to elevated temperatures. Instead of melting, the thermosets typically combust, making it impossible to recycle under the melting principle of the thermoplastics. These fundamental distinctions are pivotal in determining the recyclability of these materials. \nReal-Life Applications: Common examples of the thermoplastics include synthetic fibers such as polyester, polypropylene, Nylon, acrylic, etc. Additionally, thermoplastics are widely used in daily items such as plastic bags, water bottles, food containers, etc. In contrast, the thermoset plastics include materials like epoxy resins, which are commonly used in adhesives, paints, and coatings, as well as phenolic resins used in electrical insulators, among other applications. Moreover, composite materials are created by blending thermosets or thermoplastics with other materials to achieve unique properties. For instance, epoxy resin reinforced with fiberglass is used to produce strong, flexible vehicle bumpers that are lighter than traditional steel bumpers. This lightweight, flexible material provides significant benefits, such as reducing impacts on drivers, passengers, and pedestrians upon collision, while also contributing to improved fuel efficiency due to its lighter weight. \nMisperception: There are countless innovative applications of plastics and composites that have significantly enhanced our quality of life. For example, hollow synthetic fibers have been used in heart surgery to create artificial veins, which have extended patients'\'' life expectancy and improved their quality of life. Numerous other examples illustrate how synthetic fibers, and plastics in general, have positively impacted our lives. Listing all these benefits in detail would expand this book to thousands of pages, if only feasible.\n***\nOne of the key objectives of this book is to present substantial evidence challenging the widespread belief that plastics are inherently harmful and should be eliminated. The environmental interest groups and activists who advocate for the elimination of plastics may not fully realize the extent to which their daily lives depend on them whether in medicine, food production, health, safety, or even the environmental sustainability. Since this book focuses on textiles, I will explore the crucial role the synthetic fibers play in improving overall human well-being and their significant contributions to the environmental sustainability in the discussions that follow.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Synthetic Fibers and Plastics\n\n## What are Synthetic Fibers?\n\nSynthetic fibers belong to the plastics family, specifically known as thermoplastics. In general, the term \"plastics\" refers to materials made from polymers that can be molded or shaped when heated. Interestingly, natural rubber fits this definition as well, but in everyday language, \"plastic\" usually refers to man-made materials derived from petroleum, excluding natural products like rubber.\n\n## Types of Plastics\n\nPlastics can be divided into two main types: **thermoplastics** and **thermoset plastics**. Both of these are made from synthetic polymers that come from naphtha, a substance obtained during oil refining. However, they differ significantly in terms of environmental impact and recycling capabilities.\n\n### Thermoplastics\n\n- **Reheating**: Thermoplastics can be heated to a certain temperature, known as the **Melting Point**, which varies for each type of thermoplastic. When reheated, they become soft and can be reshaped or reprocessed.\n  \n### Thermoset Plastics\n\n- **Irreversible Change**: On the other hand, thermoset plastics undergo a chemical change when heated, which is permanent. Instead of melting, they tend to burn when exposed to high temperatures. This means thermosets cannot be recycled in the same way as thermoplastics, making them less sustainable.\n\n## Everyday Uses\n\n**Thermoplastics** are found in many everyday items:\n- Synthetic fibers: polyester, nylon, polypropylene, acrylic\n- Common products: plastic bags, water bottles, food containers\n\n**Thermoset plastics** include materials like:\n- **Epoxy resins**: used in adhesives, paints, and coatings\n- **Phenolic resins**: used for electrical insulators\n\nAdditionally, composite materials combine thermoplastics or thermosets with other substances to create items with enhanced properties. For example, fiberglass-reinforced epoxy resin is employed to make lighter and stronger vehicle bumpers, offering better safety during collisions and improved fuel efficiency.\n\n## Changing Views on Plastics\n\nThere are many innovative uses of plastics and composites that have significantly improved our quality of life. For instance, hollow synthetic fibers are now used in heart surgery to create artificial veins, enhancing patients'\'' longevity and well-being. The positive impacts of synthetic fibers and plastics could fill many pages, showcasing their benefits in various fields.\n\n### The Objective of This Book\n\nOne main goal of this book is to provide evidence that counters the common belief that plastics are inherently harmful and should be completely eliminated. Some environmental advocates might not recognize how reliant we are on plastics in various aspects of our lives, such as in healthcare, food production, safety, and environmental sustainability. Since this book focuses on textiles, I will discuss the vital role of synthetic fibers in promoting human health and their contributions to sustainability in future sections.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What are synthetic fibers primarily categorized under?"; options = vec { "Natural materials"; "Metals"; "Plastics"; "Biopolymers" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which of the following is a key difference between thermoplastics and thermoset plastics?"; options = vec { "Thermoplastics can be recycled, while thermosets cannot."; "Thermoplastics are made from natural materials, thermosets are not."; "Thermoplastics are more expensive than thermosets."; "Thermoplastics are solid at all temperatures." }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What is a common example of a thermoplastic?"; options = vec { "Epoxy resin"; "Natural rubber"; "Polyester"; "Phenolic resin" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is one of the benefits of lightweight materials made from thermoplastics in vehicles?"; options = vec { "Increase the overall weight."; "Improve fuel efficiency."; "Make the vehicle harder to repair."; "Limit design options." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What objective does the book aim to achieve regarding the perception of plastics?"; options = vec { "Encourage the complete elimination of all plastic materials."; "Show that plastics have no useful applications."; "Present evidence that plastics can be beneficial for human well-being."; "Demonstate that synthetic fibers are harmful only." }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "8.2.0";
    unit_title = "How Plastics are made";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "8.2";
    head_unit_title = "How Plastics are made";
    content = "As previously mentioned, the plastics are derived from petroleum sources. Some people may refer to the source material as naphtha, while others use the term, crude oil - In certain industries and regions, naphtha is synonymous with crude oil. However, it is more conventional to distinguish between the two, with crude oil serving as the source material and naphtha being one of the “fractions” extracted from it. Naphtha can also be derived from other sources, including natural-gas condensates, fractional distillation of coal tar, peat, etc. This discussion will focus on the crude oil as the most conventional source material.\n***Industry Specifics (6) – Start***\nRefinery Process: Crude oil is a complex mixture of thousands of different compounds, which are extracted through a process called “distillation” or “refinery”. As shown in Fig.28, it involves heating the oil, which then enters the distillation tower. \nFig.28   Refinery Process Diagram\nUpon heating, the compound with the lightest molecular weight evaporates first and rises to the topmost section of the distillation tower. Successively other compounds follow in order of molecular weight. These separated compounds are referred to as “fractions”.  \nFractions: Generally known names for these fractions are gasoline, LPG, naphtha, kerosene, diesel distillate, medium- and heavy-weight gas oil, asphalt, etc. This explanation is generalized and does not cover numerous other fractions from refinery processes. For example, there are different grades of gasoline, such as higher and lower octanes, as often seen in gas stations. As this book is not intended to delve deeply into refinery processes and related topics, the basics covered here should suffice to serve its purpose for further discussions on textiles. If there are readers who wish to learn more about it, there are plenty of information available on various sources.  \nPricing Factors: The market price of crude oil depends on the proportion of higher-value fractions, such as gasoline, compared to lower-value fractions, such as asphalt, and whether the oil has higher or lower content of sulfur, referred to as either “sour” or “sweet” oil. For example, the West Texas Intermediate (WTI) and the Brent oil are classified as light oils because they contain higher proportions of valuable fractions in lighter weights. In addition, they contain lower amount of sulfur in a given weight, making them sweet oil. These two characteristics make them more valuable in the market. In contrast, the Maya crude from Mexico contains more heavy compounds like asphalt and higher content of sulfur. It is with this reason that the Mayan crude oil is called heavy and/or sour oil and is generally lower in price. \nTo capture the fractions effectively, the distillation towers are typically quite tall and characteristic of refinery facilities. Many readers may have seen such towers while driving through the industrial areas of large cities.  \n***Industry Specifics (6) – End***\n";
    paraphrase = "# Simplified Overview of Plastics and Refinery Processes\n\nAs we discussed earlier, plastics are made from materials derived from petroleum. Some people might use the term \"naphtha,\" while others might refer to it as \"crude oil.\" In some sectors and locations, these terms can mean the same thing. However, it’s more common to see them distinguished, with crude oil being the main raw material and naphtha being one of the components extracted from it. Naphtha can also come from other sources such as natural-gas condensates, coal tar, and peat. For this discussion, we will focus on crude oil as the primary source.\n\n## Refinery Process\n\nCrude oil is a complicated mixture of thousands of different substances. These substances are separated through a method called \"distillation\" or \"refinery.\" Here'\''s how it works:\n\n1. **Heating the Oil**: Crude oil is heated and sent into a distillation tower.\n   \n2. **Evaporation and Separation**: As the oil heats up, the lighter substances evaporate first and rise to the top of the distillation tower. Heavier compounds evaporate later. These separated components are known as \"fractions.\"\n\n### What Are Fractions?\n\nThese fractions have commonly recognized names, such as gasoline, liquefied petroleum gas (LPG), naphtha, kerosene, diesel, and asphalt. This overview simplifies the numerous fractions produced during refining. For instance, gasoline comes in different grades (high and low octane), which you can see at gas stations. This book won’t go into fine details about refining but provides enough basics for discussions related to textiles. If you want to learn more about refining processes, plenty of resources are available.\n\n## Pricing Factors\n\nThe price of crude oil in the market is influenced by the amount of higher-value fractions like gasoline compared to lower-value fractions like asphalt. The oil'\''s sulfur content is also important; oil is classified as \"sour\" (high sulfur) or \"sweet\" (low sulfur). For example:\n\n- **West Texas Intermediate (WTI) and Brent oil**: These are considered light oils because they have a higher percentage of valuable lighter fractions and lower sulfur content, making them sweet oils. This combination increases their market value.\n  \n- **Maya Crude from Mexico**: This type contains more heavy compounds and has a higher sulfur content, making it classified as heavy and/or sour oil, which generally leads to lower prices.\n\nTo efficiently separate the fractions, distillation towers are typically tall and are a common sight in industrial areas of large cities.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the source material from which plastics are derived?"; options = vec { "Naphtha"; "Crude oil"; "Natural gas"; "Coal tar" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is the process called that extracts different compounds from crude oil?"; options = vec { "Filtration"; "Distillation"; "Fermentation"; "Evaporation" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which of the following is NOT a fraction derived from crude oil?"; options = vec { "Gasoline"; "LPG"; "Asphalt"; "Concrete" }; answer = 3; }; record { question = "What factor affects the market price of crude oil?"; options = vec { "Temperature"; "Packaging"; "Proportion of higher-value fractions"; "Shipping distance" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What term is used for oil that has a higher content of sulfur?"; options = vec { "Light oil"; "Sweet oil"; "Sour oil"; "Refined oil" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "8.3.0";
    unit_title = "How Synthetic Fibers are Made";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "8.3";
    head_unit_title = "How Synthetic Fibers are Made";
    content = "All synthetic fibers are subsets of plastics and are often referred to as \"polymer\" in a more scientific context. The word \"polymer\" originates from Greek, where \"poly\" means many and \"mer,\" derived from \"meros,\" means parts or units. Thus, \"polymer\" signifies a structure composed of many repeating single units. Other names for these materials include thermoplastics and man-made fibers. “Monomer” (“meros”), is the term indicating the basic repeating unit when it used independently. A monomer is a molecule capable of chemically bonding with other identical molecules to form a polymer. Monomers are typically in a liquid state at room temperature whereas polymers exist as solids. \nVarious types of polymers are made from different monomers, such as esters for polyester, amides for polyamides, propylene for polypropylene, and acrylates for acrylic.\n***Industry Specifics (7) – Start***\nPolymerization Principles: To create chemical bonding among monomers in a liquid form, specific processing conditions are required. These conditions may include such factors as temperature, pressure, catalyst, etc. When the conditions favor the synthesis of monomers, polymer structures form. Typically, these formations occur at high temperatures and in linear directions due to the chemical bonding structures of monomers, a concept elaborated in Fig.29. This process is generally referred to as “polymerization”.\nFig.29   Polymerization\nThis polymerization occurs in a metallic tank where the conditions mentioned earlier can be optimally adjusted. This equipment is generally referred to as “polymerization tank”.  \nExtrusion Principles: In the polymerization tank, the polymer chains are randomly positioned and intertwined in a viscous liquid form. To convert this into long strands of fibers, the liquid is pushed out of the tank through small holes as illustrated in Fig.30 and is subsequently pulled by a winding mechanism at the end of the process. As the processing conditions outside the tank are cooler than inside, the liquid cools and solidifies. This process is known as “extrusion”. \nFig.30   Polymerization and Dry Extrusion\nFor example, in the case of PET, a subset of polyester, the temperature at which the polymer exists in a viscous liquid, known as the Melting Point, is between 250°C(482°F) and 260°C(500°F). There is a temperature range between 220°C(428°F) and 240°C(464°F), known as the Softening Point where the polymer is in a state between liquid and solid. Then, the PET solidifies into fibers below 220°C(428°F). As the air outside the melting tank is much lower than the solidification temperature, the strands quickly cool and become the fibers.  \nWhen a polymer in a molten state is extruded from the polymerization tank into ambient air, the process is referred to as “dry” extrusion and Fig.30 is an example. When a polymer is extruded into a chemical bath, it is known as “wet” extrusion. The choice between these two methods typically depends on polymer type, solidification efficiency, desired quality of resulting fibers, etc. The polyester fibers are generally extruded through the dry extrusion, while the acrylic fibers require a bath of acidic chemicals, thus employing the wet method.\nOther Plastic Formation Principles: Principles of creating other form factors, such as the sheets for plastic films or the bottles in tubular one-end-enclosed shapes differ mainly in this extrusion process. For instance, to produce a plastic film from the melting tank of the Fig.30 process, the viscous polymer must be laid onto a flat surface and solidified into a desired thickness. Instead of the small holes used in the fiber extrusion, the mechanical setup allows the formation and solidification of the sheet form factor at the end of the polymerization tank. Similarly, the plastic bottles are the result of the viscous polymer poured into a mold shaped with a desired form factor, size and thickness during the extrusion process. \n***Industry Specifics (7) – End***\nVariations and Versatility: Differences in synthetic fiber types are determined by the chemical compositions and structures of each polymer type. As in the natural fibers, the synthetic fibers are characterized by similar metrics such as appearance, thickness, length, surface structure, texture, strength, etc. As mentioned earlier, the physical characteristics of the synthetic fibers can be easily adjusted by tweaking manufacturing parameters. For example, the thickness of the synthetic fibers can be adjusted by changing the hole sizes for the extrusion process or modifying the speed of the extrusion. This is akin to making thinner or thicker pasta noodles from flour dough by adjusting the thickness settings of pasta machine. The ability to make such fine adjustments allows for the versatile creation of different fiber characteristics, significantly impacting the properties of final products.\nWith this general overview, let'\''s now delve into the specifics of some of the most conventional types of synthetic fibers.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Synthetic Fibers\n\nSynthetic fibers are a type of plastic and are often called \"polymers\" in scientific terms. The word \"polymer\" comes from Greek, where \"poly\" means \"many\" and \"mer\" (from \"meros\") means \"parts\" or \"units.\" So, a polymer is essentially made up of many repeating units. You may also hear terms like thermoplastics or man-made fibers. When referring to individual units, we use the word \"monomer.\" A monomer is a molecule that can link up with other identical molecules to form a polymer. Typically, monomers are liquids at room temperature, while polymers are solid.\n\nDifferent types of polymers are made from various monomers. Here are some examples:\n- Polyester is made from esters.\n- Polyamides come from amides.\n- Polypropylene is derived from propylene.\n- Acrylics are formed from acrylates.\n\n## Polymerization Principles\n\nTo bond monomers together to form polymers while they are still in liquid form, specific conditions need to be met, such as temperature, pressure, and the use of catalysts. When these conditions favor the binding of monomers, polymer structures are created through a process called **polymerization**. This usually happens at high temperatures and causes the monomers to line up in a certain way, as shown in Fig.29.\n\nThis polymerization occurs in a special container known as a **polymerization tank** where these conditions are carefully controlled.\n\n## Extrusion Principles\n\nIn the polymerization tank, the polymer chains are tangled together in a thick liquid. To create long strands of fibers, this liquid is pushed out of the tank through small openings, as depicted in Fig.30, and then pulled into strands by a winding mechanism. As the liquid moves out into cooler air, it solidifies. This process is called **extrusion**.\n\nFor example, in the case of PET (a type of polyester), the liquid polymer has a **Melting Point** between 250°C (482°F) and 260°C (500°F). It enters a **Softening Point** range between 220°C (428°F) and 240°C (464°F), where it is neither fully solid nor liquid. Below 220°C (428°F), PET solidifies into fibers. Since the air outside the tank is much cooler than the solidification temperature, the strands quickly cool and turn into fibers.\n\nWhen the polymer is extruded into ambient air, it'\''s termed **dry extrusion** (see Fig.30). If the polymer is extruded into a chemical bath, this is known as **wet extrusion**. The method chosen often depends on the type of polymer, how quickly it solidifies, and the quality of the fibers desired. Generally, polyester fibers are produced using dry extrusion, while acrylic fibers are made using wet extrusion in acid baths.\n\n## Other Plastic Formation Principles\n\nThe methods for creating different forms of plastics like sheets for films or bottles differ mainly in the extrusion process. For instance, to create a plastic film, the thick polymer must be spread out on a flat surface to solidify to a specific thickness. Different setups are used compared to fiber extrusion to create solid sheets. Plastic bottles are made by pouring the thick polymer into molds that shape them to the desired form.\n\n## Variations and Versatility\n\nThe differences in synthetic fiber types stem from their chemical structures and compositions. Like natural fibers, synthetic fibers can vary in appearance, thickness, length, texture, and strength. Manufacturers can easily change physical characteristics by adjusting production parameters. For instance, changing the hole sizes during extrusion can make fibers thicker or thinner, much like adjusting a pasta machine to create different noodle thicknesses. This flexibility allows manufacturers to fine-tune fiber properties significantly, affecting the quality and characteristics of the final products.\n\nNow, let’s explore the specifics of some of the most common synthetic fibers.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the Greek origin of the word '\''polymer'\''?"; options = vec { "Mono means one"; "Poly means many and mer means parts"; "Mer means solid"; "Poly means few" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is the main purpose of polymerization?"; options = vec { "To create monomers"; "To form chemical bonds among monomers to create polymers"; "To solidify polymers into fibers"; "To adjust processing temperatures" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What happens to the polymer during the extrusion process?"; options = vec { "It cools and solidifies into short strands"; "It forms into a viscous liquid"; "It is pushed through small holes to become long strands of fibers"; "It is heated at high temperatures" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "In which state do monomers exist at room temperature?"; options = vec { "Solid"; "Liquid"; "Gas"; "Crystalline" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What defines the difference between dry and wet extrusion methods?"; options = vec { "The temperature of the polymer"; "The type of chemical bath used"; "Whether the polymer is extruded into air or a chemical bath"; "The viscosity of the polymer" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "8.4.0";
    unit_title = "Polyester, King of All Fibers";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "8.4";
    head_unit_title = "Polyester, King of All Fibers";
    content = "Polyester is arguably the most important fiber, accounting for over 50% of total fiber consumption. Given hundreds of different fiber types available to us, including natural fibers such as cotton, wool, silk, mohair, alpaca, cashmere, etc., as well as other synthetic fibers like Nylon, acrylic, polypropylene, aramid, carbon, etc., the fact that the polyester single handedly constitutes half of the global fiber consumption is significant and indicates clear advantages this fiber offers, including strength, softness, durability, flexibility, low manufacturing cost, ease of maintenance, chemical resistance, among many others.\nUsage Overview: Thanks to these excellent attributes, polyester’s applications are remarkably diverse, encompassing both personal items such as apparel, home furnishings, sports gear, etc., and industrial applications like tire reinforcement, safety belts, hard hats, spray coatings, etc. As mentioned earlier, hollow polyester fibers are used in the heart bypass surgery to carry blood around the body, and polyester fabrics are employed in surgeries requiring implantable supports in our body. The polymer is also used in stents, bone fixation devices, and numerous other important medical applications.\nChemical Inertness: Polyester'\''s suitability for the medical applications stems from its chemical inertness, meaning it does not react with other chemical elements and compounds. In comparison, if natural fibers and fabrics were used in such applications, they would dissolve in the body, as they are chemically reactive, leading to critical health issues in a short period post-surgery. \n***Industry Specifics (8) – Start***\nChemical Composition:  The monomer of polyester is comprised of the ester group, hence the name, Polyester, i.e., many ester groups. A specific type of polyester is polyethylene terephthalate (PET), and it is a material quite often spotted on in the care labels of various textile goods. The popularity and importance of this fiber type come from the favourable molecular structure in its chemical composition.  \nFig.31   Chemical Structure of Polyethylene Terephthalate (PET)\n***Industry Specifics (8) – End***\nCharacteristics: The fiber’s molecular structure is stable, and it does not react to other elements and chemical compounds. Low absorbance of water is a phenomenon representing such characteristic. Since water is a key source of a wide range of issues in manufacturing, consumption and even disposal, including bacterial growth causing odors and health issues, shrinkage, color migrations, contamination in landfills, etc., the benefits sub-branched from the low level of affinity to water are numerous. \nEnvironmental Benefits and Disadvantages: Among them are environmental benefits. For example, it uses much less water in manufacturing and laundry during consumption in comparison with natural fibers. In addition, it absorbs much lower quantity of other chemicals, including toxic ones, during its lifecycle. Textile goods made with 100% Polyester do not require drycleaning, in most cases, consume less water and energy in home laundry and need little to no ironing. \nThere are numerous other important benefits the polyester present for the environment. However, the polymer also presents significant challenges such as longevity in nature and microplastics, highlighting the importance of comprehensive analysis for assessing the true environmental impacts in comparison with other fibers. These factors will be explored in depth throughout this book including Chapter III: Lifecycle Assessment (LCA), where the 16-point evaluation criteria I developed with a focus on analysing the factors as comprehensively and objectively as possible will be utilized.  \nVersatility: The polyester is also one of the most widely used fiber types blended with other fibers. For instance, cotton and polyester blend is one of the most common types of yarns and fabrics while numerous other blends with natural fibers or other synthetic fibers popularly exist. These blends are to create a certain set of characteristics which take advantage of the benefits offered by each blended fiber type. For example, the cotton and polyester blend reduces the risks of shrinkage, color fading, ironing need, etc., thanks to the chemical inertness of the polyester, while providing natural texture and higher moisture contents close to the skin from the cotton. The trade-offs resulted from different blend proportions between two or more fibers are some of the key considerations in engineering yarns and fabrics in the textile goods we consume. \n***\nThe polyester'\''s exceptional properties, along with its relatively low manufacturing costs and widespread use across nearly every aspect of our lives, have earned it the title of the \"King of all fibers.\" Its significant environmental benefits will be examined further throughout the remainder of the book. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Polyester\n\n## Overview of Polyester\n\nPolyester is one of the most important fibers in the world, making up over 50% of all fiber consumption. With numerous fiber types available, including natural fibers like cotton, wool, silk, and synthetic fibers such as Nylon, acrylic, and polypropylene, polyester stands out due to its significant advantages. These include:\n\n- **Strength**\n- **Softness**\n- **Durability**\n- **Flexibility**\n- **Low production cost**\n- **Easy maintenance**\n- **Chemical resistance**\n\n## Uses of Polyester\n\nBecause of its remarkable qualities, polyester is used in a wide range of products. It can be found in:\n\n- **Personal Items**: Clothing, home furnishings, sports equipment, etc.\n- **Industrial Applications**: Tire reinforcement, safety belts, hard hats, spray coatings, and more.\n\nIn the medical field, hollow polyester fibers are used in heart bypass surgeries to help with blood circulation. Moreover, polyester fabrics are utilized in surgeries for implantable supports, and the material is also found in stents and bone fixation devices.\n\n## Chemical Properties\n\nOne reason polyester is suited for medical uses is its chemical inertness. This means it does not chemically react with other substances. If natural fibers were used in similar applications, they would dissolve in the body and cause serious health problems shortly after surgery.\n\n## Chemical Composition\n\nPolyester’s name comes from its composition of many ester groups. One common type of polyester is polyethylene terephthalate (PET), which you may notice on care labels of various textiles. PET’s favorable chemical structure is key to its popularity and importance in the textile industry.\n\n## Characteristics of Polyester\n\nPolyester fibers have a stable molecular structure, which does not react with other chemicals. One of its notable traits is low water absorbance. This characteristic helps avoid many manufacturing and environmental issues like:\n\n- Bacterial growth leading to odors and health risks\n- Shrinkage\n- Color bleeding\n- Environmental contamination\n\n## Environmental Impact\n\nPolyester has both advantages and challenges regarding the environment. Some benefits include:\n\n- Lower water usage in both manufacturing and laundering compared to natural fibers.\n- Reduced absorption of harmful chemicals during its lifecycle.\n- Polyester fabrics often do not require dry cleaning, consume less water and energy during washing, and need little or no ironing.\n\nWhile polyester has many environmental benefits, it poses challenges such as its persistence in nature and the issue of microplastics. This book will further explore these environmental impacts, especially in Chapter III, which discusses Lifecycle Assessment (LCA) using a thorough 16-point evaluation method developed to analyze these factors objectively.\n\n## Versatility of Polyester\n\nPolyester is frequently blended with other fibers, making it one of the most versatile materials. For example, a common blend is cotton and polyester, which offers advantages like reduced shrinkage and color fading while providing the natural feel and improved moisture retention of cotton. The balance of fiber proportions in these blends is important in designing textiles.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nDue to its impressive properties, affordability, and extensive applications in every part of our lives, polyester is often referred to as the \"King of all fibers.\" Throughout this book, we will delve deeper into its environmental benefits and challenges.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What percentage of total fiber consumption does polyester account for?"; options = vec { "25%"; "50%"; "75%"; "100%" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which of the following is a specific type of polyester mentioned?"; options = vec { "Nylon"; "Acrylic"; "Polyethylene Terephthalate (PET)"; "Cotton" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is one of the primary reasons polyester is suitable for medical applications?"; options = vec { "It is cheaper than other fibers"; "It is chemically inert"; "It is biodegradable"; "It absorbs water efficiently" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What advantage does polyester provide in terms of environmental impact during manufacturing?"; options = vec { "It consumes no water"; "It uses much less water than natural fibers"; "It requires high energy consumption"; "It produces more waste" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is a common blend mentioned that uses polyester?"; options = vec { "Silk and Nylon"; "Wool and Cashmere"; "Cotton and Polyester"; "Alpaca and Acrylic" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "8.5.0";
    unit_title = "Nylon, Mother of All Synthetic Fibers";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "8.5";
    head_unit_title = "Nylon, Mother of All Synthetic Fibers";
    content = "Nylon is the commercial name of the polyamide with the amide group as the repeating monomer unit. It is the very first invention in the family of the synthetic fibers, by brilliant scientists at DuPont at the dawn of the 20th century. Today, the fiber accounts for approximately 5% of the global fiber consumption. Nylon is renowned for its strength, smooth texture, and silk-like sheen. When the stocking made of the fiber was commercially introduced in 1940, which had been previously made with silk or cotton, the product was an instant commercial success, selling over 60 million pairs in their first year on the market, despite being more expensive than silk or cotton stockings at the time. \nAs in other synthetic fibers, it is a thermoplastic, meaning that it can be converted back into the molten state and repolymerized for recycling. There are different chemical compositions in the family of Nylon and Nylon 6 and Nylon 66 are some of the variants.  \n***Industry Specifics (9) – Start***\nFig.32   Chemical Structure of Nylon\n***Industry Specifics (9) – End***\nLike polyester, Nylon is used in a wide range of applications, both personal and industrial, including apparel, toothbrushes, automotive parts, food packaging, fishing nets, resin for 3D printing, tubes, films, etc. \nWhile both Nylon and polyester belong to the family of synthetic fibers, Nylon is more chemically reactive than polyester under certain conditions. This difference arises from the chemical composition of their monomer units with the amide functional group with nitrogen – carbon bond, which can undergo chemical reactions such as hydrolysis, etc.\nAs a result, Nylon typically has a moisture content in the range of 3 ~ 4%, while polyester has around 1%. In comparison, cotton has a moisture content of 7 ~ 8%, and wool has 16 ~ 18%. As explained earlier, the moisture content can be roughly translated to higher consumption of water and chemicals during manufacturing and consumption. \nWhile there may be more areas of interests for readers in Nylon, its relatively small consumption rate prevents me from delving deeper into other details. As a general rule of thumb, however, the environmental impacts of Nylon can be considered with its position between polyester and cotton assimilated by the different moisture contents described earlier. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Nylon\n\nNylon is a type of polyamide, which features the amide group as its repeating unit. It was the first synthetic fiber ever created, developed by innovative scientists at DuPont in the early 20th century. Nowadays, Nylon makes up about 5% of the world’s fiber usage. \n\nNylon is well-known for its durability, smooth feel, and lustrous appearance. When Nylon stockings were launched in 1940, they quickly became popular, selling over 60 million pairs in just their first year. This success was impressive, especially since the stockings were pricier than those made from silk or cotton at the time.\n\nLike other synthetic fibers, Nylon is a thermoplastic. This means it can be melted and reshaped, making it possible to recycle it. There are various types of Nylon, with Nylon 6 and Nylon 66 being two well-known examples.\n\n## Applications of Nylon\n\nNylon is used in a wide array of products, both personal and industrial, including:\n\n- Clothing\n- Toothbrushes\n- Automobile components\n- Food packaging\n- Fishing nets\n- Resin for 3D printing\n- Tubes and films\n\nAlthough both Nylon and polyester are synthetic fibers, Nylon is more chemically reactive under specific conditions. This difference can be traced back to the chemical structure of their monomer units. Nylon'\''s amide group contains a nitrogen-carbon bond, allowing it to engage in chemical reactions like hydrolysis.\n\nAs a result, Nylon typically has a moisture content of around 3% to 4%, while polyester'\''s moisture content is about 1%. In comparison, cotton retains 7% to 8% moisture, and wool has a higher moisture content of 16% to 18%. This moisture content indicates that Nylon requires more water and chemicals during its production and usage.\n\nIn terms of environmental impact, Nylon sits between polyester and cotton, largely due to its moisture content. Although there may be more to discuss about Nylon, its limited consumption means that we won'\''t explore further details extensively here. \n\nOverall, understanding Nylon’s properties and applications can help us appreciate its role in the world of synthetic fibers.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is Nylon the commercial name of?"; options = vec { "Polyester"; "Polyethylene"; "Polyamide"; "Polypropylene" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "When was Nylon first commercially introduced?"; options = vec { "1930"; "1940"; "1950"; "1960" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How much of the global fiber consumption does Nylon account for?"; options = vec { "3%"; "5%"; "10%"; "20%" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which fiber has a higher moisture content than Nylon?"; options = vec { "Polyester"; "Cotton"; "Silk"; "Wool" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is a consequence of Nylon'\''s amide functional group?"; options = vec { "Lower chemical reactivity than polyester"; "Higher strength than cotton"; "Ability to undergo hydrolysis"; "Inability to be recycled" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "8.6.0";
    unit_title = "Polypropylene, Rising Star";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "8.6";
    head_unit_title = "Polypropylene, Rising Star";
    content = "Polypropylene is a polymer made from the monomers of propylene. It belongs to the chemical group known as polyolefins and is often referred to as simply “olefin”. The invention and commercialization of the polymer occurred in the 1950s and it exhibits excellent impact and fatigue resistance properties among many other advantages. The polymer is commonly found in such everyday items as food containers, pharmacy prescription bottles, chairs, clear bags, stationery folders, etc., in addition to apparel items. The fiber forms of polypropylene are used in face masks, thermal insulation, diapers and sanitizers, as well as in many industrial applications.  \n***Industry Specifics (10) – Start***\nFig.33   Chemical Structure of Polypropylene\n***Industry Specifics (10) – End***\nI used the expression of the “Rising Star” as the title of the subsection, because the textile business world starts realising the versatility of it not only in the excellent physical properties but also in the environmental benefits.  \nOf all synthetic fibers of large commercial uses, polypropylene offers the lowest density of polymer structure. The low density offers several significant advantages. For instance, it has lower softening and melting points compared to polyester, leading to requiring lower heat and energy consumption during its manufacturing and consumption. This characteristic also contributes to the creation of lighter products. However, the lower density and melting points can lead to easier deformation, particularly when exposed to high heat in direct contact. Consequently, the industry typically avoids using the fiber for items that are in direct contact with high heat above 100oC (212oF) such as those commonly ironed like dresses, shirts, pants, etc.\nPolypropylene is one of the most environmentally beneficial materials of all fibers due to its extremely high chemical inertness. For instance, its moisture content is approximately 0.1%, only one tenth of that of polyester. In comparison, cotton has a moisture content of 7 ~ 8%, and wool has 16 ~ 18%. Therefore, the fiber incurs tens or hundreds of times lower chemical reactivity, benefiting the environment in related aspects. Personally, I have a strong affinity for this material, as it inspired me to develop the technology platform of the Clean Recycling Initiative™ - more details provided in Chapter V: Solutions.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Polypropylene\n\n**Polypropylene Overview**\n\nPolypropylene is a type of plastic made from propylene monomers, and it is classified under a group of chemicals known as polyolefins. It was invented and brought to market in the 1950s. This polymer is known for its strong resistance to impact and fatigue, making it very useful for a variety of applications. You can find polypropylene in everyday items like food containers, prescription bottles, chairs, clear bags, stationery folders, and even clothing. Additionally, the fiber form of polypropylene is used in products such as face masks, thermal insulation, diapers, and sanitizers, as well as various industrial uses.\n\n**Chemical Structure of Polypropylene**\n\n![Chemical Structure of Polypropylene](link_to_image)\n\n## Polypropylene: The \"Rising Star\" of Textiles\n\nThe textile industry is increasingly recognizing polypropylene’s versatility, both for its excellent physical traits and its environmental benefits. \n\nAmong synthetic fibers widely used commercially, polypropylene is the lightest due to its low density. This low density comes with several advantages:\n- **Energy Efficiency**: It has lower softening and melting points compared to other materials like polyester. This results in lower energy use during manufacturing and processing, and it helps create lighter products.\n- **Heat Sensitivity**: However, because of its low density and lower melting point, polypropylene can be more prone to deformation when exposed to high temperatures, especially above 100°C (212°F). Therefore, it'\''s often not used for items that are likely to be ironed, such as dresses, shirts, and pants.\n\n## Environmental Impact\n\nPolypropylene is considered one of the most environmentally friendly fibers available, primarily because it is highly chemically inert. For example, its moisture content is about 0.1%, which is much lower than polyester (7-8%), cotton (7-8%), or wool (16-18%). This low moisture content means that polypropylene reacts much less with other chemicals, which is better for the environment.\n\nPersonally, I find polypropylene inspiring and it played a role in my development of the Clean Recycling Initiative™ technology platform, which I will discuss further in Chapter V: Solutions.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is polypropylene made from?"; options = vec { "Cotton fibers"; "Monomers of propylene"; "Polyester"; "Wool fibers" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "In which decade was polypropylene invented and commercialized?"; options = vec { "1940s"; "1950s"; "1960s"; "1970s" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is one of the primary environmental benefits of polypropylene?"; options = vec { "High moisture content"; "Chemical inertness"; "Low melting point"; "High density" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Why is polypropylene typically avoided for high heat applications?"; options = vec { "It is too expensive"; "It has a high melting point"; "It can deform easily at high temperatures"; "It is highly reactive" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which item is NOT commonly made from polypropylene?"; options = vec { "Food containers"; "Chair"; "Polyester shirts"; "Pharmacy prescription bottles" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "8.7.0";
    unit_title = "Other Synthetic Fibers";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "8.7";
    head_unit_title = "Other Synthetic Fibers";
    content = "There are numerous other types of synthetic fibers including acrylic, spandex, kevlar, carbon fiber, etc., which together comprise approximately 5% of global total fiber consumption. These fibers exhibit distinct differences in their chemical compositions as well as physical and chemical characteristics. Given their relatively insignificant proportions in the total fiber consumption, a detailed examination of each is beyond the scope of this book. Rather, I present several names of different fiber types with typical application examples: \nAcrylic: sweaters, transparent boards, etc.  \nModacrylic: artificial wigs, flame retardant garments, etc. \nCarbon fiber: golf clubs, tennis rackets, helmets, etc.  \nPolyaramid: bulletproof vests, flame resistant garments, etc. \nA notable commonality among these fibers is their origin in the petroleum bases, which imparts molecular structures with significantly lower chemical reactivity compared to natural fibers. While there are variations in the chemical reactivity among different synthetic fiber types, differences within the synthetic group are generally much more subtle than those observed between synthetic and natural fibers.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Overview of Synthetic Fibers\n\nThere are many types of synthetic fibers, including acrylic, spandex, kevlar, and carbon fiber. Together, these fibers make up about 5% of the total fiber consumption worldwide. Each type has unique chemical structures and physical properties. Because they represent a small part of the overall fiber market, this book won'\''t go into deep detail about each one. Instead, here’s a brief overview of some different types of synthetic fibers along with their common uses:\n\n- **Acrylic**: Typically used in sweaters and transparent boards.\n- **Modacrylic**: Commonly found in artificial wigs and flame-retardant clothing.\n- **Carbon Fiber**: Used in sports equipment like golf clubs and tennis rackets, as well as in helmets.\n- **Polyaramid**: Known for use in bulletproof vests and flame-resistant outfits.\n\nOne important point about these synthetic fibers is that they are derived from petroleum. This origin gives them molecular structures that are much less chemically reactive compared to natural fibers. While there are differences in chemical reactivity among various synthetic fibers, these differences are generally minor when compared to those between synthetic and natural fibers.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What percentage of global total fiber consumption do synthetic fibers comprise?"; options = vec { "1%"; "5%"; "10%"; "15%" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which of the following is a typical application of acrylic fibers?"; options = vec { "Flame retardant garments"; "Artificial wigs"; "Sweaters"; "Bulletproof vests" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is a common characteristic of synthetic fibers mentioned in the content?"; options = vec { "High chemical reactivity"; "Natural origin"; "Petroleum-based origins"; "Low tensile strength" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which synthetic fiber is used in golf clubs and helmets?"; options = vec { "Modacrylic"; "Carbon fiber"; "Polyaramid"; "Acrylic" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How do synthetic fibers generally compare to natural fibers in terms of chemical reactivity?"; options = vec { "They are more reactive"; "They have similar reactivity"; "They are less reactive"; "They are completely inert" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "9.0";
    unit_title = "Semi-Synthetic Fibers, also known as Semi-Natural Fibers (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II: Basics";
    head_unit_id = "9";
    head_unit_title = ". Semi-Synthetic (also known as Semi-Natural) Fibers";
    content = "Semi-synthetic fibers are a group of fibers derived from natural materials such as wood pulp, bamboo, soy, corn starch, etc. The chemical structures of these natural ingredients are converted through various artificial re-polymerization processes using different chemicals. Typically, this involves various physical or chemical means of, for example, dissolving the main ingredients in a strong solvent chemical to create a viscous solution or turning them into powders for forming desired shapes using various types of adhesives to bond them together. Examples of the later include beverage straws and cups made of natural ingredients instead of other materials like plastics, metals, ceramics, etc. In the applications of textile materials, it is invariably the dissolution method used.  \nThe polymerization process for the semi-synthetic fibers is similar with that of the synthetic fibers particularly in the mechanics of the polymerization and extrusion: Long chains of polymers are formed in viscose liquid states under specific manufacturing conditions, then extruded through spinnerets with small holes to create linear fiber shapes. The main difference between the two fiber types is that the synthetic fibers require primarily heat energy for the polymerization of monomers with little to no intervention from other chemicals while the semi-synthetic fibers involve chemically strong solvents to dissolve the naturally sourced materials. \nExamples of the semi-synthetic fibers include rayon, modal, lyocell (branded as Tencel), bamboo, seaweed, etc. These fibers are typically known for their soft, silky and smooth textures and appearances. A more recent addition to the market is the Sorona, which utilizes corn starch as the source material. Many people perceive the fibers in this category as more sustainable than the synthetic fibers, and they are favored by many environmental interest groups and activists.\nHowever, there are critical perspectives that may be missing in these considerations. For instance, the use of the toxic solvents to dissolve the cellulose-based ingredients leaves serious toxicity footprint for the environment, not to mention that it requires large amounts of water and energy use to wash the toxic chemicals off the fibers before the subsequent manufacturing processes and consumption. Moreover, they possess the characteristics of consuming and releasing large quantities of chemicals like natural fibers and generate microplastics like synthetic fibers. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Semi-Synthetic Fibers\n\n**What are Semi-Synthetic Fibers?**\n\nSemi-synthetic fibers come from natural materials such as wood pulp, bamboo, soy, and corn starch. These natural materials undergo chemical changes through various processes, transforming their structure into fibers that can be used in textiles. \n\n**How Are They Made?**\n\nThe production of semi-synthetic fibers usually involves one of two methods:\n\n1. **Dissolving**: The natural ingredients are dissolved in strong solvents to form a thick liquid solution.\n2. **Powdering**: They can also be turned into powders, which are then combined into shapes using adhesives. \n\nAn example of products made from these materials includes biodegradable straws and cups, which are alternatives to common plastic items.\n\n**The Polymerization Process**\n\nThe process used to create semi-synthetic fibers is similar to that for synthetic fibers, particularly in how polymers are formed and shaped. Here’s a simplified overview:\n\n- **Polymer Formation**: Long chains of polymers are created from the viscous liquid under controlled manufacturing conditions.\n- **Extrusion**: This liquid is then forced through small holes in a spinneret to form long strands of fibers. \n\nThe key difference lies in the energy sources used: \n- **Synthetic fibers** primarily rely on heat to create the polymers from chemical monomers with minimal chemicals.\n- **Semi-synthetic fibers**, on the other hand, depend on strong solvents to dissolve natural materials.\n\n**Examples of Semi-Synthetic Fibers**\n\nSome common types of semi-synthetic fibers include:\n- **Rayon**\n- **Modal**\n- **Lyocell** (marketed as Tencel)\n- **Bamboo**\n- **Seaweed**\n- **Sorona** (made from corn starch)\n\nThese fibers are often appreciated for their soft, smooth, and silky textures. Many consider them more sustainable than traditional synthetic fibers, which is why they are popular among environmental groups and advocates.\n\n**Concerns and Criticisms**\n\nHowever, it is important to address some critical viewpoints regarding semi-synthetic fibers:\n- The toxic solvents used to dissolve the cellulose-based materials can negatively impact the environment.\n- The production process typically requires significant amounts of water and energy, particularly to remove these harmful chemicals from the fibers.\n- Additionally, semi-synthetic fibers can also release harmful chemicals, similar to natural fibers, and they may generate microplastics, like synthetic fibers.\n\nIn summary, while semi-synthetic fibers offer some sustainable benefits, it is essential to consider the environmental impact of their production methods and the chemicals involved.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What are semi-synthetic fibers derived from?"; options = vec { "Synthetic chemicals"; "Natural materials"; "Metallic elements"; "Ceramic compounds" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which process is primarily used to create semi-synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "Mechanical spinning"; "Chemical polymerization"; "Heat energy only"; "Natural weaving" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is an example of a semi-synthetic fiber?"; options = vec { "Nylon"; "Rayon"; "Polyester"; "Acrylic" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is a concern regarding the production of semi-synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "High cost of production"; "Use of toxic solvents"; "Short lifespan of fibers"; "Requires no water" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which semi-synthetic fiber is derived from corn starch?"; options = vec { "Lyocell"; "Modal"; "Sorona"; "Bamboo" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "9.1.0";
    unit_title = "Regenerated Cellulose Fibers";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "9.1";
    head_unit_title = "Regenerated Cellulose Fibers";
    content = "The discovery and initial development of the regenerated cellulose occurred in the late 19th century when scientists found that the cellulose from various plant materials could dissolve in specific chemicals. Upon re-solidification, the material exhibited a silk-like appearance, soft and smooth texture, which led to it being initially named “artificial silk” or “wood silk”. Driven by the favourable characteristics, it has been used for a wide range of consumer textiles such as shirts, dresses, jackets, etc.  \n***Industry Specifics (11) – Start***\nProcess Descriptions: The general description of the manufacturing process involves harvesting the cellulose, the primary component of plants, which is found in the trunks, barks, roots, and other parts of trees. This cellulose is then subjected to a chemical bath for dissolution. Breaking down the cellulose into a pulpy and viscous solution requires the use of highly intensive chemicals defined as “solvents”. The types of the solvents used in this process include the commonly utilized solution of the caustic soda and the carbon disulphide, as well as the amine oxide, the later of which is specifically used in the manufacturing of the Tencel.\nDepending on the types of wood sources, chemicals, and processes used for dissolving and processing the cellulose, these fibers are commercially known as Rayon (or Viscose), Modal, and Tencel (or Lyocell). The cellulose contents in the regenerated fibers can vary, typically ranging from high 80% to high 90%, depending on the specific processes employed. The remaining percentage is composed of various residual chemicals, impurities, and additives that result from the source materials and the production processes. The level of the residual chemicals and impurities are considerably higher in the regenerative cellulose fibers than that of the synthetic fibers, which normally ranges less than 1%. This is attributed by the naturally sourced materials containing larger amounts of impurities as well as inherently higher chemical reactivities in them compared with the petroleum sources for the synthetic fibers. \n***Industry Specifics (11) – End***\nDevelopment History: Rayon was the first developed in the category of the regenerated cellulose fibers. Subsequently, two other variations of chemical synthesis, using different source materials and solvents, led to the creation of the other fiber types, commercially known as Modal and Tencel (or Lyocell).\nThe development of Modal was primarily driven by the need to improve the wet strength of Rayon during the 1950s and 60s. Garments made of Rayon were prone to stretching or creasing when laundered with water or exposed to rain, due to the fiber’s low wet strength.\nA Japanese company, the inventor of Modal, significantly improved the fiber'\''s wet strength by using specifically the beech wood instead of other plant species. This innovation retained other desirable properties of Rayon, such as soft and smooth texture and silk-like appearance, leading to Modal'\''s popularity shortly after its commercialization. I recall purchasing a couple of shirts made of Modal in the early 2000’s and appreciating their characteristics. Additionally, Modal was recognized as a more sustainable option as the beech wood requires minimal water for growth and is resistant to pests and diseases, reducing the need for irrigation, pesticides, and fertilizers. With lower water and chemical footprints, along with the improved wet strength, Modal seemed like an ideal solution.\nDespite the Modal’s advantages, however, its overall environmental impact remained significant, as a large portion of the solvent used in the manufacturing process could not be reused. To address these environmental concerns, an Austrian company, Lenzing AG, developed a process that reclaims and reuses nearly all the solvent used in the process, significantly reducing the chemical footprint on the environment. This new generation of the regenerated cellulose fiber is called “Lyocell”, branded as “Tencel”, and its production began in the 1990s.\nAccording to Lenzing AG, 99% of the solvent is reclaimed and reused. Given the high volatility and toxicity of the solvents, reclaiming 99% is a notable achievement. Moreover, the solvent used for Tencel, amine oxide, is recognized as less toxic than those used for Rayon and Modal, as it does not produce neurotoxic carbon disulfide.\nAlthough the amine oxide is more expensive than the solvents used for Rayon and Modal, the overall production cost of Tencel is likely lower due to the high reclamation rate. This makes Tencel a prime example of the environmental sustainability not necessarily being more costly. I have long advocated for eco-friendly materials, products, and technologies that do not entail higher costs. It has been shown that only a small portion of the population is willing to pay a significant premium for eco-friendly products, while the majority will not, regardless of their expressed values. More in-depth discussion on this subject is provided in Chapter V: Solutions. \nEnvironmental Impacts: The solvents used in the production of the regenerated cellulose fibers are extremely harmful and can cause significant disruption to the ecosystems if released into the environment. In the production of Rayon and Modal, it has been reported that up to 50% of the solvents cannot be recycled and are often released into the environment. This reality makes the chemical processing of these popular soft fabrics particularly detrimental to the planet.\nMoreover, the regenerated cellulose fibers retain inherent chemical reactivity derived from the cellulose in all plant-based fibers. Although the chemical compositions of the fibers are slightly altered during their chemical synthesis, as illustrated in Fig.34, the presence of the hydroxyl groups remains abundant in the regenerated fibers. Additionally, the introduction of the xanthate functional group, highlighted in red in Fig.34, further increases their chemical activity. As repeatedly mentioned, higher levels of chemical reactivity correspond to higher levels of toxicity in the entire lifecycles of the materials in question from manufacturing to disposal, lingering in nature even long after disposal.  \n***Industry Specifics (12) – Start***\nFig.34   Xanthation of Cellulose\n***Industry Specifics (12) – End***\nWhen environmental groups and activists claim that semi-synthetic fibers are more environmentally friendly than fully synthetic fibers due to their naturally sourced materials, they often focus solely on the carbon aspect associated with the synthetic fibers from their petroleum sources, overlooking the significant environmental impacts of the toxic solvents and the heightened chemical use in this category of fibers. If we were to replace all synthetic fibers with the regenerated cellulose fibers, the resulting toxicity from the solvents alone could cause substantial and immediate environmental damages.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Regenerated Cellulose Fibers\n\n## Overview\nThe journey of regenerated cellulose began in the late 1800s when researchers discovered that cellulose—the main component of plants—could dissolve in specific chemicals. When this cellulose was reformed, it looked like silk and felt soft and smooth, earning it names like “artificial silk” or “wood silk.” Due to these appealing features, regenerated cellulose is widely used in clothing, such as shirts, dresses, and jackets.\n\n## Manufacturing Process\n### How it'\''s Made\nThe process of making regenerated cellulose fibers starts by harvesting cellulose from various parts of trees like trunks and barks. This cellulose is then treated in a chemical bath that dissolves it into a thick solution. This dissolution requires strong chemicals known as solvents. Common solvents for this process include caustic soda, carbon disulfide, and amine oxide (especially used for Tencel production).\n\nBased on the type of wood used and the solvents in the process, the resulting fibers are known commercially as Rayon (or Viscose), Modal, and Tencel (or Lyocell). The cellulose content in these fibers usually ranges from 80% to over 90%. The remaining percentage consists of chemicals, impurities, and additives from both the initial materials and production methods. Notably, regenerated cellulose fibers often have higher amounts of these impurities than synthetic fibers, which usually contain less than 1%. This higher impurity level is due to the natural origins of the cellulose compared to synthetic fibers made from petroleum.\n\n## Development History\nRayon was the first type of regenerated cellulose fiber created. Later, two additional types were developed: Modal and Tencel (or Lyocell). \n\n### Modal\nDeveloped in the 1950s and 60s, Modal was created to fix some of Rayon’s weaknesses, particularly its low wet strength, which caused garments to stretch or wrinkle when wet. The Japanese company that invented Modal improved the fiber’s performance by using beech wood, which kept the desirable attributes of Rayon like a soft texture and silk-like look. Modal became popular for its sustainability since beech trees require little water, reducing the need for irrigation and chemicals like pesticides.\n\nDespite these benefits, Modal production poses environmental challenges because a lot of solvent used can’t be reused. To counter this, Lenzing AG, an Austrian company, developed a method that recycles nearly all of the solvents used, leading to a new fiber known as Lyocell or Tencel, first produced in the 1990s. Remarkably, Lenzing AG claims that 99% of the solvents are reclaimed and reused. This is impressive considering the toxicity of these solvents. The amine oxide solvent used in Tencel is also less harmful than those used in Rayon and Modal. Although more expensive, Tencel’s production costs can be lower overall due to its high reclamation rate, proving that sustainable practices can be economically viable.\n\n## Environmental Impact\nThe solvents required for producing regenerated cellulose fibers are very harmful and can significantly disrupt ecosystems if they enter the environment. Reports indicate that as much as 50% of the solvents used in Rayon and Modal production is not recycled and is often released into nature, making the manufacturing of these fabrics damaging to the planet.\n\nAdditionally, regenerated cellulose fibers retain some of the chemical reactivity of natural cellulose. Although their structure changes slightly during production, certain functional groups increase their chemical activity, leading to greater potential toxicity during their life cycle, from manufacturing to disposal.\n\n## Important Considerations\nEnvironmental advocates sometimes argue that semi-synthetic fibers like Modal and Tencel are better for the planet compared to fully synthetic fibers because they originate from natural materials. However, this perspective often overlooks the harmful effects of the toxic solvents used in their production. If we replaced all synthetic fibers with regenerated cellulose fibers, the pollution from solvents alone could lead to significant short-term environmental damage.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "In which century did the discovery and initial development of regenerated cellulose occur?"; options = vec { "18th century"; "19th century"; "20th century"; "21st century" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is the initial name given to the regenerated cellulose due to its silk-like appearance?"; options = vec { "Artificial silk"; "Synthetic fiber"; "Regenerated nylon"; "Natural fiber" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "Which solvent is specifically used in the manufacturing of Tencel?"; options = vec { "Amine oxide"; "Caustic soda"; "Carbon disulphide"; "Water" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What was a significant improvement of Modal over Rayon?"; options = vec { "Lower production cost"; "Higher wet strength"; "Softer texture"; "Silk-like appearance" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What percentage of the solvent used in Tencel production is reclaimed and reused?"; options = vec { "50%"; "75%"; "99%"; "100%" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "9.2.0";
    unit_title = "Sorona®";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "9.2";
    head_unit_title = "Sorona®";
    content = "Sorona® is a different breed of semi-natural fibers, partially derived from corn starch and partially from petroleum-based materials, avoiding the use of solvent unlike other plant-based semi-natural fibers. It was developed by the renowned DuPont company, which has made substantial contributions to the textile industry over the years. In my view, DuPont has enriched our lives more than any other company in the textile sector. The company pioneered the development of several important synthetic materials and technologies widely used in the industry, beginning with the invention of Nylon, the first synthetic fiber, in 1935. This innovation has inspired numerous scientists and companies to develop many other critically important synthetic materials.\nThe company was awarded the 2003 Presidential Green Chemistry Challenge Award for their development of Sorona. In my opinion, if I had the authority, I would have certainly bestowed upon DuPont the highest possible award for sustainability, in recognition of the groundbreaking Nylon polymer. Thus, it seems to me that this award was granted almost a century late.\n***Industry Specifics (13) – Start***\nProcess Descriptions and Compositions:  Sorona®, known scientifically as poly-trimethylene terephthalate-co-1,4-cyclohexanedimethylene terephthalate, is a polymer that blends plant-derived polymers, specifically corn starch, with petrochemicals. It is known for its flexibility, stretch recovery, smooth and soft hand feel, among other attractive features.  \nCorn crops are utilized to extract sugar or glucose. Microorganisms are then introduced to ferment the glucose, replacing the need for chemical synthesis and resulting in the natural production of PDO (1,3-Propanediol). This Bio-PDO is then combined with TPA (terephthalic acid) sourced from petroleum processing, forming a molecular linkage and resulting in the creation of the Sorona® polymer. \nThe natural component from the corn, i.e., PDO, accounts for 37% of the mass of Sorona® while the rest is of the TPA from the petroleum. Therefore, two thirds of the composition is from the petroleum source while many may mistakenly think it is purely from the natural source of corn. \nFig.35   Molecular Structure of Sorona®\n***Industry Specifics (13) – End***\nSocial and Environmental Considerations: From a different perspective, using corn as a source material for Sorona® raises concerns, as the corn is a crucial food source for humans and animals alike. Given that one in nine people globally do not have enough food to consume and are malnourished, the sustainability of using a food source to produce fibers is questionable from a humanitarian standpoint. While there are wealthy individuals in developed economies who do not worry about their meals, a significant proportion of the world’s population is not as fortunate. These underprivileged would most certainly disagree with the practice of converting food sources into fibers, viewing it, in my view, as unworthy of the 2003 award recognition for the company.\nFurthermore, the decomposition behavior and microplastic generation of Sorona® are not markedly different from other synthetic fibers. Sorona'\''s chemical composition, characterized by multiple carbonyl groups in carbon-oxygen double bonds, is stable and exhibits low chemical reactivity. This stability means that Sorona® has a similar lifespan to other synthetic fibers in nature. \nThe question remains: what justifies the 2003 award as a significant achievement? Is replacing one third of petroleum with corn as the source material sufficient to deem Sorona more \"sustainable\"? Keeping in mind that the avoidance of toxic solvents is clearly more sustainable than the manufacturing methods employed for the regenerative cellulose fibers, we must also recognize that all synthetic fibers share the same manufacturing principles, not needing solvents. \nThe overarching theme of this book is that synthetic materials are not inherently detrimental for the environment, and their benefits outweigh the negatives. Had I been in a position to decide, I might not have awarded Sorona for its invention of Sorona®. In my view, DuPont deserved the highest accolades nearly 100 years ago for inventing Nylon, but Sorona® does not warrant the same level of recognition, particularly in the perspective of the “Green” Chemistry Challenge Award, while I have no opposition for such recognition without the “Green” decoration.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Sorona®: A Semi-Natural Fiber\n\n## Overview of Sorona®\n\nSorona® is a unique type of semi-natural fiber created from both corn starch and petroleum products. Unlike other plant-based fibers, Sorona® does not use solvents in its production, making it a more eco-friendly option. Developed by DuPont, a leading company in the textile industry, Sorona® reflects the company’s long history of innovation. DuPont is well-regarded for creating several essential synthetic materials, starting with Nylon, the first synthetic fiber, introduced in 1935. This early innovation has influenced many scientists and companies in the field of textiles.\n\nDuPont received the **2003 Presidential Green Chemistry Challenge Award** for creating Sorona®. I believe that the company should have received an even greater recognition for its invention of Nylon, which is a monumental advancement in the field.\n\n## What is Sorona®?\n\n### Composition and Production\n\nChemically known as **poly-trimethylene terephthalate-co-1,4-cyclohexanedimethylene terephthalate**, Sorona® combines plant-based polymers from corn with petrochemical ingredients. It is prized for its flexibility, ability to recover from stretching, and soft texture.\n\nTo make Sorona®, corn plants are harvested for their sugar, which is then fermented by microorganisms to produce a natural substance called **PDO (1,3-Propanediol)**. This Bio-PDO is mixed with **TPA (terephthalic acid)**, a compound derived from petroleum. This combination creates the Sorona® polymer. \n\nIt'\''s important to note that while PDO from corn makes up 37% of Sorona®'\''s composition, the remaining 63% comes from TPA derived from petroleum. This means that Sorona® consists largely of petroleum, despite its natural origin.\n\n![Molecular Structure of Sorona®](Fig.35)\n\n## Social and Environmental Considerations\n\nUsing corn as a raw material for Sorona® raises significant ethical questions. Corn is a vital food source for both humans and animals. With approximately one in nine people worldwide suffering from hunger and malnutrition, the decision to convert food into fibers can be seen as problematic. While people in wealthier countries may take their food security for granted, many others do not, and they might oppose using food resources to create non-food products.\n\nAdditionally, Sorona® behaves similarly to other synthetic fibers in terms of how it breaks down and generates microplastics. Its stable chemical structure, which has many carbonyl groups, means that it lasts in the environment for a comparable time to other synthetic fibers.\n\nThis leads us to question: does replacing a portion of petroleum with corn justify receiving the Green Chemistry Challenge Award? While avoiding toxic solvents in production is a notable achievement, it’s essential to remember that most synthetic fibers are produced without solvents. \n\nThe main idea is that synthetic materials in general are not necessarily harmful to the environment, and their advantages often outweigh their disadvantages. If I had the power to decide, I would not have given Sorona® the same level of recognition that DuPont received for Nylon. In my opinion, DuPont’s earlier accomplishments deserve the highest honors, but Sorona® does not reach that same high standard, especially in the context of the Green Chemistry Challenge Award. That said, I have no objection to recognizing Sorona® without the \"Green\" label.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is Sorona® primarily derived from?"; options = vec { "Petroleum only"; "Corn starch only"; "A blend of corn starch and petroleum-based materials"; "Synthetic chemicals" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which company developed Sorona®?"; options = vec { "BASF"; "DuPont"; "3M"; "Hanes" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What percentage of Sorona® is made from corn-derived PDO?"; options = vec { "25%"; "37%"; "50%"; "67%" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "In what year did DuPont receive the Presidential Green Chemistry Challenge Award for Sorona®?"; options = vec { "1995"; "2000"; "2003"; "2010" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is a significant concern regarding the use of corn for Sorona® production?"; options = vec { "It is less durable than synthetic fibers"; "It raises questions about food sustainability"; "It is more expensive than petroleum-based materials"; "It causes toxic waste" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "9.3.0";
    unit_title = "Other Semi-Synthetic Fibers – Bamboo, Pineapple, etc.";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "9.3";
    head_unit_title = "Other Semi-Synthetic Fibers – Bamboo, Pineapple, etc.";
    content = "A diverse array of other semi-synthetic fibers exists, and growing public environmental awareness has prompted increased interest in these materials although the usage has remained fractional in the global total fiber consumption. Examples include bamboo, soy, pineapple, seaweed, etc.\nSimilar to the previously mentioned regenerated cellulose fibers, the environmental impacts of these fiber types can be significantly negative with the use of strong solvents. To maintain the focus of this book on the most impactful and important fibers for assessing their environmental impacts, I do not delve into more details of these fibers. Instead, I present their names along with a couple of application examples:\nAcetate: cigarette filters, furniture fillings, etc. \nBamboo: pillow covers, towels, etc.  \nSoybean: socks, curtains, etc. \nSeaweed: skin moisturizing and nourishing sheets, towels, etc.  \n";
    paraphrase = "# Semi-Synthetic Fibers\n\nThere is a variety of semi-synthetic fibers available, and with increasing public awareness of environmental issues, there is growing interest in these materials. However, their usage still represents a small part of the total fiber consumption worldwide. Some examples of these fibers include bamboo, soy, pineapple, and seaweed.\n\nLike regenerated cellulose fibers, these semi-synthetic fibers can also have negative environmental impacts due to the use of strong solvents in their production processes. To keep the focus on the most significant fibers affecting the environment, I will not go into deeper details about these materials. Instead, I will list their names along with a few examples of how they are used:\n\n- **Acetate**: Used in cigarette filters, furniture fillings, etc.  \n- **Bamboo**: Found in pillow covers, towels, etc.  \n- **Soybean**: Used for making socks, curtains, etc.  \n- **Seaweed**: Utilized in skin moisturizing and nourishing sheets, towels, etc.  ";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "Which of the following is NOT mentioned as a semi-synthetic fiber?"; options = vec { "Bamboo"; "Cotton"; "Soy"; "Seaweed" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is one application example of acetate?"; options = vec { "Pillow covers"; "Socks"; "Cigarette filters"; "Towels" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which material is used for making towels according to the content?"; options = vec { "Cotton"; "Bamboo"; "Nylon"; "Wool" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What has prompted increased interest in semi-synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "Their lower cost"; "Public environmental awareness"; "Fashion trends"; "Government regulations" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which fiber is mentioned as being used in skin moisturizing sheets?"; options = vec { "Bamboo"; "Soybean"; "Acetate"; "Seaweed" }; answer = 3; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "10.0";
    unit_title = "Manufacturing (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II: Basics";
    head_unit_id = "10";
    head_unit_title = ". Manufacturing";
    content = "This chapter will examine the manufacturing principles of textile production and their implications for the environmental sustainability. The subsections will be organized in the following subjects: farming for natural fibers, synthesizing for synthetic fibers, yarn-making, fabric-making, dyeing, cut-and-sew, and other, representing a typical order from the beginning to the final stage of manufacturing before reaching consumers.  \nIn the meantime, a detailed understanding of the intricate processes involved in textile manufacturing may not be essential for addressing the important purposes of this book or for comprehending the broader environmental impacts of different textiles. With this in mind, this section focuses on providing a concise overview of the typical flow of textile production. While this approach may make it challenging for some readers to fully grasp certain specific subjects, those seeking a deeper understanding can benefit from further study. For most readers, however, the terminologies and basic concepts introduced here will be sufficient for following the discussions throughout the book and for engaging in related conversations.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Overview of Textile Production and Environmental Sustainability\n\nIn this chapter, we will explore how textiles are made and how these processes affect the environment. The topics will be arranged in a sequence that reflects the typical steps of production, beginning with the following:\n\n- **Farming for Natural Fibers**: Growing plants or raising animals for fiber.\n- **Synthesizing for Synthetic Fibers**: Creating fibers from chemical processes.\n- **Yarn-Making**: Spinning fibers into yarn.\n- **Fabric-Making**: Weaving or knitting yarn into fabric.\n- **Dyeing**: Adding color to the fabric.\n- **Cut-and-Sew**: Cutting fabric into pieces and stitching them together to create products.\n- **Other Processes**: Additional steps in textile production not covered in detail.\n\nThis sequence outlines the journey of textiles from their beginnings to when they reach consumers.\n\nWhile it is not necessary to know every detail about textile manufacturing to understand the main points of this book or the broader environmental effects of various textiles, we aim to provide a clear and simple overview of the typical production flow. \n\nSome readers might find that this summary makes it harder to grasp specific topics in depth. However, those interested in learning more can pursue additional resources. For most readers, the basic terms and concepts presented here will be enough to follow the discussions in the book and participate in relevant conversations.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What are the two main types of fibers discussed in textile production?"; options = vec { "Natural and Synthetic fibers"; "Organic and Inorganic fibers"; "Cotton and Polyester"; "Wool and Nylon" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What is the first stage in the typical order of textile manufacturing?"; options = vec { "Dyeing"; "Farming for natural fibers"; "Yarn-making"; "Cut-and-sew" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "The chapter primarily focuses on:"; options = vec { "Detailed processes of textile manufacturing"; "Environmental sustainability in textile production"; "The history of textile production"; "Consumer behavior regarding textiles" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What might some readers find challenging about this chapter?"; options = vec { "Understanding specific terminologies and concepts"; "Finding the content boring"; "The lack of visuals"; "The simplicity of the explanations" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "Who may benefit from further study of textile manufacturing processes?"; options = vec { "Most readers"; "Those seeking deeper understanding"; "Only industry professionals"; "Consumers looking to buy textiles" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "10.1.0";
    unit_title = "Fibers (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "10.1";
    head_unit_title = "Fibers";
    content = "In this discussion, we explore the origins of the three main categories of fibers particularly in the manufacturing perspective, which include farming for natural fibers.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding the Origins of Fiber Categories\n\nIn this section, we will look into how the three primary types of fibers come about, particularly focusing on the manufacturing side. This includes the farming practices used to produce natural fibers.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What are the three main categories of fibers discussed?"; options = vec { "Synthetic, Natural, and Artificial"; "Natural, Artificial, and Man-made"; "Natural, Synthetic, and Regenerated"; "Natural, Chemical, and Biological" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What aspect of fibers is primarily focused on in the discussion?"; options = vec { "Washing techniques"; "Manufacturing perspective"; "Design applications"; "Coloring processes" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which category includes fibers derived from plants and animals?"; options = vec { "Synthetic fibers"; "Natural fibers"; "Recycled fibers"; "Man-made fibers" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is one method mentioned for obtaining natural fibers?"; options = vec { "Harvesting"; "Synthesis"; "Processing chemicals"; "Weaving" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "Which term refers to fibers that are not produced from natural sources?"; options = vec { "Natural fibers"; "Organic fibers"; "Synthetic fibers"; "Plant-based fibers" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "10.1.1";
    unit_title = "Farming";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "10.1";
    head_unit_title = "Fibers";
    content = "A brief review of the related discussions previously presented: Natural fibers are derived from farming plants that naturally produce fibers, such as cotton, or farming animals that grow hair, such as wool, while leather and down feather is the byproduct of animal farming. Cotton is the most widely used natural fiber and is second only to polyester in overall usage.\nCultivation \nCotton cultivation requires specific agricultural conditions, typically frost-free environments with daily temperatures ideally ranging from 20 to 30oC (68 to 86 oF) and ample sunlight. The world'\''s major cotton-producing countries include United States, Uzbekistan, China, India, Brazil, Pakistan, Turkey, etc. Cotton occupies a significant portion of some of the most prolific agricultural lands around the world.  \nThirsty Crop: Cotton is known as a “thirsty” crop and the water footprint of it is among the largest of all crops either for personal and animal food consumption or any other purposes. On average, cotton cultivation requires 8,000 to 10,000 liters of water per kilogram of fiber produced. This compares with 3,000 to 5,000 liters for rice and 500 to 4,000 litres for wheat. \nThese water consumption figures vary widely by various factors including weather conditions and agricultural practices. As such, the quoted figure of 8,000 ~ 10,000 liters for cotton can further increase in hot climates. This excessive water consumption presents significant challenges in both environmental and humanitarian perspectives - Water scarcity is a critical issue affecting the health of humans, animals and other plants in many areas of cotton cultivation. \nWater Contamination: Beyond the sheer volume of water used, cotton irrigation practices also lead to significant contamination in water with toxic chemicals such as pesticides and fertilizers. As mentioned earlier, one of the most serious humanitarian crises our global society face today is a significant lack of fresh water in many underdeveloped and developing countries. Highly toxic chemicals used in farming reach wide areas of neighboring regions through runoff water and contamination in soil, leading to pollution in ground water, and further exacerbating the water scarcity. \nToxic Elements and Compounds: Cotton cultivation poses particularly increased environmental challenges due to the toxicity of the chemicals used, many of which recognized as hazardous by the World Health Organization (WHO). A couple of examples of the pesticides include:\nAldicarb: One of the most toxic pesticides applied to cotton. A powerful nerve agent.\nEndosulfan: One of the most widely used pesticides for cotton. Linked to comas, seizures, and even death. Believed to be the most important source of fatal poisoning among West African cotton farmers.\nBasic Chemistry: The toxicity of harmful chemicals such as pesticides are partly driven by the containment of heavy elements, which we learned in the periodic table of high school chemistry, e.g., #80 mercury, #82 lead, etc., and other harmful compounds. These harmful chemicals remain in nature, accumulate and magnify within food chains, a process known as bioaccumulation and biomagnification, subsequently being ingested by living organisms. Some of these chemicals can persist in nature for extended period, easily exceeding lifetimes of humans and animals. Notably, Dr. Clair Patterson, whom I will highlight as “GREEN HERO” in Chapter V: Solutions, used a specific lead isotope to calculate the Earth'\''s age as approximately 4.5 billion years, as the element endures in nature almost indefinitely. \nToxicity Migration and Bioaccumulation \nA significant amount of harmful chemicals, once washed away from one material, do not disappear, but instead, migrate to other materials, either in their original forms or the byproducts of their chemical reactions, through intermediary carriers such as water, air and food sources. This phenomenon results in widespread and persistent impacts on the health and safety of all living organisms on Earth.\nTo illustrate this issue, I present a report issued by National State of Environment Report, Ministry of Ecology, Environmental Protection and Climate Change of Republic of Uzbekistan and International Institute for Sustainable Development (IISD), in December 2023.  \nhttps://www.iisd.org/system/files/2024-02/uzbekistan-state-of-the-environment-en.pdf \nCotton’s Contribution for Environmental Harm: The report offers a comprehensive analysis of key factors contributing to the degradation and desertification of the agricultural lands in the country, alongside the drying of the Aral Sea. Across its extensive 120-page length, it depicts the cotton cultivation as a primary factor influencing the current environmental conditions, ranking ahead of the textile industry and other agricultural crops.\nUzbekistan, along with its neighboring Kazakhstan, has played a significant role as a major exporter of high-quality cotton in competitive prices. As the cotton industry has been a cornerstone of Uzbekistan'\''s economy for centuries, with some characterizing the country’s economies as \"one-crop\" economy, this historical emphasis on cotton helps contextualize its prominent listing in the report as the leading cause of numerous environmental challenges facing the country, including agricultural land degradation, water contamination, and even impacts related to climate change.\nNature of Pollution through Air: Upon reviewing the 2023 report, I find it both interesting and alarming that the air quality, expressed as the Maximum Permissible Concentration (MPC) levels in the Atmospheric Air Quality analysis for several specific pollutants, such as ammonia, formaldehyde, phenol, and heavy metals (cadmium, copper, zinc, and lead), common components of pesticides or fertilizers, was below the maximum threshold, found on the page 27 of the report.\nIn general, the spray methods used to apply pesticides over large areas are significant contributors to airborne toxicity in farming. This method disperses high concentrations of chemicals as aerosols into the air. Some of these chemicals land on targeted crops, while others are carried away by the wind. As we know, air flows freely, moving at much higher speeds than other mediums that carry harmful chemicals. Unlike soil and water contamination, which can take weeks, months, or even years to spread to other regions via runoff or groundwater, air has no physical barriers and is the most efficient means of spreading pollutants globally.\nConsidering these factors, it is only natural that the high soil and water toxicity levels of the surveyed areas did not directly translate into the air quality results in the report. Instead, it highlights how the airborne toxicity generated by the country’s farming activities has rapidly spread and contaminated other parts of the world.\nLow and High Dosage Exposure: Moreover, an excerpt of another research paper which discusses the environmental and health impacts of harmful elements such as heavy metals raises a flag in this regard. \n“Chronic low dosage exposure to numerous elements is a substantial threat to public health in many regions with metal pollution, particularly in places where metal pollution is ubiquitous.” \nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1018364722000465  \nA notable example is the trend in “Blood Lead Levels (BLL)” in people around the globe, which closely align with the periods of industrialization, increasing proportionally with the industrial outputs including the expansion of pesticide use in agriculture and peaking during the decades when leaded gasoline was used to enhance vehicle performance. Following the global ban on the leaded gasoline, the BLLs have declined, although they remain markedly higher than the pre-industrial levels. This highlights the persistent environmental toxicity from the accumulation of heavy metals and other harmful substances in the ecosystems and organisms, impacting the health of human and animal populations. More on the health impact from harmful chemicals will be presented in Chapter V: Solutions. \nOrganic Cotton: With the heightened awareness regarding the environmental harm of the conventional cotton farming, some farmers have turned to growing organic cotton. They often present various certificates to appeal the organic nature of their cotton to consumers. However, it is important to understand that this may not necessarily imply a total ban on harmful chemicals and no negative environmental impacts. As in the nature of many other certification programs, this practice may involve presenting only a limited scope to appeal to consumers while intentionally or mistakenly missing important perspectives of environmental harm in their certificates and farming processes. As this subject merits a dedicated discussion, I will present more details and perspectives in Chapter IV: Misinformation Crisis.\nMore specifically, the organic cotton cultivation may involve certain methods to inhibit the growth of bacteria and insects, such as bollworms, particularly harmful for cotton. In some cases, genetically modified cotton, such as Bt cotton, is used to reduce damage from insects. Similar to concerns over other genetically modified crops and vegetables, there is apprehension regarding the long-term effects of these modified crops on the ecosystems and human health. Furthermore, organic pesticides and fertilizers may be used instead of synthetic counterparts. However, despite the term \"organic\" providing reassurance to many, any substance designed to kill living organisms poses risks to human health and environment. This principle is similar to the comparison between organic and synthetic dyes, as organic dyes are not free from toxicity.\nMoreover, the yield rate of the organic cotton can be lower, resulting in higher water and energy consumption, and consequently, higher quantities of greenhouse gas emissions. It may also require more agricultural land. Currently, organic cotton accounts for about 1% of the total cotton consumption globally, and this proportion is rising rapidly.\nWhile I have some concerns about the organic cotton, I don’t conclude that it is necessarily better or worse than their conventionally farmed counterparts. To be honest, I lack the comprehensive knowledge needed to fully understand its overall impact on the environmental sustainability. My point here is to emphasize that the true environmental impacts are rarely limited to a singular scope and require deeper analysis beyond the claims made by advocates. If a careful and thorough evaluation reveals a net positive effect, it should be supported as a way to reduce the significant environmental burden associated with cotton farming.\n***\nIt is evident that cotton farming significantly influences the global environmental health. Therefore, I firmly believe that promoting natural fibers over synthetic fibers, solely based on a limited scope which favors associated arguments will not result in a healthier overall environment. Additionally, promoting synthetic fibers over natural fibers without considering complex factors such as consumers'\'' tactile preferences, emotional connections, and the socioeconomic realities faced by natural fiber farmers worldwide would be equally counterproductive. Instead, efforts should focus on reducing the environmental impacts of both fiber types and making gradual, mid- to long-term transitions toward the most sustainable options.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Cotton Farming and Its Environmental Impact\n\n## Overview of Natural Fibers\nNatural fibers come from two main sources: plants and animals. For example, cotton is a plant-based fiber, while wool comes from animals. Other products like leather and down feathers are also sourced from animals. Cotton is the most popular natural fiber, following polyester in usage.\n\n## Cotton Cultivation\nCotton grows best in specific conditions—areas without frost and with daily temperatures between 20 to 30°C (68 to 86°F) and plenty of sunlight. Key cotton-producing countries include the United States, Uzbekistan, China, India, Brazil, Pakistan, and Turkey. Cotton cultivation occupies significant portions of valuable agricultural land globally.\n\n### Water Requirements\nCotton is often labeled as a “thirsty” crop due to its high water usage. On average, producing one kilogram of cotton fiber requires around 8,000 to 10,000 liters of water. In comparison, rice needs 3,000 to 5,000 liters, and wheat uses about 500 to 4,000 liters. These figures can vary depending on weather and farming practices, and water demand can increase in hotter climates. This heavy water use raises environmental and humanitarian concerns, especially in areas facing water shortages.\n\n### Water Contamination\nAlongside high water needs, cotton farming often results in water contamination due to the use of pesticides and fertilizers. Many developing countries grapple with a severe lack of fresh water. Chemicals from farming can pollute nearby areas through runoff, contaminating soil and drinking water sources.\n\n### Toxic Chemicals in Cotton Farming\nThe pesticides used in cotton farming can be harmful. For instance:\n- **Aldicarb:** Extremely toxic, acts as a strong nerve agent.\n- **Endosulfan:** Widely used, linked to severe health issues like comas and seizures. It poses a significant poisoning risk to cotton farmers in West Africa.\n\nThe harmful effects of these chemicals are partially driven by their content of heavy metals, which can accumulate in the environment—a process known as bioaccumulation and biomagnification. Some harmful substances remain in the ecosystem for long periods.\n\n## Migration of Toxic Chemicals\nChemicals washed away from cotton fields do not just disappear; they often move to other areas through water, air, or food. This movement contributes to ongoing health risks for all living beings.\n\n### Report on Environmental Conditions\nA recent report from the Uzbekistan government'\''s Ministry of Ecology and the International Institute for Sustainable Development provides data highlighting cotton cultivation as a leading cause of environmental damage, including soil degradation and increased water scarcity, especially concerning the Aral Sea.\n\n## Air Quality Issues\nInterestingly, air quality analysis in the report showed acceptable levels for pollutants like ammonia and heavy metals. However, pesticide spray methods contribute significantly to air pollution, dispersing chemicals as aerosols. These can travel great distances, making air a highly effective medium for spreading toxins quickly.\n\n### Health Effects of Heavy Metals\nResearch indicates that chronic exposure to heavy metals can pose serious health risks, particularly in polluted areas. For example, blood lead levels have increased alongside industrialization and pesticide use.\n\n## Organic Cotton Farming\nIn response to environmental concerns, some farmers have started growing organic cotton, which comes with certifications to attract consumers. However, it’s important to realize that \"organic\" does not guarantee a complete absence of harmful chemicals. Organic cotton farming may still utilize methods that pose risks, including the use of genetically modified organisms like Bt cotton to control pests.\n\nThough organic methods can reduce dependence on harmful synthetics, they might also have lower yields, which can lead to greater water, energy, and land use.\n\n## Conclusion\nCotton farming indeed impacts global environmental health significantly. Promoting one type of fiber over another due to limited viewpoints won'\''t effectively create a healthier environment. We should focus on minimizing the negative effects of both natural and synthetic fibers, striving for sustainable practices and gradual transitions towards better options.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What are natural fibers primarily derived from?"; options = vec { "Mining minerals"; "Farming plants and animals"; "Synthetic processes"; "Recycling materials" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which of the following is known as a '\''thirsty'\'' crop due to its high water requirements?"; options = vec { "Wheat"; "Rice"; "Cotton"; "Corn" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is one major environmental issue associated with cotton cultivation?"; options = vec { "Soil erosion"; "Deforestation"; "Water contamination"; "Loss of biodiversity" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which heavy metal is mentioned as a toxic element that can accumulate in nature?"; options = vec { "Iron"; "Copper"; "Lead"; "Zinc" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is a potential concern with organic cotton farming?"; options = vec { "Always uses harmful chemicals"; "Cannot require more water"; "May have lower yield rates"; "Is always better for the environment" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "10.1.2";
    unit_title = "Polymerization (Synthesis) of Synthetic Fibers";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "10.1";
    head_unit_title = "Fibers";
    content = "As discussed earlier, synthetic fibers are polymers created from the basic repeating units of monomers, derived from petroleum sources. The process of converting monomers to polymers is known as polymerization or synthesis. The overview of the polymerization and extrusion was discussed earlier in Section 8. Synthetic fibers. In this subsection, I present a commonly employed method for obtaining desired fibers from an intermediary material, known as polymer pellets.\n***Industry Specifics (14) – Start***\nFiber Extrusion from Polymer Pellets \nIn some circumstances, the molten polymer in polymerization tank is converted into small, solidified pieces in the shapes and sizes similar with the grains of rice or barley – examples shown in Chapter I: Fig.22, instead of extruding into the long strains of fibers. These small pieces are generally referred to as “polymer-pellets”, “-granules” or “-chips”.  \nPelletizing and Conversion: As also reviewed in Section 8. Synthetic fibers, once the polymerization reaches a desired viscosity in the polymerization tank, the liquid undergoes the extrusion process that allows it to cool down and solidify. To produce pellets instead of fibers during this process, the polymer extrudes in larger thicknesses (similar to making thicker noodles in pasta machine), then cut to obtain the desired sizes of pellets. This process is generally referred to as “pelletizing”.  \nIn subsequent processes, the pellets are remelted in a melting tank and converted into various forms such as fibers, films, plastic molds, zippers, and more. For instance, a fiber manufacturing company can purchase these pellets, put them into the melting tank at their facility, and extrude fibers from the tank. Similarly, a zipper manufacturing company can melt them, and cast the molten polymer into the shape of plastic zippers. A water bottle company can follow a similar process to mold the liquid polymer into the shape of bottles. This method of using pellets to convert into desired shapes is akin to 3D printing, where plastic granules serve as source material, melted to make it flow, and then formed into specific shapes, thanks to the fluidity of the molten polymer and its solidification characteristics.\nRationale of Intermediary Pelletizing Process: Many may question the necessity of converting the liquid viscous polymer formed in the initial polymerization process into pellets only to reheat it in subsequent processes, considering the additional energy consumption this process entails. The rationale lies in the nature of the polymerization process itself. \nPolymerization is an extensive and complex process requiring significant investment for large machinery setups and expansive land areas. Often, hundreds or even thousands of engineers, machine operators, and administrative staff work collaboratively in a single facility.\nIn the meantime, many factories producing fibers, zippers, bottles, and other plastic products lack the capacity to house such resource-intensive polymerization processes within their facilities. For instance, a zipper company with tens of employees only focuses on producing high-quality zippers. Such a company may not have necessary resources or interest to invest in extensive and costly polymerization processes. Instead, they can install a simpler, smaller, and less expensive melting tank to melt the pellets, then turn the molten polymer into desired shapes. This scenario is akin to a 3D printer owner who would not undertake the installation of a vast polymerization setup, even if he or she had a football field sized backyard and enough money. Consequently, the demand and market for various types of polymer pellets always exist and are substantial in size.  \nMelt-Blown Process\nAn illustrative example of the use of polymer pellets is a non-woven manufacturing process, specifically the “melt-blown” process. This process became critically integral to our daily lives when the COVID-19 pandemic broke out as it is used to produce face masks with high-filtration grades, such as N95 in US and FFP2 in Europe. Other examples include various goods consumed routinely by the public like sanitary pads, diapers, automotive filters, etc.\nSignificant Shortage and Efficient Industry Response: At the beginning of the pandemic, there was a significant shortage of face masks, especially those with high filtration grades, worldwide. Mask prices increased several folds within days and weeks, yet they were not accessible for weeks by the general public. However, the manufacturing capabilities of the melt-blown fabrics increased rapidly and responded to the public needs swiftly.  \nIf the melt-blown manufacturing companies had to install complex and heavy setup of polymerization tanks to convert monomers into polymers, then into masks, building such facilities would have taken years. However, due to the extremely efficient and nimble industry supply chains, thanks in large part to the flexibility involving this pelletizing process, the global demand for the high-filtration masks was quickly met.\n***Industry Specifics (14) – End***\nFace Masks made with Natural Fibers: On a related note, masks made from natural fibers are significantly less efficient in blocking pathogens. As discussed earlier, natural fibers carry much higher moisture contents and it leads to creating a more favourable environment for the growth of microorganisms. Since human breath contains nutrients for microorganisms, masks made of natural fibers could easily become a habitat for various pathogens, such as viruses and bacteria. If humanity had relied on masks made from natural fibers, the pandemic would likely have caused much more damages. On the other hand, polypropylene used as the main ingredient of the high filtration masks is one of the most hydrophobic materials available, with a moisture content of less than 0.1%. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Synthetic Fibers and Polymer Pellets\n\nSynthetic fibers are made from long chains of molecules called polymers, which are formed from smaller units known as monomers derived from petroleum. The process of creating polymers from monomers is called polymerization or synthesis. In this section, we'\''ll explain how fibers are made from an intermediary material known as polymer pellets.\n\n## Fiber Extrusion from Polymer Pellets\n\nSometimes, instead of directly creating long fibers, molten polymer is shaped into small solid pieces similar to grains of rice or barley, which are referred to as **polymer pellets**, **granules**, or **chips**.\n\n### Pelletizing Process\n\nOnce the polymer reaches the right viscosity in the polymerization tank, it goes through a process called **extrusion**. In this process, the liquid polymer is cooled and solidified. If the goal is to create pellets instead of long fibers, the polymer is extruded in thicker strands (like making thicker noodles) and then cut into the desired pellet sizes. This process is known as **pelletizing**.\n\nAfter pelletizing, these pellets can be remelted in another tank and formed into various products such as fibers, films, plastic molds, zippers, and more. For instance, a fiber manufacturer can melt these pellets to produce fibers, while a zipper company can mold them into zipper shapes. Similarly, water bottle manufacturers can mold the polymer into bottle shapes. This use of pellets is comparable to 3D printing, where plastic granules are melted, made fluid, and then shaped as needed.\n\n### Why Use Pelletizing?\n\nSome may wonder why it’s necessary to turn liquid polymer into pellets only to melt them again later, especially since this requires extra energy. The answer lies in the complexity of the polymerization process itself. \n\nPolymerization is a large-scale process that requires substantial investment in machinery and facilities, often employing hundreds or thousands of specialized workers in a single location. Many businesses that manufacture items like fibers and zippers simply do not have the resources to manage such extensive operations. For example, a small zipper company focusing on quality production can’t afford or choose to set up an expensive polymerization process, but they can use a more straightforward and economical melting tank to work with polymer pellets.\n\n### Example: The Melt-Blown Process\n\nA practical application of polymer pellets is in the **melt-blown process**, which became crucial during the COVID-19 pandemic for producing high-quality face masks, like N95 in the U.S. and FFP2 in Europe. Other products made from this process include everyday items like sanitary pads, diapers, and automotive filters.\n\nAt the start of the pandemic, there was a rapid shortage of face masks, and prices surged while availability dwindled. However, due to efficient manufacturing capabilities and flexible supply chains that utilize the pelletizing method, the production of melt-blown fabrics was able to scale up quickly to meet public demand.\n\nIf melt-blown manufacturers had to set up complex polymerization systems to make masks, it would have taken years to establish the necessary infrastructure. The pelletizing process allowed manufacturers to respond swiftly to the urgent need for high-filtration masks.\n\n## Natural Fiber Masks vs. Synthetic Fiber Masks\n\nMasks made from natural fibers are less effective at blocking pathogens compared to those made from synthetic fibers. Natural fibers tend to hold more moisture, which can encourage the growth of microorganisms. Since human breath provides nutrients that help these microorganisms thrive, natural fiber masks can become breeding grounds for pathogens like viruses and bacteria. If everyone had relied on natural fiber masks during the pandemic, the consequences could have been much worse. In contrast, **polypropylene**, the main ingredient in high-filtration masks, is highly resistant to moisture, containing less than 0.1% moisture, making it a far better choice for protection.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the process called that converts monomers into polymers?"; options = vec { "Polymer extrusion"; "Polymerization"; "Pelletizing"; "Extrusion molding" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What are small, solidified pieces of polymer known as?"; options = vec { "Polymer chips"; "Polymer nuggets"; "Polymer chunks"; "Polymer grants" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "Why do companies use polymer pellets rather than undergoing the polymerization process?"; options = vec { "Pellets are cheaper to produce"; "Polymerization requires large machinery and space"; "Extruding pellets is faster"; "Pellets are more flexible in shape" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is the melt-blown process primarily used for?"; options = vec { "Producing natural fibers"; "Creating high-filtration face masks"; "Making polymer pellets"; "Manufacturing plastic bottles" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What type of material is used in high-filtration masks for its hydrophobic properties?"; options = vec { "Cotton"; "Polyester"; "Polypropylene"; "Nylon" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "10.1.3";
    unit_title = "Polymerization (Synthesis) of Semi-Synthetic Fibers";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "10.1";
    head_unit_title = "Fibers";
    content = "As reviewed earlier in Section 9, the principles of producing semi-synthetic fibers are largely similar to those for synthetic fibers. Both involve polymerization in molten state to create a viscous liquid, which is then passed through spinnerets to solidify into thin, long fibers. The primary distinction lies in the source of the monomers: synthetic fibers are derived from petroleum resources, whereas semi-synthetic fibers originate from natural materials, such as wood pulp, using harmful solvents.  \n";
    paraphrase = "## Understanding Semi-Synthetic and Synthetic Fibers\n\nIn Section 9, we learned that the manufacturing processes for semi-synthetic fibers and synthetic fibers share many similarities. Both types of fibers are created through a process called polymerization, where materials are heated until they melt into a thick liquid. This liquid is then pushed through small holes called spinnerets, allowing it to cool and solidify into long, thin fibers.\n\n### Key Differences\n\nThe main difference between semi-synthetic and synthetic fibers is the source of their building blocks, known as monomers:\n\n- **Synthetic Fibers**: These fibers are made from petroleum-based resources, meaning they originate from oil and other fossil fuels.\n- **Semi-Synthetic Fibers**: These fibers start from natural materials, such as wood pulp. However, their production involves the use of harmful solvents to complete the process. \n\nBy understanding these key concepts, we can better appreciate how different types of fibers are produced and their environmental implications.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the primary source of monomers for synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "Natural materials"; "Wood pulp"; "Petroleum resources"; "Harmful solvents" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What process is used to create both semi-synthetic and synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "Spinning yarn"; "Weaving fabric"; "Polymerization in molten state"; "Dyeing fibers" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is used to solidify the liquid in fiber production?"; options = vec { "Heat treatment"; "Cooling air"; "Spinnerets"; "Chemical reactions" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which of the following is a key difference between synthetic and semi-synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "The length of the fibers"; "The color of the fibers"; "The origin of the monomers"; "The viscosity of the liquid" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What natural material is commonly used for semi-synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "Cotton"; "Wood pulp"; "Silk"; "Leather" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "10.2.0";
    unit_title = "Yarn-Making";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "10.2";
    head_unit_title = "Yarn-Making";
    content = "As many people may already know, yarn is an intermediary material necessary for fabric manufacturing. It is also utilized as sewing thread, ropes, and in various other applications outside fabric production.\nFiber Types: There are two primary types of fibers based on their form factors: staple fibers and filaments. Filaments are long, continuous fibers produced synthetically. In contrast, staple fibers are shorter and naturally found in materials like cotton and wool, or they can be created by cutting long synthetic fibers into short lengths.\nThick filaments can be used directly as yarn because they provide sufficient strength and necessary properties on their own for certain applications. A good example is the fishing line, which is a continuous synthetic fiber in its original extruded form. In other cases, thinner filaments are twisted together to achieve certain characteristics which cannot be obtained from a single strand of a thick filament.\nChoosing fiber types and form factors like filaments or staples is a part of textile engineering, guided by the desired characteristics of finished goods such as texture, pliability, strength, and appearance, among others. \nSpinning Principles: Staple fibers are too weak and short by themselves to be used for most textile applications except for the non-woven fabric manufacturing. To convert short and weak staple fibers into yarn, a process called “spinning” is employed. The spinning process arranges many strands of short fibers into a collection in length direction, multiplies them together, and finally twists the fiber group while adjusting the quantity of fibers in the finished yarn by pulling and winding onto a spinning stick. As a deeper exploration in the spinning processes extend beyond the scope of this book, I omit further details. If any reader is interested, the YouTube link below provides comprehensive overviews.  \nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YC638CmoOsU&list=PLkeQwaJxiD7ijEx-QkpX-YC4ye0xod8am   \nDyeing: In some instances, yarns are dyed to achieve the desired look and feel of finished textiles before undergoing subsequent knitting or weaving process. If a yarn is not dyed prior to weaving or knitting, the resulting fabric is then dyed afterward to obtain specific aesthetic qualities. Additionally, dyeing can be performed on finished garments, particularly for highly customized and promotional items for specific events.\nFrom a sustainability perspective, it is important to note that fibers and fabrics even in white color are typically dyed, contrary to common belief. The natural colors of natural fibers post-harvest are not pure white as they often contain various imperfections and impurities along with unique color tones formed in cultivation. For example, cotton has a yellowish tint while wool is in greyish shade post-harvest. To achieve a pure white appearance, various methods such as bleaching and dyeing are employed. \nGiven that dyeing imposes significant environmental burdens, it is crucial to highlight its impact on the environment. In contrast, virgin synthetic fibers present uniform white or transparent colors, while recycled fibers come with greyish tint due to the presence of contaminants, discussed earlier. Although the degree of a desired whiteness can determine whether a virgin synthetic material is dyed or not, the likelihood of synthetic materials not requiring dyeing process, thus benefiting the environment, is higher than that of natural fibers. This is apparent with widely used plastics such as bags, bottles, food containers, transparent films, etc., which do not typically contain any dyeing chemicals. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Yarn and Fiber Types\n\nYarn is an essential material used to create fabrics. Besides fabric production, yarn has other uses, including sewing threads and ropes.\n\n## Types of Fibers\n\nFibers come in two main types based on their structures: **staple fibers** and **filaments**.\n\n- **Filaments**: These are long, continuous fibers typically created in a factory.\n- **Staple fibers**: These fibers are shorter and can be naturally sourced, like cotton and wool. Alternatively, they can be made by cutting long synthetic fibers into shorter pieces.\n\nThicker filaments can be directly used as yarn because they are strong enough for certain uses. For example, fishing lines are made from long, synthetic fibers straight from the production process. On the other hand, thinner filaments are often twisted together to create yarn, allowing for specific qualities that a single thick filament cannot provide.\n\nSelecting the right type of fiber and whether to use staple fibers or filaments is a crucial part of textile engineering. This choice depends on the desired qualities of the final product, such as feel, flexibility, strength, and appearance.\n\n## Spinning Process\n\nTypically, staple fibers are too weak and short to be used alone in most textile applications, except for making non-woven fabrics. To turn these short, weak fibers into yarn, a technique called **spinning** is used. The spinning process involves:\n\n1. Lining up many strands of short fibers in a lengthwise direction.\n2. Twisting them together for strength.\n3. Pulling and winding the fibers onto a spinning tool to control the final yarn'\''s thickness.\n\nFor those interested in a deeper understanding of spinning processes, many informative videos are available [here](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YC638CmoOsU&list=PLkeQwaJxiD7ijEx-QkpX-YC4ye0xod8am).\n\n## Dyeing Yarns\n\nYarns may be dyed before knitting or weaving to achieve specific colors and effects in the final fabric. If the yarn isn’t dyed beforehand, the fabric can be dyed later to achieve the desired look. Additionally, dyeing can be applied to finished garments, especially those made for special events or promotions.\n\nFrom a sustainability perspective, it is essential to know that even white fibers and fabrics are often dyed, contrary to popular belief. Natural fibers, straight after harvest, aren'\''t pure white; they often exhibit various tints and imperfections. For instance, cotton may have a slight yellow color, while wool can appear greyish. To create a truly white appearance, methods like bleaching and dyeing are necessary.\n\nDyeing has significant environmental impacts, so it’s critical to consider this aspect. In contrast, virgin synthetic fibers tend to be uniformly white or clear, while recycled fibers usually appear grey due to contaminants. While the amount of whiteness required can dictate whether virgin synthetic fibers are dyed, they generally have a lower likelihood of needing dye compared to natural fibers. This is also true for common plastic products like bags, bottles, and food containers, which typically do not contain dyes.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What are the two primary types of fibers based on their form factors?"; options = vec { "Staple fibers and filaments"; "Natural fibers and synthetic fibers"; "Twisted fibers and continuous fibers"; "Thick fibers and thin fibers" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What process is used to convert short and weak staple fibers into yarn?"; options = vec { "Weaving"; "Knitting"; "Spinning"; "Dyeing" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Why are thick filaments sometimes used directly as yarn?"; options = vec { "They are softer."; "They provide sufficient strength on their own."; "They are more colorful."; "They are cheaper to produce." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is a common characteristic of virgin synthetic fibers compared to natural fibers?"; options = vec { "They are always dyed."; "They present uniform white or transparent colors."; "They are stronger in all applications."; "They are made from plant materials." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What impact does dyeing have on the environment?"; options = vec { "It has no impact."; "It imposes significant environmental burdens."; "It improves yarn strength."; "It reduces the cost of production." }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "10.3.0";
    unit_title = "Fabric-Making";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "10.3";
    head_unit_title = "Fabric-Making";
    content = "There are four primary types of fabrics commonly used in textile applications: woven, knitted, non-woven fabrics, and naturally grown sheet materials such as leather and fungi-grown mycelium textiles, also known as vegetable leather.\nThe desired characteristics of finished products determine the appropriate manufacturing methods of these fabrics. Except for the leather, the other three fabric types offer a variety of particular construction techniques. For instance, woven fabrics can have visibly distinctive patterns such as plain, twill, satin, herringbone, jacquard, etc., on their surfaces. Knitted fabrics can include patterns like plain, double lock, warp knit, etc. In contrast, non-woven fabrics are constructed by randomly depositing fibers to form a fabric form factor, thus neither knitted nor woven. Therefore, it bypasses the yarn-making process and does not typically create any noticeable surface pattern. \nThroughout human history, a vast array of fabrics has been developed, particularly in the woven and knitted construction methods. Given the extensive diversity, it is impractical to explain different fabric patterns comprehensively here, nor is it necessary for the environmental theme of the book. Therefore, I will provide the most basic concepts of the three main fabric types; woven, knitted and non-woven. \nWoven:  Warp yarns, running in length directions, and weft yarns in cross directions intersect to form a woven fabric structure. Patterns formed by crossing yarns determine fabric structures such as plain, twill, satin, etc. While traditional woven fabrics are known for their strength and non-stretch nature, there are also stretch woven fabrics where a portion of the comprising yarns impart stretch properties. Such yarn examples include spandex and elastane. Woven fabrics find widespread use in various applications including apparel, home textiles, outdoor gear, bags, etc.  \nKnitted: Knitted fabrics are formed by interlacing one strand or more into loop formations. Unlike woven textiles, knitted fabrics are inherently characterized by their stretch properties, which stem from these loop structures. However, various other knitting techniques creating different fabric constructions also exist that restrict structural movement, and a typical example is a warp knit. Examples of knitted fabric applications include sweaters, shirts, socks, bath towels, carpets, among others.\nNon-Woven:  Non-woven fabrics are created by intertwining numerous strands of fibers to form sheet structures. Unlike woven or knitted fabrics, the primary characteristic of the non-wovens fabrics lies in their low-density structure and capacity to hold large volumes of air. This attribute stems from the absence of the yarn-spinning process where fibers are bundled up and compacted by twisting. The voluminous structures of non-woven fabrics lend themselves well to specialized functionalities required in products such as face masks, sanitary pads, thermal insulation, filters, etc. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Types of Fabrics in Textiles\n\nThere are **four main types of fabrics** used in textiles:\n\n1. **Woven Fabrics**\n2. **Knitted Fabrics**\n3. **Non-Woven Fabrics**\n4. **Naturally Grown Materials** (like leather and mushroom-derived mycelium, known as vegetable leather)\n\nThe **manufacturing method** of these fabrics depends on the desired properties of the final product. Except for leather, the first three types of fabrics have various construction techniques.\n\n## 1. Woven Fabrics\nWoven fabrics are made by intertwining two sets of yarns: the **warp** (lengthwise) and the **weft** (crosswise). The pattern created by these yarns determines the type of fabric, such as **plain**, **twill**, **satin**, and **herringbone**. \n\n- **Strength and Stability**: Traditional woven fabrics are strong and don’t stretch. However, some woven fabrics can stretch if they include special yarns like **spandex** or **elastane**.\n\n- **Uses**: Woven fabrics are commonly found in clothing, home textiles, outdoor gear, bags, etc.\n\n## 2. Knitted Fabrics\nKnitted fabrics are made by **interlocking one or more yarns** into loops. This loop structure gives knitted fabrics their natural **stretch**.\n\n- **Variations**: There are different knitting techniques that can also create fabrics with less stretch, like **warp knitting**.\n\n- **Uses**: You can find knitted fabrics in sweaters, shirts, socks, bath towels, carpets, and more.\n\n## 3. Non-Woven Fabrics\nNon-woven fabrics are created by **bonding fibers together** without the yarn spinning process, which makes them different from woven and knitted fabrics.\n\n- **Characteristics**: These fabrics have a **low-density structure** and can trap a lot of air, making them voluminous.\n\n- **Applications**: Non-woven fabrics are used in products like face masks, sanitary pads, thermal insulation, and filters due to their specialized properties.\n\n## Conclusion\nThroughout history, many types of fabrics have been developed, especially in woven and knitted forms. While there are countless patterns and styles, this overview focuses on the essential characteristics of woven, knitted, and non-woven fabrics to support the environmental theme of this book.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What are the four primary types of fabrics commonly used in textile applications?"; options = vec { "Woven, knitted, non-woven, and leather"; "Spandex, elastane, leather, and knitted"; "Woven, knitted, woven leather, and mycelium"; "Silk, cotton, polyester, and leather" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "Which fabric type is characterized by being inherently stretchable?"; options = vec { "Woven fabrics"; "Knitted fabrics"; "Non-woven fabrics"; "Leather" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is a distinctive feature of non-woven fabrics?"; options = vec { "They are made from yarns."; "They are woven into intricate patterns."; "They hold large volumes of air."; "They require complex knitting techniques." }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which fabric uses warp and weft yarns that intersect to form its structure?"; options = vec { "Knitted fabrics"; "Non-woven fabrics"; "Woven fabrics"; "Leather" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What type of knitted fabric restricts structural movement?"; options = vec { "Plain knit"; "Double lock knit"; "Warp knit"; "Satin knit" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "10.4.0";
    unit_title = "Dyeing (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "10.4";
    head_unit_title = "Dyeing";
    content = "Dyeing process in textile manufacturing encompasses various form factors, including fibers, yarns, and fabrics. Analogously, in the leather industry, this process is known as “tanning”. Moreover, dyeing may occur on finished goods following the final manufacturing stage of textiles, known as “cut-and-sew” process.\nChemical Intensiveness and Toxicity: As reviewed earlier, dyeing is almost always the most chemically intensive and toxic process of all textile manufacturing except for farming natural fibers where more toxic chemicals such as pesticides may be used. The chemical compositions of dyes and associated chemicals encompass a wide array of harmful elements and compounds, including heavy metals such as lead, chromium, and mercury, aromatic amines, halogens like chlorine and bromine, solvents, additives, chlorinated phenols, and others.\nSignificant Misperceptions: There is a common misconception that the toxicity associated with dyeing is limited to manufacturing facilities and does not affect consumers. Unfortunately, this belief is incorrect and contributes to a significant misunderstanding about the sustainability of textiles. \nMany of us have likely noticed color fading in textiles after multiple home launderings. This is direct evidence of color pigments and other chemicals used in manufacturing being released into water, circulating through the water streams globally, and exposing us to the effects of these harmful substances in our daily lives.\nTextile dyeing is far more complex than simply adding color pigments, as one might with food coloring in cooking. It involves a wide range of additional chemicals to ensure that dyes penetrate the fiber structures, either chemically or physically, and remain in the materials for as long as possible. Poor dye fixation, for example, can result in noticeable color loss and the transfer of the dyes to other textiles during home laundering.\nWhile textile goods stored in a closet typically pose little risk, as the concentration of harmful chemicals is low in isolation, the situation changes dramatically when large amounts of textile waste are buried, burned, or left in dumping grounds without proper environmental control. In these cases, harmful chemicals become highly concentrated and are released into air, soil, and water through natural environmental processes such as wind, runoff water, and bacterial degradation. This can be observed in many regions where mountains of textile waste are destroyed with no environmental safeguards. A clearly visible example often seen in these circumstances is the slow leaching of heavily colorized pollutants from harmful chemicals in textile waste into river streams, resulting in ecosystem destruction, evident in the discoloration of water and the death of fish. Similar impacts occur in landfills and incineration sites, where pollutants spread through air circulation or contaminate groundwater.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding the Dyeing Process in Textile Manufacturing\n\nThe dyeing process in textile production involves adding color to different materials, such as fibers, yarns, and fabrics. In the leather industry, this similar process is called \"tanning.\" Dyeing can also take place after textiles are fully made, during a stage known as the \"cut-and-sew\" process.\n\n## Chemical Use and Toxicity\n\nDyeing is typically one of the most chemical-heavy and toxic steps in textile manufacturing. The only exception is the farming of natural fibers, which might use harmful substances like pesticides. The chemicals found in dyes can include various dangerous components, such as heavy metals (like lead, chromium, and mercury), aromatic amines, halogens (like chlorine and bromine), solvents, and other additives.\n\n## Common Misunderstandings\n\nMany people incorrectly believe that the toxicity of dyeing only affects manufacturing facilities and does not impact consumers. This viewpoint is misguided and leads to misunderstandings about the sustainability of textiles. \n\nFor instance, if you'\''ve noticed that clothes lose color after several washes, this is evidence that the color pigments and chemicals from manufacturing are being released into the water. This means that these harmful substances can enter our water systems and affect our daily lives.\n\n## The Complexity of Textile Dyeing\n\nDyeing textiles is not as simple as adding color like you would with food dye in cooking. It involves using various chemicals to make sure dyes are absorbed into the fibers effectively and stay attached for as long as possible. If the dye doesn'\''t hold well, it can lead to color fading and transferring dyes onto other clothes during washing.\n\n## Environmental Impact of Textile Waste\n\nWhile clothes stored away in closets are usually not a major risk due to low chemical concentrations, the situation worsens with large amounts of textile waste. When textiles are buried, burned, or dumped without proper care for the environment, harmful chemicals can become concentrated and leak into the air, soil, and water. \n\nThis is often seen in areas where large piles of textile waste are disposed of improperly. One visible issue is the leakage of brightly colored pollutants from these waste sites into rivers, harming ecosystems, evident through water discoloration and fish deaths. Similar problems occur in landfills and incineration sites, where pollutants can contaminate the air and groundwater. \n\nBy understanding these processes and impacts, we can better appreciate the complexities of dyeing in textile manufacturing and its effects on health and the environment.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the dyeing process in textile manufacturing compared to in the leather industry?"; options = vec { "Cut-and-sew"; "Spinning"; "Weaving"; "Tanning" }; answer = 3; }; record { question = "Which of the following is NOT mentioned as a harmful element involved in dyeing?"; options = vec { "Lead"; "Chlorine"; "Benzene"; "Mercury" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is a significant misconception about the toxicity of dyeing?"; options = vec { "It only affects the manufacturing facilities."; "Natural fibers are safer to dye."; "Home laundering does not release toxins."; "Dyeing does not involve additional chemicals." }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What happens to harmful chemicals when large amounts of textile waste are disposed of improperly?"; options = vec { "They become harmless over time."; "They are absorbed by the fibers."; "They become highly concentrated and released into the environment."; "They are neutralized by bacteria." }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is a visible sign of ecosystem destruction due to textile waste?"; options = vec { "Increase in fish populations"; "Discoloration of water and death of fish"; "Brightly colored textiles"; "Reduction in chemical exposure" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "10.4.1";
    unit_title = "Chemical Consumption and Environmental Impacts";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "10.4";
    head_unit_title = "Dyeing";
    content = "As previously mentioned, dyes and associated chemicals contain harmful chemicals, including heavy metals and various compounds, each playing crucial roles in achieving specific colors and desired color-fading resistance. For instance, removing certain heavy metals from a particular dye formulation to reduce environmental toxicity can diminish the color tone and vibrance perceived by consumers. \nTo illustrate the diversity of chemicals employed in dyeing processes, it may be beneficial to review the range of substances supplied by a single chemical company - While most of the specific chemical names presented below may not carry much meaning to most readers, the long list serves the purpose to highlight the diversity and quantity of chemicals used in dyeing, contradicting a notion that simple color pigments are used.   \nBasic chemical:  Soda ash, Hydrochloric, Hydrogen Peroxide, Sulphuric acid, Acetic acid, Formic acid, Caustic soda, etc.  \nWashing/Soaping agent: Serafast CRD, Kappatex R98, Seraperse CSN, Crosden LPD, Resotex WOP, Diypol XLF, Jintex WRN, etc.\nDetergent/Scouring agent: Jintex-GD, Felosan RGN, Jintex-GS, etc.\nLeveling agent:  Levelex-P, Jinleve leve-RSPL, Serabid-IP, Dyapol XLF, Lubovin-RG-BD, etc.\nSalt: Common salt, Glauber salt, etc.\nSequestering agent: Resotext 600S, Heptol-EMG, Heptol-DBL, etc.\nWhitening agent: Uvitex2B, Uvitex BHV, Bluton BBV, Tuboblanc col, Uvitex BAM, Synowhite, Hostalux ETBN, etc.\nFixing agent:  Sandifix EC, Tinofix-ECO, Protefix-DPE-568, Jinfix-SR, Optifix-EC\nSoftner:  Cetasaft CS, Resomine Supper, Acelon, Resosoft-XCL, Silicon, etc.\nReducing agent:  Hydrose\nStablizer:  Stablizer PSLT, Kappazon H53, STAB, Tinoclarite CBB, etc.  \nEnzyme : Tinozyme 44L, Rzyme 1000, Avozyme CL PLUS, Enzyme-B50, etc.   \nAnticreasing agent: Kappavon CL, Biovin 109, AC-200, Cibafuid-C, MFL, etc.\nAntifoaming agent: Jintex TPA, AV-NO, VO, Cibaflow-JET, etc.\nPH controller: Soda ash, Acid, Caustic, Neutracid RBT\nI grew up in Taegu, South Korea, a city known as a major hub for textile dyeing during my childhood where the creeks and rivers in the city often resembled the images depicted in Fig.36.\nFig.36   Contaminated Water Streams \nSouth Korea has undergone rapid development from one of the world'\''s poorest countries following the Korean War to becoming an OECD member country today. This transformation has been accompanied by the establishment of stringent environmental regulations. Notably, visible pollution events such as contaminated rivers and creeks were swiftly addressed through strict controls on wastewater from industrial and residential sources. Consequently, dyeing factories were required to install water treatment facilities to meet government quality standards before discharge into natural water bodies.\nHowever, while traveling to many underdeveloped and developing countries where environmental regulations may be less stringent, I still encounter numerous instances of water pollution of this nature. \nAs repeatedly mentioned, water circulates freely and globally through oceans, rivers, and precipitation, meaning that environmental impacts from distant locations can affect us no matter where we live within days, weeks, or months. Moreover, harmful chemicals persist in nature for extended periods, entering our ecosystems through food sources, air and drinking water, regardless of geographical location or dietary habits people have.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Dyes and Their Environmental Impact\n\nDyes and their associated chemicals can contain harmful substances, such as heavy metals and various compounds, which are essential for producing specific colors and for preventing color fading. For example, if a manufacturer tries to eliminate certain heavy metals from a dye to make it less toxic to the environment, the resulting dye may lose its vividness and appealing color, affecting consumer perception.\n\nTo demonstrate the variety of chemicals used in dyeing, let’s look at a list of substances provided by a single chemical company. While many of these chemical names may not be familiar, the extensive list emphasizes the wide range and quantity of chemicals involved in dye production, challenging the idea that dyeing only uses simple color pigments.\n\n### Types of Chemicals Used in Dyeing Processes\n\n1. **Basic Chemicals**: \n   - Soda Ash\n   - Hydrochloric Acid\n   - Hydrogen Peroxide\n   - Sulphuric Acid\n   - Acetic Acid\n   - Formic Acid\n   - Caustic Soda\n\n2. **Washing/Soaping Agents**: \n   - Serafast CRD\n   - Kappatex R98\n   - Seraperse CSN\n   - Crosden LPD\n   - Resotex WOP\n   - Diypol XLF\n   - Jintex WRN\n\n3. **Detergent/Scouring Agents**: \n   - Jintex-GD\n   - Felosan RGN\n   - Jintex-GS\n\n4. **Leveling Agents**: \n   - Levelex-P\n   - Jinleve leve-RSPL\n   - Serabid-IP\n   - Dyapol XLF\n   - Lubovin-RG-BD\n\n5. **Salt**: \n   - Common Salt\n   - Glauber Salt\n\n6. **Sequestering Agents**: \n   - Resotext 600S\n   - Heptol-EMG\n   - Heptol-DBL\n\n7. **Whitening Agents**: \n   - Uvitex2B\n   - Uvitex BHV\n   - Bluton BBV\n   - Tuboblanc col\n   - Uvitex BAM\n   - Synowhite\n   - Hostalux ETBN\n\n8. **Fixing Agents**: \n   - Sandifix EC\n   - Tinofix-ECO\n   - Protefix-DPE-568\n   - Jinfix-SR\n   - Optifix-EC\n\n9. **Softeners**: \n   - Cetasaft CS\n   - Resomine Supper\n   - Acelon\n   - Resosoft-XCL\n   - Silicon\n\n10. **Reducing Agents**: \n    - Hydrose\n\n11. **Stabilizers**: \n    - Stabilizer PSLT\n    - Kappazon H53\n    - STAB\n    - Tinoclarite CBB\n\n12. **Enzymes**: \n    - Tinozyme 44L\n    - Rzyme 1000\n    - Avozyme CL PLUS\n    - Enzyme-B50\n\n13. **Anti-creasing Agents**: \n    - Kappavon CL\n    - Biovin 109\n    - AC-200\n    - Cibafuid-C\n    - MFL\n\n14. **Antifoaming Agents**: \n    - Jintex TPA\n    - AV-NO\n    - VO\n    - Cibaflow-JET\n\n15. **pH Controllers**: \n    - Soda Ash\n    - Acid\n    - Caustic\n    - Neutracid RBT\n\n### My Personal Experience\n\nI grew up in Taegu, South Korea, a city that was a major center for textile dyeing during my childhood. The local waterways often appeared polluted, resembling the scenes shown in the images of contaminated water streams.\n\nSouth Korea has transformed from one of the poorest countries post-Korean War to an OECD member today, implementing strict environmental laws. Issues like polluted rivers were quickly tackled through stringent regulations on wastewater from industries and households. As a result, dyeing factories had to install water treatment systems to ensure their water met government standards before it was released into natural water bodies.\n\nHowever, during my travels to underdeveloped and developing nations with less strict regulations, I often witness similar water pollution problems. \n\nIt'\''s important to remember that water moves freely across the globe through oceans, rivers, and rainfall. This means that environmental issues from one location can impact people in completely different areas within days, weeks, or even months. Additionally, harmful chemicals can stay in the environment for long periods, entering our ecosystems via food, air, and drinking water—regardless of where we live or what we eat.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What types of harmful chemicals are commonly found in dyes?"; options = vec { "Only organic compounds"; "Inert substances"; "Heavy metals and various compounds"; "Natural color pigments only" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which of the following is an example of a washing/soaping agent used in dyeing processes?"; options = vec { "Soda ash"; "Jintex WRN"; "Uvitex BAM"; "Hydrogen Peroxide" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What environmental change occurred in South Korea following the Korean War?"; options = vec { "It became the world'\''s poorest country"; "It established stringent environmental regulations"; "It increased the use of natural dyes only"; "It stopped industrial dyeing completely" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is the significance of water treatment facilities in dyeing factories?"; options = vec { "They enhance the vibrance of colors"; "They are a legal requirement for pollution control"; "They reduce the use of heavy metals in dyes"; "They increase dye production capacity" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What challenge is still faced by many underdeveloped and developing countries regarding environmental regulations?"; options = vec { "Stringent control of wastewater"; "Limited impact of water pollution"; "Numerous instances of water pollution due to lax regulations"; "Complete eradication of dyeing factories" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "10.4.2";
    unit_title = "Dye Types and Toxicities";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "10.4";
    head_unit_title = "Dyeing";
    content = "There is a wide variety of dye formulations used in manufacturing, chosen based on such variables as fiber types, specific colors, vibrancy, color fastness (fading resistance against washing, abrasion, etc.), and efficiency of dye absorption.\nDye Type Categorization: For the purposes of this discussion, I categorize the dyes into two groups: chemically reactive dyes and non-reactive dyes. Chemically reactive dyes, referred to as “Reactive Dyes”, form bonds with the chemically active functional groups of fibers. Examples include the hydroxyl groups in the cellulose of cotton and the proteins in wool. In contrast, chemically non-reactive dyes are used for fibers lacking chemically active functional groups, such as polyester and polypropylene. A common type of dyes used for these fibers is called “Disperse Dyes”. As the name indicates, this type of dye disperses and impregnates between the polymer chains of synthetic fibers by physical means rather than chemical bonding.  \nColor Fading: Understanding how different types of dyes interact with various fibers involves numerous scientific details. However, the basic concepts of the environmental impacts from different dye types can be grasped through simple observations in our own textiles. Many readers, including myself, may have observed that colors on textile goods made from natural fibers tend to fade more quickly in home laundering than those on synthetic fibers. A dark colored cotton shirt, for instance, can loose its color noticeably after several washes at home whereas a similarly colored polyester does not. This phenomenon is attributed to the chemically reactive nature of both the fibers themselves and a wide array of chemicals used in dyeing. \nChemical Reactions in Water: The chemically functional groups of natural fibers and reactive chemicals become activated in water. Water molecules exhibit polarity due to the presence of a partial positive charge on hydrogen atoms and a partial negative charge on oxygen, promoting chemical reactions with neighboring substances. Reactive dye pigments and other chemicals loosely fixed to natural fibers’ functional groups interact easily with water and result in detaching themselves from the functional groups and forming bonds with neighboring water molecules. Color fading on textiles or discolored water during or after laundry are evidence of such interactions and subsequent pollution in water from the loosened chemicals. This phenomenon can lead to “accidents” in home laundry, where color migrations occur from one item to another during laundry.  \nIn contrast, the disperse dyes and non-reactive chemicals used in most synthetic fibers do not create such chemical reactions in water, resulting in considerably lower pollution and risk of “accidents”. \nOrganic Dye: It is important to address another common misconception surrounding “organic” dyes. With the growing environmental awareness, there has been a trend toward using naturally sourced dyes, also known as “organic” dyes, instead of synthetic equivalents. Many people assume that natural dyes, derived from plants, insects, and minerals, are free from negative environmental and health impacts. However, this belief is misguided.\nWhile natural dyes do come from natural sources and typically do not contain harmful chemicals on their own, they have significant drawbacks, including producing duller colors and having poor adhesion to fibers, which leads to significant fading and the \"washed out\" effect during use. Combined with the heightened chemical reactivity of natural fibers, these issues pose challenges for textile applications. To address this, additional chemical agents known as \"mordants\" are often used to achieve desired tones, enhance vibrancy, and improve color fastness. Many of these mordants are metal-based and contain harmful elements such as chromium, copper, tin, and iron. In fact, the overall environmental impact from these natural dyes can be more severe than synthetic dye formulations due to the high toxicity level of mordants.   \nDespite the use of these toxic chemicals, textiles with natural dyes tend to lose their colors more easily during home washing than those using synthetic dyes. This often forces consumers to resort to drycleaning, which introduces further environmental harm.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Dye Formulations in Textile Manufacturing\n\nIn textile manufacturing, dye formulations vary widely. Different factors guide the choice of dye, including the types of fibers, desired colors, brightness, how well the color resists fading from washing or rubbing, and how efficiently the dye is absorbed by the fabric.\n\n## Types of Dyes\n\nFor our discussion, dyes can be divided into two main categories: **chemically reactive dyes** and **non-reactive dyes**.\n\n### Chemically Reactive Dyes\nThese are also known as **Reactive Dyes**. They bond chemically with functional groups in fibers, like the hydroxyl groups in cotton or the proteins in wool. This reaction gives better color retention in textiles.\n\n### Non-Reactive Dyes\nIn contrast, **non-reactive dyes** are used for synthetic fibers that lack these chemically active groups, such as polyester and polypropylene. A common example of non-reactive dye is called **Disperse Dyes**. These dyes work by dispersing within the fibers’ polymer chains without forming chemical bonds; instead, they physically migrate into the material.\n\n## Color Fading\n\nUnderstanding how different dyes interact with various fibers involves complex science, but some basic observations can be made from our experiences with textiles. Many people have noticed that colors in natural fiber textiles often fade faster when washed at home than colors in synthetic fibers. For example, a dark cotton shirt may noticeably lose its color after a few washes, while a similar colored polyester shirt retains its vibrancy much longer. \n\nThis is primarily due to the reactive nature of natural fibers and the chemicals used in dyeing processes.\n\n## Chemical Reactions in Water\n\nNatural fibers and reactive dyes interact with water because of their functional groups. Water molecules have a unique polarity, which helps promote chemical reactions. When textiles made from natural fibers are washed, the reactive dye molecules can detach from the fibers and bond with water molecules instead. This results in color fading and can lead to water pollution, as chemicals can leach out during the wash. This might even cause colors to bleed onto other items in the wash.\n\nOn the other hand, the disperse dyes and non-reactive chemicals used in synthetic fibers do not engage in such chemical reactions with water, leading to much lower pollution and fewer color transfer incidents during laundry.\n\n## Organic Dyes\n\nAnother important point to discuss is the common misconception about **organic dyes**. With growing awareness about environmental issues, more people are turning to dyes derived from natural sources—often referred to as “organic” dyes—instead of synthetic options. There’s a belief that natural dyes, which are obtained from plants, insects, or minerals, are free from negative environmental and health effects. However, this belief can be misleading.\n\nWhile natural dyes typically come from safer sources and do not contain harmful chemicals outright, they often have significant drawbacks. These dyes tend to produce less vibrant colors and don’t adhere well to fibers, which can cause them to fade significantly over time. When used on natural fibers, this reactivity only compounds the issue.\n\nTo enhance the brightness and durability of natural dyes, additional agents called **mordants** are usually added. These mordants, often metal-based, can include harmful substances like chromium, copper, tin, and iron. Surprisingly, the environmental impact of natural dyes, including the use of these toxic mordants, can be greater than that of synthetic dyes.\n\nDespite using mordants, textiles dyed with natural colors often fade more quickly during home washing. This can lead consumers to choose dry cleaning as an alternative, which poses further environmental concerns.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What types of dyes are categorized as chemically reactive?"; options = vec { "Disperse Dyes"; "Reactive Dyes"; "Synthetic Dyes"; "Natural Dyes" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which type of dye is commonly used for fibers like polyester and polypropylene?"; options = vec { "Reactive Dyes"; "Disperse Dyes"; "Natural Dyes"; "Acid Dyes" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Why do natural fiber textiles tend to fade more quickly than synthetic ones?"; options = vec { "They are made from organic materials."; "They have fewer color options."; "They react chemically with water, causing color loss."; "They are dyed with synthetic dyes." }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What are mordants used for in dyeing?"; options = vec { "To enhance color vibrancy and fastness"; "To fix the dye into the fiber"; "To make dyes non-toxic"; "To increase dye absorption" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What misconception exists regarding organic dyes?"; options = vec { "They are always vivid in color."; "They do not fade during washing."; "They are free from harmful chemicals."; "They are more efficient than synthetic dyes." }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "10.4.3";
    unit_title = "Water Consumption";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "10.4";
    head_unit_title = "Dyeing";
    content = "Textile manufacturing is widely recognized as the second largest consumer of freshwater globally, following the agricultural industry. While the agriculture primarily uses freshwater during farming (and sometimes for a final round of washing before consumption), textile goods require continuous freshwater use throughout its lifecycle. This includes excessive amounts of water consumption during the cultivation of natural fibers and laundering textiles over many years during consumer use.\nWhen considering the total freshwater consumption across its full lifecycle encompassing numerous home washing cycles, textiles may even surpass the agriculture to become the largest consumer of freshwater resources – As there are large variations in both farming and laundry practices, it is difficult to compare the two accurately. Thus, this statement is based on my personal estimate.\nDyeing and Rinsing: During a typical dyeing process, textile materials such as yarns and fabrics are immersed in a large water bath containing a combination of necessary chemicals, including color pigments. These chemicals are then chemically activated for the reactive dyes and distributed for the disperse dyes in the water, facilitating the fixation of dyes and related chemicals into the chemical and physical structures of the fibers. The coloration process typically occurs within the same enclosed machinery system, ensuring all chemicals work uniformly to achieve desired colors in the fibers.\nFollowing the coloration phase, multiple rounds of rinsing occur within the dyeing machines. Proper rinsing is crucial; inadequate rinsing can result in visibly adverse effects such as color fading or contamination onto other textiles during subsequent home launderings. In the initial rinsing stages, a significant amount of residual chemicals is removed, and the color of the water used in rinsing serves as an indicator of the extent to which the chemicals were not absorbed into the fibers during dyeing. Subsequent rinses involve multiple rounds of freshwater injections into the machine, progressively reducing the quantity of the excess chemicals until no color is detectable in the rinsed water.\nDyeing facilities implement various strategies to optimize chemical usage during the dyeing process, aiming to minimize the chemical quantities while maximizing effectiveness in achieving desired colors. However, in practice, excess quantities of chemicals are often injected to ensure successful coloration in the initial dyeing attempt. Failing to achieve the desired color in the first attempt can lead to significant challenges and costs in correction. To mitigate this risk, excess chemicals are applied to saturate the fibers to attain target colors, which, in turn, necessitate more water usage to rinse off the residual chemicals.\nIn some cases, “screen printing” techniques are employed in certain types of dyeing process, particularly for fabrics featuring intricate designs such as floral patterns. Unlike the water-immersion dyeing method explained earlier, the screen printing deposits dyes and related chemicals through screens, eliminating the use of water during coloration. However, thorough rinsing is still essential to remove excess dyes and chemicals after the printing. \n***\nAs briefly mentioned in the earlier chapter, readers who dye their hair can easily understand some of the dyeing principals, particularly when dyeing wool fibers using the screen printing method. Like wool dyes, which are reactive and designed to chemically bond with the protein in wool, hair dyes also involve a chemical reaction with the protein contained in human hair. Hair dyeing doesn'\''t require submersion in water, mimicking the screen printing method, but excess dye is necessary for a successful result, followed by thorough rinsing with significant water usage to remove the unabsorbed dye. Additionally, the dyed hair color fades over time relatively quickly, and proportionally with the frequency of washing. These characteristics closely resemble the process and behavior of natural fiber dyeing.\nRoom for Misunderstanding on Internet: There is a wealth of information available on the internet discussing the water consumption of textile materials and goods. However, many sources present data without citing specific references, leading to varying degrees of accuracy among the figures quoted.  Some examples are listed below:\n200 tons of fresh water per ton of dyed fabric - https://www.theconsciouschallenge.org/ecologicalfootprintbibleoverview/water-clothing#:~:text=It'\''s%20estimated%20that%20a%20single,per%20ton%20of%20dyed%20fabric   \nAbout 1,800 gallons (approx., 6,800 liters) of water are needed to produce a pair of jeans – \nhttps://www.oldhamcountywater.com/interesting-water-facts.html#:~:text=About%201%2C800%20gallons%20of%20water,about%20150%20gallons%20of%20water   \n75 liters of water goes in making your jeans (YOUTUBE) – \nhttps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3PKzGvSaWYA   \nIt takes 2,700 litres of water to make one cotton t-shirt. That'\''s enough water for one person to drink for 900 days or almost two and a half years! – World Wildlife Fund (WWF),\nhttps://www.linkedin.com/pulse/how-much-water-does-take-make-t-shirt-md-jubair-hasan/   \nWith the lack of scientific evidence, it is challenging to determine the reliability and accuracy of such information. For instance, one source claims that producing a pair of jeans requires 6,800 liters (1,800 gallons) of water, while another states only 75 liters (20 gallons), resulting in a discrepancy of approximately 90 times.\nClearly, water consumption can vary widely based on many factors such as agricultural practices, weather conditions specific to individual cotton farms, dyeing methods, etc. Given these variations, it is crucial to approach such information with caution.\nLack of Balance: Moreover, a significant issue with these types of data is the frequent omission of the differences in water consumption between different materials, for example, cotton and polyester, as this omission may lead to a considerable misunderstanding on the environmental impacts of different fiber types. \nFor instance, the first bullet point, stating 200 tons of fresh water per ton of dyed fabric, lacks the disclosure of a significant difference in water consumption between natural and synthetic materials. Typically, dyeing natural fibers incurs more rounds of rinsing cycles, requiring more amount of fresh water, compared with synthetic fibers. However, the figure of 200 tons does not address such discrepancy. \nOne example specifying water consumption by a material type is the bullet point citing World Wildlife Fund (WWF), which states that 2,700 liters of water are needed to produce a cotton t-shirt. While this information is more precise, it would have been more helpful to compare it with the water consumption of an equivalent polyester t-shirt. While I understand that the purpose of the WWF article might not be to provide scientific comparison for different textile materials, the lack of opportunities for the public to gain more comprehensive understanding contributes to the widespread misinformation and misperception crisis we face today – more discussions in Chapter V: Misinformation Crisis.  \n";
    paraphrase = "# Simplified Overview of Textile Manufacturing and Water Usage\n\nTextile manufacturing is the second largest user of freshwater globally, just after agriculture. While agriculture mainly uses water for growing crops (and occasionally for washing before consumption), textiles rely on water throughout their production and use. This includes significant water usage for growing natural fibers and washing textiles over time.\n\nWhen we look at the overall water used throughout its entire lifecycle, including numerous home washing cycles, textiles might actually use more freshwater than agriculture. However, since farming and laundry practices vary widely, accurately comparing the two is challenging. Thus, this statement is more of a personal estimate.\n\n## Dyeing and Rinsing Processes\n\nDuring dyeing, textiles like yarn and fabrics are placed in a large water bath mixed with chemicals and color pigments. These chemicals are activated for reactive dyes and dispersed for disperse dyes in the water, helping to fix the color into the fibers'\'' structure. The dyeing usually happens in closed machinery to ensure the dyes are applied evenly.\n\nAfter dyeing, rinsing takes place in the same machines. Proper rinsing is essential; if a textile isn’t rinsed well, it may fade or bleed color onto other items during later washes. In the early rinsing stages, a lot of leftover chemicals are removed, and the color of the rinsing water indicates how much dye wasn'\''t absorbed. Later rinses involve adding freshwater to reduce the leftover chemicals until the rinsed water is clear.\n\nDyeing facilities strive to use chemicals efficiently to minimize waste while still ensuring the desired colors are achieved. However, to overcome potential issues with dye saturation, they often use extra chemicals to ensure the dyeing is successful in one go, which increases the need for water during rinsing.\n\nFor certain fabrics with complex designs, \"screen printing\" is sometimes used instead of immersing the fabric in dye. This technique applies dyes and chemicals through screens, avoiding water during the dyeing phase, but thorough rinsing is still necessary to remove excess materials afterward. \n\n## Dyeing Hair as an Analogy\n\nPeople who dye their hair can relate to some dyeing principles, especially with wool fibers and screen printing. Hair dyes work similarly to wool dyes by chemically bonding with the protein in hair, and like screen printing, they don’t require submersion in water. However, excess dye and thorough rinsing with water are needed to remove unabsorbed dye, similar to how natural fibers are dyed.\n\n## Misinformation Online\n\nThere is a lot of information available online about water use in textiles, but many sources lack references, leading to varying accuracy. Some examples include:\n\n- 200 tons of fresh water is needed for one ton of dyed fabric ([source](https://www.theconsciouschallenge.org/ecologicalfootprintbibleoverview/water-clothing#:~:text=It'\''s%20estimated%20that%20a%20single,per%20ton%20of%20dyed%20fabric)).\n- About 1,800 gallons (approximately 6,800 liters) of water are required to create a single pair of jeans ([source](https://www.oldhamcountywater.com/interesting-water-facts.html#:~:text=About%201%2C800%20gallons%20of%20water,about%20150%20gallons%20of%20water)).\n- 75 liters of water are used to make jeans (YouTube video).\n- It takes 2,700 liters of water to produce a cotton t-shirt, which is enough for one person to drink for 900 days ([source](https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/how-much-water-does-take-make-t-shirt-md-jubair-hasan/)).\n\nDue to a lack of scientific backing, it can be difficult to assess the reliability of such claims. For instance, one source says it takes 6,800 liters to make jeans while another claims it’s only 75 liters, showcasing a massive difference.\n\n## Importance of Context in Data\n\nIt’s also crucial to understand that water consumption varies greatly depending on multiple factors, including agricultural methods and weather conditions. Additionally, different materials have different water needs, such as cotton versus polyester. Often, data fails to highlight these differences, leading to a misunderstanding of environmental impacts between fiber types. \n\nFor instance, the claim of 200 tons of water per ton of dyed fabric doesn’t explain the discrepancy in water usage between natural and synthetic fibers; natural fibers typically require more rinsing and thus more water. \n\nSome sources, like the World Wildlife Fund, provide better context by stating that producing a cotton t-shirt takes 2,700 liters. Still, it would be beneficial to compare this to the water needed for making a similar polyester t-shirt. Simplified and separate figures does not contribute to a well-rounded understanding of water impacts in textiles and leads to widespread confusion and misinformation, as discussed further in Chapter V: Misinformation Crisis.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "Which industry is recognized as the largest consumer of freshwater globally?"; options = vec { "Textile manufacturing"; "Agriculture"; "Automobile manufacturing"; "Pharmaceutical manufacturing" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is a significant factor in the water consumption of textile dyeing?"; options = vec { "The type of fabric being dyed"; "The color of the dye used"; "The application of screen printing"; "The season of the year" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "How much water approximately does it take to make one cotton t-shirt according to WWF?"; options = vec { "1,800 liters"; "2,700 liters"; "200 tons"; "75 liters" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What key challenge is noted regarding the accuracy of water consumption data on the internet?"; options = vec { "It is always consistent across sources"; "Many sources do not cite specific references"; "All figures have been scientifically verified"; "Water consumption data is obsolete" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is a common consequence of inadequate rinsing in the dyeing process?"; options = vec { "Increased fabric strength"; "Color fading or contamination"; "Reduced water consumption"; "Enhanced color vibrancy" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "10.5.0";
    unit_title = "Cut-and-Sew";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "10.5";
    head_unit_title = "Cut-and-Sew";
    content = "In textile manufacturing, the “cut-and-sew” process is typically the final stage before the finished goods are packaged and transported to various retail fronts. This process requires minimal investment and can be operated with a few sewing machines, skilled workers, and a modest space to manage the operations. It is akin to setting up a workspace in a corner of the living room in a household with a sewing machine. Numerous manufacturing facilities around the world engage in these cut-and-sew operations. \nWaste from Cut-and-Sew: Large-width fabrics, commonly 152cm (60 inches), are cut into the shapes and sizes of the finished goods, which are then sewn together to create the final products for consumption. A crucial aspect of this process is the significant amount of waste it generates. Depending on the shapes and sizes of finished goods, this cutting process can easily produce 5 ~ 30% waste from the incoming fabrics. An example is shown in Fig.37 where the blue part (1) will be sewn together to make a shirt, and the yellow part (2) will be unwanted after the cutting. \nFig.37   Waste (2 in yellow) after Cutting\nWhile some factories may sell the leftover materials to manufacturers who use them as stuffing for, for example, teddy bears, such applications are quite limited. As a result, most factories treat these leftovers as industrial waste, paying for either burial or incineration. Considering that tens of billions of textile products are produced annually, the scale of this waste and its environmental impacts are massive. Moreover, the amount and chemical reactivity of reactive dyes and chemicals lead to consequential environmental impacts from enormous quantities of waste from the cut-and-sew process. \nGiven the importance of effectively handling the waste from this process, an in-depth analysis and solutions will be discussed in Chapter V: Solutions, Section 21. Clean Recycling Initiative™. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding the Cut-and-Sew Process in Textile Manufacturing\n\nIn textile production, the cut-and-sew process is usually the last step before the completed items are packaged and sent to stores. This part of production requires a low investment, as it can be done with just a few sewing machines, skilled workers, and a small workspace—similar to how one might set up a sewing area at home. Many manufacturing facilities worldwide are involved in these cut-and-sew operations.\n\n## Waste Generated by Cut-and-Sew\n\nDuring the cut-and-sew process, large fabrics, often 152 cm (60 inches) wide, are cut into specific shapes and sizes to create finished products. However, a significant challenge is the amount of waste produced, which can range from 5% to 30% of the fabric used, depending on the designs of the products. For instance, in Figure 37, the blue section (1) represents the material used to make a shirt, while the yellow section (2) illustrates the waste created from cutting.\n\n![Waste after Cutting](#)  \n*Figure 37: Waste (2 in yellow) after Cutting*\n\nSome factories may sell leftover fabric scraps for uses like stuffing in teddy bears, but such options are limited. Consequently, many factories classify these leftovers as industrial waste and have to pay to dispose of them through methods like burying or incineration. With billions of textile products produced each year, the scale of waste generated is enormous and poses significant environmental challenges. Furthermore, the reactive dyes and chemicals used in the process contribute to these environmental concerns due to their toxicity and large quantities.\n\nBecause of the critical need to address waste management in this process, comprehensive discussions and potential solutions will be explored in Chapter V: Solutions, Section 21, focusing on the Clean Recycling Initiative™.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the final stage of textile manufacturing before goods are packaged?"; options = vec { "Weaving"; "Dyeing"; "Cut-and-sew"; "Final inspection" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What percentage of waste can the cut-and-sew process generate from incoming fabrics?"; options = vec { "1 ~ 5%"; "5 ~ 15%"; "5 ~ 30%"; "30 ~ 50%" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "How do most factories handle the leftover fabrics from the cut-and-sew process?"; options = vec { "They reuse them in production"; "They sell them to other manufacturers"; "They treat them as industrial waste"; "They donate them to charity" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is one potential application for the leftover materials from cut-and-sew?"; options = vec { "Making garments"; "Stuffing for toys"; "Packaging materials"; "Home insulation" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What will be discussed in Chapter V, Section 21 of the document?"; options = vec { "Cost analysis of textile production"; "Solutions for handling cut-and-sew waste"; "The history of textile manufacturing"; "Global textile market trends" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "10.6.0";
    unit_title = "Other";
    chapter_id = "II";
    chapter_title = "Chapter II";
    head_unit_id = "10.6";
    head_unit_title = "Other";
    content = "Subsequent to the cut-and-sew, typical processes include packaging, transportation, stocking, and retailing. Some of these processes have sparked debates, such as the amount of plastics used for packaging, methods of transportation, etc. \nThese concerns are independent of material types, manufacturing and consumption cycles in environmental aspects. Whether a shirt is made of cotton or polyester, these processes do not create a considerably different impact from one another. Given the simple nature and straight forward assessment of the involved factors such as the quantity of packaging materials, shipping methods, etc., I do not explore further on this part of textile manufacturing.  \n";
    paraphrase = "# Simplified Overview of Post-Cut-and-Sew Processes\n\nAfter the cut-and-sew stage, several important steps follow: packaging, transportation, stocking, and retailing. Each of these steps has raised some concerns, particularly regarding:\n\n- **Plastic Usage**: The amount of plastic used for packaging.\n- **Transportation Methods**: How the products are moved from one place to another.\n\nThese issues are relevant regardless of the type of materials used, whether it’s cotton or polyester. In terms of environmental impact, the differences between these materials during the subsequent processes are not significant. \n\nBecause the factors involved—like the amount of packaging materials and the shipping methods—are straightforward to evaluate, I won’t go into further detail about these aspects of textile manufacturing.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What processes typically follow the cut-and-sew phase in textile manufacturing?"; options = vec { "Quality testing, marketing, sales, and washing"; "Packaging, transportation, stocking, and retailing"; "Design, advertising, shipping, and disposal"; "Sourcing, cutting, sewing, and finishing" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What aspect of the packaging process has sparked debates?"; options = vec { "The design of the packaging"; "The amount of plastics used for packaging"; "The color of the packaging"; "The branding on the packaging" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Does the type of material (cotton vs. polyester) significantly impact the environmental aspects of textile manufacturing processes?"; options = vec { "Yes, it makes a huge difference"; "No, there is not a considerably different impact"; "It only affects the recycling process"; "Yes, but only in terms of production emissions" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What kind of aspects does the content state the concerns are independent of?"; options = vec { "Material types, manufacturing, and consumption cycles"; "Packaging, transportation, and labor conditions"; "Market demand, fashion trends, and consumer behavior"; "Environmental policies, regulations, and certifications" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What does the author choose not to explore further regarding textile manufacturing?"; options = vec { "The design aspects of cut-and-sew"; "Transportation methods"; "The quantity of packaging materials, shipping methods, etc."; "The types of fabrics used in clothing" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "11.0";
    unit_title = "LCA - Farming / Fiber-Making (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III: Lifecycle Assessment";
    head_unit_id = "11";
    head_unit_title = ". LCA - Farming of natural fibers / Fiber making of synthetic fibers";
    content = "This section examines the initial stages of the fiber lifecycle: farming for natural fibers and synthesis for synthetic and semi-synthetic fibers. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Introduction to the Fiber Lifecycle\n\nIn this section, we will explore the very first steps in the fiber lifecycle. We will look at how natural fibers are grown through farming, as well as how synthetic and semi-synthetic fibers are created through chemical processes.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the first stage of the fiber lifecycle for natural fibers?"; options = vec { "Synthesis"; "Farming"; "Processing"; "Distribution" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What process is used to create synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "Farming"; "Synthesis"; "Harvesting"; "Weaving" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which of the following is a semi-synthetic fiber?"; options = vec { "Cotton"; "Nylon"; "Rayon"; "Wool" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is the primary source for natural fibers?"; options = vec { "Petroleum"; "Plants and animals"; "Minerals"; "Recycled materials" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which stage follows farming in the fiber lifecycle for natural fibers?"; options = vec { "Synthesis"; "Processing"; "Sourcing"; "Marking" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "11.1.0";
    unit_title = "Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) Analysis - Farming / Fiber-Making (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "11.1";
    head_unit_title = "Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) Analysis - Farming / Fiber-Making";
    content = "Before delving into the toxicity analysis in this section, it is important to revisit a discussion from the previous chapter regarding the definition of \"toxicity\". While many environmental interest groups and activists often label synthetic fibers as \"toxic\", this characterization does not align with the traditional understanding of toxicity. Synthetic fibers exhibit minimal chemical reactivity, if any. When a material does not induce chemical reactions, it cannot accurately be described as \"toxic\". In fact, synthetic fibers are often referred to as chemically \"inert\", which is fundamentally the opposite of \"toxic\"  \nThis distinction is critically important when evaluating the short-, medium-, and long-term impacts of these materials, and when strategizing effective actions to address them with prioritization on more imminent threats.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Toxicity in Synthetic Fibers\n\nBefore we dive into analyzing toxicity in this section, let'\''s revisit a key point from the previous chapter about what \"toxicity\" really means. \n\nMany environmental groups and activists often label synthetic fibers as \"toxic.\" However, this doesn'\''t match the traditional definition of toxicity. Synthetic fibers generally have very low chemical reactivity. This means that they don'\''t cause chemical reactions. Since a material that doesn'\''t provoke chemical reactions can'\''t be accurately called \"toxic,\" we can describe synthetic fibers as chemically \"inert.\" This term essentially means they are the opposite of toxic.\n\nThis distinction is crucial when assessing the short-term, medium-term, and long-term effects of synthetic fibers. It also guides us in choosing the right actions to address environmental concerns, allowing us to focus on more immediate threats.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the traditional understanding of '\''toxicity'\'' in relation to synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "Synthetic fibers are highly toxic substances."; "Synthetic fibers have minimal chemical reactivity."; "Synthetic fibers induce many chemical reactions."; "Synthetic fibers are always harmful to health." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How are synthetic fibers often described in terms of chemical activity?"; options = vec { "Highly reactive"; "Chemically inert"; "Moderately toxic"; "Dangerously reactive" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What misconception do environmental groups often have about synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "They believe synthetic fibers are inert."; "They label synthetic fibers as toxic."; "They think synthetic fibers are natural."; "They consider synthetic fibers beneficial." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Why is it important to distinguish the toxicity of synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "To promote the use of more synthetic materials."; "To evaluate impacts and strategize effectively."; "To ignore the presence of synthetic materials."; "To reduce the use of natural fibers." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What should be prioritized when addressing synthetic fibers'\'' impact?"; options = vec { "Long-term environmental changes"; "More imminent threats"; "Global manufacturing processes"; "Consumer education on fiber types" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "11.1.1";
    unit_title = "Cotton Cultivation";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "11.1";
    head_unit_title = "Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) Analysis - Farming / Fiber-Making";
    content = "A significant majority of cotton fibers are cultivated with the use of pesticides and fertilizers. As discussed in the previous chapter, both pesticides and fertilizers contain highly toxic elements and compounds. For instance, pesticides are designed to eliminate living organisms such as insects, bacteria, fungi, actinomycetes, algae, etc., that negatively impact the growth of desired plants. Even without specialized knowledge in chemistry or health science, one can easily understand that pesticides are also harmful to other living organisms, including humans.\nPesticides\nPesticides have been utilized for thousands of years, with the earliest records dating back to 2500 B.C. The Sumerians used natural sulfur compounds, known for their strong odor, to repel bugs and insects. By 400 B.C., the Persians were using a plant-derived organic compound sourced from flowering Chrysanthemum plants to repel insects.\nIn the meantime, the use of naturally occurring ingredients in pesticides does not imply that they are harmless to the environment. When harmful substances are highly concentrated, they lead to environmental toxicity. A parallel can be drawn with mining, where the extraction of natural elements like copper, iron, gold, silver, etc., from the Earth crust results in the concentration of toxic elements, creating significant environmental toxicity. This issue will be explored in greater depth in Chapter V: Solutions.\nIndustrialization of Synthetic Pesticides: The history of pesticides took a significant turn in the 1940s, post-World War II, with the development of synthetic pesticides. These synthetic pesticides proved to be significantly more effective than their natural counterparts in creating more favourable outcomes in farming. For instance, DDT (dichloro-diphenyl-trichloroethane) was widely used not only for growing crops but also on humans and animals to repel mosquitos and other insects for decades - It was among the first synthetic pesticides, followed by a series of other toxic chemical compounds. Although DDT was banned in most countries between the 1970s and 1990s due to its potent impacts, earning it the nickname \"silent killer\", it is still used in some regions.\nToxicity and Persistence: A short description of the USA Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) to describe the nature of the chemical is as follows:  \nDDT is:\nknown to be very persistent in the environment,\nwill accumulate in fatty tissues, and\ncan travel long distances in the upper atmosphere.\nSome studies have shown that DDT can remain in soil for 15 years and can easily endure longer depending on soil types, temperatures, bacterial compositions of each soil type. Furthermore, its breakdown compounds, DDE (Dichlorodiphenyldichloroethylene) and DDD (Dichlorodiphenyldichloroethane), also persist in the environment and can be found for many years after the original application and breakdown of DDT.\nConsequently, DDT and related chemical compounds can be found in the environment today, including in the bloodstreams, tissues, organs, breast milk, etc., of both humans and animals even in remote locations from their original sources. \nDirtiest Crop: Cotton is often referred to as the world’s dirtiest crop due to its extensive use of insecticides, accounting for 16% of the global insecticide consumption. Various pests, such as bollworms, plant bugs, stink bugs, etc., are particularly attracted to cotton, necessitating the use of significant quantities of toxic agrochemicals to manage these pests. Given that cotton occupies only 2.5% of agricultural land, the disproportionately high percentage of the insecticide use highlights the considerable toxicity impact associated with the cotton cultivation. \nFertilizers\nRegarding the toxicity of fertilizers, they are generally considered less toxic than pesticides, as the fertilizers are designed to promote plant growth rather than eliminate pests. However, this does not necessarily mean that what benefits plants is equally beneficial for humans. In fact, both organic and synthetic fertilisers create significant amount of greenhouse gas emissions from the release of CO2, CH4, NO2, etc., while involving many other chemical impacts. \nHistory of Natural Fertilizers: Similar to pesticides, fertilizers have a long history of use by humans. They were among the most accessible natural materials because human- and animal-waste, and other organic matters such as food waste, animal carcasses, etc., are rich sources of plant nutrients with such elements as nitrogen, phosphate, potassium, etc., generated from the natural decomposition of such substances. This long-standing relationship indicates that fertilizers have been utilized since the beginning of the agricultural history.\nOne of the earliest commercialized natural fertilizers was guano, the natural deposit of bird remains and droppings. However, like many other natural resources exploited the post-industrial revolution era, the guano quickly became scarce and led to conflicts over national interests and a source of imperialism in the early 19th century. For instance, United States passed the Guano Islands Act in 1856 to claim the ownership of the guano in the Pacific Ocean.\nIndustrialization of Synthetic Fertilizers: The fertilizer industry underwent a significant transformation in 1913 with the invention of the Haber-Bosch process by two German scientists Fritz Haber and Carl Bosch. This process enabled the synthesis of ammonia from atmospheric nitrogen in industrial settings at low costs, leading to the widespread use of the synthetic fertilizers and largely replacing the guano and other natural fertilizers. The Haber-Bosch process is recognized as one of the most important developments in the modern human history, as it significantly increased agricultural productivity and supported the rapidly growing global population. However, as with all other human acts, there were unintended side effects.\nDensification and Concentration: Harmful elements and substances such as nitrogen, phosphate, potassium, etc., which are either initially contained in the fertilizers or produced as the byproducts of their use in agriculture, have led to widespread environmental issues. These elements are carried by runoff water and wind, contributing to the pollution in various water bodies and air streams globally. The core issue, whether the source is natural or synthetic, lies in the concentration and densification of these harmful elements. In their natural, dispersed states, these elements pose minimal risk to the ecosystems. However, when they become highly concentrated, they can cause significant environmental and health hazards.\n***\nToxicity from farming natural fibers is easily the most harmful component of all environmental factors in textile manufacturing for most consumer goods. While dyeing is generally considered a chemically intensive process in the manufacturing segment, its toxicity level is incomparably lower than that created by the farming. Given these considerations, the Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) of cotton in the farming segment is rated as “High” gaining the score of 3 in the three-step scoring system of this LCA analysis.  \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Cotton Production and Its Environmental Impact\n\n## Use of Pesticides and Fertilizers in Cotton Farming\n\nThe majority of cotton fibers are grown using pesticides and fertilizers. As mentioned earlier, both of these substances can contain very toxic elements and compounds. Pesticides, for example, are meant to eliminate harmful organisms like insects, bacteria, fungi, and algae that can affect the growth of cotton plants. Even without any scientific background, it'\''s clear that pesticides can also harm other living beings, including people.\n\n### Pesticides\nPesticides have been used for thousands of years. The oldest records date back to 2500 B.C., when the Sumerians used natural sulfur compounds to keep bugs away due to their strong smell. By 400 B.C., the Persians had discovered a plant-based organic compound from flowering Chrysanthemums to repel insects.\n\nUsing natural ingredients in pesticides doesn'\''t mean they are safe for the environment. When these harmful substances are concentrated, they can cause environmental pollution. This is similar to mining, where extracting metals like copper and gold can lead to toxic waste. We will explore solutions to address this issue in Chapter V.\n\n#### The Shift to Synthetic Pesticides\nThe pesticide industry changed dramatically in the 1940s, after World War II, with the introduction of synthetic pesticides. These are often more effective than natural ones. For example, DDT (dichloro-diphenyl-trichloroethane) was widely used for many years on crops and even for humans and animals to keep away mosquitoes and other pests. Although DDT was banned in many countries due to its harmful effects and nickname as the \"silent killer,\" it is still used in some areas.\n\n#### Toxicity and Longevity of DDT\nAccording to the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), DDT is:\n- Very persistent in the environment\n- Can accumulate in body fats\n- Capable of traveling long distances in the atmosphere\n\nResearch shows that DDT can linger in the soil for up to 15 years or longer, depending on various factors like soil type and temperature. Its breakdown products, such as DDE and DDD, also remain in the environment for many years after DDT is used. Today, traces of DDT and its derivatives can still be found in the bloodstream, tissues, organs, and breast milk of both humans and animals, even in remote areas far from where it was originally used.\n\n### Cotton: The Dirtiest Crop\nCotton is often labeled as the \"dirtiest crop in the world\" because it represents about 16% of global insecticide usage, despite covering only 2.5% of agricultural land. This high usage is due to various pests that are attracted to cotton plants, such as bollworms and stink bugs, requiring large amounts of harmful agrochemicals for pest control. The impact of this insecticide use is substantial.\n\n## Fertilizers\nFertilizers are typically seen as less toxic than pesticides since they are used to enhance plant growth rather than kill pests. However, what benefits plants may not necessarily be safe for humans. Both organic and synthetic fertilizers produce significant greenhouse gases and have other chemical effects.\n\n### A Brief History of Natural Fertilizers\nFertilizers have been used for a long time, with humans utilizing natural materials like animal waste, food scraps, and decaying organic matter to provide nutrients like nitrogen, phosphate, and potassium to plants. This practice dates back to early agriculture.\n\nOne of the first commercial natural fertilizers was guano, a type of fertilizer made from bird droppings. However, guano became scarce after the industrial revolution, leading to conflicts and imperialism. For example, the U.S. claimed guano-rich islands in the Pacific Ocean through the Guano Islands Act of 1856.\n\n### The Rise of Synthetic Fertilizers\nThe fertilizer industry saw a major change in 1913 with the development of the Haber-Bosch process by Fritz Haber and Carl Bosch. This process allowed for the cost-effective creation of ammonia from atmospheric nitrogen, leading to the widespread use of synthetic fertilizers instead of natural ones like guano. This innovation greatly increased agricultural productivity and helped support the growing global population. However, it also led to unintended environmental consequences.\n\n#### Concentration and Environmental Impact\nThe use of fertilizers, whether natural or synthetic, has resulted in environmental issues due to the accumulation of harmful substances like nitrogen and phosphate. These chemicals can run off into water bodies and air, causing pollution. The problem lies in the concentration of these elements; while they are relatively harmless in small amounts, they become dangerous when concentrated.\n\n## Conclusion: The Environmental Cost of Cotton Farming\nFarming natural fibers, especially cotton, contributes significantly to environmental harm. While dyeing processes typically involve a lot of chemicals, they are not as toxic as the effects of farming itself. This leads to cotton receiving a \"High\" toxicity rating of 3 in the Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI), according to a Life Cycle Assessment (LCA).";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What percentage of global insecticide consumption is attributed to cotton cultivation?"; options = vec { "5%"; "10%"; "16%"; "25%" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is DDT known for in terms of environmental impact?"; options = vec { "Rapid decomposition"; "Being harmless to animals"; "High persistence in the environment"; "Low toxicity" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What process allowed for the synthesis of ammonia from atmospheric nitrogen, leading to the rise of synthetic fertilizers?"; options = vec { "Photosynthesis"; "Haber-Bosch process"; "Nitrogen fixing"; "Guano extraction" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which natural substance was one of the earliest commercialized fertilizers?"; options = vec { "Bone meal"; "Fish emulsion"; "Guano"; "Manure" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What toxic impact does the use of fertilizers have on the environment?"; options = vec { "Decreased crop yield"; "More beneficial for humans"; "Greenhouse gas emissions"; "None of the above" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "11.1.2";
    unit_title = "Polyester Synthesis";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "11.1";
    head_unit_title = "Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) Analysis - Farming / Fiber-Making";
    content = "Polyester’s journey to become consumable products begins with the synthesis of monomers into polymers as reviewed in the earlier chapter. \nIARC Classification: To understand the nature of the chemicals involved in the synthesis of polyester, I use the classifications of International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) for estimated health impacts, particularly cancer, of different substances with the examples below – The IARC classifications are also used for broader health impacts beyond cancer:\nGroup 1: “Sufficient evidence of carcinogenicity” in humans, and these agents have been linked to cancer through epidemiological studies. Exposure can lead to respiratory issues, skin irritation, and sensitization. Examples - Tobacco and Tobacco Smoke, Alcoholic Beverages, Processed Meats, Diesel Engine Exhaust, etc. \nGroup 2B: \"Possibly carcinogenic to humans\".  There is some evidence that it can cause cancer in humans but at present it is far from conclusive. Exposure can cause irritation of the eyes, skin, and respiratory tract. Examples – Roasting fumes of coffee, some pickled vegetables, gasoline engine exhaust, etc.  \nGroup 3: \"Not classifiable as to their carcinogenicity to humans\". This classification is used when there is insufficient evidence of carcinogenicity in humans and inadequate or limited evidence in experimental animals. Essentially, it means that current studies do not provide enough data to determine whether these agents cause cancer. Examples – Caffein, chlorinated drinking water, fluorescent lighting, etc.   \nChemicals for Polyester Synthesis: The key chemicals involved in the synthesis of polyester include Ethylene Glycol, which is classified as Group 3 by IARC, indicating it is not classifiable as to its carcinogenicity to humans. Similarly, Terephthalic Acid (TPA) also falls under Group 3, while Dimethyl Terephthalate (DMT) has not been classified by IARC, suggesting no significant health concerns associated with it. On the other hand, Antimony Trioxide and Acetaldehyde are classified as Group 2B, meaning they are “possibly” carcinogenic to humans, similar with such mundane components of our daily lives as roasting coffee fume, some pickled vegetables, etc., while Formaldehyde is classified as Group 1, known to be carcinogenic to humans.\nDespite the use of Formaldehyde in polyester synthesis that fall into the Group 1, it is important to note that these chemicals are used invariably in closed manufacturing systems under strict controls, which significantly reduces or eliminates its exposure risk to workers. This contrasts sharply with the cultivation of natural fibers like cotton, where toxic chemicals such as pesticides and fertilizers are applied in open fields without recovery systems, leading to significant health risks for farmers who are exposed to these substances during and after the initial application.\nNumerous deaths have been linked to the toxicity of pesticides and other chemicals used in cotton cultivation, as farmers are exposed to these substances through aerosols during spraying and residual contact during cultivation. In contrast, there have been no reported deaths linked to the exposure to Formaldehyde in the synthetic fiber production. \nOperational Efficiency: Profit-driven organizations in the petroleum and plastics industries have become remarkably efficient at maximizing profitability while minimizing their environmental footprint, particularly in terms of their resource utilization and chemical management. These industries are among the leaders in efficient conversion processes, transforming raw materials into finished products with minimal waste, an achievement made possible by continuous innovation over their long histories. For example, almost every ounce of crude oil is refined into various fractions, and plastics manufacturing similarly achieves extremely high efficiency in material use. Toxic chemicals involved in these processes are often reclaimed and reused, or they undergo strict environmental treatment. This is not only essential for their environmental compliance but also for the cost management, as accidental releases of harmful substances could result in significant financial losses.\nCenter of Attention: Oil refinery and polymerization facilities are typically located in industrial parks, often near major city centers to optimize transportation and supply chain efficiencies. These facilities are invariably subject to strict environmental regulations and are heavily monitored to ensure compliance.\nDuring my tenure as engineer in South Korea, I worked in the facility, which included a large polymerization process for acrylic fibers, situated just 10 minutes from the core city center of Masan, a city of 700,000 ~ 800,000 residents at the time. The facility was surrounded by numerous residential houses and shared a river stream with its neighbors. It was therefore closely monitored to ensure its operations adhering to both local and federal environmental standards. While accidental releases of harmful chemicals can occur in any industrial settings, such incidents are extremely rare and, if it happens, it attracts significant public and regulatory scrutiny. \nLater in my career, I served as an environmental representative at a manufacturing facility in Edmonton, Alberta, Canada, which produced various paper and roofing products. Any wastewater leakage into natural water bodies had to be immediately reported to the provincial government of Alberta, with potentially significant fines depending on the nature of leakage.\n***\nDue to the stringent monitoring and regulatory systems in place, it is rare for harmful chemicals to be released into the environment during polymer synthesis. This is in stark contrast to the virtually uncontrolled application of toxic pesticides and other chemicals by cotton farmers worldwide. As a result, the Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) for polyester in the Fiber-Making segment is rated as \"Low\", with the score of 1.\nThe evaluation results for the Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) of cotton, rated as “High”, and polyester, rated as “Low”, will be tabulated and presented at the end of this subsection in a graphical format alongside three other evaluation criteria in the Farming and Fiber-Making segment: Water Footprint Index (WFI), Food Footprint Index (FFI), and Carbon Footprint Index (CFI). \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Polyester and Its Health Implications\n\n## Introduction to Polyester Synthesis\nThe process of transforming polyester into products starts with combining small molecules (monomers) into larger ones (polymers), a topic covered in an earlier chapter.\n\n## IARC Classification of Chemicals\nTo grasp the potential health risks associated with the chemicals used in making polyester, we refer to the classifications by the International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC). These classifications estimate the health impacts of various substances, especially regarding cancer.\n\n1. **Group 1**: This group indicates that there is \"sufficient evidence of carcinogenicity\" in humans. Substances in this category are linked to cancer through study findings. Exposure may also cause respiratory problems and skin irritation. Examples include:\n   - Tobacco and tobacco smoke\n   - Alcoholic beverages\n   - Processed meats\n   - Diesel engine exhaust\n\n2. **Group 2B**: This category is for substances that are \"possibly carcinogenic to humans.\" There is some evidence of a cancer link, but it is not definite. Exposure can lead to irritation of the eyes, skin, and lungs. Examples include:\n   - Roasting fumes from coffee\n   - Certain pickled vegetables\n   - Gasoline engine exhaust\n\n3. **Group 3**: This group covers substances that are \"not classifiable as to their carcinogenicity to humans.\" It means there isn'\''t enough evidence to determine if they cause cancer in humans or animals. Examples are:\n   - Caffeine\n   - Chlorinated drinking water\n   - Fluorescent lighting\n\n## Chemicals Used in Polyester Synthesis\nIn polyester production, key chemicals include:\n\n- **Ethylene Glycol**: Classified as Group 3 (not classifiable regarding cancer risk).\n- **Terephthalic Acid (TPA)**: Also falls under Group 3.\n- **Dimethyl Terephthalate (DMT)**: Not classified by IARC, suggesting no major health risks associated.\n- **Antimony Trioxide and Acetaldehyde**: Classified as Group 2B, indicating they are “possibly” carcinogenic.\n- **Formaldehyde**: Classified as Group 1, known to be carcinogenic in humans.\n\nDespite the involvement of Formaldehyde (Group 1) in polyester production, strict manufacturing controls significantly reduce exposure risk to workers. This is a stark contrast to the cultivation of natural fibers like cotton, where farmers face health risks from toxic chemicals like pesticides applied openly in fields.\n\nNumerous deaths have been connected to pesticide toxicity during cotton cultivation, as farmers can be exposed through spraying and contact with treated plants. In comparison, there have been no reported deaths associated with Formaldehyde exposure in synthetic fiber production.\n\n## Operational Efficiency in the Industry\nCompanies in the petroleum and plastics sectors work hard to boost profitability while minimizing their environmental impact through efficient resource use and chemical management. They excel at converting raw materials into finished products with minimal waste, thanks to continuous innovation. An example is oil refineries, where nearly every drop of crude oil is processed into usable products, and plastic manufacturing achieves high efficiency in material usage. Toxic chemicals in these processes are often recycled or treated to limit environmental impact. This practice is critical not only for compliance but also for managing costs, as leaks can lead to significant financial penalties.\n\n## Location and Regulation of Facilities\nOil refineries and polymerization plants are typically situated in industrial parks near major cities to optimize transportation. These facilities are subject to strict environmental regulations and are closely monitored for compliance.\n\nFor instance, during my time as an engineer in South Korea, I worked at a polymerization plant for acrylic fibers located near the city center of Masan, a city with around 800,000 residents. The plant was close to residential areas and shared a water stream with its neighbors, leading to rigorous monitoring to ensure environmental standards were upheld. Although chemical leaks can occur in any industry, they are rare and receive public and regulatory attention when they do.\n\nLater in my career, as an environmental representative in Edmonton, Canada, I had to report any wastewater leaks to the provincial government immediately, with substantial penalties possible depending on the leak'\''s nature.\n\n## Conclusion\nThanks to stringent monitoring and regulations, harmful chemicals are rarely released into the environment during polyester synthesis. This is in stark contrast to the uncontrolled use of toxic pesticides in cotton farming worldwide. Consequently, the Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) for polyester in the fiber-making segment is rated as **Low** (score of 1), while cotton receives a **High** rating. \n\nResults of the Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) evaluation for cotton and polyester, along with other criteria such as Water Footprint Index (WFI), Food Footprint Index (FFI), and Carbon Footprint Index (CFI), will be presented graphically at the end of this subsection.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the IARC classification for substances with sufficient evidence of carcinogenicity in humans?"; options = vec { "Group 1"; "Group 2B"; "Group 3"; "Group 4" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "Which chemical used in polyester synthesis is classified as '\''possibly carcinogenic to humans'\'' by IARC?"; options = vec { "Ethylene Glycol"; "Terephthalic Acid"; "Antimony Trioxide"; "Dimethyl Terephthalate" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "How does the Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) for polyester compare to that of cotton?"; options = vec { "Higher for polyester"; "Lower for polyester"; "The same for both"; "Not mentioned" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is the main reason for the low release of harmful chemicals during polymer synthesis?"; options = vec { "Cyclic production methods"; "Strict environmental regulations"; "Use of natural materials"; "High temperatures used in synthesis" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which substance is classified under Group 1, indicating it is known to be carcinogenic to humans?"; options = vec { "Formaldehyde"; "Caffeine"; "Gasoline engine exhaust"; "Roasting fumes of coffee" }; answer = 0; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "11.2.0";
    unit_title = "Water Footprint Index (WFI) Analysis - Farming / Fiber-Making";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "11.2";
    head_unit_title = "Water Footprint Index (WFI) Analysis - Farming / Fiber-Making";
    content = "Water consumption is a crucial factor often overlooked in the sustainability assessments of both natural and synthetic fibers. To address this, I reference a research paper by Jennifer Xiaopei Wu and Li Li, which provides an in-depth analysis of overall water consumption for various fiber types.\nAs illustrated in Fig.42, over 90% of the water footprint is attributed to the natural and semi-natural fibers (the sum of cotton, wool, silk, flax/linen and viscose). Specifically, cotton and viscose together account for 81% of the total water footprint, with cotton alone contributing 60% and viscose 21%. In contrast, the synthetic fibers are responsible for only about 8% of the total water footprint across all fibers.\nFig.42   Water Footprint - Total Processing – UK, 2016 \nhttps://www.researchgate.net/figure/Water-footprint-for-the-total-processing-phase-of-each-fiber-type-for-the-UK-m3-in_fig3_335139274 \nWhen combined with the analysis of the total fiber consumption presented in Fig.1 and 2 of Chapter I, it becomes clear that the synthetic fibers, which constitute 65% of the total fiber consumption, account for only 8% of the total water consumption, highlighting a significant advantage of the synthetic fibers. In contrast, the natural and semi-natural fibers, which make up 35% of the total fiber consumption, are responsible for 92% of the water footprint. \nThis stark difference arises from the nearly waterless polymerization process used in the synthetic fiber production, compared to a vast amount of water required for the farming. While this study examines the full lifecycle of the fibers and is not limited to just farming and synthesis, the contrast would be even more pronounced if focused solely on this segment, given the minimal water usage in the processing of most synthetic fibers.\nThe extensive use of groundwater by the agricultural industry has raised significant concerns about long-term sustainability. Given that groundwater replenishment is a slow process, often taking hundreds or even thousands of years, excessive extraction is exacerbating global water scarcity. Cotton, in particular, has a notorious reputation as “thirsty crop” for requiring more water than most other crops. Moreover, this high water consumption extends throughout its entire lifecycle, from farming and manufacturing to home laundering, further intensifying its environmental impact.\n* A recent study published in 2023 found that excessive groundwater extraction has shifted Earth'\''s axis of rotation by about 4.36 cm per year, totaling an 80 cm shift between 1993 and 2010. While I always take cautionary approach on the information of this nature and this finding has not been linked to any considerable harm in our daily living, it serves as an example of the need for more comprehensive views in global environmental management as the changes such as this can be detrimental. \n***\nBased on the clear findings, the Water Footprint Index (WFI) for cotton is rated \"High,\" with the score of 3, while polyester is rated \"Low,\" with the score of 1 in the Farming/Fiber-Making segment. If a precise numerical measurement method were applied to this criterion instead of the simple three step scoring system adopted for this LCA analysis with the maximum possible gap of 2, the difference between the two fibers would likely be in the range of tens of times, clearly illustrating the significant disparity in water usage.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Water Consumption in Fiber Production\n\nWater usage is an important factor that is often ignored when assessing the sustainability of natural and synthetic fibers. A study by Jennifer Xiaopei Wu and Li Li thoroughly examines the overall water consumption related to different types of fibers.\n\n## Key Findings on Water Footprint\n\nAccording to the research illustrated in **Figure 42**, over 90% of the total water usage is linked to natural and semi-natural fibers, such as cotton, wool, silk, flax/linen, and viscose. Specifically:\n\n- **Cotton** accounts for **60%** of the total water footprint.\n- **Viscose** contributes **21%**.\n- Combined, these two fibers make up **81%** of the total water footprint.\n- In contrast, **synthetic fibers** contribute only about **8%** to the total water footprint of all fiber types.\n\n![Water Footprint - Total Processing – UK, 2016](https://www.researchgate.net/figure/Water-footprint-for-the-total-processing-phase-of-each-fiber-type-for-the-UK-m3-in_fig3_335139274)\n\nWhen we look at **Figures 1 and 2** from Chapter 1 that discuss total fiber consumption, it becomes clear that synthetic fibers represent **65%** of total fiber use but only account for **8%** of the water consumption. On the other hand, natural and semi-natural fibers, which make up **35%** of fiber consumption, are responsible for **92%** of water usage.\n\nThis difference is largely due to the nearly water-free production process for synthetic fibers, compared to the substantial water needed for farming natural fibers. While the study reviews the complete lifecycle of these fibers rather than just farming or production, the contrast in water usage would be even greater if we only focused on those areas, as synthetic fibers generally require much less water during processing.\n\n## Concerns About Groundwater Use\n\nThe agricultural sector'\''s extensive reliance on groundwater has raised serious sustainability issues. Groundwater takes a long time—often hundreds to thousands of years—to replenish. Over-extraction of groundwater is worsening global water shortages. Notably, cotton is often referred to as a \"thirsty crop\" due to its high water demand, which impacts not only the farming process but also manufacturing and washing at home, amplifying its environmental footprint.\n\nA **2023 study** revealed that excessive groundwater extraction has even shifted Earth'\''s axis of rotation by about **4.36 cm per year**, totaling an **80 cm shift** from 1993 to 2010. While this finding has not been linked to any immediate harm in daily life, it highlights the need for a broader perspective in global environmental management.\n\n## Water Footprint Index (WFI)\n\nBased on the findings, the Water Footprint Index (WFI) scores show a significant disparity:\n\n- **Cotton:** Rated \"High\" with a score of **3** for water use in Farming/Fiber-Making.\n- **Polyester:** Rated \"Low\" with a score of **1** in the same segment.\n\nIf a more precise numerical measurement were used instead of the simple three-point scoring system for this life cycle assessment (LCA), the difference in water usage between these two fibers would probably be in the range of **tens of times**, clearly illustrating the vast variance in water consumption.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What percentage of the total water footprint is attributed to natural and semi-natural fibers?"; options = vec { "50%"; "75%"; "90%"; "92%" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "How much of the total water footprint do cotton and viscose together account for?"; options = vec { "60%"; "81%"; "75%"; "90%" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is the Water Footprint Index (WFI) rating for cotton?"; options = vec { "Low"; "Moderate"; "High"; "Very High" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which fiber type is responsible for only about 8% of the total water footprint across all fibers?"; options = vec { "Cotton"; "Wool"; "Silk"; "Synthetic fibers" }; answer = 3; }; record { question = "What environmental concern is raised by the extensive use of groundwater in agriculture?"; options = vec { "Increase in crop yield"; "Global water scarcity"; "Enhanced soil quality"; "Improved fiber strength" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "11.3.0";
    unit_title = "Food Footprint Index (FFI) Analysis - Farming / Fiber-Making";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "11.3";
    head_unit_title = "Food Footprint Index (FFI) Analysis - Farming / Fiber-Making";
    content = "All natural fibers require large areas of agricultural land for growth and harvest. In contrast, synthetic fiber production does not necessitate such land use. While some large manufacturing facilities for synthetic fibers might be built on previously agricultural lands, potentially impacting food sources, this issue is more economic than intrinsic to the manufacturing process. In other words, they can be constructed without sacrificing agricultural land, leading to fundamentally different impacts on agriculture compared to the cultivation of natural fibers.\nAgricultural Land Use\nCotton, for instance, thrives in climates conducive to prolific agricultural outcomes, where multiple rounds of harvest for other crops can be achieved in a single season. In addition, as discussed earlier, cotton is a particularly water-intensive crop, demanding significantly more water than other food crops like soy, rice, wheat, potatoes, etc. \nReplacement of Synthetic Fibers with Cotton: If we were to replace the current 65% of the total fiber consumption of the synthetic fibers with the natural fibers like cotton, as proposed by many environmental interest groups and activists, assuming a one-to-one substitution ratio, would necessitate tripling the agricultural land dedicated to cotton. Consider this: the world'\''s land area is 13,003 million hectares, with 4,889 million hectares classified as agricultural by the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) of UN, representing 37.6% of the total land area. The 2021/2022 agricultural season saw the production of 25.2 million metric tons of cotton, occupying about 2.5% of total agricultural land. To replace the synthetic fibers, this proportion would need to increase to 7.5%, assuming a direct land-use swap.\nHowever, such a one-to-one land swap is impractical. As mentioned, cotton grows in some of the most agriculturally productive areas, which yield more outputs per unit area than less fertile regions. Moreover, the assumption of cotton replacing synthetic fibers on a one-to-one physical property basis is flawed. For instance, cotton is five to ten times weaker than polyester. To match the strength of polyester, five to ten times larger quantities of cotton would be required to compensate the considerably weaker strength, further increasing the agricultural land required. \nFactoring in these variables, the cotton cultivation could potentially consume well over 10% of the total agricultural land if the synthetic fibers were to be replaced by cotton. Additionally, cotton'\''s particularly high water and pesticide demands would exacerbate the environmental and agricultural impacts. \nWorld in Hunger: Reports from the World Health Organization (WHO) and the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) indicate that, as of 2023, 10% of the global population lacks sufficient food. This underscores the critical importance of judicious land use and resource management in balancing fiber production and food security.\nFig.43   World Hunger Map 2023\nhttps://www.aljazeera.com/news/2023/5/28/why-is-global-hunger-on-the-rise-2  \nConsidering the argument put forth by many environmental groups and activists that \"synthetic fibers, being derived from petroleum, are harmful to the environment and should be replaced with natural fibers\", we must ask: Would the 828 million malnourished individuals worldwide agree with this substitution, knowing that it could further compromise their already limited food sources? In reality, if we were to follow these recommendations, a significant number of those advocating for such changes might find themselves facing food shortages as well. \nHuman Nature and Near-Certain Outcome: Throughout human history, it has been proven time and time again that, while the affluent often have an abundance of food, frequently discarding large quantities, the impoverished struggle to meet their basic nutritional needs. As global food security becomes more problematic, this disparity in food distribution becomes even more pronounced. If we were to replace agricultural lands used for growing food crops with cotton fields to swap polyester with cotton, I estimate that more than half of the world’s population would struggle with food scarcity. This shift could most certainly lead to conflicts and exacerbate the global instability.\nPerplexities of Wrongful Environmental Actions: Many of the largest non-governmental organizations (NGOs) today are environmental groups, primarily based in advanced economies such as Europe and North America. These entities, along with influential voices from politicians, governments, crown corporations, and private companies in developed countries, often advocate for sustainability measures without considering even the most basic scopes such as the food security challenges faced by many underdeveloped and developing nations.\nUnfortunately, this disparity underscores a significant disconnect in the global sustainability management. It is truly perplexing that such claims and actions are made without addressing the basic needs of others. Effective and equitable sustainability practices must consider the diverse and urgent needs of all communities, ensuring that environmental goals do not exacerbate the existing inequalities and hardships.\nMoreover, when we examine the environmental impacts and sustainability of the natural fibers in comparison with the synthetic fibers, it becomes evident that there is no justification for such illogical actions.\n***\nWith the preceding considerations, cotton is rated as “High” with the score of 3 in Food Footprint Index (FFI) whereas Polyester receives the “Low” and 1 score.  \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Natural vs Synthetic Fibers\n\n## Agricultural Land Requirements\nNatural fibers, such as cotton, need large areas of farmland for their growth and harvesting. On the other hand, synthetic fibers can be produced without using agricultural land. While some factories for synthetic fibers may be built on land that was once used for farming — which could affect food production — this is more about economic choices than the manufacturing process itself. Essentially, synthetic fiber production can occur without harming agricultural land, leading to different effects on farming compared to growing natural fibers.\n\n## Cotton and Land Use\nCotton grows best in regions that can produce a lot of crops, allowing multiple harvests in a single season. However, cotton requires significantly more water than many other food crops, like soy, rice, and wheat. \n\n### Impact of Replacing Synthetic Fibers with Cotton\nLet’s say we want to replace 65% of synthetic fiber use with cotton, as some environmental activists suggest. This would mean we would need to triple the amount of agricultural land used for cotton farming. \n\nTo put this in perspective, the total land area of the world is about 13,003 million hectares, with 4,889 million hectares designated as agricultural land by the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO), which is about 37.6% of all land. During the 2021/2022 farming season, cotton made up 25.2 million metric tons, using about 2.5% of all agricultural land. To replace synthetic fibers, cotton'\''s share would need to rise to 7.5% if we swapped them directly.\n\nHowever, directly swapping synthetic fibers with cotton is unrealistic. Cotton is cultivated in some of the most productive agricultural areas. Additionally, cotton is much weaker than polyester — it’s five to ten times weaker. Therefore, to achieve the same strength as polyester, we would need to grow five to ten times as much cotton, leading to even greater demands on agricultural land.\n\nTaking all these factors into account, switching from synthetic fibers to cotton could use more than 10% of the total agricultural land. Cotton also needs a lot of water and pesticides, worsening the environmental and agricultural challenges we face.\n\n## Global Hunger Concerns\nReports from the World Health Organization (WHO) and FAO show that, as of 2023, 10% of the world'\''s population struggles with hunger. This highlights the essential need for careful land use and management of resources to keep fiber production balanced with food security.\n\n### The Dilemma of Changing Fiber Types\nMany environmental groups argue that synthetic fibers are harmful because they come from petroleum and should be replaced with natural fibers. But would the 828 million people who are malnourished worldwide agree? They might find that this substitution could worsen their limited food supplies. Following these suggestions could lead to food shortages for many of those advocating for the change.\n\n## The Nature of Food Distribution\nHistorically, there has been a persistent divide where wealthier individuals waste food while poorer ones struggle to find enough to eat. As global food security worsens, this gap widens. If we convert farmland for food into cotton farms, it’s likely that more than half the global population would face food shortages, potentially leading to conflict and instability.\n\n## Misguided Environmental Actions\nMany leading NGOs are focused on environmental issues but often originate from wealthier countries like those in Europe and North America. These organizations push for sustainability but may overlook basic challenges like food security in developing nations. \n\nThis disconnect is concerning; it seems unreasonable to promote actions without considering the basic needs of others. Sustainable practices should consider the urgent requirements of all communities to ensure environmental efforts do not deepen existing inequalities.\n\nWhen we evaluate the environmental impacts of natural fibers alongside synthetic fibers, it becomes clear that there’s no rational basis for ignoring these essential issues.\n\n## Food Footprint Index Comparison\nBased on these considerations, cotton scores “High” (3) on the Food Footprint Index (FFI), while polyester scores “Low” (1).  \n\n---\n\nThis simplified content retains the important concepts and terminology while making it more accessible for understanding the complex issues surrounding fiber production, agricultural land use, and food security.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What percentage of the world'\''s land area is classified as agricultural according to the FAO?"; options = vec { "25.2%"; "37.6%"; "50%"; "15%" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How much cotton is produced annually as of the 2021/2022 agricultural season?"; options = vec { "10 million metric tons"; "25.2 million metric tons"; "50 million metric tons"; "15 million metric tons" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which fiber is five to ten times weaker than polyester?"; options = vec { "Wool"; "Cotton"; "Silk"; "Acrylic" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What would be the estimated agricultural land usage percentage if synthetic fibers were entirely replaced by cotton?"; options = vec { "2.5%"; "5%"; "7.5%"; "Over 10%" }; answer = 3; }; record { question = "Which organization reported that 10% of the global population lacks sufficient food as of 2023?"; options = vec { "UNICEF"; "World Health Organization (WHO)"; "Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO)"; "World Bank" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "11.4.0";
    unit_title = "Carbon Footprint Index (CEI) Analysis - Farming / Fiber-Making";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "11.4";
    head_unit_title = "Carbon Footprint Index (CEI) Analysis - Farming / Fiber-Making";
    content = "One of the primary arguments made by many environmental interest groups and activists against synthetic fibers is the petroleum-based source materials and their inherent carbon footprints. While the cotton cultivation relies on natural sunlight, the polyester production requires energy from various sources. Although a small portion of this energy may come from the renewable sources, such as solar or wind, the majority still derives from the traditional resources like petroleum, coal, water, and natural gas. This further strengthens the claims of the environmental groups and activists.  \nHowever, a more nuanced analysis reveals that the issue is not as straightforward as merely considering the source materials and the energy need of polymer production. For instance, cotton cultivation involves the production and application of large quantities of chemicals such as pesticides and fertilizers. In addition, operations of manpower, machinery, etc., contribute significantly to its overall carbon footprint. Thus, the process of growing cotton is far from being carbon-free. \nScientific Analysis of Carbon Footprint Comparison: Understanding the overall carbon impacts of different fibers involves numerous factors. To provide an objective comparison, I refer to a research paper that employs comprehensive methodologies, as illustrated in Fig.44 and the provided website link.\nAccording to this report, the production of 1 pound of cotton fiber generates approximately 1.2 kg (2.7 lbs) of CO2, while the production of polyester fiber results in about 1.1 kg (2.4 lbs) of CO2. This close similarity may surprise many readers and challenges the common perception that synthetic fibers are inherently more carbon-intensive than natural fibers. In fact, the research highlights that some natural fibers, such as wool and silk, have their carbon footprints that are five to more than twenty times higher than that of polyester.\nFig.44   Carbon Footprint Comparisons\nhttps://www.researchgate.net/figure/Impact-of-the-production-of-264-g-cotton-polyester-flax-viscose-wool-Nylon-and_fig2_349651454  \n* Special mention - It is crucial to approach this type of information with caution. This advice applies not only to this specific data set but to all scientific data, regardless of the source. Given the multitude and complexity of the factors involved, such as weather conditions, farming methods, and regional differences, it is virtually impossible to calculate a carbon footprint that accurately represents the global cotton population. Consequently, there are inherent limitations in this type of scientific data, and it is essential to understand the specific context and nuances of each data set.\n***\nDespite these limitations and considering the comparable carbon footprints between cotton and polyester as well as relatively lower values compared with other fibers reported in the research paper, I rate both fibers as \"Low,\" with the score of 1 on the Carbon Footprint Index (CFI) for the Farming and Fiber-Making segment. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding the Carbon Footprint of Synthetic and Natural Fibers\n\nMany environmental groups and activists argue against synthetic fibers because they are made from petroleum-based materials, which contribute to their carbon footprints. In contrast, cotton is grown using natural sunlight. However, polyester, a synthetic fiber, requires energy for its production, which mainly comes from fossil fuels like petroleum, coal, water, and natural gas, though a small amount can come from renewable sources like solar or wind. This reinforces the concerns voiced by environmental advocates.\n\n## A Closer Look at Cotton Production\n\nWhile it seems simple to compare the energy sources for polyester and cotton, the situation is more complex. Growing cotton also involves using a lot of chemicals, such as pesticides and fertilizers. Additionally, the use of machinery and labor adds to the carbon footprint of cotton cultivation. Thus, cotton growing is not a process free of carbon emissions.\n\n### Scientific Analysis of Carbon Footprints\n\nTo assess the environmental impact of different fibers, many factors must be considered. A research study provides a detailed comparison, which is summarized in Figure 44 and linked [here](https://www.researchgate.net/figure/Impact-of-the-production-of-264-g-cotton-polyester-flax-viscose-wool-Nylon-and_fig2_349651454).\n\nAccording to the research, producing 1 pound of cotton fiber emits about 1.2 kg (2.7 lbs) of CO2, while producing 1 pound of polyester generates approximately 1.1 kg (2.4 lbs) of CO2. This surprising similarity challenges the common belief that synthetic fibers are always more polluting than natural fibers. Interestingly, some natural fibers, like wool and silk, can have carbon footprints that are five to over twenty times higher than that of polyester.\n\n### Caution When Interpreting Data\n\nIt’s important to be careful when interpreting this kind of information. This applies to all scientific data, not just this specific example. Many factors, including weather conditions, farming practices, and geographical differences, make it difficult to estimate a single carbon footprint that accurately reflects the entire cotton industry. Therefore, any scientific data has limitations, and it’s crucial to understand the context and details behind each dataset.\n\n### Conclusion on Carbon Footprint Ratings\n\nDespite the challenges and limitations in measuring the carbon footprints, the study indicates that both cotton and polyester have comparable emissions. Based on these findings, I rate both fibers as \"Low\" on the Carbon Footprint Index (CFI), giving them a score of 1 for the Farming and Fiber-Making category.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is one of the primary arguments against synthetic fibers made by environmental interest groups?"; options = vec { "They are too expensive to produce."; "They require a lot of manual labor."; "They are made from petroleum-based materials."; "They do not require any energy to produce." }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "How much CO2 is generated from the production of 1 pound of cotton fiber?"; options = vec { "1.1 kg"; "1.2 kg"; "2.4 kg"; "2.7 kg" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What type of fibers are mentioned as having higher carbon footprints than polyester?"; options = vec { "Nylon and acrylic"; "Wool and silk"; "Rayon and hemp"; "Cotton and flax" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How should one approach the information regarding carbon footprints?"; options = vec { "With absolute certainty."; "With caution and consideration for context."; "Ignoring the limitations of the data."; "Assuming all data is reliable." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What score is assigned to both cotton and polyester on the Carbon Footprint Index (CFI)?"; options = vec { "0"; "1"; "2"; "3" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "11.5.0";
    unit_title = "Total Impact Index (TII) Analysis - Farming / Fiber-Making";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "11.5";
    head_unit_title = "Total Impact Index (TII) Analysis - Farming / Fiber-Making";
    content = "Based on the analyses conducted throughout this section, comparing the farming of cotton and the fiber synthesis of polyester, Fig.45 represents the overall environmental impacts. \nFig.45   LCA – Cotton vs. Polyester – Farming / Fiber making\nWhile polyester earned the “Low” score of 1 in all evaluation criteria at this initial stage of its lifecycle, cotton received the “High” score of 3 in three of the four areas, including the Toxicity, Water, and Food Footprint Indexes. The final score for cotton, 10 out of the maximum possible score of 12, starkly contrasts with the lowest possible score of 4 for polyester.\nIn summary, the results unequivocally demonstrate that cotton exhibits significantly higher levels of negative environmental and also humanitarian impacts from the food security perspective in the Farming and Fiber-Making segment.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Environmental Impact Analysis of Cotton vs. Polyester\n\nBased on the analysis conducted in this section, we will look at the environmental impacts of cotton farming compared to polyester fiber production, as shown in Fig. 45.\n\n### Key Findings from Fig. 45 - LCA: Cotton vs. Polyester\n\n- **Polyester** received a \"Low\" score of **1** in all categories during the initial phase of its lifecycle.\n- **Cotton**, on the other hand, scored \"High\" with a **3** in three out of four categories: \n  - Toxicity\n  - Water Footprint\n  - Food Footprint\n\nThe total score for cotton was **10** out of a possible **12**, which is much higher compared to polyester'\''s lowest score of **4**. \n\n### Summary of Results\n\nThe results clearly show that cotton has a much greater negative impact on the environment, as well as significant humanitarian consequences related to food security in both the farming and fiber-making processes.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the overall score for cotton in its environmental impact assessment?"; options = vec { "4"; "10"; "12"; "3" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What score did polyester receive in the initial stage of its lifecycle?"; options = vec { "3"; "4"; "1"; "10" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "In how many areas did cotton receive a '\''High'\'' score of 3?"; options = vec { "1"; "2"; "3"; "4" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which environmental index did NOT score high for polyester?"; options = vec { "Toxicity Index"; "Water Index"; "Food Footprint Index"; "All of the above" }; answer = 3; }; record { question = "What are the implications of cotton'\''s higher score from a humanitarian perspective?"; options = vec { "Lower food security impacts"; "Higher environmental impacts"; "Significantly higher humanitarian impacts"; "No implications noted" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "12.1.0";
    unit_title = "Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) Analysis - Manufacturing";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "12.1";
    head_unit_title = "Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) Analysis - Manufacturing";
    content = "All manufacturing processes for textile goods leave an environmental footprint, just like any other human activity. For example, operating a sewing machine requires energy, and although the energy consumption of a small sewing machine is minimal, it still contributes to the overall environmental impact. In this section, my focus is not on heavily critiquing manufacturing processes with relatively minor environmental footprints. Instead, I concentrate on the most significant causes and impacts that are more detrimental to the environment.\nChemical Toxicity in Dyeing Process: As previously emphasized, dyeing is the most toxic process in the manufacturing of most textile goods, excluding the farming of natural fibers. The toxic pollutants generated during the dyeing spread globally through air and water circulation, creating long-lasting impacts on the health of all living organisms.\nEarlier in the book, specifically in Chapter II, Section 10.6 Dyeing, I discussed the variety of chemicals used in the dyeing processes, including dye pigments, whitening agents, fixing agents, mordants, etc. Many of these chemicals contain heavy metals, aromatic amines, and other harmful compounds, either as primary ingredients or as the byproducts of various chemical reactions. These substances are crucial in many dye formulations for achieving vibrant colors consumers expect and for ensuring that these colors remain stable on the textiles during use. In other words, the colors would neither meet consumer preferences nor retain their vibrancy over time without these harmful chemicals.\nToxicity Comparison between Natural and Synthetic Fibers: During my hands-on dyeing experiences, one notable observation I made was the significant disparity in the chemical usage between dyeing natural and synthetic fibers. Achieving a certain color tone and hue in natural fibers similar to that of synthetic fibers often required multiple times higher quantities of chemical usages. Moreover, the dyes and associated chemicals employed for natural fibers are inherently more chemically reactive, where higher chemical reactivity leads to more harmful environmental impact. In contrast, the disperse dyes used in most synthetic fibers are chemically inert. \nOther Areas of Manufacturing: Outside the dyeing process, various levels of toxicity can be introduced in different manufacturing stages to achieve specific performance features. For example, highly toxic chemicals are used to impart flame-retardant properties to cotton fabrics, particularly for specific types of personal protective equipment (PPE), where the property is essential to perform highly dangerous job functions such as fire-fighter gear. Given the focus of this book on high overall impact areas, I will not delve into the niche areas of manufacturing as they constitute a very small portion of the overall textile manufacturing while the needs for these specialized chemical treatments are often unavoidable. \n***\nIn consideration of these factors, cotton is assessed with “High” in Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) in the Manufacturing segment, gaining the score of 3. In contrast, polyester garners “Low” rating with the score of 1, reflecting its comparatively lower environmental impact in terms of the chemical toxicity during its manufacturing processes. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding the Environmental Impact of Textile Manufacturing\n\nAll textile manufacturing processes, like any human activity, have an environmental footprint. For example, running a sewing machine requires energy. While the energy use of a small sewing machine may be low, it still adds to the overall environmental impact. This section focuses on the major causes and effects that harm the environment, rather than critiquing processes with minimal effects.\n\n## Chemical Toxicity in Dyeing\n\nDyeing is one of the most harmful processes in textile production, second only to the farming of natural fibers. The toxic pollutants released during dyeing can spread worldwide through air and water, negatively affecting the health of living organisms for long periods.\n\nIn Chapter II, Section 10.6 on Dyeing, we discussed various chemicals used in dyeing, such as dye pigments, whitening agents, fixing agents, and mordants. Many of these chemicals include heavy metals, aromatic amines, and other harmful compounds, either as main ingredients or byproducts of chemical reactions. These substances are necessary to achieve the bright colors that consumers want and to keep these colors stable when the textiles are used. Without these harmful chemicals, textiles would not meet consumer expectations or maintain their vibrancy over time.\n\n## Comparing Natural and Synthetic Fiber Toxicity\n\nDuring my practical dyeing experience, I noticed a significant difference in the amount of chemicals needed for dyeing natural fibers compared to synthetic fibers. To produce similar colors in natural fibers as in synthetic ones, often many times more chemicals are required. Additionally, the dyes used for natural fibers tend to be more chemically reactive, which results in greater environmental harm. In contrast, the disperse dyes used for synthetic fibers are usually chemically inert.\n\n## Other Manufacturing Areas\n\nApart from dyeing, different stages of textile manufacturing can introduce various levels of toxicity to achieve desired performance features. For instance, the addition of highly toxic chemicals can provide flame-retardant properties to cotton fabrics, especially for essential personal protective equipment (PPE) for high-risk jobs, like firefighting. This book focuses on areas with high overall environmental impact and will not go into specialized manufacturing areas, as they only represent a small portion of textile production, and the need for such chemical treatments is often unavoidable.\n\n## Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI)\n\nWhen evaluating these factors, cotton scores a “High” on the Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) in the Manufacturing section, receiving a score of 3. In contrast, polyester is rated “Low” with a score of 1, indicating its relatively lower environmental impact in terms of chemical toxicity during manufacturing.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is considered the most toxic process in textile manufacturing?"; options = vec { "Sewing"; "Spinning"; "Dyeing"; "Weaving" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What rating does cotton receive on the Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) in the manufacturing segment?"; options = vec { "1"; "2"; "3"; "4" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which type of fibers requires significantly more chemicals to achieve vibrant colors?"; options = vec { "Synthetic fibers"; "Natural fibers"; "Both equally"; "None" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What property is often imparted to cotton fabrics using highly toxic chemicals?"; options = vec { "Water-repellent"; "Flame-retardant"; "Antimicrobial"; "Colorfastness" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How do disperse dyes used in synthetic fibers compare to dyes used in natural fibers?"; options = vec { "More chemically reactive"; "Less chemically reactive"; "Same reactivity"; "Not applicable" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "12.2.0";
    unit_title = "Water Footprint Index (WFI) Analysis - Manufacturing";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "12.2";
    head_unit_title = "Water Footprint Index (WFI) Analysis - Manufacturing";
    content = "For textile manufacturers, water usage relates closely with the overall operational efficiency and cost management. The more water used, the more energy required to dry, thus more costly. In fact, the energy required for drying water-heavy materials is often one of the largest operational costs for dyeing facilities. \nIncreased quantities of the chemical use and higher chemical reactivity, which are closely interrelated, for the natural fibers like cotton significantly contribute to higher water consumption in comparison with the synthetic fibers like polyester. Thorough rinsing, as previously explained with the analogy of hair dyeing, is crucial, especially given the harmful nature of these chemicals. Consequently, natural fibers require substantially more water during the dyeing process to effectively remove excess chemicals.  \n* Special Mention – Wool: Animal-based fibers, such as wool, present distinct challenges in their manufacturing processes, particularly due to their extensive cleaning requirements. For instance, sheep, the primary source of wool, often come into contact with their own manure, resulting in contaminated fibers at time of the harvest. This necessitates thorough cleaning before using them in subsequent processes.  \nDuring my tenure in South Korea, I recall that the company sold some byproducts from their wool cleaning process as the wastewater contained oil residue extracted during washing, valuable for some cosmetic products, highlighting an eco-friendly aspect of upcycling within this cleaning process. \nDespite these beneficial side-effects, the initial cleaning of wool demands a significant amount of water and chemicals to effectively wash off the contaminants. Moreover, compared to plant-based fibers, animal-based fibers necessitate even higher quantities of dyes and chemicals. This increased demand is attributed to the protein-based molecular structure of animal fibers, resulting in higher densities of chemically reactive functional groups in their molecular structures. These functional groups not only enhance the affinity for water but also require more extensive use of harmful chemicals during the dyeing process. The manufacturing processes of the animal-based fibers, therefore, entail even higher water consumption and heightened use of toxic chemicals than the plant-based fibers, underscoring the environmental challenges associated with these materials in textile production.\n***\nGiven these considerations, cotton is assigned as “High” impact with the score of 3 in the Water Footprint Index (WFI) for the Manufacturing segment. In contrast, Polyester receives “Low” rating with the score of 1, indicative of its low water footprint driven by its inherent low chemical reactivity.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Water Usage in Textile Manufacturing\n\n## Importance of Water in Textile Production\n\nFor companies that make textiles, how much water they use is closely linked to their efficiency and cost control. Using more water means they need more energy to dry the materials, which increases costs. In dyeing facilities, the energy needed to dry items that hold a lot of water is often one of the major expenses.\n\n## Water Consumption and Fiber Types\n\nNatural fibers, such as cotton, require larger amounts of chemicals and are more reactive. This leads to greater water use when compared to synthetic fibers like polyester. Just like rinsing hair dye, it'\''s essential to thoroughly rinse these natural fibers to remove harmful chemicals. Because of this, the dyeing process for natural fibers demands much more water to get rid of any leftover chemicals.\n\n### Wool Considerations\n\nWool, an animal-based fiber, has unique challenges during manufacturing, primarily due to the need for extensive cleaning. For example, sheep can often get their wool dirty from manure, making it essential to clean the fibers thoroughly before further processing.\n\nDuring my experience in South Korea, I observed that the company sold some byproducts from the wool cleaning process because the wastewater contained valuable oil residues that could be used in cosmetics. This aspect showcases an environmentally friendly upcycling opportunity within the cleaning process.\n\nHowever, even with these benefits, cleaning wool requires a significant amount of water and chemicals to remove contaminants. Moreover, animal fibers like wool need even more dyes and chemicals compared to plant-based fibers. This is because the protein structure of animal fibers contains many chemically reactive groups, making them more water-absorbent and necessitating a higher use of harmful chemicals during dyeing. As a result, the production of animal-based fibers consumes more water and toxic chemicals than plant-based fibers, raising serious environmental concerns in textile manufacturing.\n\n## Water Footprint Index Ratings\n\nTaking these factors into account, cotton is rated as “High” impact in the Water Footprint Index (WFI) for manufacturing, receiving a score of 3. On the other hand, polyester has a “Low” impact rating with a score of 1, reflecting its lower water usage due to its lower chemical reactivity.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the relationship between water usage and operational efficiency for textile manufacturers?"; options = vec { "More water usage decreases operational costs"; "Less water usage increases energy required for drying"; "More water usage increases operational costs"; "Less water usage has no effect on energy requirements" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Why do natural fibers like cotton consume more water than synthetic fibers like polyester?"; options = vec { "Natural fibers have lower chemical reactivity"; "Natural fibers are easier to dye"; "Natural fibers require more thorough rinsing to remove excess chemicals"; "Natural fibers do not require dyeing" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What is a significant challenge in the manufacturing process of wool?"; options = vec { "Wool is easier to clean than cotton"; "Wool requires less water than synthetic fibers"; "Wool fibers often come into contact with manure, needing thorough cleaning"; "Wool has no cleaning requirements" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "How does the water consumption of animal-based fibers compare to plant-based fibers?"; options = vec { "Animal-based fibers require less water"; "Animal-based fibers require equal amounts of water"; "Animal-based fibers require more water and chemicals"; "Animal-based fibers do not require dye" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What Water Footprint Index (WFI) score is assigned to cotton in the Manufacturing segment?"; options = vec { "1"; "2"; "3"; "4" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "12.3.0";
    unit_title = "Food Footprint Index (FFI) Analysis - Manufacturing";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "12.3";
    head_unit_title = "Food Footprint Index (FFI) Analysis - Manufacturing";
    content = "Impacts on the food footprint in textiles are created mostly during the farming segment of the natural fibers. Therefore, the manufacturing of textile goods using either cotton or polyester does not create any direct impact on the food securities.  With this, both cotton and polyester receive the score of 1 for “Low” in the Food Footprint Index (FFI) during the Manufacturing segment.  \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding the Food Footprint in Textiles\n\nThe effect of textiles on food resources mainly happens during the farming of natural fibers. This means that when textiles are made using materials like cotton or polyester, they do not have a direct effect on food security. As a result, both cotton and polyester have a rating of **1**, which indicates a **Low** impact on the Food Footprint Index (FFI) during the manufacturing process.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What segment of the natural fibers primarily impacts the food footprint in textiles?"; options = vec { "Manufacturing"; "Farming"; "Distribution"; "Retail" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which fibers are mentioned as having a low impact on food securities during manufacturing?"; options = vec { "Wool and Silk"; "Cotton and Polyester"; "Nylon and Spandex"; "Rayon and Linen" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What score do both cotton and polyester receive in the Food Footprint Index during the manufacturing segment?"; options = vec { "5 for High"; "3 for Moderate"; "1 for Low"; "0 for None" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Does the manufacturing of textile goods using cotton or polyester create a direct impact on food securities?"; options = vec { "Yes, it creates a significant impact"; "Yes, it creates a moderate impact"; "No, it does not create a direct impact"; "Only cotton creates an impact" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "In the context of the Food Footprint Index, what is the main focus of scoring for textiles?"; options = vec { "Farming practices"; "Manufacturing processes"; "Consumer usage"; "Recycling methods" }; answer = 0; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "12.4.0";
    unit_title = "Carbon Footprint Index (CFI) Analysis - Manufacturing";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "12.4";
    head_unit_title = "Carbon Footprint Index (CFI) Analysis - Manufacturing";
    content = "The disparity in the carbon footprint between natural and synthetic materials is pronounced particularly in the Manufacturing segment, primarily attributable to the dyeing process. Natural fibers exhibit higher water absorption during dyeing, which subsequently escalates the energy consumption in drying.\nWhile a direct experience in a dyeing factory may be limited for most readers, a comparative estimation can be made at home - Conceptually, the carbon footprint impacts of the dyeing operations in factories can be loosely interpreted as higher magnitudes than those in the home laundry as both involve the usage of large quantity of water and rinsing operations. To illustrate this, I present a set of data derived from a controlled experiment conducted in a domestic setting, outlined in 13.4 Carbon Footprint Index (CFI) – Consumption section later in this chapter. \n***\nGiven that the Carbon Footprint Index (CFI) is closely related with the Water Footprint Index (WFI), cotton is evidently scored with 3 as “High” and polyester as “Low” acquiring the score of 1 for the Manufacturing segment of the LCA. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding the Carbon Footprint of Natural vs. Synthetic Materials\n\nThe difference in carbon footprints between natural and synthetic materials is especially noticeable in the manufacturing process, mainly due to how each is dyed. Natural fibers tend to absorb more water during dyeing, which increases the energy needed for drying them afterward.\n\nAlthough most readers may not have firsthand experience in a dyeing factory, we can make a general comparison based on home laundry experiences. The impact of dyeing in factories is usually much greater than what occurs during typical laundry at home since both processes involve large amounts of water and extensive rinsing. To provide clarity, I'\''ll share some data from a controlled experiment conducted in a home setting, which is detailed in section 13.4 Carbon Footprint Index (CFI) – Consumption later in this chapter.\n\nFurthermore, the Carbon Footprint Index (CFI) is closely linked to the Water Footprint Index (WFI). In this context, cotton receives a CFI score of 3, indicating a \"High\" impact, while polyester scores a 1, indicating a \"Low\" impact for the manufacturing phase in the Life Cycle Assessment (LCA).";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What process is primarily responsible for the carbon footprint disparity between natural and synthetic materials?"; options = vec { "Weaving"; "Dyeing"; "Spinning"; "Sewing" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How does the water absorption of natural fibers during dyeing affect energy consumption?"; options = vec { "It decreases energy consumption"; "It has no effect"; "It increases energy consumption"; "It makes dyeing unnecessary" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which material scored higher on the Carbon Footprint Index (CFI) for the Manufacturing segment?"; options = vec { "Cotton"; "Polyester"; "Nylon"; "Wool" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What score does polyester receive on the Carbon Footprint Index (CFI) for the Manufacturing segment?"; options = vec { "3"; "1"; "2"; "4" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What can be inferred about the carbon footprint of dyeing operations in factories compared to home laundry?"; options = vec { "Factory dyeing has a lower carbon footprint"; "Home laundry has a higher carbon footprint"; "Factory dyeing has a higher carbon footprint"; "There is no difference in carbon footprint" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "12.5.0";
    unit_title = "Total Impact Index (TII) Analysis - Manufacturing";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "12.5";
    head_unit_title = "Total Impact Index (TII) Analysis - Manufacturing";
    content = "Summing up the scores of the four separate indexes in the Manufacturing segment, cotton has the final score of 10 out of the highest possible score of 12. Cotton received the highest scores in all the other segments but the Food Footprint Index (FFI), as the criteria excludes the Farming, whereas polyester receives the total score of only 4, registering the lowest score for all indexes in the same segment.  \nFig.46   LCA – Cotton vs. Polyester - Manufacturing\n";
    paraphrase = "# Summary of Scores in the Manufacturing Segment\n\nWhen we look at the scores from the four different indexes in the Manufacturing segment, cotton achieves a total score of **10 out of a possible 12**. It performs the best across all categories except for the **Food Footprint Index (FFI)**, where cotton is not assessed because the criteria do not consider farming practices. In contrast, polyester has a much lower total score of **4**, marking it as the lowest scorer among all indexes in this segment.\n\n![LCA – Cotton vs. Polyester - Manufacturing](Fig.46)";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the final score of cotton in the Manufacturing segment?"; options = vec { "8 out of 12"; "10 out of 12"; "12 out of 12"; "4 out of 12" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "In which segment did cotton receive the highest scores?"; options = vec { "Manufacturing"; "Food Footprint Index (FFI)"; "Recycling"; "Transport" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What score did polyester receive in the Manufacturing segment?"; options = vec { "10"; "12"; "8"; "4" }; answer = 3; }; record { question = "Cotton received the highest scores in all segments except for which index?"; options = vec { "Farming"; "Food Footprint Index (FFI)"; "Manufacturing"; "Recycling" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which material registered the lowest score for all indexes in the Manufacturing segment?"; options = vec { "Cotton"; "Polyester"; "Wool"; "Silk" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "13.0";
    unit_title = "Consumption (Intro)";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III: Lifecycle Assessment";
    head_unit_id = "13";
    head_unit_title = ". LCA - Consumption";
    content = "Having explored the environmental impacts associated with the earlier stages of a textile'\''s lifecycle, namely, the farming for natural fibers and the fiber synthesis for synthetic materials, as well as the manufacturing processes, this section will now shift focus to the environmental considerations during the consumption phase of textile goods.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding the Environmental Impact During Textile Consumption\n\nIn the previous sections, we discussed the environmental effects linked to the earlier stages of a textile'\''s lifecycle. This includes the farming of natural fibers and the production of synthetic materials, along with the manufacturing processes involved. Now, we will turn our attention to the environmental factors to consider during the **consumption phase** of textile products.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What phase of the textile lifecycle is the focus of this section?"; options = vec { "Farming for natural fibers"; "Fiber synthesis for synthetic materials"; "Manufacturing processes"; "Consumption phase" }; answer = 3; }; record { question = "Which of the following is NOT mentioned as part of the earlier stages of a textile'\''s lifecycle?"; options = vec { "Farming for natural fibers"; "Fiber synthesis for synthetic materials"; "Consumption phase"; "Manufacturing processes" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What type of materials does the section address in terms of environmental impacts?"; options = vec { "Only natural fibers"; "Only synthetic materials"; "Textile goods in general"; "Only recycled materials" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Which environmental aspect is being shifted to in this section?"; options = vec { "Production impacts"; "Consumption impacts"; "Waste management"; "Transportation impacts" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is a primary focus area of the content discussed?"; options = vec { "Economic impacts of textile production"; "Cultural significance of textiles"; "Environmental considerations during consumption"; "Technological advancements in textile production" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "13.1.0";
    unit_title = "Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) Analysis - Consumption";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "13.1";
    head_unit_title = "Toxicity Footprint Index (TFI) Analysis - Consumption";
    content = "Before scoring the impacts associated with the toxicity of textile goods during consumption, already discussed throughout the book in various related subjects, I present short summaries below. \nChemical Absorption and Release: Natural fibers absorb and release higher quantities of chemicals due to their heightened chemical reactivities of the fibers themselves as well as the chemicals used in farming and manufacturing. Furthermore, Fig.14 Breaking Energy Comparison (between cotton and polyester) and related discussions revealed clear scientific evidence in the higher quantity of dust generated from natural fibers in comparison to synthetic ones. Finally, natural fibers incur higher probability of drycleaning as extensively discussed in 1.1.1 Care Method Overview.\nCombining these metrics, the natural fibers present unequivocally more significant environmental challenges during consumption. \nPersistence in Nature: While some environmental advocacy groups present the decomposition speed between natural and synthetic fibers as a main argument in their environmental sustainability evaluations, it is critical to note that some of the chemicals absorbed in these materials will last multiple times longer than the fiber materials in their pure forms, including synthetic fibers; more in-depth discussion will be presented in the LCA – Disposal section of this chapter. \n* Special Mention - Personal Shopping Habits and Maintenance Routines: I avoid purchasing items generally considered as “slow fashion” for several reasons. \nFirstly, with my background, it is not difficult for me to assess the cost-quality ratio and recognize the significant markups associated with \"slow fashion\" brands. A stark difference between manufacturing costs and retail prices discourages me from paying a premium to support high executive salaries, luxurious office spaces, marketing expenses, costly retail locations and operations of these brands.\nSecondly, more affordable textile items, often made from synthetic fibers, offer superior durability without the need for drycleaning. While these items might be more prone to minor issues like losing buttons or seam breakage, the overall strength and longevity of the synthetic fabrics are undeniably superior to those of natural fibers.\nThirdly, and most importantly, from an environmental perspective, I understand that synthetic materials offer significant advantages in most aspects of their lifecycles.\nIn my care routines, I sort laundry by dark and light colors, much like most people, and avoid overloading the washing machine to prevent excessive physical stress inside the machine. If buttons fall or seamlines break, I bring them to tailors. By following these routines, I maintain my textiles in good condition, allowing them to last for extended periods without the need for dry cleaning.\n***\nGiven these considerations, it is evident that cotton generates significantly higher environmental harm during consumption, earning it \"High\" rating with the score of 3, while polyester is rated \"Low\" with the score of 1.\n";
    paraphrase = "# Simplified Overview of Textile Toxicity Impacts\n\nBefore discussing the environmental effects of toxic substances in textile goods during their use, here is a brief summary of some key points covered in this material.\n\n## Chemical Absorption and Release\n\nNatural fibers, like cotton, have a strong tendency to absorb and release more chemicals compared to synthetic fibers such as polyester. This is due to the chemical properties of the fibers themselves and the chemicals used in their production. Research, as illustrated by Figure 14, shows that natural fibers produce more dust during use than synthetic ones. Additionally, natural fibers often require dry cleaning, as discussed earlier in the chapter about care methods.\n\nFrom these insights, it’s clear that natural fibers pose greater environmental challenges during their use.\n\n## Persistence in Nature\n\nSome groups argue that the speed at which natural and synthetic fibers break down is a key factor in assessing environmental sustainability. However, it’s important to recognize that certain chemicals absorbed by these materials can persist in the environment much longer than the fibers themselves, including synthetic fibers. This topic will be explored further in the section on Life Cycle Assessment (LCA) and disposal later in this chapter.\n\n## Personal Shopping Habits and Maintenance Routines\n\nI personally avoid purchasing items labeled as \"slow fashion\" for several reasons:\n\n1. **Cost-Quality Ratio**: With my experience, I can easily spot the high markups in \"slow fashion\" brands. The gap between production costs and retail prices makes me reluctant to pay extra to support the lavish lifestyles of brand executives, expensive marketing, and operations.\n   \n2. **Durability of Alternatives**: Cheaper textile items made from synthetic fibers are often more durable and don’t usually require dry cleaning. While these items can have minor issues like missing buttons or broken seams, they generally outlast natural fibers in strength and longevity.\n   \n3. **Environmental Impact**: From an ecological angle, I understand that synthetic materials often have distinct advantages throughout their life cycles.\n\nIn my laundry routine, I separate dark and light clothes, like most people, and avoid overloading the washing machine to reduce wear and tear. If a button falls off or a seam tears, I take the item to a tailor. By following these maintenance practices, I keep my textiles in good shape and extend their lifespan without needing dry cleaning.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nConsidering all these factors, it is clear that cotton has a much higher environmental impact during its use, earning a \"High\" rating with a score of 3. In contrast, polyester receives a \"Low\" rating with a score of 1.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is a key reason natural fibers face greater environmental challenges during consumption compared to synthetic fibers?"; options = vec { "They are more affordable to produce."; "They generate more dust and require dry cleaning."; "They decompose faster."; "They are easier to maintain." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which fiber type is rated '\''High'\'' for environmental harm during consumption?"; options = vec { "Polyester"; "Wool"; "Cotton"; "Nylon" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What advantages do synthetic materials offer according to the provided content?"; options = vec { "They are biodegradable."; "They are more durable and do not require dry cleaning."; "They are always cheaper than natural fibers."; "They enhance environmental sustainability." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What personal care routine does the author follow to maintain textiles?"; options = vec { "Dry cleaning all items regularly."; "Sorting laundry by color and avoiding machine overload."; "Only using natural fibers."; "Purchasing items from '\''slow fashion'\'' brands." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Why does the author avoid purchasing '\''slow fashion'\'' items?"; options = vec { "They prefer natural fibers."; "They believe in supporting high executive salaries."; "They recognize significant markups in prices."; "They find these items more durable." }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "13.2.0";
    unit_title = "Water Footprint Index (WFI) Analysis - Consumption";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "13.2";
    head_unit_title = "Water Footprint Index (WFI) Analysis - Consumption";
    content = "As previously established, natural fibers, such as cotton, exhibit a higher affinity for chemical reactions compared to synthetic fibers like polyester. Conversely, cotton can absorb much more quantity of water than polyester during laundry. This disparity in water absorption is readily apparent when comparing the weights of cotton and polyester garments during laundry, more of which will be discussed in the subsequent subject with an experiment designed to illustrate the difference.  \nMoreover, cotton'\''s higher affinity to water can contribute to easier odor development. High moisture contents of natural fibers provide habitats for living organisms and human sweat containing food source for them such as urea, ammonia, fatty acid, etc., facilitate bacterial growth. This, in turn, necessitates more frequent washing cycles for cotton than polyester.\n***\nGiven these considerations, cotton receives the score of 3 for “High”, while polyester receives 1 for “Low” in the Water Footprint Index (WFI) for the Consumption segment.  \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding Natural vs. Synthetic Fibers\n\nNatural fibers, like cotton, react more readily to chemicals than synthetic fibers, such as polyester. Importantly, cotton can soak up significantly more water during washing than polyester. This difference in water absorption is noticeable when you weigh cotton and polyester clothes after doing laundry, which we will explore further in an upcoming experiment.\n\nCotton'\''s ability to hold more water means it can also attract odors more easily. The high moisture in natural fibers creates an environment for bacteria to thrive, especially since human sweat contains nutrients like urea, ammonia, and fatty acids that bacteria feed on. As a result, cotton garments need to be washed more often than polyester ones.\n\n### Water Footprint Index (WFI)\n\nTaking these factors into account, cotton is rated a **3** for “High” in the Water Footprint Index (WFI) for the Consumption segment, while polyester is rated a **1** for “Low.”";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "Which type of fibers has a higher affinity for chemical reactions?"; options = vec { "Synthetic fibers"; "Natural fibers"; "Neither"; "Both" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What is one of the main reasons for more frequent washing cycles of cotton compared to polyester?"; options = vec { "Cotton is cheaper"; "Cotton absorbs more water"; "Cotton dries faster"; "Cotton is used more often" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which fiber is more prone to odor development due to higher moisture content?"; options = vec { "Polyester"; "Nylon"; "Cotton"; "Acrylic" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "In the Water Footprint Index (WFI), what score does cotton receive for the Consumption segment?"; options = vec { "1"; "2"; "3"; "4" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "What contributes to easier bacterial growth on natural fibers like cotton?"; options = vec { "Absence of water"; "High moisture content"; "Synthetic materials"; "Low pH" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "13.3.0";
    unit_title = "Food Footprint Index (FFI) Analysis - Consumption";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "13.3";
    head_unit_title = "Food Footprint Index (FFI) Analysis - Consumption";
    content = "Consumption of textile goods using either cotton or polyester does not create any direct impact on the food securities.  Thus, both cotton and polyester receive the score of 1 for “Low” in the Food Footprint Index (FFI) of the Consumption segment. \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding the Impact of Textile Consumption on Food Security\n\nWhen we use textile products made from cotton or polyester, there is no direct effect on food security. For this reason, both cotton and polyester are assigned a score of **1**, indicating a **\"Low\"** impact on the Food Footprint Index (FFI) within the Consumption category.";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What score do cotton and polyester receive for their impact on food securities in the Food Footprint Index?"; options = vec { "0"; "1"; "2"; "3" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What does FFI stand for in the context of textile goods?"; options = vec { "Food Footprint Index"; "Fabric Fiber Index"; "Fashion Footprint Index"; "Footwear Footprint Index" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "In terms of food security impact, how are cotton and polyester classified?"; options = vec { "High"; "Medium"; "Low"; "Critical" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "Does the consumption of textile goods made from cotton or polyester directly impact food securities?"; options = vec { "Yes"; "No"; "Only cotton"; "Only polyester" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "Which segment does the Food Footprint Index relate to in the context of this content?"; options = vec { "Production"; "Consumption"; "Distribution"; "Recycling" }; answer = 1; }; };
})'

dfx canister call learning_engine add_learning_unit '(record {
    unit_id = "13.4.0";
    unit_title = "Carbon Footprint Index (CEI) Analysis - Consumption";
    chapter_id = "III";
    chapter_title = "Chapter III";
    head_unit_id = "13.4";
    head_unit_title = "Carbon Footprint Index (CEI) Analysis - Consumption";
    content = "As previously established, cotton cultivation requires large amounts of water due to the inherent hydrophilicity of its cellulose structure. This water affinity persists throughout the lifecycle, necessitating more water usage during washing and rinsing cycles and increasing energy consumption in the drying process of home laundry.  \nA home-based experiment was conducted to compare the energy consumption of laundering between cotton and polyester. The experiment is aimed to mimic real-life laundry scenarios with the detailed methodology presented as follows.\nPreparations: \nTwo groups of towels as the test samples:  \nGroup 1: Four towels made with 100% polyester; each towel sized at 69 x 132cm (27 x 52 inches)\nGroup 2: Four towels made with 100% cotton; each towel sized at 69 x 132cm (27 x 52 inches)\nWasher make and model: Blomberg WM77120 NBL01, \n          Front loading\nDryer make and model:  Blomberg DV1542 model, 15   Amp, 2,000 Watt, 3.7 cu.ft capacity, Front loading \n30kg x 1g Electronic Computing Scale \nTest Procedure: \nEach group of the four towels is placed in a room with temperature controlled at 23oC (or 73oF) and relative humidity between 50 ~ 60% for a minimum of 24 hours, a process generally known as “conditioning” in typical laboratory tests. \nAfter the conditioning, each group of the four towels is measured in weight. This initial weight is identified as the “DRY (weight)” in Fig.47. \nEach group is washed separately in the same setting of the washing machine, which includes the spinning at the end to remove excess water\nOnce the washing cycle is complete, the weight of the four towels in the same group is measured and marked as “WET (weight)” in the result.  \nDuring the drying cycle, the weight of the four towels in the same group is measured in 10 minutes interval until it reaches the initial DRY (weight). \nThe results of the experiment are as follow:\nFig.47   Towel Wash Experiment Results - Table\n* Notes: For readers’ reference, it is natural to reach a lower weight than the initial DRY weight after drying because the initial weight includes moisture absorbed by textile goods during storage (or conditioning in the case of this test). The test extended to dry this pre-existing moisture. Fine adjustments to calculate the time required to reach the exact initial dry weight could have been made. However, the significant difference in the test results between the two groups did not justify such fine adjustments. \nThe Group 2 cotton towels retained 240% more water after the washing-spinning process, with the \"WET\" weight of 1.2 kg (or 2.65 lbs) compared to 0.499 kg (or 1.10 lbs) for the polyester towels. Additionally, the drying time for the cotton group was significantly longer, taking 45 minutes versus 20 minutes for the polyester group. \nConverting the above figures to energy consumption: \nThe Cotton Group consumed 1.5 kWh of energy (=2,000 watt/1,000 x 45/60)\nThe Polyester Group consumed 0.67 kWh of energy (=2,000 watt/1,000 x 20/60)\nThis extended drying time for the cotton group resulted in an energy consumption difference of 0.87 kWh between the two groups (or 124% higher for the cotton). Considering that textile goods can be washed easily tens or even hundreds of times throughout their lifecycles, this difference translates to significantly different outcomes in the carbon footprint.\nIn a graphic format, the results are demonstrated in Fig.48.  \nFig.48   Towel Wash Experiment Result - Graph\n***\nAs the experiment results clearly indicate, cotton requires considerably more amount of energy during consumption. Based on these factors, cotton receives the score of 3 for “High”, while polyester receives 1 for “Low” in the Carbon Footprint Index (CFI) for the Consumption segment.  \n";
    paraphrase = "# Understanding the Energy Consumption in Laundering Cotton vs. Polyester\n\nCotton is known to need a lot of water due to its cellulose structure, which attracts water. This high water demand continues throughout its use—from washing and rinsing to drying—which leads to increased energy usage in household laundry.\n\nTo explore the energy consumption differences between cotton and polyester fabrics, a home experiment was conducted that simulates everyday laundry situations. Here’s a breakdown of the experiment.\n\n## Experiment Setup\n\n### Materials Used\n- **Towel Samples**:\n  - **Group 1**: Four towels made of 100% polyester (each measuring 69 x 132 cm or 27 x 52 inches).\n  - **Group 2**: Four towels made of 100% cotton (each measuring 69 x 132 cm or 27 x 52 inches).\n  \n- **Washer Model**: Blomberg WM77120 NBL01 (front-loading).\n- **Dryer Model**: Blomberg DV1542 (15 Amps, 2,000 Watts, 3.7 cu.ft capacity, front-loading).\n- **Scale**: 30 kg x 1 g electronic computing scale.\n\n### Procedure\n1. Each group of towels was placed in a controlled environment with a temperature of 23°C (73°F) and relative humidity between 50-60% for at least 24 hours. This process is referred to as \"conditioning.\"\n   \n2. After conditioning, the initial weight of each group was recorded as the “DRY weight.”\n   \n3. Each group of four towels was washed separately in the same washing machine settings, which included spinning to remove extra water.\n   \n4. After washing, the weight of each group of towels was recorded as the “WET weight.”\n   \n5. During the drying cycle, the towels'\'' weight was measured at 10-minute intervals until they returned to their initial DRY weight.\n\n### Experiment Results\n\n- **Note**: It'\''s normal for the towels to weigh less after drying compared to their DRY weight because the initial weight includes moisture absorbed during storage. This test aimed to dry any pre-existing moisture. While adjustments could be made to calculate drying time more precisely, the significant differences in results between the two groups didn'\''t warrant such changes.\n\n- The **Group 2** cotton towels retained 240% more water after washing and spinning, weighing 1.2 kg (2.65 lbs) compared to 0.499 kg (1.10 lbs) for the polyester towels. \n\n- The drying time for the cotton group was significantly longer, taking 45 minutes, while the polyester group took only 20 minutes.\n\n### Energy Consumption\n\n- **Cotton Group**: Used 1.5 kWh of energy \n  \\[\n  (2,000 \\text{ W} / 1,000 \\times 45/60)\n  \\]\n  \n- **Polyester Group**: Used 0.67 kWh of energy \n  \\[\n  (2,000 \\text{ W} / 1,000 \\times 20/60)\n  \\]\n\nThis longer drying time for the cotton group resulted in an energy consumption difference of 0.87 kWh, meaning cotton consumed 124% more energy than polyester. This difference is significant because textiles are usually washed many times during their lifecycles, affecting their overall carbon footprint.\n\n### Graphical Representation\n\nThe results can be visualized in a graph as shown in **Fig.48**.\n\n## Conclusion\n\nThe results clearly show that cotton requires much more energy compared to polyester during washing and drying. Therefore, cotton received a score of 3 for “High” on the Carbon Footprint Index (CFI) for the Consumption segment, while polyester received a score of 1 for “Low.”";
    quiz = vec { record { question = "What is the main reason cotton cultivation requires large amounts of water?"; options = vec { "Its cellulose structure is hydrophobic."; "Its cellulose structure is hydrophilic."; "It requires less water for laundering."; "Its fibers are resistant to moisture." }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "How much energy did the cotton group consume during the drying process?"; options = vec { "0.67 kWh"; "1.5 kWh"; "2.0 kWh"; "1.2 kWh" }; answer = 1; }; record { question = "What was the drying time for the polyester towels?"; options = vec { "20 minutes"; "30 minutes"; "45 minutes"; "15 minutes" }; answer = 0; }; record { question = "What score did cotton receive in the Carbon Footprint Index for the Consumption segment?"; options = vec { "1"; "2"; "3"; "4" }; answer = 2; }; record { question = "How much more water did the cotton group retain compared to the polyester group after washing?"; options = vec { "100%"; "140%"; "240%"; "300%" }; answer = 2; }; };
})'

